<HEADLINE>
AT 90, BORGE STILL WOWS AUDIENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE _ Warned that temperatures in the Phoenix area could still
be in the 90s when he plays a concert at Gammage Auditorium on Nov.
7, pianist and humorist Victor Borge responded brightly, ``I'm in
the 90s, too!''
</P>
<P>
   As Borge approaches his 91st birthday in January, the genial
entertainer is as hot as ever, having just returned from a tour of
his native Scandinavia that had him playing eight sold-out concerts
in nine days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly get a ticket myself,'' he says with a laugh,
phoning from his home in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing can slow the man known as the Great Dane, who made his
orchestral debut at age 10.
</P>
<P>
   Only the rigors of travel take their toll. Once he's on stage,
his mind and his fingers are as nimble as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Though Borge began his musical career as a child prodigy, the
son of a violinist with the Danish Symphony, he began to combine
his exquisite skills at the piano with his irrepressible wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't decide it,'' he says. ``It came absolutely
naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   He would make a humorous remark, the audience would laugh, and
that encouraged him. The wisecracks also helped to ease his
nervousness at the piano.
</P>
<P>
   His characteristic style evolved: A few bars of a classical
piece, a few witticisms. Music and mirth. It's a mix that has kept
him among the top entertainers in the country he adopted 60 years
ago after he fled Europe and the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   In his early 20s, he had become a leading film star in
Scandinavia, but when the Nazis invaded Denmark in the late 1930s,
he couldn't resist taking shots at the stormtrooping interlopers.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What's the difference between a dog and a Nazi?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: A Nazi lifts his arm.
</P>
<P>
   After such jabs landed Borge a spot on Hitler's blacklist, he
fled to Finland and then to America on the last American passenger
ship out of northern Europe before World War II began.
</P>
<P>
   For more than half a century, he has performed on stage, in
films and on radio and television in this country, endearing
himself to legions of fans who warm to his gentle humor and his
musical prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Borge's musical gifts come from his father, as does his sense of
humor. His father was quite the card, he says: ``He always had a
joke, even if it was the same one over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Borge style comes spontaneously. He writes no monologue,
preferring to speak off the cuff, tickling the funny bone while
tickling the ivories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's time to talk, sometimes it's time to play,'' he
says. ``It depends on the audience and how I feel at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not jokes. It's like a caricature. I'm a caricaturist of
happenings.''
</P>
<P>
   Borge's caricatures never lampoon current politics. Audiences,
he says, ``want to be entertained, not irritated.''
</P>
<P>
   His music is all classical, nothing ``strange or modern.'' He
shudders to think he would bore someone with strange, modern music.
</P>
<P>
   When he's performing in another country, his conversations are
still in English, though he favors the Scandinavians with dialogue
in Danish, which most northern Europeans understand in addition to
English.
</P>
<P>
   Humor loses much in a translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't translate humor,'' he says. ``I explain things that
happen. I use expressions that come to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Borge will be a featured guest in a Kennedy Center
Honors tribute for which he says ``it's hard to express the
gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Also a recipient of the Medal of Honor presented by the Statue
of Liberty Centennial Committee, he jokes that he's disappointed
that Kennedy Center honorees are not asked to perform, just bask in
the adulation of their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the honors he's garnered, this is ``one of the most
important,'' he says, because he will be singled out as a
celebrated Dane:
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects my home country.''
</P>
<P>
   Borge, married 46 years to his second wife, Sanna, has five
children and nine grandchildren. He's also an accomplished
yachtsman.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent visitor to the Phoenix area, he says he enjoys the
audiences here but bemoans the fact that he never gets to see the
sights _ he flies in, performs, sleeps, retreats.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve of the next millennium will be spent at his
Connecticut home with Sanna, and he'll begin celebrating around 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That's midnight in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Just another evening for Borge, a man for whom the ship of
freedom took him to a new and celebrated life 60 years ago, with
hope and optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day,'' he says, ``is a new year.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
