<HEADER>
A3212 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BBO-YANKS-PARADE-1STL     10-30 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PARADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GETTING TO BE A HABIT: A TICKER-TAPE PARADE FOR THE YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS number of injuries to 30 in 3rd graf) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With toilet paper streaming from office buildings and
cheers roaring up from teeming sidewalks, New York threw yet
another ticker-tape parade for its world champion Yankees on Friday
that was by turns jubilant and somber, but at times surprisingly
rowdy.
</P>
<P>
   The clear skies above lower Broadway were a shimmering blizzard
of shredded spreadsheets and endless printouts, the streets below
athunder with the cheers of truant schoolchildren and their
compliant parents, as the Bronx Bombers rolled by in what threatens
to become an annual rite.
</P>
<P>
   But the long wait for those who rose at dawn to claim a decent
vista along the parade route seemed to have exhausted the patience
and civility of a number of people, who hurled refuse at each
other, at police, and at the riders of open flatbed trucks and
double-decker buses whose names they did not know. At least 30
people were injured and police arrested at least six people on
charges ranging from sexual abuse and indecent exposure to inciting
a riot and assaulting a police officer, the authorities said late
Friday afternoon, though the number of arrests was expected to grow
as reports filtered in.
</P>
<P>
   The parade once again culminated in an afternoon rally for the
25-time champions at City Hall, where pure politics was the order
of the day in ways seen and unseen. As the players waited to be
introduced, the banner of a police department band draped
momentarily over a larger banner, briefly obscuring the name of the
celebration's host, ``Mayor Rudy Giuliani.'' But only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the crowd of dignitaries who had been allowed beyond
locked gates to within sight of the stage included dozens of local
politicians eager to soak up a little Yankee glory and electoral
goodwill. But some Democratic members of the state Assembly were
officially barred from the day's events because they had voted to
repeal New York City's commuter tax, aides to Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Any suggestion that the third such celebration in four years
might produce a blase response in a city legendary for its
been-there, done-that affectations was rendered ridiculous long
before the parade began at 12:10 p.m. By 10:30, the sidewalks along
Broadway between Battery Place and Chambers Street were crammed
full _ police, who are given to generous estimates of ticker-tape
crowds, estimated this year's attendance at slightly more than last
year's figure of 3.5 million _ and the more athletic fans had
clambered atop telephones and traffic lights and bus-stop signs and
even the old bell tower in the Trinity Church graveyard. Everything
and everyone was covered in paper; the gargoyles that adorned
dignified office buildings could have been wearing Yankee hats
underneath, for all anyone knew.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A block off the parade route, vendors near the Municipal
Building and along Church Street did a brisk business in Yankee
T-shirts and hats, while dime stores and hardware shops sold out of
mops, scrub-brushes and anything else that could pass for a broom,
to signify the Yankees' second consecutive sweep in the World
Series. Sanitation crews, walking behind mounted police in
performance of perhaps the least-desired job in New York, were
greeted as enthusiastically as Yankee Stadium's groundskeepers
dancing to ``YMCA,'' as fans giddily chanted ``Sweep! Sweep!
Sweep!'' _ and no one mistook the shouting for a directive.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though Wall Street did manage to function Friday, it seemed
likely that businesses and government agencies all over the
metropolitan area were operating at less than full strength,
judging from the number of prison janitors, elevator mechanics,
teachers and software developers who left work to be at the parade,
with permission or without. Rose Minoughan, 34, a police officer in
Newark, N.J., who held a bright-pink sign saying ``Torre for
Pope,'' said she had called in sick with a ``migraine'' _ just like
last year. ``You're going to get me in trouble!'' she joked.
</P>
<P>
   But children, tens of thousands of them pressed against police
barriers, seemed to outnumber the grown-ups. If these ticker-tape
parades continue much longer, school officials may want to think
about writing them into the official calendar. As it was, public
high school students were given a half-day off for afternoon
parent-teacher conferences, but many youngsters _ and their
parents, too _ seemed to have borrowed a lesson from math class and
rounded up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Diane Carusalle, who shepherded her sons Dean, 13, and Lenny,
10, and their three cousins from Staten Island, said she would fess
up on Tuesday in her note to the nuns at her boys' parochial school
explaining their absence. ``I'll take my chances admitting we went
to the Yankee parade,'' she said, as the boys stared down Broadway
for a glimpse of the first float. ``I pay them enough every year.
They'll have to get over it. Plus, Friday was a teacher conference,
and Monday they're off for All Saints' Day. So we'll call it a
five-day weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   As the parade slowly lurched up from Bowling Green, which was
declared by one fan's poster as ``Yankee Stadium South,'' many in
the crowd showed off the swagger that visiting players said made a
trip to the Bronx a foray into truly hostile territory,
bad-mouthing the nowhere-to-be-found Boston Red Sox and Atlanta
Braves, the last two victims of the Yankees' postseason juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   There were, too, the usual hordes of girls and young women
waiting to swoon for Derek Jeter, the Yankees' star shortstop and
reigning heartthrob. And this year, for the first time, there were
nearly as many young and not-so-young women holding signs declaring
their love for Chuck Knoblauch, the second baseman of the errant
throws; it seemed as if some wanted to take care of him more than
to adore him, as if all he needed was some TLC to clear his head.
</P>
<P>
   But many less boisterous parade-goers seemed deeply affected by
the human travails that this year's Yankee players were forced to
overcome, to tell from the dozens of carefully lettered banners
held aloft memorializing the fathers of Paul O'Neill, Luis Sojo and
Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ana Jordan, 19, of Staten Island, who had scrawled O'Neill's
name on her right cheek, and his number, 21, on her left, said she
had gotten the day off from her job at a supermarket to come to the
parade to show her admiration for the right-fielder, who lost his
father early Wednesday but still played in the series clincher that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was really brave of him to play through the last
game after his father died,'' Ms. Jordan said. ``He also played
with a broken rib, that's how into the team he is. Jeter cares more
about looking good on the field. O'Neill is just concerned about
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   That humanity came pouring out later on the platform in front of
City Hall, when Darryl Strawberry followed a number of teammates to
the podium to say a few words. After a short speech, the
oft-troubled Yankee designated hitter, who recovered from a battle
with colon cancer last fall only to be arrested for solicitation
and drug possession early this year, began to thank his manager,
Joe Torre, when he broke down and doubled over, sobbing
uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   As he cried for a full minute, Torre walked to Strawberry and
put his arms around him, and the crowd began to applaud, louder and
louder, until even the Yankee players were clapping in a standing
ovation of moral support. Finally, Strawberry lifted his head, his
eyes hidden behind sunglasses, and managed: `I'd just like to say
to Joe, thank you for caring for me.'' To his teammates, he added:
``And I love you guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the bunting and balloons that bedecked City Hall seemed
fitting for a presidential inauguration, Giuliani, who apparently
would settle for a Senate seat for now, kept his remarks brief,
nonpartisan and sentimental, also noting the Yankees' ability to
turn the ``adversities of life'' into ``something positive.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how the season started on a rainy day in April. ``It
ends on a beautiful and glorious day in an October New York sun
that is shining and that's bright,'' he added. ``Because the
Yankees and New York own October.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
