<SLUG> BC-BBO-PARADE-PROBLEMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS, INJURIES AND SCUFFLES AMID CELEBRATION FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS number of injured to 30 from 35 in 2nd graf, ADDS details
of arrests in last 3 grafs) 
(ATTN: Ind.) (With BBO-YANKS-PARADE) 
(mk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the New York Yankees' ticker-tape parade marched
up Broadway and dignitaries celebrated the team's World Series
victory inside the gated confines of City Hall Park on Friday,
police were kept busy with scattered scuffles and unruliness among
the throngs of fans packed into the surrounding blocks and along
the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday evening, officials said that more than 30 people
had been injured, and police had made at least six arrests. Those
numbers were expected to grow as the tallies continued to be
compiled overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries included people who were hit with bottles,
newspapers, rolls of toilet paper and other objects, officials
said. Two police officers suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that the event was
relatively calm. ``They were all minor arrests,'' he said at a news
conference Friday afternoon to announce the seizure of $130,000 in
unauthorized Yankees clothing and the arrests of seven people who
were involved in two separate souvenir-knockoff operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's appropriate that on the day that we are celebrating their
victory, we are stopping people who are illegally profiting from
their success,'' added Safir, who attended the ceremony at City
Hall and rode in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   As Safir and the rest of the parade participants passed, the
sound of bottles crashing into the ground could be heard, along
with the angry yells of fans who could not get a good view.
</P>
<P>
   Official crowd estimates were not released by city officials
Friday, but Safir said that he believed there were between 100,000
and 150,000 more people than the 3.5 million estimated by police to
have attended last year's parade. ``It was bigger than '96,'' Safir
said. ``And I can tell you it was a lot bigger than '98.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department deployed 5,000 officers for the parade.
Safir said the number of officers was larger than it had been in
previous years. Other police officials said that additional
officers had been needed partly because Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had
tacitly approved of schoolchildren taking the day off to celebrate
the Yankees' victory.
</P>
<P>
   There were no incidents comparable to some of those that
occurred in previous years, when fans pushed against police
barricades and trashed cars outside the federal building at 26
Federal Plaza. But fans on Friday could be seen throwing everything
from confetti and toilet paper to cans and bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Police responded to reports of missing children, assaults,
people attempting to scale the Brooklyn Bridge to catch a better
glimpse of the rally in City Hall Park and other incidents, leaving
little time to enforce the Giuliani's zero-tolerance policies
toward public drinking and other such offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Near the steps of the U.S. attorney's office, only about 100
feet from the entrance to police headquarters, high school students
guzzled beer as confetti drifted in the air around them.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the day started off relatively quietly for
the thousands of police officers posted along the parade route and
near subway stations in lower Manhattan. But as the parade
entourage progressed north on Broadway to City Hall Park from
Battery City Park, the streets along the route began to resemble
New Orleans during Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, Sara Miltenberger, a 21-year-old college student from
Indiana, was arrested for taking her clothes off on a terrace above
the crowds at 71 Broadway, and an unidentified man standing along
the route was arrested for throwing an explosive object that burst
into flames in the street in front of a group of people, officials
said. Another man, Carlos Vargas, 37, was arrested for gropping at
a female spectator.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, as the crowds became increasingly raucous and
roving groups of teen-agers began to cause trouble in the crowd,
police commanders launched a rapid mobilization, requesting
hundreds of additional officers to respond to the parade, law
enforcement officials said. But no serious problems materialized,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Det. Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman, said the final tally
of arrests would not be available until later Saturday. During last
year's parade, 18 people were arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
