<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GHOSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON OF THE WITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The season of darkness is moving in. It started Saturday morning
at 7:15 with the latest sunrise of the year. Saturday night the
clocks turned back to winter _ psychologically, at least, for
although the weather is still mild, the mood shifts deep into
sweater country when Standard Time steals the late-afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   September was a comparative romp, when summer lingered in the
promise of a bright autumn. There was plenty of time to think about
putting gardens to bed, cleaning storm windows, and getting ready
for the long slog to March. But on the cusp of November a person
has to pick up the ax and get serious about the woodpile.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, the dark season begins with Halloween. A person
can put on a fright mask and stare down the inevitable or become a
clown and laugh it off. The celebration of goblins and ghosts is
supposedly for kids, but adults love the magic of disguise and the
freedom to become someone, or something, else.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Celts used to dress up in animal skins when they
honored Samhain, the lord of the dead, who supposedly allowed
departed spirits to return to earth on the night of Oct. 31. It was
a kind of new year's eve festival, for the Celts began their year
on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   There will probably be no authentic animal skins at the door
Sunday when early nightfall starts the doorbell ringing well before
supper. The first trick-or-treaters will be the cutest _ the
under-6 set masquerading as bunnies, ballerinas, and black cats.
Later the more sophisticated space aliens and famous, or infamous,
political characters will come up the steps _ and in New Hampshire
they really could be running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Later still some very big kids dressed as pirates or robbers may
ring the bell, and the wary homeowner might decide to turn out the
porch light and chance a pumpkin-smashing. It's a scary world out
there 365 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Time to burrow in, light the fire, nail down the flapping
shutter, and seal the cracks against the whistling wind. That noise
is the wind, isn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
