<P>
   MEXICO-CARS (Mexico City) _ A Mexican government plan to charge
travelers who drive cars with American license plates into Mexico a
deposit of up to $800 has provoked expressions of dismay from
critics who say it could persuade hundreds of thousands of tourists
to cancel plans for travel to Mexico. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-BEEF (Paris) _ Developments in the growing
Britain-France food war: the European Union to rule today on
whether France is justified in continuing its ban on British beef
even though the EU has lifted its ban. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-COUP (Islamabad) _ Poor Pakistanis feel coup merely
toppled a sham democracy. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASH-CAR-TAX (Seattle) _ Washington gears up for a vote Tuesday
on doing away with an enormous car tax and replacing it with a flat
$30 fee. Arguments on both sides of the issue are all about sprawl.
Also contains a provision saying all taxes and fees have to be
approved by voters. The tax is the fourth biggest source of income
in the state. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   LA-SCHOOLS-FIGHT (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles school district
fires its superintendent after a lengthy battle over management of
the troubled urban district. The struggle over ousting and
replacing Rubin Zacarias, a Latino, shows how the political power
struggle between Anglos and Latinos in the city is coming to a
head. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
