<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-STEWART-MEMORIAL-     10-30 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-STEWART-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stewart's zest-filled life remembered
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ You remember the oddest things at times like
this. Moments that made the man. Things you took for granted or
thought were long forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   On display Friday morning inside the huge sanctuary at First
Baptist Church of Orlando was a collection of the stuff that was
William Payne Stewart. A picture of him hugging the U.S. Open
trophy he won in June. Gold-framed paintings of his family. A
collage of newspaper and magazine clippings about his career. A
note from his two kids, daughter Chelsea and son Aaron, saying:
``We love you dad. We will miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   And there, tucked amid the mementos and his favorite harmonica,
a bottle of Rogaine was left by his kids, because Payne Stewart was
no different than any other middle-aged man. He worried about those
skid marks his hairline was leaving on its race from forehead to
scalp. And because apples never fall far from trees, his kids would
give him grief about it. Stewart certainly wouldn't think twice
about needling Tom Lehman, Paul Azinger or anybody else who was
follicely challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne Stewart was just a regular guy,'' said Pastor J.B.
Collingsworth, ``who happened to be a great golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what made his life worth honoring. And the people who
lived, laughed, cried with and loved Payne Stewart for his entire
42 years gathered Friday to do it all again during the service
celebrating the PGA Tour player who died Monday in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the party in heaven begin,'' said Tracey Stewart, Payne's
wife who spoke bravely and tearfully for nearly 10 minutes during
the most touching part of the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stewart's zest for life was what his friends will
remember, even more than his syrupy-smooth golf swing. Stewart's
fun-loving lifestyle, his devotion to family and faith, his
affinity for good wine and good song, and his flair for doing
everything with a certain style were remembered during the two-hour
ceremony at the church where he was a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you celebrate the life of the greatest celebrator of
life?'' said Austin's Chuck Cook, who was Stewart's close friend
and coach. ``I can just imagine how much louder heaven is going to
be now.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people tapped deep into the emotional vault, led by
Stewart's widow, who not only found strength to speak Friday but
also to attend the funeral Thursday for Robert Fraley, the agent
and close friend of Stewart who was also on the doomed plane along
with four other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw Payne was at a cocktail party at the
Malaysian Open in 1980,'' Tracey said. ``I saw him, and he was the
most beautiful man I had ever seen. It really was love at first
sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after 18 years of marriage, he's still the most beautiful
man I know. Not because of the way he looks on the outside. But
because of the way I know he looks on the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to 100 PGA Tour players attended the service, including
most of the 29 golfers participating in the Tour Championship at
Champions Golf Club. The tournament will resume today with 27
holes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups in the service that was open to the public and
drew a crowd of 3,000 in the 6,000-seat church was the Pop Warner
football team on which Aaron Stewart, 10, plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much to my despair that Aaron wanted to play
football,'' Tracey said. ``But little did I know how much joy would
come from it for Payne and Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught three passes, all of them for touchdowns. The last
one was on Saturday (last week), and Payne was there to cheer
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Tracey Stewart and Cook, Paul Azinger was one of the
featured speakers during the tribute. Azinger, who survived a
battle with cancer in 1993, put the large audience in a Payne frame
of mind when he approached the podium and pulled a tam-o'-shanter
out of his jacket pocket and put it on his head.
</P>
<P>
   He then pulled the pant legs of his suit up and tucked them into
argyle socks, giving him a Stewart-looking pair of makeshift
knickers.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd applauded. Then Azinger opened his heart about
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to accept the magnitude of this tragedy is the most
difficult thing I've ever had to do,'' he said. ``Payne Stewart has
finished the race. He has kept the faith, and now the crown of
righteousness is his.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger, who also was represented by Fraley, said the same
phrase for Fraley and Van Ardan during his 20 minutes at the podium
that was half monologue and half tear-jerking storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne wasn't the most mechanically inclined person,'' Azinger
said. ``I remember he got an endorsement for a weed whacker a few
years ago. And when I got to his house the other day, the yard was
looking so good I thought about the weed-whacker deal. We all knew
full well that Payne didn't know how to even start that weed
whacker.''
</P>
<P>
   The wonderfully done ceremony also featured a recorded musical
tribute from country music star Vince Gill, who wrote Hey God _ A
Tribute to Payne this week in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   During the past couple of years, Stewart could never be found
without having a modest bracelet on his wrist made out of fabric
imprinted with the initials W.W.J.D. _ What Would Jesus Do? Friday,
similar bracelets were given to everyone in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gift from Aaron,'' said Pastor Jim Henry. ``And it
came to represent how Payne wanted to live his life. He told me
after he won the U.S. Open that he wanted to do what Jesus would do
for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf can stand for different things. It can stand for Go Out,
Lost Forever. Or, it can stand for God Offers Love, Forgiveness.
God's going to call us all home someday. And Payne had opened up
his heart to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Other musical tributes and a video of Stewart highlights and
insights ensured dry eyes were nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   During the video, an interview with Stewart summed up perfectly
his devotion to God and family that had become so strong in the
past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about dreams is that sometimes you can live them
out,'' Stewart said. ``If something happened tomorrow, and I
couldn't play golf anymore, my life is complete, because I have a
wonderful family, and I am so happy about being a good father and
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the pulpit, a framed Bible passage from the 40th chapter of
Isaiah was displayed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even youths grow tired and weary, and young men stumble and
fall. But those who hope in the Lord will renew their strength.
They will soar on wings like eagles. They will run and not grow
weary. They will walk and not be faint.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, underneath the inscription, read: Payne soared with eagles
and awakened in the arms of God.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the ceremony was a time for a complete
outpouring of support to Tracey Stewart and the two children who
will have to build a lifetime of memories about their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard an interview with Payne a couple days ago, and he was
asked what he thought his legacy would be,'' Tracey said. ``He
said, `I didn't even know I had a legacy.' But those two kids will
be his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever they wanted to shoot hoops or play softball or throw
the football, he was right there to do it with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Aaron and Chelsea are gifted with their father's athletic
abilities. And I know he'll be there on the front row shouting
encouragement to them for them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the service, the PGA Tour players attending gave
one final tribute, lining the center aisle of the church and
offering personal greetings to the families of Stewart, Fraley and
Ardan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service was just beautiful,'' Lehman said. ``The messages
were very heartfelt. Obviously, Payne has about a zillion great
fans and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus attended, but Arnold Palmer did not. Palmer's wife
has been ill for some time, and he has limited his public
appearances of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always going to remember the rhythm of Payne's swing and
his love of life,'' Nicklaus said. ``Payne was all about having
fun. He had a lot of fun in life and in golf. He even knew how to
have fun when he was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Azinger was among Stewart's closest friends on tour. And while
everybody will search for ways to cope with Stewart's loss, Azinger
tried to offer some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the land of the living who are going to the land
of the dying,'' Azinger said. ``We're in the land of the dying who
are going to the land of the living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
