<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-tour-HNS &LR;      10-30 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-tour-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Champions' stillness serves as tribute
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JAYNE CUSTRED
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The bleachers next to the No. 1 tee at Champions Golf Club were
empty Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Silence echoed down the first fairway, broken only by the hum of
maintenance carts as they hurried down the pathways, or the steady
beat of the flags at half-staff and flapping in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The clock standing between No. 1 and No. 10 tees ticked off the
minutes as the second day of the 1999 Tour Championship came and
went without a stroke of golf played.
</P>
<P>
   Champions was saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1,000 miles away, in a church in Orlando, Fla., those who
knew and loved Payne Stewart best, were remembering the man whose
life was taken so suddenly in Monday's plane crash. There were
emotional speeches and fitting tributes, tears and laughter and
music.
</P>
<P>
   But in Houston, where Stewart had planned to spend this week,
there was only silence. And that, perhaps, was the greatest tribute
of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to shut a big tournament like this down in
midstream,'' said Frank Watson, a parking lot security guard at
Champions who spent most of Friday not guarding much of anything.
``But Payne Stewart was a much-loved man. This was out of a deep
respect for him. And every one of us are feeling real bad about why
we're having this day off today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here like this is very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   The course was ready, perfectly groomed, meticulously tended,
but squirrels ran where fans should have walked, and nothing landed
on the greens except an occasional bird.
</P>
<P>
   The ropes that are such a necessary part of a tournament of this
magnitude stretched endlessly down the fairways as usual, but
looked strangely out of place on a deserted tract.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate tents, normally rowdy and loud by Friday
afternoon, were dark and empty. The faint roar of cars traveling in
the distance replaced the usual din of laughter, raised voices and
spiritedings under thul eyes of diehard fans. Instead, there was
the sound of a mower cutting an already perfect fairway on an
already perfect course.
</P>
<P>
   And missing was the spirit of the game. The camaraderie, the
sportsmanship, the essence of what makes golf so different and
unique. Instead, there was a void, and the hollow, empty feeling
that comes with having just 29 players to fill a 30-man field.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Champions clubhouse is the bronze statue of a young
boy swinging a golf club, clad in Stewart-like knickers, his eyes
looking off to the distance. The much-beloved statue, which is
surrounded by the brightest of flowers, is called ``Tomorrow's
Child,'' and depicts a young golfer with a bright future and
endless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few yards away, also covered in flowers, was the empty
parking spot bearing the name of Payne Stewart, the U.S. Open
champion who brought laughter, then silence, to the game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the rest of the golfers will return to Champions. The
stands will fill up once more, fans will spill out of the corporate
tents to watch the best in the game, and the tournament will go on.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, in the most fitting way possible, Champions said
goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
