<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER ISSUES FACE FUNERAL HOME DIRECTORS AT KC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
 HOME INDUSTRY 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Around 6,000 U.S. funeral home directors will
be in Kansas City next week for their annual convention and trade
show.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day event begins on Halloween, but the nation's
undertakers are already plenty frightened by industry critics who
have been after them all year. And the worst may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in fear'' of the Federal Trade Commission's Funeral
Rule, which can bring six-figure fines, said Ronald E. Troyer, a
Minnesota funeral home manager and one of six national spokesmen
for the 14,000-member National Funeral Directors Association.
</P>
<P>
   Though its provisions are many, the heart of the 15-year-old
Funeral Rule is its requirement that anyone who asks must be
provided a written copy of a funeral home's general price list. The
rule has helped an increasing percentage of Americans who now
comparison-shop funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   And, Troyer said, the FTC rule may be cinched even tighter in
response to critics who say funeral customers often are misled and
manipulated in their time of grief, and pressured into buying
services that are overpriced or that they don't need or don't want.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the FTC has heard hundreds of hours of testimony
and next year plans to rewrite and reissue its consumer rights
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa, chairman of the Senate
Special Committee on Aging, is promising congressional hearings
next year after what he called ``disturbing questions'' raised in a
General Accounting Office audit released last week.
</P>
<P>
   That report, performed at Republican Grassley's request, found
FTC oversight of the funeral industry to be spotty and weak.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC disputed the findings and said compliance with consumer
protection rules had improved.
</P>
<P>
   But FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky also said: ``Our experience has
demonstrated that we are able to accomplish a good deal by working
with industry groups...by cultivating harmonious rather than
acrimonious relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC and the industry, he said, have developed ``a remedial
rather than a punitive law enforcement program that is more
effective in stimulating compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassley suggests that might not be good enough: ``We want to
know how the FTC can assure consumers of fair treatment when they
walk into a funeral home. When consumers shell out thousands of
dollars for a service, they should get what they pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Troyer and Kelly Smith, another association spokesman, say
consumers not only get their money's worth but are getting more for
their money today than a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals have evolved, said Troyer, from mostly straightforward,
faith-based memorial services to celebrations of the deceased's
life. And funeral directors who genuinely care about their
customers are the ones who make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals, he said, have become ``a theater experience'' that aid
in the healing process for the grieving.
</P>
<P>
   Troyer recounted a recent funeral he performed for a truck
driver who was known for the unique belt buckle he always wore.
</P>
<P>
   He said long _ and cathartic _ talks with the family gave him
enough material for a 20-minute eulogy that played off that belt
buckle.
</P>
<P>
   But Troyer wasn't done. He then turned to his funeral home's
library of stereophonic sound effects to close the service with the
throaty rumble of a diesel engine firing up.
</P>
<P>
   And then, mimicking an up-and-down pulling motion, he said, ``We
sounded the air horn. Whoo, whoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a dry eye in the house, because that was a
wonderful memory for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, too, have their stories.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Carlson, executive director of the consumer-based Funeral
and Memorial Societies of America and one of the industry's most
persistent watchdogs, was among 150 people who testified on the FTC
Funeral Rule earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   She recounted tales of families charged $200 to fax obituary
information to the local newspaper, and funeral homes charging $600
or more to handle the donation of bodies to medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industrywide practices are contrary to the letter and spirit
of the Funeral Rule,'' she said, and ``continue to impose
unwarranted and anti-competitive costs on funeral consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Two issues dominate the Funeral Rule controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The first is whether to expand the rule to cover cemeteries,
monument dealers, retail coffin outlets and other product and
service providers. On that issue, consumers and the funeral homes
agree that the playing field should be level for all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
