<HEADER>
A3240 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-SENIORS-LADN     10-30 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAHAFFEY, JACOBS LEAD PACIFIC BELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It has been a time for mourning and remembrance
this week in golf. But Friday at the Wilshire Country Club, it was
time to play.
</P>
<P>
   John Jacobs and John Mahaffey each shot 6-under-par 65s to share
the first-round lead in the $1.2 million Pacific Bell Senior
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   It was an especially difficult day for Mahaffey. He was a close
friend to Payne Stewart, who perished in a plane crash in Mina,
S.D. earlier this week and was honored in the form of black ribbons
on the hats and shirts of the field Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mahaffey, like most of his fellow competitors, watched the
Orlando, Fla., memorial service for Stewart early Friday.
Afterward, the 51-year-old barely had the strength to tee it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely difficult to play golf today,'' he said.
``Especially when you're watching the service, and a lot of grown
men are crying. You lose one of your own like that, it really,
really hits close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't sound jovial today ... I'm happy with the round,
but really saddened by the loss of a great friend and great
competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   On the demanding par-71, 6,575-yard layout, Mahaffey played the
back nine in 5-under 31 to forge a tie with the long-hitting
Jacobs, who finished moments earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Mahaffey loves the course, particularly its fast greens. Jacobs
said he is fearful of Wilshire because it doesn't suit his game.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who leads the tour in driving distance at just less than
290 yards, hit only three drivers Friday in his no-bogey round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to stay away from it,'' Jacobs said with a grin. ``It's
not my kind of course because it's narrow. A friend of mine would
say, `Hey, let's go play Wilshire.' I'd say, `I'll catch up to you
on a different course.'
</P>
<P>
   ``To shoot a 65 ... maybe I'm getting smarter in my old age.''
</P>
<P>
   He's getting healthier, too. The 54-year-old recently underwent
a couple of minor operations to remove scar tissue from his right
elbow and wrist. He said he had been playing ``terrible'' golf for
the past eight weeks _ until his second-round 63 in last week's
Kaanapali Classic in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he still feels pain, but he has learned to put up
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only really hurts to hit a wedge or 9-iron,'' he said. ``It
doesn't hurt to hit a driver. `But that's no big deal. Everybody
hurts in some way out here.''
</P>
<P>
   One shot behind the leaders was Bruce Summerhays at 5-under 66,
followed by Jim Thorpe, Gary Player (who turns 64 on Monday), Lee
Trevino and Dave Stockton at 67.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Joe Inman was in a large group at 3-under 68
that also included leading seven-time winner Bruce Fleisher, Hale
Irwin and Gil Morgan. Chi Chi Rodriguez and Jim Colbert were in a
group at 69.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilshire CC layout has been reworked this year, to where
this year's 18th hole, a 162-yard par three, was last year's No.
10. This year's holes 10-through-17 were last year's 11-through-18.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the par-three finale promises to cause plenty of
drama, according to Summerhays.
</P>
<P>
   It provided plenty for the 55-year-old father of eight, who left
what he thought was a perfect nine-iron tee shot buried in the
front bunker. He blasted out to 20 feet and made the putt for a
par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy to get it out to 20 feet,'' he said. ``That
little par three will take its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Summerhays had, perhaps, an even more critical hole on the
par-4, 321-yard 14th hole. He left his tee shot in the trees and,
instead of playing it safe in the fairway and taking his chances
for par, he negotiated his approach through a small opening to
within 12 feet. He made the putt and played his final five holes in
three-under.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everything that could go right for me did go
right,'' Summerhays said. ``It was a pleasant day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
