<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3243 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHICAGOCOWS-KAN &LR;      10-30 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN KC THINK COW EXHIBIT LIKE CHICAGO'S WOULD BE UDDERLY
GREAT 
</HEADLINE>
 COWS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cowrazy.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the climate in Chicago for the past five months, and
now there are those in Kansas City who are hoping for our own form
of mad-for-cows disease next summer.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone missed the madness, Chicago has been gripped with
cow mania since June, when a herd of 320 acrylic Brown Swiss
bovines began grazing and lounging inside the city's famed Loop.
</P>
<P>
   All of the cows were decorated by artists _ some wildly
whimsical, others conspicuously commercial. Most have names,
including some that make you want to groan, or perhaps giggle _
such as Udder Gold, PiCowso and On the Moooooove. Starting Monday
most of them will be auctioned off for charity.
</P>
<P>
   The attention the cows have brought to Chicago has been
astounding.
</P>
<P>
   The officially named Cows on Parade has been covered by everyone
from the Jakarta Post to the Wisconsin State Farmer, brought more
publicity to Chicago than the 1996 Democratic National Convention
and generated up to $200 million in tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been overwhelming but phenomenally successful,''
said Kimberly Costello of the Chicago Department of Cultural
Affairs, which brought the exhibit to Chicago. ``We never in a
million years dreamed it would turn into something this big.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in Kansas City has such a grand plan for this area, but
in the minds of many, there's no reason why this city can't head up
a more modest cattle drive.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Holland, who's involved in area arts organizations, is one
of those blazing the trail for the local effort.
</P>
<P>
   Like many area residents who have seen or heard about the
exhibit, Holland wondered why Kansas City couldn't do something
similar. Given the city's heritage, it seems natural.
</P>
<P>
   While St. Louis says it's the gateway to the West, many
historians think the tag is more fitting for Kansas City. In the
later part of the 1800s, Kansas City is where civilization ended,
with many of the trails to the great West beckoning just beyond the
city's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kansas City was home to the second-largest livestock
industry in the nation, behind only Chicago. The stench emanating
from the stockyards was often referred to as the smell of money.
Indeed, in the early 1900s livestock accounted for 90 percent of
the value of everything produced in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kansas City is home to the Hereford Association; the
Dairy Farmers of America Inc., the country's largest dairy
cooperative; and Farmland Industries, the country's largest
agricultural cooperative, just to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   And what icon _ until perhaps the Bartle Hall baubles _ has been
more associated with Kansas City than the big plastic Hereford bull
lording over the city from downtown?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the American Royal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year will be the 101st American Royal,'' Holland said.
``I think it would be neat to have a tie-in with the 100 cows _ the
next 100 years of the American Royal.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland envisions the cows being placed throughout Kansas City
next summer, ranging from perhaps the River Market to the Plaza.
Then, in the fall, they could be rounded up to ride in the American
Royal Parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we could buy one of the Chicago cows, and it could be
carrying a suitcase with Chicago stickers, sort of the cows coming
home to Kansas City, to where they belong,'' Holland said. ``And
then maybe we could even get Kansas City Southern to bring them in
by train.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland is just brimming with ideas, and she isn't at all
worried that people will cringe at the perpetuation of Kansas
City's cow-town heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a cow town,'' Holland said. ``Not an ordinary cow town,
but a cow town nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chappell, president of the Convention and Visitors Bureau
of Greater Kansas City, loves the idea of the exhibit but is less
comfortable with promoting Kansas City as a cow town.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that he has a problem with the heritage. After all, his
organization touts the area's birthright to potential visitors all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   His problem is one of being misleading. And besides, he said,
when he thinks of cow town, he thinks of slow and backward, a
definition supported by most dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no horses tied to the side of buildings, and there
are no cows in the street _ except when Mike Murphy does his cattle
drive,'' Chappell said. ``We don't even have a lot of people who
wear cowboy hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a lot of Kansas City-area residents have a fear of what
writer Calvin Trillin, a Kansas City native, calls rubophobia.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Wilson, director of the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, agrees
with Trillin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some here who are afraid people outside of Kansas
City will think they're rubes if they're associated with cows and
horses and things like that,'' he said. ``So they leave to others
their fright of being thought of as unsophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyandotte County hasn't let fear of rubophobia stop it from
using cows to tout its attractions. Everywhere _ on billboards,
golf balls, license plates and coffee cups _ are spotted cows
sporting sunglasses, touting the area as ``Not Your Ordinary
Cowtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schenkein, president and chief executive officer of the
Kansas City Kansas Area Chamber of Commerce, said he's not worried
about being tagged with a cow-town image because of the way the
campaign is set up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cow is the messenger, not the message,'' Schenkein said.
``We're proud to use a cow to bring the good news of what we are.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas City does end up roping its own cow exhibit, it would
have Zurich to thank _ not Chicago. It was Zurich where 800-plus
Brown Swiss cows were first rounded up and exhibited in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A businessman saw the exhibit and brought the idea home to
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in that city has been moooved by the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune's art critic, Alan G. Artner, wrote a piece
earlier this year titled: ``Here's the Beef: `Cows on Parade' Draws
Too Fine a Line Between Advertising and Art.''
</P>
<P>
   The critique began: ``Most everything I've heard and read about
`Cows on Parade,' the public art project that has taken over
Chicago in the last week, has been bull.''
</P>
<P>
   And Carol Becker, dean of the faculty at the School of the Art
Institute of Chicago, finds the exhibit sophomoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a big coloring book, you know, like
fill-in-the-blank cow,'' Becker said. ``It's not that interesting
of a project for artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mike Eggly, an investment banker who moved to
Chicago from New York just as the exhibit was beginning last
summer. Recently, in his own neighborhood, he saw a woman in a cow
outfit videotaping the cows. Eggly was astounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand the attraction of the cow exhibit,''
Eggly said. ``I'm not anti-Chicago _ I'm anti cows.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are many in Kansas City who think a stampede of
artistically painted and decorated cows would be a big boost for
the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows spunk and confidence,'' said Wilson of the
Nelson-Atkins. ``We could use both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
