<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-Holes-Bullets-KAN &LR;      10-30 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Holes-Bullets-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING THE LEGEND OF UNION STATION MASSACRE'S `BULLET HOLES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day during Union Station's restoration, a group of
preservation advisers toured the station with hardhats on.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jane Fifield Flynn split off from the group,
scurried out the front doors and stood facing one block of the
facade's granite wainscoting.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, a noted Jackson County historian, rubbed a hand gently
over the smooth, gray-colored finish, back and forth, searching.
Finally, she felt an indentation, a hole. She ran a finger around
it. Then she walked around the corner of the protruding wall and
fingered another hole.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she thought, they were still there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' were the long-accepted artifacts of one of the city's
most shocking crimes _ the bullet holes from the Union Station
Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn had first touched them as a child. She heard about them
from her parents and passed on the tale to subsequent generations.
Most everyone who spent childhood or adulthood in Kansas City has
heard about the famous holes and perhaps even poked a finger in
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely part of the folklore of Kansas City,'' said
William Worley, director of the Kansas City Regional History
Institute at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But are they really bullet holes?
</P>
<P>
   Are they in fact remnants of that bloody morning of June 17,
1933, when five men _ four of them law-enforcement officers _ were
gunned down in broad daylight in front of the station?
</P>
<P>
   As with most everything associated with the massacre, the truth
may come as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Shootout
</P>
<P>
   On that infamous Saturday morning in 1933, seven lawmen escorted
gangster and Leavenworth escapee Frank Nash to a Chevrolet parked
in Union Station's front driveway. Nash had arrived on a train
after being caught in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   As the lawmen were getting in the car, three gunmen appeared
from nearby parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, bullets whizzed in and out of the Chevrolet,
shredding Nash's head inside the car, piercing one federal agent's
head outside the car, riddling a small-town police chief in the
back seat and dropping two Kansas City detectives next to the car.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the fusillade, another federal agent outside the
Chevrolet sprang to his feet and dashed for the station's east
front doors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the gunmen turned and sprayed machine-gun fire in his
direction. As the agent ducked through the doors, bullets bounced
off the front of the building _ something the federal government's
investigative file later reported.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting stopped, the legend of the holes began.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were there at the time said they saw holes in the
granite,'' said Robert Unger, an authority on the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The story soon spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were children and raised by their fathers to put
their finger in the holes have raised their children to put their
finger in the holes,'' said Unger, a professor at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of such memories was one written to The Kansas City Star
earlier this year: ``My grandfather would take me down to the
station on Saturday afternoons to watch the trains come in. He
would always take me to the outside wall...`There's the bullet
holes' as he ran his hand down the front of each one. Sure enough,
there were holes in the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, as Union Station reopens next month, the Gray Line bus
service intends to start a guided tour of Kansas City's gangster
past _ with the bullet holes as a highlight.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Testing holes
</P>
<P>
   This year, at the request of The Star, the Kansas City Police
Department's crime laboratory tested the holes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Newhouse, a senior criminalist, stood on a wood pallet
against Union Station's granite facade, holding a white cotton
swab. The swab contained a nitric acid solution, which can extract
lead off any surface it touches.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a gunshot's impact would have left some lead
residue in the holes that years of rainwater could not remove, said
Gary Howell, the crime lab's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was there, we would find it,'' Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   So Newhouse dabbed his swab into the first hole, about the size
of a quarter, tapering inward about half an inch, on a south-facing
wall. Then Newhouse dabbed a second swab on the second hole, about
the size of a marble, on a wall facing east.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Newhouse stood at a black lab table with sodium
rhodizonic acid. If the station swabs contained any lead, the acid
would turn their cotton tips a bright red. He dripped droplets on
the swabs. The cotton didn't change color. Negative _ no lead
traces.
</P>
<P>
   If the lead test were the one and only uncertainty with the
holes, the bullet myth might endure as just another mystery of the
massacre. But it's not. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   - The massacre criminals used machine guns that fired bullets in
rapid succession, yet the holes on Union Station's facade are
single indentations, not part of a string or circle of marks
expected from such gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   - Those two holes aren't the only ones on the station's
exterior. Two more holes the size of half-dollars are on the west
wing. This confirms that something else poked holes in the facade,
although no one knows what it was.
</P>
<P>
   - The east hole is around a corner from where the massacre
gunmen stood. This means it could only be caused by a ricochet,
which ballistics experts doubt.
</P>
<P>
   - As for the south hole, its half-inch depth is more consistent
with a bullet ripping into pine than granite.
</P>
<P>
   To prove this last point, John Cayton, a longtime ballistics
expert with the crime lab, conducted one more test. He obtained a
slab of the same granite on Union Station, a Barre Vermont gray. He
propped the slab against a fence on his farm and shot at it with
.45-caliber, copper-jacketed bullets from a carbine similar to what
the massacre guns were thought to be.
</P>
<P>
   The bullets bounced off, revealing small scuffs, no
indentations.
</P>
<P>
   Cayton maintains a massacre bullet ``wouldn't cause the big chip
that's there'' on Union Station's granite.
</P>
<P>
   Still, purveyors of Kansas City folklore aren't ready to let the
myth die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn all the revisionists who ruin good stories,'' said Walt
Bodine, KCUR-FM talk-show host and dean of Kansas City
broadcasters. ``I want them to be bullet holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Added UMKC's Worley: ``It doesn't matter what the tests show.
People are going to believe what they want to believe. That's the
nature of myth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
