A3247 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-SANDPIPER-SHARES-LADN     10-30 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDPIPER-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER NEWS TRIPLES DIGITAL'S STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
 
 
Merger news triples Digital's stock 
 
 
By Jason Z. Cohen 
 
 
THOUSAND OAKS _ The inadvertent effect of a well-timed merger
announcement has propelled Digital Island's stock _ and the
excitement level around a Thousand Oaks Internet startup _ to
record levels.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They couldn't have timed it better if they had tried to, but
Sandpiper Networks officials said their company's merger with the
San Francisco-based Digital Island wasn't timed to coincide with
Friday's initial public offering of its competitor, Akamai
Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's reaction to Sandpiper's announcement it will merge
with publicly traded Digital Island looks like what you'd expect
from a stock making its public debut. Digital Island's stock has
risen from $23 on the Friday before the merger announcement to
Friday's close of $67.50. At one point Friday, shares hit $75.125.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that a merger originally priced at $630 million
now is worth $1.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz surrounding Akamai's IPO is being credited with driving
the climb in Digital Island's stock as well. Akamai shares more
than quintupled in the fourth-hottest initial public offering ever.
</P>
<P>
   James Linnehan, stock analyst for Thomas Weisel Partners, said
the Sandpiper-Digital Island merger grew out of discussions between
the two companies over partnering their technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm for Akamai combined with the timing of the deal
_ that's what has been propelling Digital Island,'' Linnehan said.
``It's purely a serendipitous result.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Scott Yara, Sandpiper's vice president of marketing, said
of Digital Island's growing share price: ``That certainly was not
the intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Linnehan said he believes there is more punch left in Digital
Island's stock, even though it has risen to nearly three times its
prior value in the week following the merger announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has rewarded us in the short term for the
transaction. This is a marathon, not a sprint,'' Yara said. ``It
has been a very fun week _ it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper employees stand to benefit richly from the merger,
which still must receive regulatory and shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   The company has an employee stock ownership plan, the specifics
of which are not being made public while the merger is pending,
Yara said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the merger agreement, each share of Sandpiper stock will
be replaced with 1.07 shares of Digital Island stock, to a total of
27.4 million shares. At last week's price, that would have been
$630.2 million. At Friday's close, that values Sandpiper's total
shares at $1.85 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sandpiper's roughly 25.6 million shares are closely held by
management and employees, but Yara said the company has received
some $28 million in financing from venture capital firms, who have
some ownership stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
