A3249 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FUNERALHOMEINDUSTRY-K     10-30 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER ISSUES FACE FUNERAL HOME DIRECTORS AT KC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
 HOME INDUSTRY-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Cemetery operators and the others may have a
different point of view when the issue comes to a head next year.
</P>
<P>
   As the rule stands, only funeral homes must disclose their price
lists.
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies in precisely what is listed and how that
information is presented to consumers to ensure that the list is
useful for comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for embalming, cremation, hearse rental and the like are
clear-cut and generally not in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlson said consumer confusion and outrage abounds over the
rule's allowance for a ``nondeclinable basic service fee'' intended
to cover a funeral home's utilities, insurance and other costs of
doing business that are not itemized.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, she said, some homes list a low basic service fee
and pad other items on the general price list to make up the
difference. Others pad their overhead charge and discount itemized
services.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson calls it ``magical math'' and said her group's review of
price lists nationwide discloses ``a clear pattern of abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of those who drafted the Funeral Rule was the
nondeclinable fee would be modest,'' she said. ``Anything that is
nondeclinable takes away consumer choice.''
</P>
<P>
   She urges that the basic fee be eliminated and that those
charges be spread across the cost of each itemized product or
service.
</P>
<P>
   The industry will resist, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the present system is the best system for
consumers,'' he said, because it promotes accurate prices for
itemized goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The Funeral and Memorial Society of Greater Kansas City surveys
funeral homes in the metropolitan area every few years.
</P>
<P>
   Its latest findings, released last summer, found the area's 60
funeral homes charged a mandatory basic fee that ranged from $690
to $2,700.
</P>
<P>
   Such
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
