r a BC-Canadian-Mounties-KAN     10-30 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canadian-Mounties-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Canadian Mounties to perform at American Royal event  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED FLETCHER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Famous for their red coats, wide-brimmed hats and black mounts,
the Royal Canadian Mounted Police will bring their precision
routine to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Mounties will perform their 25-minute ``Musical Ride''
during the intermission of the American Royal Rodeo starting today
through Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really excited about the Mounties coming,'' said
American Royal spokeswoman Colleen Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Mounties have not been here for 20 years, this could
be a once-in-a-lifetime experience for some people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 125 years, the Mounties' performance has entertained
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever we go people enjoy it,'' said Inspector J.J.
Gaudet.``They see how difficult it is to have 32 horses moving in
unison.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaudet, a 29-year veteran with the Canadian law enforcement
agency, is the team leader.
</P>
<P>
   In one portion of the show, four lines of horses and riders
approach the center at right angles.
</P>
<P>
   As the four horses pass through the center, they come within
inches of a horse moving from right to left in front of them. The
maneuver called ``thread the needle'' is the hardest to pull off
cleanly, riders said. The horses must trust their riders and resist
their instincts to avoid the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Other maneuvers include tight formations often seen by marching
bands, but seldom, if ever, seen on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   All of the riders must have three years of service in the law
enforcement agency before they are eligible to apply to be a member
of the Musical Ride, Gaudet said. Those selected take a five-week
basic riding course.
</P>
<P>
   The best of those riders will train for seven months before
beginning a three-year stint as a member of the Musical Ride,
Gaudet said. The riders and horses will then work three to four
hours a day for 16 weeks to learn the routine set to music.
</P>
<P>
   The horses are specifically bred for duty. The youngest horse
performing is 6 years old, and the oldest are 19 years old, Gaudet
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stables will be open to visitors for two hours before and
after each performance. The Royal Canadian Mounted Police will
perform during rodeo performances today through Nov. 6, except for
matinees Monday and Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
