<SLUG> BC-MUTUAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUND OWNERSHIP IS ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
 FUNDS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Odd lots from a bulging column portfolio: Workers of the world
unite...in your quest for financial security! You have nothing to
lose but your worries about whether Social Security will be there
when you retire!
</P>
<P>
   The Investment Company Institute estimates that 48.4 million
U.S. households, or almost half, own mutual funds this year. That's
up almost 10 percent from last year, and more than 950 percent
since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is that most of the growth, the Institute
says, occurred in households with under $50,000 of income in which
the person most influencing the financial decisions is under 55.
Nearly 60 percent of the households owning mutual funds have
incomes between $25,000 and $74,999.
</P>
<P>
   The number of individual investors owning mutual funds,
meanwhile, hit nearly 83 million this year, which is a 7 percent
increase over 1998. Among the types of funds owned, 31 percent of
all households own stock funds, 24 own bond or hybrid funds, and 21
percent own money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 only 4.6 million households, or just under 6 percent,
owned funds.  &LR; brkstr  &LR; tx:The American Medical Association can be
excused if it's feeling double-crossed by the administration about
now. After the AMA backed the proposed Patients Bill of Rights
legislation, which would expose the health-care system to more
lawsuits, the White House has asked Congress for laws that would
steer Medicare patients to discount doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't quite the way the request is phrased, but what the
initiative amounts to is the first big push to transform all of
Medicare into a preferred-provider system. The proposal calls for
Medicare to set up a system under which those included on the
preferred list agree to charge lower rates for procedures and
services.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says the health-care providers could make up
the difference on volume by treating more patients. All of which
sounds like what irks physicians most about private-sector plans.
The deal is they work harder and longer for less money, so those
who pay the bills can enhance their bottom lines.  &LR; brkstr  &LR; tx:If
the federal government can pay down the publicly held portion of
the national debt, everything will be hunky-dory, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well...maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   A little-publicized wrinkle of less marketable debt is the
challenge it presents for the Treasury Department. The market for
Treasury securities is one of the most important debt markets in
the financial world. As such, it is critical to ensure that it
remains as liquid as possible, which means investors are assured
that they can buy and sell whenever the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   If the publicly held debt component shrinks to under $1 trillion
over the next decade, as anticipated, a Congressional Budget Office
report predicts Treasury will be under greater pressure to
concentrate debt in fewer issues.
</P>
<P>
   One of the expected benefits of reducing the national debt is
lower interest payments. If, however, Treasury cannot assure deep
and liquid markets, investors may demand a higher interest rate to
compensate for less liquid Treasury markets. That would offset much
of the expected interest savings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
