<SLUG> BC-UNION-EMBEZZLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR EX-UNION OFFICIALS CHARGED WITH EMBEZZLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ Federal authorities unveiled embezzlement charges
against former top officers of four different Southern California
unions Friday, including a Canyon Country man accused of
misappropriating over $14,000 in funds from the United Food and
Commercial Workers Union.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney has charged the officials with converting over
$37,000 in union money for personal use in four unrelated cases.
</P>
<P>
   Among those charged was David Arnold Coupe, 37, of Canyon
Country, a former financial secretary of UFCW Local 47C in
Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Coupe and two other former union officials made their initial
appearance on the charges Tuesday; a judge issued an arrest warrant
for the fourth, Covina resident Kenny Lambey, who failed to respond
to a summons.
</P>
<P>
   Embezzlement usually occurs at smaller unions with disinterested
members, said Jeffrey Gitomer, district director of the U.S.
Department of Labor's Office of Labor Management Standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``An apathetic membership leads to this kind of thing,'' Gitomer
said. ``That's why we encourage members to take an active part in
their unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Other former officials facing embezzlement charges include:
</P>
<P>
   Brian V. Carter, 41, former secretary-treasurer of the Paper,
Allied-Industrial, Chemical and Energy Workers Union Local 307 in
Bell, accused of embezzling $5,968.
</P>
<P>
   Herminio Louis Garcia Sr., 48, former president of the Utility
Workers Union Local 522 in Moreno Valley, accused of embezzling
$7,768.
</P>
<P>
   Lambey, 42, former secretary-treasurer of the United Plant Guard
Workers Union Local 155 in Corona, accused of embezzling $9,189.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing for Carter, Coupe and Garcia is scheduled
for Nov. 15. Each faces up to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
