<HEADER>
A3270 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v BC-ZACARIAS-FALLOUT-LADN     10-30 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZACARIAS-FALLOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZACARIAS SUPPORTERS ADMIT DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ One day after Superintendent Ruben Zacarias lost an
angry showdown with the Los Angeles school board, some of his most
vocal supporters conceded defeat Friday but pledged to fight for a
say in picking his successor.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although furious at the school board majority that voted
Thursday to buy out Zacarias' contract, several key members of the
city's Latino community acknowledged they could now do little to
keep him in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's never been about salvaging Ruben's job,'' said
Theresa Fay-Bustillos, vice president of legal affairs for the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unfortunately become the poster child for a process that
ignored open decision making and community input. And there's got
to be some kind of community input.''
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF and other groups withheld the right to take legal action
against the board over its handling of Zacarias' ouster. And they
continued calling Friday for the board to rescind its selection of
real estate lawyer Howard Miller as the district's new chief
operating officer, whose appointment touched off the board's
dispute with Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   But many acknowledged the fight to protect Zacarias was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, our goal was to keep Zacarias in his position, and
at this point, obviously that's not going to happen,'' said Gerardo
Guzman, president of the San Fernando Valley chapter of the Mexican
American Political Association. ``Now, the goal is to get someone
in there who has what it takes to give us quality education. And
Mr. Miller doesn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   California Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles,
said the city needed to put the divisive fight over Zacarias behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on,'' he said. ``We need to get behind an
interim superintendent and develop a public process whereby we
select a permanent superintendent who understands the diverse needs
of an urban school district.''
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias, who spent the day in his office, referred all calls to
his attorney, Joseph Coyne, who was out of town. Both said on
Thursday night after the board vote that they would challenge
Miller's appointment next week in court. No action had been filed
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Julie Korenstein, who backed Zacarias, said
the board should welcome community input when searching for his
permanent replacement. But she doubted parents or community groups
would have a hand in picking an interim superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Cortines, former head of Pasadena and New York City
schools, was the leading candidate. He is scheduled to be
interviewed for Tuesday, and Korenstein said there might not be any
room for community suggestions on alternate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been room up to now. I don't know that that will
change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Valerie Fields, who voted to buy out Zacarias'
contract, said she welcomed community suggestions on who should
become the interim superintendent. But any nominations must be made
immediately. The board hopes to pick an interim schools chief soon,
possibly as early as Tuesday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have anyone they want to put forward, they should do
that rapidly,'' Fields said. ``I don't want anyone from inside. We
need to have someone from outside to effect the changes we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Angry Zacarias supporters also talked again of breaking up the
nation's second-largest school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gathering information and looking at maps and data so we
can talk to people intelligently about the need to break up the
district and determine how it should be broken up,'' said Allan
Clayton, regional chairman of the Los Angeles City/County Latino
Redistricting Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to create districts that are so small as to
render them without any clout in Sacramento or Washington, D.C.,
where you get the majority of your funding. But we don't want them
so large like the current district with the problems they have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Clayton has vocally opposed any breakup. In fact,
he helped the school board divide up the constituency divisions
during the last redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an opponent of this up until a month ago. Things have
changed. There is more discussion of this issue in the Latino
community than I have ever seen before,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   THE BREAKUP ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Several state legislators, even those not sold on the idea of
splitting the district, said the idea was worth exploring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I myself am not convinced that breakup is the way to go,''
said Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, ``although from my
investigations into L.A. Unified, I'm convinced it really needs
dramatic reform, and maybe in the end, breakup would be the only
way.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for state Senator Richard Polanco said breakup was
gaining momentum following the board's vote on Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fundamental thing,'' said Bill Mabie. ``If parents
don't believe that they're being respected by the board, they say,
OK, we're going to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
