<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3276 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     10-30 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE START, KINGS KNOW IT'S A LONG ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There was a time _ like a month ago _ when many
thought the Los Angeles Kings would be battling the Chicago
Blackhawks for the final playoff spot rather than tied with San
Jose atop the NHL's Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But new coach Andy Murray said he knows how quickly things can
change. After opening last year 2-1-1, the Kings lost goalies
Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr to injuries within seven minutes of
each other. It was only the fourth game of the season, but they won
just two of the next 16 and never were heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have put ourselves in a better position to be
successful,'' Murray said. ``But you can never sit back when things
go well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we play the 'Hawks I'll tell the coaches, `This is the
most important game of the year' because it is. And they'll say,
`Didn't you say that about the last game?' They all are so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings have won three straight heading into
tonight's game against the Blackhawks (1-4-4), they are not without
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Steve McKenna and Marko Tuomainen, who
both have missed playing time with eye injuries, the Kings have
been very healthy. But captain Rob Blake, who has missed big chucks
of seasons to injuries during in his career, logged a whopping 29
minutes on defense in Thursday's 5-3 victory over the Pittsburgh
Penguins. His busy nights include a prominent role on the power
play, which has gone 0 for 9 in the last two games to drop behind
the Sharks as the league's No.1 unit.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's game, the Kings were 13 for 50 with the man
advantage (22 percent). Last season, the Mighty Ducks led the
league with the same conversion rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not possible to continue at the pace we were going,''
Murray said. ``We have to work on a few things, but overall the
power play has gone well.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray also is trying to remain calm over a rough stretch by
young defenseman Aki Berg, whose mistakes have led to goals the
past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Berg made a poor decision to pass up ice late in Sunday's game
against San Jose. It became worse when he fanned on the puck and
turned it over to the Sharks, who scored.
</P>
<P>
   Against Washington, a puck hopped over his stick and right to
Peter Bondra, who scored the game's first goal.
</P>
<P>
   And in the first minute of Thursday's game, Berg was manhandled
by Penguins star Jaromir Jagr, who muscled past the Kings'
strongest defenseman for a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows what a great player Jagr is,'' Murray said.
``But Aki has to make that play. This is not meant to be a
criticism, but this is the NHL and he has to be able to make those
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg's defensemate Sean O'Donnell, who scored a rare goal
Thursday, said the 22-year-old Fin is improving. Berg is back after
a year playing in his native country and is still making
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you have to remember that he is still
young,'' O'Donnell said. ``He has tremendous talent, but sometimes
he falters.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray disagrees. ``We cannot allow ourselves excuses,'' he
said. ``When you allow that to creep into your game, it will come
back to haunt you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
