<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     10-30 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY FACES QUITE A DODGER MESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's blue-splattered edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to have someone who understands Dodgers blue blood
tradition, new CEO Bob Daly, in charge of the franchise. But let's
not fool ourselves into thinking this is all it will take to get
the franchise into the black, financially and in the National
League standings.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's plate will be full once he settles into his office.
</P>
<P>
   He has a general manager and a manager who do not agree very
often. G.M. Kevin Malone was hired by the departed (but possibly
returning) Bob Graziano. Davey Johnson was hired by the departing
Fox hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The manager isn't fond of his current roster, but it's
impossible to force change when it involves players with little
value and too many years left on their contracts (Devon White, Eric
Young, Raul Mondesi).
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure if I agree with all of Johnson's assessments on his
roster, either. He tried to force-feed a ill-fitting leadership
role on Gary Sheffield, has something against Eric Karros, and had
his own bungling role in the Raul Mondesi saga.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to get the organization moving forward together
by giving Johnson the opportunity to entertain offers from other
clubs and then moving in another direction, toward former Dodgers
like Kevin Kennedy or Davey Lopes. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to know Tommy Lasorda and Daly are good friends. But
name me someone who isn't Lasorda's friend? Here's hoping Lasorda's
influence is limited to that of an long-range adviser, and that
Daly tunes him out when he starts talking about megalomaniac Bobby
Valentine. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would be very smart to pursue former pitching coach
Dave Wallace, who may be looking to move on after two years with
the Mets. Wallace, originally hired by the Mets as a special
assistant, became pitching at mid-season and did not get along with
Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the only person I know of who does get along with
Valentine is Lasorda. ...
</P>
<P>
   Would now be a good time to remind everyone that the Angels once
employed three-time World Series champ Joe Torre as an announcer?
...
</P>
<P>
   Torre's biggest accomplishment as Yankees manager may be the way
he ended the annual clubhouse circus that George Steinbrenner
operated. ...
</P>
<P>
   Is it me, or has the World Series lost some of its sheen since
the expansion of the playoffs? The last three World Series were
dogs, making me think the series has become the equivalent of the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL playoffs routinely are crisp until the Super Bowl, when
the strength of one team becomes apparent or the other finds itself
just pleased to be there. ...
</P>
<P>
   Through seven weeks of the season, 45 different quarterbacks
have started NFL games, more proof that the second-most important
position in football is backup quarterback. ...
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL's quarterback woes seem bad now, after five
quarterbacks were drafted in the first round, think what it will be
like next year.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of NFL-caliber college quarterbacks for the '00 draft
is considered thin. Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton is a fave and
ex-Los Al star Kevin Feterik of BYU has big numbers, but both fall
short physically: Hamilton is 5-10, and Feterik reed-thin at 6-0
and 190.
</P>
<P>
   The top college quarterbacks who meet the NFL's usual physical
standards are Tennessee's Tee Martin and three fellows who have
playing at lower-rung Division I-A schools, Marshall's Chad
Pennington, Louisiana Tech's Tim Rattay and Louisville's Chris
Redman. Florida State's Chris Weinke is considered slow. If there's
a sleeper out there, it's former St. John Bosco star Todd Husak of
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The best college quarterbacks, according to one scout, are all
underclassmen Purdue junior Drew Brees, USC's injured Carson
Palmer, Texas sophomore Major Applewhite, and Virginia Tech
redshirt freshman Michael Vick, who is the rarest of rares, a
strong-armed left-hander. ...
</P>
<P>
   The question is when, not if, Jeff George will break hearts in
Minnesota, as he has in Indianapolis, Atlanta and Oakland. ...
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the demise of UCLA is how fortunate they were to claim
their lone Pac-10 win, against an injured Oregon team that saw the
game end on the UCLA one-yard line. ...
</P>
<P>
   Things I'd like to see: Penn State and Florida State lose twice,
all one-loss teams lose one more game, and the BCS try to sell
Marshall-Virginia Tech as the national title game.
</P>
<P>
   Or, even better, deny those two unbeatens the title game, and
try to pass off a game between two one-loss teams as the
championship. ...
</P>
<P>
   The new BCS ranking system has neutered the computer ratings by
increasing the number of computers involved and throwing out the
lowest possible score. But this was a predictable move after the
Sagarin ratings had Kansas State No.1 after its Big XII title game
loss. ...
</P>
<P>
   Based on what I've seen of the Lakers during the preseason, they
need the Triangle Defense more than the Triangle Offense. This is
one of those questions no one thought to ask when hiring Phil
Jackson. His offense is swell, but can he make Shaquille O'Neal and
Glen Rice better defenders? ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: Knicks offer Latrell Sprewell a five-year, $61.9
million contract. Reaction: Who do I have to choke to get that kind
of contract? ...
</P>
<P>
   I say we get O.J. Simpson and Jim Gray together and see what
develops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
