<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S FOSTER FROZEN SO FAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA tailback DeShaun Foster always runs best when
it counts most. Two Decembers ago, he rushed for 377 yards and six
touchdowns in the Southern Section Div. V title game. Last
November, he scored four touchdowns in UCLA's victory over USC.
</P>
<P>
   But for Foster to produce another scintillating finish _ and for
UCLA to salvage a bowl bid from this arduous season _ he must
overcome a nagging ankle injury and the accompanying frustration.
As sophomore seasons go, this has been one to rest, ice and
elevate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like hell,'' Foster said. ``I can't play. We're not
winning. I can't even be there at road games to motivate Keith
(Brown) and Jermaine (Lewis). I haven't felt like I'm part of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   That should end tonight when Foster returns after a two-game
absence. He won't play more than 10 or 15 snaps, and he won't be in
top form. But his presence alone should energize a sagging running
game that totaled 166 yards against Cal and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks pretty good,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``I
don't know if he'll be his old self, but this is the best I've seen
him since the injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster set a UCLA freshman record with 673 yards last year
despite averaging just 11.5 carries per game. He knew flashy stats
weren't possible this year, not with UCLA's three-man tailback
rotation. But everywhere he turned, friends and fans talked of a
sensational season to come. He'd lead the league in rushing. He'd
break the school record. He'd lead the Bruins to their
third-consecutive conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's been a dud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to be satisfied with whatever happened, but I
didn't want to let other people down,'' he said. ``That's made it
harder to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's best game was his undoing. He rushed for 100 yards and
scored two touchdowns Sept. 25 at Stanford and didn't think much of
the mild sprain he suffered in the first half. But the next
morning, he woke up and saw a softball where his right ankle was
supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in the training room, receiver Danny Farmer, who
had suffered the same injury a month earlier, took one look and
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be able to run,'' Farmer cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   Foster tried to play at Arizona State, but the ankle was weak
and he gave up after two plays. A week later, he aggravated the
ankle on his only carry of the Oregon game. He didn't play against
Cal or Oregon State, UCLA's worst performances in years.
</P>
<P>
   To relieve frustration, Foster turned to his NCAA 2000
PlayStation. He always chose UCLA, and he'd run plays for his
computerized image time and again. It was the only place he knew
he'd never get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke my hand and missed the last six games of my freshman
season (in high school), but that was nothing like this,'' he said.
``It's been one of the hardest things I've been through in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not over yet. He has three games to ease the pain _ and
help UCLA save its season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
