<HEADLINE>
FOR HACKETT, CAL BRINGS BACK FOND MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY _ USC coach Paul Hackett hasn't been to Cal's Memorial
Stadium in 20 years, but there are plenty of fond memories for the
school he almost attended.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett, whose father was a professor at Cal, grew up in nearby
Orinda and attended his first college football game at Memorial
Stadium in 1963 when he was a sophomore at Miramonte High.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really my beginning of college football,'' Hackett
said. ``I worked as an usher. People would stand outside the
coaches room and yell `We want Willsey. We want Willsey.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to then-Cal coach Ray Willsey, whom Hackett
almost decided to play for when he graduated from Miramonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was there or (UC) Davis,'' Hackett said. ``If I went there,
I had to walk on and would never get to play. But at Davis, they
told me I would be a star.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett eventually became an assistant coach at Cal from
1972-75, but says ``I haven't been in that stadium in a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett last coached a game in Berkeley in 1979, when he was an
assistant at USC. The Trojans won 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really remember us going up there,'' Hackett said.
``But I imagine it will be noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down review: Cornerback Kris Richard said that Sunday
film sessions have become an eye-opening experience for the Trojans
recently as they get a chance to see how they blew two 21-point
leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch the film and see why we make mistakes and why they
happen,'' Richard said. ``And you're in a daze watching it. Your
mouth is just open because you don't understand how we could make
these mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mailo out: Offensive guard Faasea Mailo, who badly bruised his
left shin against Stanford, did not make the trip. Donta Kendrick
will start at left guard again, now that he has recovered from a
sprained ankle, with Trevor Roberts the backup.
</P>
<P>
   Boller update: Cal quarterback Kyle Boller of Hart High has
averaged only 124 yards passing per game with eight interceptions
and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Cal coach Tom Holmoe is being patient with the true
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kyle wants to do it now,'' Holmoe said. ``But he doesn't get
down. Still, he is very hard on himself. He would say he is the
reason we aren't tearing it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want him to understand that the things he does are
very, very good. We're going to win with him, there is no doubt
about it in my mind. He's got a ton of hope and he's got a
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week: In games decided by seven points or less, the
Trojans are 1-6 under Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Going for the sweep: Cal may be 3-4, but the Bears are going for
their second sweep of the Los Angeles schools since 1958. The last
time Cal defeated USC and UCLA in the same season was 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at this game as a dogfight,'' Holmoe said. ``This is a
USC team that's ticked off and wanting to get back into the win
column.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
