<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC NEEDS ONE THING: A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY _ With a sigh more than a bang, USC wrapped up practice
this week and embarked for the Bay Area. There's no motivational
speech, T-shirts or gimmicks that could shake the Trojans out of
their current malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing will cure USC from the anguish associated with
losing 21-point leads on back-to-back weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a lingering plague around here until we win,'' free
safety David Gibson said. ``Practice went as well as it could have
gone. But it won't be great around here until we win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never lost three games in a row. I've kind of forgotten
what a win feels like.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's game against California (3-4, 2-2) might be the perfect
answer to the Trojans' ailments. The Golden Bears are the model of
inconsistency that has characterized the Pacific-10 Conference.
They have the conference's top-rated defense, but also feature the
worst-ranked offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe we have the superior team and more talent,''
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one important intangible that makes this game
another stressful outing for the Trojans (3-4, 1-3): They had to
get on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much been a death knell as far as victory is
concerned this season. USC has developed a reputation as road kill,
with a 1-3 record away from the Coliseum and 3-7 on the road
overall the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're in town, it's a big event,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``This is a big hurdle for us. Struggling on the road is the
theme this year. We need to get a win big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Cal is so inconsistent, and features true freshmen at
quarterback (Kyle Boller) and tailback (Joe Igber), Hackett
believes USC needs to get off to a quick start to shatter the
Bears' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, that shouldn't be a problem. USC led Notre Dame 24-3 and
Stanford 21-0 before losing both games the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the second half that the Trojans have deteriorated.
Hackett joked early in the week that his halftime speeches must be
awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything at halftime this week,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the players believe the problem is more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's trying to do everybody else's job,'' linebacker
Markus Steele said. ``You just forget about where you're at.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team, it's mental,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno added.
``There's nothing wrong physically. The only thing preventing us
from being in the right spots on plays is mental mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   USC can ill afford any more miscues. The Trojans have to win
four of their final five games just to become bowl eligible. How
they fare against Cal could determine the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over the Golden Bears revives confidence heading into
November, when three of the four games are at the Coliseum. A loss
could cause the Trojans to collapse the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentum, it's tough to get that back,'' Hackett said. ``No
one's interested in how close you've come (to winning). Now we have
to focus on one thing _ beating Cal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
