<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS' ODOM STARTS WITH PROMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You hear it all the time. He's going to be the
next Larry Bird. So and so's the next Kareem. That guy's the next
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But when you hear what a Los Angeles Clippers player has to say
about Lamar Odom, the team's first-round pick and fourth overall in
the June draft, it's hard not to do a double-take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already dubbed him Magic Johnson with more athletic
ability,'' says Eric Murdock, a veteran of eight NBA seasons.
``He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson with more athletic ability?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' says teammate Maurice Taylor. ``I love him. I
keep him around me 24 (hours), 7 (days a week). He's a special kind
of player.''
</P>
<P>
   Living up to that comparison is tricky, especially considering
the 6-foot-10 Odom's past.
</P>
<P>
   He played just one year of college basketball after first
deciding to go to Nevada Las Vegas then opting for Rhode Island.
Academic problems sidelined him for one year before he finally
played for the Rams last season. Odom average 17 points and nine
rebounds in leading Rhode Island to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After declaring for the NBA Draft, Odom decided to return to
school. But because he had already signed with an agent, he was
forced to go pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard comparison to live up to,'' says Odom, who has
attempted to integrate the court awareness of Johnson and Bird into
his game. ``If that's what people see, then I'm flattered. I don't
consciously go out and try to play like him, but it's really an
honor to be even mentioned with Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he certainly jumps higher and jets around the court
quicker than the ex-Lakers great.
</P>
<P>
   Dribbling? Forget it. Magic was functional, textbook; Odom has
those next-millennium, schoolyard handles.
</P>
<P>
   Defense? Odom, while still guilty of system mistakes, has the
length, quickness and desire to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has to learn to play defense and offense in our
system,'' says coach Chris Ford, who's paid to keep us grounded.
``Rookies don't just come into this league and take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Odom's shooting needs work, but Johnson, who lacked
Odom's ability to square and shoot off the dribble, wasn't a
sharp-shooter when he arrived in L.A. 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a feel for the game you don't see very often,'' Lakers
vice president Jerry West said. ``He could be the steal of the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson, Odom seeks and delivers the spectacular pass, but
an ability to match this boyhood idol for wisdom in his play-making
decisions and the knack for overpowering adversity will determine
if he can carry the weight of yet another ``next Magic''
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Magic came in,'' said Derek Anderson, another new
Clipper, ``the Lakers already had Kareem, Jamal Wilkes, Norm Nixon
... ''
</P>
<P>
   What Anderson was emphasizing is the modest caliber of teammates
Odom has joined. While Anderson, Taylor and center Michael
Olowokandi are good prospects, they don't provide the caliber of
comfort zone, the margin for error, the aforementioned Lakers gave
Johnson. In return, Johnson helped give the Lakers five
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulls weren't very good when Jordan got there,'' Odom
says. ``Every team has to start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that if I don't do well I'll be criticized because
of my past. But I think I can handle that because the pressure I
put on myself is so much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   That self-imposed challenge includes clearing a path for the
next phenom whose youthful uncertainty grows a field of red flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that all the time,'' Odom says. ``You know, if I
do well, it might be easier for the next guy. It might be someone
from my own neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest assist may come in passing the torch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day,'' said former Clipper Scott Brooks, ``we're going to
be comparing guys to Lamar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
