<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHCUTT WILL POSE PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every challenge is massive for the UCLA football
team's beleaguered secondary, and this week's comes in a 5-foot-11,
180-pound package named Dennis Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona receiver might be the best player in the Pacific-10.
He's at least as good as Stanford receiver Troy Walters, who burned
the Bruins for 278 receiving yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do the same kind of thing,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo
said. ``There's no question, Northcutt's one of the best. He's
explosive, and they put him all over the field, so it's hard to
(double-cover) him.''
</P>
<P>
   Northcutt, a Dorsey High graduate, leads the conference in
receptions per game (7.13) and all-purpose yards (193), and he's
second in receiving yards (121 per game). He also averages 19 yards
per run (ie: reverse) and plays cornerback. Add his highly charged
personal situation _ this is his last game in his hometown _ and
UCLA should expect Northcutt's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the yards he's generating, and he's done a phenomenal
job,'' Wildcats coach Dick Tomey said. ``He's been the brightest
light for us. There isn't anybody helping their team more than he's
helping us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for the best: Despite their talent, the Wildcats might be
an easier matchup for UCLA's young defensive backs than Oregon
State, which played an unconventional spread offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't faced anyone that passes like Oregon State,''
Bruins cornerback Ryan Roques said. ``I don't think we'll have
those problems against another team.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble spot: Each week seems to produce another ignominious
statistic from UCLA's secondary, and today's is no different: Five
players have started at strong safety in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Stephens, Julius Williams, Roques, Eric Whitfield and
Lovell Houston (today's starter) have lined up alongside free
safety Joey Strycula, a former walk-on who leads the team in
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Punt of no return: Northcutt is averaging 19.4 yards a return
(second in the nation) and has scored one touchdown. Meanwhile, the
Bruins have the lowest punt-return average in the league, 6.6
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, UCLA's longest return (16 yards) is less than
Northcutt's average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one thing that's happened to us,'' Toledo said. ``But
we have faced a couple great punters.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: While most of his teammates played their worst
game of the season at Oregon State, outside linebacker Ryan Nece
played his best, with a team-high 10 tackles and his first sack of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous games, I wasn't playing up to my expectations or
the coaches' expectations,'' said Nece, a freshman All-American
last season. ``I was struggling. But I managed to get rid of the
distractions. Confidence was a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   So was motivation: The Bruins let true freshman Marcus Reese
compete for Nece's starting job, but Nece repelled the rookie's
challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
