<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-CAPITALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA, SELANNE LIFT DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Anaheim Mighty Ducks defenseman Ruslan Salei was back
from his 10-game exile. Former Ducks coach Ron Wilson was making
his third trip to the Pond as coach of the Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, the headliners wound up being Paul Kariya and
Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   The two Anaheim superstars combined for three goals and eight
points Friday night as the Ducks defeated the struggling Capitals
5-2 before 13,586.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Salei, who has become NHL's latest villain, was
relatively uneventful. He was cheered when he stepped on the ice
for his first shift, did not draw any penalties, nor was he
involved in any questionable plays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wilson's third visit to Orange County since being
fired by Anaheim resulted in a third loss. It was also his second
loss to the Ducks in 10 days. Anaheim defeated the Capitals 7-1 on
Oct. 19. Wilson is 2-4 against the Ducks since becoming
Washington's coach.
</P>
<P>
   For 1{ years, Wilson had the pleasure of having Kariya and
Selanne on his side, but Friday night they needed only one period
to put his team in a hole it would never climb out of.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim stars, with the able assistance of Matt Cullen and
Oleg Tverdovsky, were on the ice for three first-period goals, all
scored against Washington's top line of Peter Bondra, Adam Oates
and James Black.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya capped his night with a third-period goal giving the
Ducks' No.1 line six goals and 18 points in the two games versus
the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't playing the way we're capable, but we're getting
better,'' Kariya said. ``I myself struggled with my conditioning
the first five, six games, and it's been tough to get going. We're
far from 100 percent, but we're going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Kariya and Selanne finished with four points _ a first
since they began playing together in 1996. It was 23rd time Selanne
has recorded four or more points in a game, while Kariya has
reached that level 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' sixth win in October is a team record for the opening
month of the season and moved them within two points of the Western
Conference- and Pacific Division-leading Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya started the first-period blitz with a nifty
behind-the-back move to keep the puck in the Capitals' zone. His
effort was rewarded when he one-timed a pass by Tverdovksy past
Washington goalie Olaf Kolzig at 5:24.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of three points that Kariya recorded in the
opening 20 minutes. He picked up assists on Selanne's goal at 12:21
and Tverdovsky's at 19:26.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne extended his point-scoring streak to six games when he
took a nice pass from Cullen and leaned into a one-timer that beat
Kolzig high on the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky made it 3-0 in the final minute when he scored his
fourth goal of the year on 60-footer from the right point that went
through a maze of bodies in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks weren't nearly as dynamic in the second period. They
gave up a power-play goal to Bondra at 1:21 and then failed to
generate even one shot of their own after Sergei Gonchar was
assessed a double-minor for high sticking Steve Rucchin.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, Kariya, Rucchin and Tverdovsky worked a
beautiful three-way passing play, but Selanne missed a wide-open
net.
</P>
<P>
   After the Ducks (Fredrik Olausson at 3:25) and Caps (Steve
Konowalchuk at 7:19) traded goals in third period, Kariya picked up
his second of the night, shoving home a rebound of Cullen's shot at
8:59.
</P>
</TEXT>
