<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE PSYCHIC'S EFFORTS, RACES RUN TRUE TO FORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ When it comes to picking horses, extra sensory
perception doesn't work as well as reading a Racing Form.
</P>
<P>
   That was the conclusion resulting from a publicity stunt for
local television stations at Santa Anita Park on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunt that was essentially a promotion for today's
California Cup races, the track had a psychic match wits with a
professional handicapper. Each picked likely winners in Races 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   When it ended, Bill Downes, a handicapper and announcer employed
by Santa Anita, came out on top with three winners. Linda Salvin,
the psychic, had none.
</P>
<P>
   Because bets were placed across the board on horses chosen by
Downes and Salvin, each won some money. Downes final tally after a
$30 investment was $30.90; Salvin's was $22.40.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this proves is that coming to the races is fun, whether
you are a professional handicapper or just playing a hunch,'' said
Stuart Zanville, Santa Anita's head of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   The event was videotaped by a local public relations firm and
copies were hand-delivered to several area television stations for
inclusion in Friday evening newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to choosing, Downes employed a more traditional
method of picking horses, based upon their published past
performances. Salvin, on the other hand, took into account
vibrations, heat and colors given off by the horse's names in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just get a certain feeling,'' she said. ``It's a feeling
inside me that I can't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Downes, who was nervous after a slow start, relished his
come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I won the competition, but it was by a very slim
margin,'' he said. ``I was just using horses that I thought had a
chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting of today's Cal Cup races is the
$150,000 Distaff on the hillside turf course.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's interesting because there's 15 horses entered,
making for a 15-1 mutuel field.
</P>
<P>
   There's some pretty good horses available there, too. Among them
is Sweetcakesandshakes, the horse that gave Eddie Delahoussaye his
6,000th career victory. Also in the field are Pert Laura and Dusty
Heather. But there's no reason to count out Iza Bon Bon and rider
Joy Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 Distaff, Iza Bon Bon finished third. This year, the
6-year-old mare has earned more than $115,000, and both Scott and
trainer Lewis Cenicola are encouraged by recent works.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mare has been amazing for us,'' Cenicola said. ``She won
her first race for us and has just kept giving and giving all these
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
