<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Oct. 31:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, East Timor) _ Ending a failed 24-year
occupation that culminated in a rampage of destruction, the last
900 Indonesian soldiers left on this island territory pulled down
their red-and-white flag Saturday and began heading home. Their
officers were seen off at the airport by the people who took their
place: the U.N. representative, the Australian general who heads an
international peacekeeping force and the guerrilla chief who led a
separatist war against them. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade) _ Special Report: Slobodan Milosevic _
gray and remote, internationally isolated and politically
unpopular, indicted for war crimes, his army restive and reservists
outraged, his economy ruined, his refineries and electricity system
smashed and his sources of fuel unclear, his roads and railways
holed and his bridges collapsed _ has not only survived the loss of
Kosovo, but he has gained a second wind. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-BOSNIA-REPORT (Washington) _ Four years after the fighting
stopped in Bosnia, an international study group has concluded that
Western efforts have failed to realize the driving principle of the
Dayton accords: a single, multi-ethnic country. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CULT-LAW (Beijing) _ After a week of secret deliberations,
China's top legislative body Saturday issued a stringent new
``anti-cult'' law designed to aid the government's crackdown on the
Falun Gong spiritual movement. Press accounts suggested that the
law will be used _ apparently retroactively _ in prosecuting
organizers of the banned movement. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-CONSCRIPTION (Taverny, France) _ Europe's armies are
abandoning the draft. France now requires its 18-year-old males
only to spend a day watching movies about the armed forces in hopes
of tempting them into services; Italy and Spain are following suit,
leaving Germany as the only major NATO power with conscription. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ISOLATIONISM-DEBATE (Washington) _ Ostrichism and nativism will
always be found in American politics. But the current foreign
policy debate roiling Washington, many experts say, is about what
form of internationalism makes sense for an unchallenged
superpower. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ News analysis: Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, American officials, and even some Israelis have
begun worrying that peacemaking momentum is slowing from a gallop
to a saunter. Nonetheless, Arafat and Prime Minister Ehud Barak
will meet in Oslo with President Clinton this weekend for one more
confidence-building session between the parties. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires) _ As his administration begins
to take shape, President-elect Fernando de la Rua is preparing
Argentina for sharp cuts in public spending and revealing an open
style of governing full of trial balloons and freewheeling public
debate among his advisers. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REFORMER-TRIAL (Tehran) _ Opening of the trial of Abdullah
Nouri, an important reformer and confidante of Iran's liberal
president, Mohammed Khatami. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE (Belfast) _ The rescue mission by George Mitchell
aimed at ending the stalemate that has stalled progress in the
Northern Ireland peace accord entered its final stages Saturday
with scant hope of a breakthrough. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S.-DUES (United Nations) _ On America's legal obligation
to pay its dues. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CRUISES-MEDICAL-CARE (Undated) _ Special Report: When a medical
emergency arises on a cruise ship hundreds of miles out at sea,
passengers are on their own more than they might imagine. Even on
the largest ships those aboard must rely on infirmaries that are
better equipped for sunburn and seasickness than for heart attacks.
And they are often staffed by doctors not qualified to work in the
United States. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   RESORTS-VS-PRESERVATION (Pagosa Springs, Colo.) _ Amid millions
of acres of national forest, private deluxe resorts are blooming,
from Colorado to Maryland to Alaska, sparking fierce battles over
land preservation and the rights of the taxpayers. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   WICCA-MOVEMENT (Rehoboth, Mass.) _ Encouraged by a federal court
decision recognizing witchcraft as a legal religion, together with
a growing number of books on the subject and the ongoing cultural
concern for the environment, Wicca _ as contemporary witchcraft is
called _ has been growing in the United States and abroad. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-MUSEUM (New York) _ The director of the Brooklyn Museum
of Art and his assistants raised hundreds of thousands of dollars
from those who stood to profit most from the works of the young
British artists in the ``Sensation'' exhibition _ a practice that
other museum executives say was practically unheard of and
ethically problematic. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   ORLEANS-CASINO (New Orleans) _ The biggest ever land-based
casino in New Orleans opens to the sounds of controversy and fears
it will change the French Quarter riverfront. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-JUVENILE-TRIAL (Pontiac, Mich.) _ Two years to the day
after an 11-year-old boy fatally shot a stranger walking out of a
convenience store, opening statements were made Saturday in his
trial on a charge of first-degree murder, in a case that is drawing
attention to Michigan's tough three-year-old juvenile justice law.
By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-ENVIRONMENT (Washington) _ For the first time since the
beginning of the environmental movement three decades ago, the
critically important Senate Committee on the environment is about
to have a chairman opposed to many of the landmark laws of the era.
By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CENSUS (Washington) _ After three years of partisan
wrangling, legislative brinkmanship and legal suits, a strange new
mood has enveloped the battle over the 2000 census: peace. By
Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FRIENDS (Washington) _ Al Gore's closest friends have made
millions in lobbying fees, mostly by selling their proximity to the
vice president. But in recent months, the vice president and his
campaign have become concerned about those connections. By Don Van
Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   DECARBONING-ENERGY (Undated) _ Experts say atmospheric levels of
carbon dioxide may be double that of the pre-industrial era by the
end of the next century. But they also say the levels would be much
higher except for a trend toward lower-carbon fuels that has been
going on for more than 100 years, but has been largely unnoticed
except by a small band of energy specialists. The question now,
they say, is whether the trend can be accelerated enough to stave
off or lessen what many scientists believe is a potentially
disruptive global warming. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
