</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filming in Black and White &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hard as Hollywood tries to get it right, it often falls back on
the old cliches. The latest offering in this genre is ``Music of
the Heart,'' with Meryl Streep playing the real-life Roberta
Guaspari. Abandoned by her Navy officer husband, she moved her two
small sons and a crate of violins to New York's East Harlem and
talked her way into a job at Central Park East school. Threatened
by budget cuts, Ms. Guaspari conducted her best violin students in
a triumphal concert at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, Central Park East is one of the most acclaimed
public schools in the country, a harmonious blend of races and
classes in a rough neighborhood; even middle-class parents beg for
their children to be admitted. In the movie, it becomes a
stereotypical ghetto school with lazy tenured teachers, racial
discord and routine violence, where one stern but courageous
teacher saves the day.
</P>
<P>
   While lauding Ms. Guaspari, Deborah Meier, the founder of
Central Park East, complains that the movie turned a chance to tell
a complex story of a good school nurturing a fellow risk-taker into
a simple tale of good guys versus bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS
</P>
<P>
   Exacting Change &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as an invisible hand regulating the soda machine.
Just when you're thirstiest, the price zooms up.
</P>
<P>
   Automatically.
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea the Coca-Cola Company has begun testing _ a
vending machine that has the ability to raise prices when the
weather gets hot.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Coca-Cola has been looking at the
technology for temperature-sensitive machines ``for more than a
year,'' adding that none of the machines are on the market yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear where the first ones will appear, but chances are
excellent that it won't be Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   _ CONSTANCE L. HAYS
</P>
<P>
   An Odd Couple Fights for a Nomination
</P>
<P>
   When last seen in battle, Pat Buchanan's fabled pitchfork
brigades had successfully crossed the moat in the 1996 New
Hampshire presidential primary but were subsequently driven from
the Republican castle by the establishment forces of Bob Dole. Now
Buchanan is back under a different banner, aiming to mount up on
Ross Perot's Reform ticket with its $12.6 million in federal
subsidy. He vows a charge upon the two ``party elite'' nominees.
</P>
<P>
   If talk is any measure, New York real-estate developer Donald
Trump, the tabloids' favorite creation, may carry out his threat to
challenge Buchanan as a ``Hitler lover'' and darling of the
``wacko'' right.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever the Reform Party's presidential nomination may be
worth, Buchanan says he's finally a front runner.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRANCIS X. CLINES
</P>
<P>
   A New Protest In Tiananmen Square
</P>
<P>
   They looked like dazed tourists in tennis shoes, but the
appearance on Tiananmen Square of clusters of Falun Gong believers
was a sign that the campaign to crush the popular spiritual
movement was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Those venturing onto the square for certain arrest were just
some of the thousands _ upright citizens who believed its mystical
exercises brought good health _ who dodged the police and traveled
to Beijing, hoping to convince officials they posed no threat.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities were tightening the screws, officially
labeling the group an ``evil cult'' and preparing for show trials
of leaders. Desperate members held a clandestine press conference
and pleaded for international pressure to halt China's crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ ERIK ECKHOLM
</P>
<P>
   A Birthday Bash For a (Presumed) Candidate  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton found another way to mix business and
pleasure, using the occasion of her 52nd birthday to hold a
fundraiser in New York to finance her expected campaign for the
U.S. Senate. An array of Broadway stars, from Joel Grey to Rosie
O'Donnell, presented a night of songs, skits paying tribute to Mrs.
Clinton, and insults directed at Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is
Mrs. Clinton's presumed opponent in the contest for the Senate seat
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The night raised $1 million for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory
committee.
</P>
<P>
   It also provided a chance for President Clinton to campaign for
his wife; he gave what was surely the most effusive tribute to Mrs.
Clinton heard that night, and than, as the cameras flashed, turned
for a long embrace with his spouse.
</P>
<P>
   _ ADAM NAGOURNEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Mysterious Flight to Death
</P>
<P>
   Something, possibly something quite small, went wrong on a
Learjet chartered in Orlando, Fla., on Monday by pro golfer Payne
Stewart. It was evidently big enough to disable or kill the two
pilots, but not big enough to stop the airplane from flying 1,400
miles, presumably on autopilot, to a pasture in South Dakota, where
it crashed when one of its engines ran out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Cockpit voice recorders usually provide clues in crashes, but in
this case the tape was a 30-minute loop, and the plane flew for
about 4 hours without human intervention. It had no flight data
recorder. But investigators still hope for clues from the wreckage,
and from interviews with maintenance workers and fighter pilots who
were scrambled to see what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   Peron's Heirs Lose Their Grip
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years of the flamboyant rule of President Carlos Saul
Menem, Argentines gave a landslide presidential election victory to
the unabashedly uncharismatic mayor of Buenos Aires, Fernando de la
Rua, and his center-left Alianza coalition. De la Rua is not
expected to take Argentina in a direction very different from the
policies of Menem, but his victory broke a decade of dominance by
the Justicialist party founded half a century ago by Gen. Juan
Domingo Peron. More than anything else, the vote for De la Rua
appeared to reflect a popular rejection of the extravagance and
perceived tolerance of corruption by Menem and other Peronist
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLIFFORD KRAUSS
</P>
<P>
   An Editor Calls It Quits  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of an embarrassing recall of a controversial
biography of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, St. Martin's Press
editor-in-chief Robert Wallace resigned, saying he did not want to
be associated with such books and had had no control over
publication of this one.
</P>
<P>
   The book _ acquired for a modest $25,000 advance _ was written
by J.H. Hatfield, who the publisher belatedly discovered was a
felon who had been paroled on a charge of plotting the murder of
his boss in a failed car bombing. Wallace quickly landed a job as a
Talk magazine editor.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Assassination in Armenia  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Vazgen Sarkisian had just finished answering
questions from members of Armenia's Parliament when five men in
trench coats, some toting Kalashnikov automatic rifles, rushed in.
One emptied his weapon into Sarkisian while others turned on the
audience, firing into the front row where government dignitaries
sat.
</P>
<P>
   When it ended some 17 hours later, eight men were dead,
including the prime minister and the speaker of the Parliament, and
about 40 hostages had spent a terrifying night under siege by
police and a special anti-terrorist team sent from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Why remains somewhat foggy. The five gunmen, led by an Armenian
ex-journalist and ultra-nationalist named Nairi Unanian,
surrendered and released their hostages Thursday morning after
being allowed to broadcast a statement on national television. In
it, they accused Sarkisian and other leaders of destroying the
economy and allowing corruption to rot the government.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, Unanian and two others had been charged with
terrorism, potentially punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHAEL WINES
</P>
<P>
   A Vote Against Doctor-Assisted Suicide  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the governor of the state to the people in the street,
residents of Oregon responded angrily when the U.S. House of
Representatives passage of a measure that would effectively block
the state's first-in-the-nation law permitting physician-assisted
suicide for the terminally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Death with Dignity Act was approved by the
narrowest of margins in 1994 but then, facing a legal challenge,
was reaffirmed by a 60 percent to 40 percent vote three years
later. And however fiercely they debated the issue among
themselves, many Oregonians were clearly perturbed after Congress
acted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Congress really saying that our vote doesn't count, it
doesn't matter?'' explained one man _ even though he voted against
the act both times. State officials, saying the matter was a
states' rights issue, said they were considering a way to get a
challenge before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The chief House sponsor, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said doctors
should never be permitted to ``put down the stethoscope and pick up
the poison pill and assist in the execution of their patients.''
Last year, 15 people in Oregon took their own lives with
doctor-prescribed medication.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Rubin Takes a Job
</P>
<P>
   When Robert Rubin, the recently retired Treasury secretary,
announced that he would join Citigroup, America's largest financial
services company, heads turned both in Washington and on Wall
Street. Rubin, a veteran financier, had long said that he might
return to the trading pit. But few expected the 61-year-old to jump
back into the sea of commerce head first, much less accept an offer
from an arch-rival of Goldman, Sachs, his old company. In his new
role, Rubin will help plot strategy at Citigroup's helm.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
</TEXT>
