<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3358 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HEALTH-FEAR-REVIEW-NY     10-30 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-FEAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIGHT DOSE OF SCARE TACTICS TO DISCOURAGE THE WRONG TYPE OF
BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JEFF STRYKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be afraid. Be very afraid.
</P>
<P>
   This is the message at the heart of public health campaigns that
hope to stop young people from unsafe sex, smoking or binge
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the products of Baby Think It Over, Inc. This company
in Eau Claire, Wis., is best known for its ``simulator'' doll,
RealCare Baby, which gives teen-agers in ``life skills'' classes
the experience of diaper changing, simulated breast or bottle
feeding and burping. RealCare Baby also has two unhealthy siblings:
``Drug Affected Baby'' features the recorded cry of an actual baby
whose mother smoked crack; ``Fetal Alcohol Syndrome Manikin'' has
physical features that mimic those of an infant whose mother drank
to excess while pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The fetal alcohol syndrome doll is the latest in scare tactics
used to warn young people of the dangers of drinking, smoking and
unprotected sex. Some critics have called such approaches ``health
terrorism.'' Yet such fear appeals continue despite mixed reviews
from experts who doubt that they can change behavior in the long
term.
</P>
<P>
   The war on binge drinking, in particular, has increased since
widely publicized incidents like the death in 1997 of a
Massachusetts of Institute of Technology freshman after drinking
too much at a fraternity pledge event. Last month 113 state
universities and colleges signed on to an advertising campaign
sponsored by the National Association of State Universities and
Land-Grant Colleges. The campaign, which will be aimed at an
estimated 3 million college students who drink specifically to get
drunk, relies heavily on fear. One proposal for an ad that was
abandoned as too graphic featured a body on a gurney, with the
caption: ``Millions of college students called home last weekend.
Others didn't get the chance.'' Instead a series of sarcastic ads
will show a bottle labeled ``Binge Beer'' with the headline
``Hitting Colleges This Fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ad campaign sponsored last spring by the Michigan
Department of Community Health featured the slogan, ``Binge
drinking. It can make you dead drunk.'' Many churches around the
country stage ``hell houses'' in which teen-agers play the victims
of drunk driving and unsafe sex.
</P>
<P>
   Misgivings about such approaches have inspired more nuanced
campaigns. Some colleges like Darmouth College and Montana State
University are publicizing statistics to get across the message
that the majority of students do not routinely drink to excess,
hoping for the effects of peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the proponents of programs that rely on peer
pressure suggest that fear appeals simply do not work, Professor
Lawrence Wallack, a professor of public health at the University of
California at Berkeley, says he believes a balance must be struck
when trying to frighten people into healthy behavior. Too little
fear and a message to change behavior may have no impact; too much
fear, and denial may kick in. While acknowledging that scare
tactics might be useful in the appropriate dose, Wallack says he is
still wary of heightening anxiety about health issues without
``showing a safe, easy, quick and manageable way to reduce that
anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking campaigns are another area where approaches vary
wildly. The recent tobacco settlement, with its estimated yield of
$1.5 billion for anti-smoking media campaigns over the next five
years, has public health mavens puzzling over the most effective
media strategies. Should the ads rail against the evil tobacco
industry? Should they suggest that smoking is uncool or gross, ``a
tumor-causing, teeth-staining, smelly, puking habit'' _ as an
Arizona ad puts it? Or should ads warn of the greatly enhanced risk
of death or disease, even though some teen-agers may see a certain
cachet in danger and risk?
</P>
<P>
   Social and behavioral research shows that ``some kinds of
communication have some kinds of effects on some kinds of people
some of the time,'' Wallack said. Begun at the beginning of the
decade, California's anti-tobacco ad campaign is the oldest in the
country, but research on its effectiveness is still preliminary.
Dr. Gina Agostinelli, a researcher with the Prevention Research
Center in Berkeley, Calif., said, ``We know very little about the
most basic question: Is tobacco counter-advertising effective?''
</P>
<P>
   California health officials say that vilifying the tobacco
industry executives is one key to changing attitudes. Their latest
round of ads has coupled anti-industry salvos with messages
emphasizing the dangers of secondhand smoke to friends and family.
Although the ads are somewhat tamer today than nine years ago, the
state may still hold the prize for the most gruesome and fearful
anti-tobacco ad ever seen on television. In a spot entitled Voice
Box, a 50-ish woman complains that her addiction has made it
impossible to live without cigarettes; she then takes a deep drag
on her cigarette through a tracheotomy tube in her throat.
</P>
<P>
   Strategies such as increasing tobacco taxes, limiting access to
vending machines or prohibiting smoking in public spaces may have
much greater impact than advertising strategies. ``More awareness
and information is good,'' Wallack said, ``but we end up mistaking
part of the solution for the whole solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These campaigns might actually do more harm than good,'' he
said, ``by disproportionately placing the responsibilities on the
individual, neglecting broader social factors and giving people a
false sense that something substantial is being done to address the
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
