<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 31 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Lori Stassi at (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   LEGACY-LAUSD (Los Angeles) -- The Los Angeles Unified School
District has endangered thousands of students and teachers in 11
environmentally troubled schools, allowed crucial safety systems to
fail, used ill-prepared maintenance workers to check for hazardous
gases and even covered up dangerous conditions, a Daily News review
of district and state records shows. The most troubling situation
may be Park Avenue Elementary School in Cudahy, a school that has
been declared a state Superfund site. The school's scenario eerily
echoes the Belmont situation -- a history of district officials so
eager to build a school on cheap land that they only acknowledged
hazards when they were made public in embarrasing headlines. By
Terri Hardy (Will move on ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   RAIDERS-FANS (Los Angeles) -- For three off-duty hospital
workers clad in silver and black, Oct. 24 at the Oakland Raiders
game began in a Burbank Airport terminal. In an otherwise empty
bar. At 8:45 in the morning. With the first beers of the day in
front of them and an NFL pregame show on the television set
overhead, Michael McConaghy of Eagle Rock, Frank Kleineisel of
Chatsworth and Andy Rivera of Santa Clarita summoned the
us-against-the-world bravado they would need to fit in with 45,000
fellow Raiders fans later in the day at the Oakland Coliseum. (Will
move on the ``a'' national and the ``n'' California news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
