<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-ASIA-MUSLIMS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL ASIAN MUSLIM ZEALOTS' LATEST TARGETS ARE POOR, REMOTE,
VULNERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSH, Kyrgyzstan _ The appearance of Islamic insurgents in this
remote Central Asian country in recent weeks has not only shocked
regional leaders and their Russian and Chinese neighbors. It has
also awakened the world to a troubling new phenomenon: the
existence of a floating army of religious fighters who are roaming
this part of the world in search of regimes to overthrow.
</P>
<P>
   Kyrgyzstan is one of eight new nations that emerged in Central
Asia and the Caucasus following the collapse of the Soviet Union in
1991. The region is poor, unstable and populated mostly by Muslims.
It sparkles as a glittering prize for religious zealots.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters who appeared here in mid-August, like most of the
armed bands that have emerged in Central Asia recently, have their
roots in Afghanistan. They have now apparently withdrawn back to
bases there and in neighboring Tajikistan, freeing hostages they
had seized. No one believes, however, that they will lay down their
weapons or give up their dream of bringing the whole region under
religious rule. Their zeal poses a serious threat to stability in a
vast area that stretches from Turkey's eastern border all the way
to China.
</P>
<P>
   This year, even as civil war continues in Afghanistan, religious
violence has broken out not only in Kyrgyzstan, but also in three
other parts of this volatile belt. In Chechnya, which is officially
part of Russia, fundamentalists are leading a violent campaign for
independence. An apparently even more radical group is fighting in
the neighboring republic of Dagestan, which is also nominally under
Russian sovereignty. Further east, along the border that separates
India and Pakistan, the province of Kashmir is at temporary peace
following a bloody conflict this year in which Muslim radicals
played a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the religious militancy that is spreading through
Central Asia and the Caucasus may be traced back to the U.S.
campaign to drive Soviet forces from Afghanistan in the 1980s.
During that campaign, the CIA spent hundreds of millions of dollars
training religious fighters and buying them modern weapons. Now
they are using those skills, and in some cases those weapons, to
topple what they say are godless regimes.
</P>
<P>
   These religious militants want to fight wherever they believe
they can do God's bidding. They have attracted thousands of young
people who have no strong convictions, religious or otherwise, but
who know no trade other than war and who fight for a wage. Drug
gangs, realizing the importance of controlling trade routes through
the region, also eagerly contribute fighters.
</P>
<P>
   This odd collection of warriors is sponsored by a murky network
of religious and political visionaries. The Saudi millionaire Osama
bin Laden, whom the United States blames for last year's attacks on
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, and who now lives in
Afghanistan, is only the most visible.
</P>
<P>
   Part of these militants' strategy has been to build mosques and
pay to educate impoverished young people across the Caucasus and
Central Asia. But now they are beginning to foment little wars.
They are probing for places where they can win battles, and believe
they have found some in Chechnya, Dagestan, Kashmir and here in the
Fergana Valley, the heart of Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   These militants consider Kyrgyzstan only a secondary target, at
least for now. Their proclaimed goal is an Islamic state in
Uzbekistan next door. When they retreat, they move back to bases
not only in Afghanistan but also in Tajikistan, where warlords have
as much control as the central government.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Osh, one of the main towns in the Fergana Valley, people
are bewildered and frightened by the idea of insurgency. Most
people here are Muslims. But their tolerant and permissive brand of
Islam has little in common with the radicalism of those who are up
in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is very dangerous for all of Central Asia,''
said Bakyt Beshimov, a former president of Osh University who now
represents this region in the Kyrgyz Parliament. ``Part of the
danger is that these militants are being supported by religious
forces and governments abroad. The other problem is the terrible
social situation in this region, which makes people ready to
support radical alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   People across this region have seen living standards plummet
since the Soviet Union disintegrated. Once they enjoyed guaranteed
jobs, education and health care for all and pensions for the
elderly. Now most are in poverty, with little prospect for
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people live in terrible circumstances, the slogans of
fundamentalists are very attractive,'' Beshimov said. ``They are
telling people to fight against the political regimes that are the
source of their difficulties. They say they have the formula for a
better and fairer society. It is very tempting.''
</P>
<P>
   Western powers have been slow to focus on this isolated region,
and Kyrgyzstan President Askar Akayev said in an interview that he
relies on China to crack the whip. ``They have to care,'' he said.
``They have Xinjiang.''
</P>
<P>
   Xinjiang is China's westernmost province. Its population is
mainly Muslim, and its people feel little loyalty to Beijing. They
are restive, and radicals among them have set off bombs that some
outsiders believe are the beginning of a separatist campaign. So
far there is no indication that militants in Xinjiang have made
contact with ``the Afghans,'' as Islamic fighters who have fought
in Afghanistan are called. But it is tempting to see the Caucasus,
Central Asia and Xinjiang as ripe targets for a nascent religious
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand the feeling in the West, that all of this is
happening very far away,'' said Askar Aitmatov, an advisor to
Akayev. ``But religious fundamentalism is a big force. It is a
challenge for the entire world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
