<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISOLATIONISM-DEBATE-(     10-30 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISOLATIONISM-DEBATE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DEMISE OF COLD WAR HARMONY, DEBATE ON U.S. IDENTITY IS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ohio, Neb.)  (mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the aftermath of the White House's acrid defeat
on a treaty banning nuclear testing, President Clinton declared
that the Republicans in Congress were now driven by a reckless
``new isolationism.'' The treasury secretary charged Congress with
``malign neglect'' of America's obligations. The national security
adviser accused Republicans in Congress of pursuing a
``survivalist'' foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   But within days of delivering these broadsides, administration
officials began to backpedal. Lawrence Summers, the treasury
secretary, said in a speech that economic isolationism ``does not
spring from a single party or agenda.'' Sandy Berger, the national
security adviser, said that he did not intend to label all
opponents of the weapons treaty isolationists or to tar the entire
Republican Party with the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to reduce this to Republicans vs. Democrats,''
Berger said in an interview last week. ``But there are serious
issues and we ought to talk about them. We are at the pinnacle of
our power ... Are we going to seize this opportunity to lead the
world, or are we going to pull back?''
</P>
<P>
   Ostrichism and nativism will always be found in American
politics. But the debate, many foreign policy experts say, is about
what form of internationalism makes sense for an unchallenged
superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did little to advance his brand of internationalism with
his angry outburst after the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty was
spiked. He alienated Republicans who believe the United States has
global obligations but question the administration's strategy for
meeting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These attacks are both dangerous and bad judgment,'' said
Robert Zoellick, undersecretary of state in the Bush administration
and a foreign policy adviser to George W. Bush, the Texas governor
and presidential candidate. ``That pattern is to brand all
opponents as isolationists. It's not only inaccurate, it runs the
serious risk of undermining the larger case for America's
engagement in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoellick believes that the American people today favor an active
role in the world, but prefer to leave the specific terms of
engagement up to the president. He believes that Clinton has
squandered that opportunity. But Republicans are also to blame for
the current confusion, Zoellick said, because they have allowed
their distaste for Clinton to cloud their judgment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a moderate, agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and the national security adviser have attempted
to use the word `isolationist' as a political attack word,'' Lugar
said. Clinton has resorted to name-calling over his foreign policy
defeats rather than making a good-faith effort to narrow
``differences of opinion in how the United States should be engaged
in fulfilling its international goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are Republicans _ and former Republicans, like
Pat Buchanan _ who argue that the United States need not sully
itself in the messy conflicts of the Balkans or East Timor, nor
participate in the mushy do-goodism of international bodies. But
there are Democrats as well who opposed American military
intervention in Haiti and Bosnia and who question the value of
free-trading arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There is a long tradition _ in both major political parties _ of
mistrust of foreign entanglements and lack of faith in
multinational organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats overwhelmingly opposed the use of force in the Persian
Gulf in 1991 and voted heavily against the North American Free
Trade Agreement in 1993. For decades during the Cold War,
Republicans were outspoken advocates of internationalism, proposing
robust military spending and aggressive intervention in foreign
conflicts, from Southeast Asia to Central America.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, the discussion that began with the end of the
Cold War is not about treaties or trading arrangements, but about
the American identity and national purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It is a debate that preceded the formation of the republic and
that George Washington addressed in his valedictory upon leaving
the presidency in 1797, in which he warned his countrymen against
``permanent alliances'' with foreign powers. (It was Jefferson who
warned of ``entangling alliances'' in his inaugural address four
years later.)
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been renewed after every major conflict, from the
War of 1812 to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``One side believes the United States is exceptional and unique,
unique because it is isolated by the oceans and uncontaminated by
foreign influences,'' said Michael Hogan, dean of the College of
Humanities at Ohio State University. ``They believe that the more
the country enters into entangling alliances, the more likely it is
that it will be corrupted and its unique nature will be
subverted.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side argues that while the United States is singular,
Hogan continued, ``it has the mission to spread the blessings of
American liberty to people around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   That tension was largely stilled during the Cold War. Congresses
and presidents, from Truman to Reagan, shared a broad consensus on
the need to pay the price of advancing liberty around the globe,
although there were deep and even violent disputes on where and
when American troops should be the instruments of that cause. That
consensus has now broken down and the debate is once again raging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much easier during that era to rally the public and the
Congress to engagement under the banner of containment,'' Berger
said. ``But with the end of the Cold War, it is tempting to some to
want to pull back, but it is equally dangerous. There is a range of
threats out there that will affect America's prosperity and
security. Our well-being is tied to the well-being of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans mostly agree. Their quarrel is with the
administration's approach to those threats. They do not want to see
American troops under U.N. command, they believe that Europeans
should take the lead in dealing with bloodshed in the Balkans, and
they think that global treaties infringe on American sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   And they resent the charge of isolationism as a substitute for
substantive debate and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, we've got a president who very few people up
here trust and, on the Republican side, very few like,'' said Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., a member of the Foreign Relations Committee.
``He's never gone out of his way to develop any kind of relations
up here, and this is all coming home now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
