<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CRUISES-MEDICAL-LAW-N     10-30 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISES-MEDICAL-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLOSER LOOK AT THE HIGH SEAS AND THE FINE PRINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Alaska, N.Y.)   (With CRUISES-MEDICAL-CARE)  
(lh) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to medical malpractice suits, the law, the fine
print and recent congressional action favor the cruise industry.
</P>
<P>
   First, maritime law governs claims. The Death on the High Seas
Act limits damages to real monetary losses, eliminating punitive
damages and payments for pain and suffering. And judges, not
juries, decide maritime cases.
</P>
<P>
   The law of the sea also specifies that a ship owner has no duty
to provide medical care and, as stipulated in the small print on
cruise tickets, is not liable for the ship's doctors and other
independent contractors. That precedent is rooted in the 19th
century, when trans-Atlantic ships gave doctors free passage in
exchange for looking after passengers informally.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise companies argue that they still need the protection today
because their expertise lies in operating vessels, not supervising
doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Miami rejected the argument in 1993, saying
that cruise ships enticed passengers aboard by advertising the
presence of a doctor and could therefore be liable for the doctor's
actions. But other courts have sided with the ship owners.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers have tried without success to take up the issue by
accusing ships of false advertising, because the fine print of
tickets says they provide medical care and because doctors wear the
same uniforms as other officers.
</P>
<P>
   The fine print also specifies where a passenger can file suit.
Most cruise companies choose Miami, where most have their
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   This means that a passenger who boards a cruise in California
and later decides to sue must do so in Miami, even if the passenger
never got within 2,000 miles of Miami. Lawyers for passengers say
the requirement makes suing cruise companies more expensive and
cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ranni, 78, who was injured in a fall on a Royal Caribbean
ship last year, is challenging the requirement. Her lawyer, Daniel
H. Greenberg, said the print on the ticket was too small to
constitute proper legal notice in New York, where she bought her
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the industry sought congressional approval to cap the
amount passengers could collect for medical malpractice in certain
instances. Under the proposal, when an ill or injured passenger was
referred to a doctor or hospital in port, the cruise line's
liability was capped at the limit in the location where the medical
treatment occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The industry said the cap meant that the burden of paying a
malpractice award was not shifted unfairly away from the hospital
or on-shore doctor to the cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   The restriction was one of three provisions sought by the
industry and introduced with a public hearing by Rep. Don Young,
R-Alaska, who is a leading voice for the industry in Congress. The
others would have prohibited foreign crew members from suing cruise
companies in U.S. courts if they were injured and limited damages
for victims of sexual assault on ships.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation opposed all the changes,
saying they would help the cruise industry, most of whose ships
operate under foreign flags, at the expense of American travelers,
who make up more than 90 percent of cruise passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus,'' Nancy E. McFadden, the department's general counsel,
wrote in a letter to Congress, ``the adverse impact of the
provisions falls mainly on U.S. passengers while at the same time
benefiting foreign-flag cruise operators _ operators who pay few
U.S. taxes and avoid U.S. minimum wage and fair labor laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The provisions dealing with crew lawsuits and rape were defeated
after lawyers and women's rights groups objected. The malpractice
cap was approved and enacted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1328EDT &QL; 
