<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IRAN-REFORMER-TRIAL-2     10-30 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-REFORMER-TRIAL-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERIC'S TRIAL BECOMES FLASH POINT OF IRAN'S POLITICAL FATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran's ruling Muslim clerics Saturday began the
apostasy trial of one of the country's most popular politicians,
Abdullah Nouri, a cleric who has gone from being one of the most
trusted aides to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to taking a key
leadership role in a campaign to end the clerical dictatorship
Khomeini imposed after the Islamic revolution in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As turbaned clerics gathered in a courtroom ringed by armed
commandos, few Iranians doubted that the outcome of the trial,
before the much-feared Special Court for the Clergy, will go a long
way toward determining whether the country moves toward greater
democracy, or to a new era of clerical repression. A guilty verdict
could conceivably carry the death penalty, although a lengthy
prison term is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   For many of Iran's 65 million people, the trial has assumed the
significance Americans attached to the Scopes trial in 1927, or
people in England to the treason trial of Sir Thomas More during
the reign of Henry VIII _ a moment when a courtroom becomes a
testing ground for irreconcilable views about the future of a
society and its beliefs, with huge social, philosophical and
political stakes resting on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In the Tehran trial, which could last weeks, reformers and
hard-liners will battle over issues that only a few years ago were
taboo, the most crucial of them over whether the right to rule
rests with the Iranian people, or with the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   But other, more tangible questions are on trial, too, including
Iran's relations with the United States. High on the list of
charges outlined in a 44-page indictment of the defendant is that
the newspaper he publishes has advocated re-establishing relations
with the United States. The prosecutor, a cleric, said that by
running an article quoting another high-ranking cleric as saying
that relations with the United States are ``now a possible, not
impossible thing,'' Nouri had betrayed the revolution and the
Islamic principles that underpinned it.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is Nouri who is on trial, the 50-year-old cleric is
widely regarded in Iran as a surrogate for the man many powerful
clerics would like to see as the defendant, President Mohammad
Khatami. But for the time being, Khatami, 53, another cleric, is
untouchable, having won a landslide victory in the presidential
election in 1997 over the hard-liners' candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Nouri's trial began, Khatami landed back in Tehran
from an official visit to Paris, part of his campaign to break
Iran's isolation and open what he calls ``a dialogue of
civilizations'' with the world.
</P>
<P>
   Though most Iranians expect Nouri to be convicted, many say the
trial could be costly for the hard-liners, underlining an
intolerance that could strengthen reformers' support. Even in the
courtroom, the sense of the hard-liners' isolation from the society
around them was reinforced by signs of the rapid changes afoot in
Iran _ in the ringing mobile phones of reporters and clerics, and
in the high-rise block of luxury condominiums rising across the
road, evidence of a new business class that has thrown its support
behind the reformers.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri, dressed in a cleric's collar-less white shirt, black robe
and white turban, appeared to stun peers appointed to sit in
judgment over him _ a judge and a nine-man jury, all of them
clerics _ by taking the witness stand immediately after the
indictment was read to say that it was they, not he, who had
betrayed the revolution. More than that, he rejected their right to
judge him, saying that the clergy court itself was illegal, having
no place in the Islamic Constitution that was drawn up in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally reject the court, its membership, and its competence
to conduct this trial, and any verdict you reach will have no
legitimacy,'' he said, in a clear, steady voice. ``What I was
thinking as I listened to the indictment being read out was, `This
is not a court, this is a self-appointed cabal.''' He added: ``I
ask myself, what has happened to us, to our revolution, to our
faith, that it has come to this, that one group of clerics can make
allegations against another like this?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mohammed Salimi, who is in his late 30s, warned Nouri not
to insult the court. ``You say now that this court has no
legitimacy, because you are here on trial, but I don't remember you
saying that about this court when you were holding high positions
of state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Mohammed Nikounam, in his 50s, reminded Nouri,
ominously, that left-wing opponents of the ruling clerics also
contested the court's legitimacy after placing a bomb in a Tehran
building, killing 73 people, including many top clerics, in 1981.
The bombers were executed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By challenging the court's legitimacy, Nouri came close to doing
something virtually unheard of in Iran, even among reformers _
questioning the legacy of Ayatollah Khomeini, the stern-faced
cleric who became an absolute ruler in the years between the
upheaval that ousted the shah and his death in 1989. Khomeini
established the clergy court by personal decree to deal with rising
resistance to Islamic rule, but Nouri, citing the 1980
constitution, said that not even ``the leader'' _ a reference to
Khomeini _ had the right to establish courts outside the framework
of the constitution. ``Are we supposed to accept that the law
applies to everybody except the leader?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Nouri opened the key issue in the trial, and in the
wider political struggle across Iran: Whether power will be vested
in the people, through the president and Parliament they elect, or
will continue to rest, as it effectively does now, with a group of
deeply conservative clerics who take their authority from
Khomeini's successor as the country's spiritual leader, Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei. Khamenei and his supporters say that their right to
rule rests in a principle known in Iran as ``velayat-i faghi,''
which means, loosely, that the country's top cleric, as ``God's
representative on earth,'' has sovereign powers.
</P>
<P>
   By holding Nouri's trial now _ and many other trials in which
newspaper editors, reporters, student protesters and clerics who
have joined the reform movement are defendants _ the clerical elite
apparently hopes to strike a blow against the reformers ahead of
parliamentary elections that are scheduled in February. The
reformers' political strategists, prominent among them Nouri, hope
that by winning a landslide victory in the elections they can move
on to constitutional reforms that will vastly reduce the clerics'
arbitrary powers.
</P>
<P>
   But if Nouri is convicted, or even if his trial is not
concluded, he will automatically be disqualified from competing in
the elections, in which he has been expected to be the reformers'
biggest vote-getter. In February, after stepping down as one of
Khatami's vice presidents, he won the largest number of votes in
municipal elections that were held among the 12 million people of
Tehran. Until hard-liners in Parliament impeached him in 1998, he
was Khatami's interior minister, winning widespread popularity with
steps that curbed excesses by the police and the judiciary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The charges Nouri faces could hardly be more serious. He is
accused of using his newspaper, Khordad, which has the biggest
circulation among dozens of daily newspapers in Tehran, to ``insult
Islam,'' its prophet, Mohammed, his descendants, and Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   But as the indictment was read out in court, it became clear
that hard-line clerics intend to use the trial to strike out
against just about everything else they dislike in the reformers'
more tolerant social philosophy. Among other things, the prosecutor
cited an article in Khordad that said that people should be allowed
to clap, whistle and cheer at concerts and political rallies _ an
Islamic taboo in Iran, even though it has been frequently ignored
in the freer atmosphere ushered in by Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Other articles the prosecutor cited as examples of
``un-Islamic'' attitudes included one in which an Italian woman
journalist criticized Iran's divorce laws, which are heavily
weighted against women, and another that argued, in a reference to
the clergy, that ``absolute power corrupts absolutely.'' Still
another questioned the Islamic legal precept of ``qisas,'' or
eye-for-an-eye justice, under which Iranian courts frequently
impose the death penalty, amputations and other harsh penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Nikounam, the prosecutor, raised his voice indignantly. ``What
you are saying, in effect, is that people should be able to do
anything they want, even to drink alcohol, no matter how offensive
that may be to our Islamic beliefs,'' he said. He stood before a
handwritten quotation from Khomeini that court officials had pasted
on the courtroom wall in which Khomeini warned followers to
``beware of false clerics and false revolutionaries who pretend to
be holy,'' but conspire to betray Islam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-CULT-LAW-650&AMP;AD     10-30 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CULT-LAW-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ENACTS STRICT LAW AIMED AT SMASHING CULT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After a week of secret deliberations, China's top
legislative body issued a stringent new ``anti-cult'' law on
Saturday designed to aid the government's crackdown on the Falun
Gong spiritual movement.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, reportedly passed by a vote of 114-0 with two
abstentions by the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, ``calls on courts, prosecutors, police and administrative
judicial organs to be on full alert for cult activities and smash
them rigorously,'' the New China News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Press accounts suggested that the law would be used _ apparently
retroactively _ in prosecuting organizers of the Falun Gong
movement, which was banned on July 22 and has been vilified for
months in the official news media, with thousands of its adherents
detained.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the law allots jail terms of three to seven
years to cultists who ``disrupt public order'' or distribute
publications ``spreading malicious fallacies.'' Those found
organizing or recruiting face terms of seven years or more.
</P>
<P>
   The standing committee is led by Li Peng, a former prime
minister who played a prominent role in the crushing of the student
democracy movement in 1989, and includes the most powerful and
trusted members of the Parliament. On important issues it carries
out the secret directives of the Communist Party, led by Jiang
Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement a week ago that the committee would be adopting
a new law on cults helped set off daily silent demonstrations here
by unrepentant believers. They insist that Falun Gong _ which
combines slow ritual exercises with mystical theories of health and
happiness _ is not a cult or a political danger.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown has brought on a crisis with surreal aspects for
the government, which had hoped that the popular movement would
dissolve after it was officially condemned as a fraud and key
leaders were jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, thousands of fervent believers, from graduate students
in Beijing to retired clerks and bureaucrats in provincial cities,
have refused to repudiate a practice they regard as vital to their
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, for the sixth straight day, dozens of followers
were detained in Tiananmen Square, next to the Great Hall of the
People, where the legislators met. Many came from other cities in
the naive hope of convincing officials that Falun Gong was not a
social threat. Instead, they were picked up as soon as they were
identified by the scores of plainclothes police roaming the vast
square.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong members say that thousands of desperate
practitioners, most of whom faced harassment or imprisonment in
their hometowns, have converged on Beijing, where they are now
trying to elude the vast police dragnet.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have privately said that more than 3,000 people were
detained in Beijing in the last week, most of them not in the
public setting of Tiananmen Square. Many were immediately sent to
their home provinces, where they may face further imprisonment or
other punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Some local people were quickly released _ with their company
managers, university department chairmen or neighborhood government
officials ordered to help ``re-educate'' them. Some who were
identified as organizers will be held for possible serious charges.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday, at least 10 of the 30 Falun Gong members who
took part in a clandestine news conference with foreign reporters
on Thursday had been arrested, an organizer said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the believers who came to Beijing have described a
worsening pattern of persecution in the provinces. According to a
report Saturday from a human rights monitor in Hong Kong, for
example, a women's labor camp in the northeastern city of Changchun
now holds 50 Falun Gong believers, including 12 schoolteachers who
refused to give up the practice and who were sentenced _ without
trial _ to one year in prison.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Falun Gong, invented only in 1992 by a former grain clerk named
Li Hongzhi, combines ancient theories about cosmic forces in the
body with elements of Buddhism and Taoism. Practitioners do a
series of exercises that are said to ward off disease.
</P>
<P>
   Li's writings purport to offer a new spiritual path in a corrupt
world, and condemn drinking, smoking and homosexuality. They also
suggest that believers can attain supernatural powers. His
teachings spread quickly in China, attracting millions of people
who practiced in city parks until the July ban.
</P>
<P>
   Li moved to New York in 1998 but communicates with his devotees
worldwide on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In late April the Chinese government began laying plans to
destroy the group, after more than 10,000 members mounted a
surprise illegal vigil around the Communist Party leadership's
compound in Beijing demanding official recognition. At first the
official response was hesitant, perhaps because so many current and
former officials and otherwise upright citizens were involved.
</P>
<P>
   But China's Communist government tries to keep all social
institutions under its thumb and on July 22 it banned the group,
charging that it had political ambitions to subvert the state _
something Li and his followers deny.
</P>
<P>
   With the branding of the group as a cult, and new charges that
leaders stole state secrets, the new law, an intense news media
campaign to discredit the theory and its founder, and the imminent
prosecutions of key leaders, the campaign to stamp out Falun Gong
is gathering force.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's official news report of the anti-cult law says it
``stresses that deceived followers and practitioners should be
differentiated from cult leaders.'' Local governments are supposed
``to educate those deceived while punishing a small number of cult
leaders and those who have committed crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the curious hidden struggle with true believers in the back
alleys of Beijing last week suggests that exterminating the
movement _ if it is possible at all _ will be far uglier than party
leaders may have anticipated, requiring harsh punishment for
thousands. Furthermore, the devotees protesting last week are not
some strange breed of democracy dissident, but colleagues and
relatives and law-abiding citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations last week, many Beijing residents said they
felt that the government had overreacted to the rise of Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The troubles this week show how mistaken the government's
approach has been,'' said a high-ranking intellectual of the
Communist Party. ``Now, Falun Gong has been transformed into a
completely antagonistic social force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3389 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-MEXICO-LACARGADA-$ADV     10-30 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 BC- MEXICO-LACARGADA-$ADV30-1stLD &HT;    AUTHORITARIAN POLITICAL TRADITION SURVIVES ON EVE OF FIRST
MEXICAN PRIMARY ELECTION
 &HT;    EDS: Restores dropped lines at end of story.
 &HT;    1,100&AMP;add
 &HT;    NOTE: Ecatepec is in the state of Mexico about five miles north
of Mexico City.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECATEPEC, Mexico Gabriel Medina says he recently got his job
peddling a bicycle taxi by agreeing to join Mexico's ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has little education and few marketable skills,
Medina intends to keep that $10-a-day job by doing exactly what a
local PRI-affiliated leader tells him to do. That's why he
dutifully accepted his leader's instruction about a month ago to
put campaign bumper stickers for PRI presidential hopeful Francisco
Labastida on his cab.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, the leader told Medina and about 70 other workers,
was the best man to vote for in Mexico's historic Nov. 7
presidential primary _ the first ever held by the powerful PRI,
which has controlled Mexico's highest office for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's true that Mr. Labastida will help us, I don't mind
voting for him,'' shrugged Medina, 21, who has to pay his leader $1
a week for the right to drive his bicycle taxi around this
sprawling working-class city just
</P>
<P>
   outside Mexico's capital. ``Me, I just want to work and live
without any problems. The truth is I don't think our lives will
change much no matter which of these politicians is elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Medina's compliance _ and his party leader's pressure _
represent the street-level version of a system deeply ingrained in
Mexico's political life. It's known here by the nickname ``la
cargada.'' And it means, loosely, that PRI-affiliated state
governors down to the lowest party functionary will ``carry'' a
candidate's campaign by using subtle to extreme coercion as well as
public resources to garner votes.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of a widespread ``cargada'' in favor of Labastida
have become a flash point in the PRI's Nov. 7 primary election.
Labastida, who was most recently Mexico's interior minister, and
another candidate, Roberto Madrazo, the former Tabasco state
governor, are locked in a close race that has them fighting for the
endorsement of PRI sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   For decades the PRI has dominated Mexican politics in large part
by mustering to the polls its vast network of PRI-affiliated
unions, neighborhoods, farmers and business associations. These are
groups that have long held the keys to jobs, contracts and simple
services like water, drainage, electricity and food subsidies in
this country where half the population lives in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, candidates for all elections here have been
selected by party leaders without primaries. For the 70 years that
the PRI has controlled the presidency, the sitting president of the
republic has always
</P>
<P>
   picked the party's nominee in an autocratic process known
jokingly as the ``dedazo,'' the ``big finger.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 7, however, the PRI is trying to break with that
tradition and construct a more democratic image by holding a
self-supervised primary. The balloting will be open to all Mexican
voters, but PRI loyalists are expected to be the majority of those
who turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Competition has appeared fierce among four candidates,
particularly between Labastida and Madrazo, who have been running
close in opinion polls for most of the three-month campaign.
Madrazo's television ads and his rhetoric, especially, have been
unusually bold in their attacks on Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, Mexican society thought this process was a show and
would end up with a designation as things used to be done. But as
days, weeks and months passed, people realized this was for real,''
PRI primary organizer Fernando Gutierrez Barrios told foreign
reporters on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the primary's democratic blush has been marred by the
perception that Labastida alone is benefiting from the PRI's
traditional well-oiled political machine. Indeed, at least one
state governor _ Roberto Albores of Chiapas _ has been verbally
reprimanded by the PRI for using his position to support Labastida
in his state, acknowledged Gutierrez Barrios.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, those complaining the loudest about Labastida's
alleged advantage are Madrazo and two other contenders, Manuel
Bartlett and Humberto Roque Villanueva. Like Labastida, all are
party insiders who in the past have advanced in their careers with
the help of the same system they are now attacking.
</P>
<P>
   But others are also casting a jaundiced eye toward campaign
methods employed during the primary, which could be a dress
rehearsal for Mexico's July 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is using the same tactics it always has,'' said
Rogelio Gomez, a national representative of Civic Alliance, an
independent organization monitoring election fraud and questionable
campaign activities here. ``There is a culture of doing politics in
Mexico where people with low incomes and little education give
their votes in exchange for government services that should just be
given to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, who is mounting a strong opposition campaign as the
presidential candidate for Mexico's National Action Party, or PAN,
said that ``only a blind person'' couldn't see that ``the
unconditional support of the whole state apparatus and the PRI's
party apparatus is behind Labastida.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Estudillo, an analyst with the Mexican Institute for
Political Studies, said that many PRI affiliates, especially those
in very poor urban and rural areas, appear to still be locked into
the habit of waiting to be
</P>
<P>
   told for whom they should vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the principle dilemma of the PRI and of Mexico as both
try to make a transition to democracy,'' Estudillo said. ``The PRI
member is asking: Do I respond to that tradition of 70 years, which
may be serving me in some way, or do I dare to rebel? ``
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Labastida workers have reportedly been
observed handing out T-shirts, hats, shopping bags, free breakfasts
and free medical exams and legal advice at a greater pace than
Labastida's opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to a meeting with (Labastida) not long ago,'' recalled
Medina. ``They gave us our sandwich, a dessert and a banana. The
truth is it was fun. Our leader didn't really force us to go, but
she suggested we go to support him so he'll support us later.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as such services and gifts are not paid for by
government funds, their provision to would-be voters at campaign
rallies does not violate the PRI's internal primary rules or
Mexican law. Other parties hand
</P>
<P>
   out gifts, too, but the PRI is considered the king of such
practices after 70 years of power.
</P>
<P>
   What is strictly prohibited, however, is using public money,
services or the influence of government or high-ranking party
officials to buy votes. In the primary, the PRI has also required
that governors and other officials refrain from even expressing a
preference for a candidate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the party did not publicize it, Gutierrez Barrios
revealed this week that the PRI verbally sanctioned Gov. Roberto
Albores of Chiapas early in the campaign. But according to
newspaper reports here, some state congressmen in Chiapas accused
Albores of recently trying to force them into delivering votes for
Labastida. The accuracy of the charges is in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo has complained about other governors using their clout
on behalf of Labastida. The PRI is supposed to investigate the
complaints. So far, no other governors have been reprimanded. But
about a dozen lower-ranking PRI figures have been sanctioned for
using their positions to support certain candidates, not just
Labastida, Gutierrez Barrios said.
</P>
<P>
   For many Mexicans, the mere fact that Labastida has many former
cabinet secretaries and other powerful PRI figures working in his
campaign is a sign that he has the stamp of approval of President
Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   And during a trip to Europe, newspapers here reported, a group
of the PRI representatives reportedly praised Labastida in a
meeting with German officials and spoke harshly about Madrazo,
characterizing him as a corrupt figure.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida has tried to fight the notion that he is considered
the party elite's preferred candidate. His campaign touts his
experience as governor of Sinaloa state, agriculture minister and
interior secretary in Zedillo's cabinet. He also has the benefit of
some new polls showing that voters believe he is more honest and
more of a leader than Madrazo.
</P>
<P>
   But the fuss inside the PRI over the alleged ``cargada'' has
dogged Labastida as well as Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's three rivals recently implored Zedillo to speak out
against governors and other public officials taking sides during
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Zedillo met with PRI functionaries and governors
last week, reiterating that he had no preferred candidate. He also
warned: ``In a democratic and open election . . . attempts at
manipulation, coercion or fraud will not only not work, they will
come back to hurt those who attempt to commit them.''
</P>
<P>
   But after decades of authoritarian politicking, the public
response to Zedillo was skeptical. The Mexican newspaper La Jornada
published a cartoon with Zedillo's finger telling him, ``You don't
have a favorite, but what about me?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
