<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-PEACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE EFFORT IN ULSTER BRINGS GAINS, NOT A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The rescue mission by George
Mitchell aimed at ending the stalemate that has stalled progress in
the Northern Ireland peace accord entered its final stages Saturday
with scant hope of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   In eight weeks of talks, conducted in unusual secrecy and on
some occasions away from Belfast itself, Mitchell, the former U.S.
senator turned mediator, has developed a negotiating atmosphere in
which the feuding Ulster Unionist and Sinn Fein parties directly
addressed each other's concerns for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   That is a considerable achievement in Ulster's bitterly
polarized politics and makes it likely that even if the current
salvage operation fails, the province will not return to the
systematic violence of the past. But it has not yet been enough to
break the impasse preventing the start-up of the new provincial
government planned in the peace accord signed by both sides in
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute centers on the insistence of the Ulster Unionists,
the province's largest party, that the Irish Republican Army begin
disarming before its political representatives, Sinn Fein, can take
their seats on the 10-person executive that will run the new
Northern Ireland Assembly. That group will be, in effect, the
cabinet in the new administration that is supposed to take over
governing the province from London.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists, who are largely Protestant, are so called because
they believe in keeping Ulster as part of the United Kingdom, while
republicans, most of whom are Catholics, want to see Northern
Ireland ultimately become part of the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The peace settlement was agreed to as a way of ending decades of
paramilitary violence between the Protestant majority and the
Catholic minority that has cost more than 3,300 lives. The
agreement, the cause of widespread euphoria at the time, created
shared political structures and demanded the disarming of guerrilla
groups by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It was approved by overwhelming margins in referendums held in
Ireland and Northern Ireland, and the 108 members of the new
legislature were elected more than a year ago. Based on that vote,
Sinn Fein gained the right to two of the 10 executive cabinet
positions.
</P>
<P>
   After that, however, the mood in Ulster became more despairing
as the matter of when paramilitary groups would start disarming _
no date was set in the accord _ became first a concern and then an
insurmountable barrier to progress.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein argues that the accord placed no disarmament condition
for entering government and that the IRA has proved its commitment
to peace by maintaining a cease-fire since 1997. The Ulster
Unionists say that the IRA commitment will become trustworthy only
with the surrender of weapons and that it would be unthinkable to
let a party into government while its paramilitary force stayed
fully armed.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15 the whole matter descended to chaos, then farce, when
the Ulster Unionists boycotted a raucous meeting of the assembly
held to name the members of the new executive. Unable to create a
cabinet with the required Protestant-Catholic mix, the legislature
had to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, the sponsors of the peace agreement, sent for
Mitchell, who had been the chairman of the original talks.
</P>
<P>
   An official who has participated in the recent weeks of talks
said that Mitchell was a ``master deal maker'' and was the only
person in public life in Northern Ireland who enjoyed the trust of
all sides. ``It also helps that he is an outsider,'' the official
added.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has spent part of each of the past eight weeks in
Northern Ireland, and he has gradually narrowed the focus of his
attention on the two parties of the eight who signed the agreement
_ Sinn Fein and the Ulster Unionists. He had been expected to end
his mission last weekend but extended it over signs that the frosty
relations between the long-feuding parties were thawing.
</P>
<P>
   Each party fears being identified as the one responsible for
holding up progress. There seems little doubt that their leaders
want to see the accord work but face internal demands not to
compromise. David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist leader, is under
pressure from dissidents in his party to maintain the ``no guns, no
government'' position. Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, says
he could not compel IRA disarmament even if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has hinted that he would be agreeable to creating the
crucial executive, or a shadow form of it, in advance of
disarmament, but only if Sinn Fein guaranteed that weapons
turnovers would occur shortly thereafter. Adams, while saying ``I
understand the difficulties, the challenges which this process
presents,'' was unable or unwilling to take the step that Trimble
sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
