<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-HAWKS31-COX     10-30 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New team, another shot
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Hawks already are a step ahead with Jim Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   It's three months since he joined his fifth team in 2 1/2 years
and the Hawks haven't promised Jackson anything. That means they
haven't lied to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we told Jim is what we tell all our players, that we're
committed to improving our team,'' general manager Pete Babcock
related. ``We told all of them: If we can markedly improve our team
or our future by trading you, we'll do it. That's the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson understands, but entering the second year of a
three-year contract worth almost $2 million, he knows there is
opportunity here as there was in Portland last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working hard to earn a position, to show this team
some of the things I'm capable of doing once I get comfortable with
the system,'' he said Thursday before the Hawks staged a scrimmage
for season ticket holders in Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson has shown something. He was the team's
second-leading scorer in the exhibition season at 13.3 points per
game, shooting .469 from the field, .864 from the line, starting as
a shooting guard, playing a little point and a little more small
forward, too.
</P>
<P>
   A weapon coach Lenny Wilkens uncovered during two-a-days proved
very effective in two Hawks victories, as Wilkens teamed Jackson
and Isaiah Rider with point guard Bimbo Coles to set up scoring
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says it's a natural counter to teams that feature
high-octane offensive sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at New York with Chris Childs or Charlie Ward with
Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell in the backcourt. Similar
situation going on in Toronto with Vince Carter and Doug Christie.
In Charlotte with Eddie Jones and Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's conducive. I don't think there's a lot big three
men (small forwards) around. You've got a lot of swing players,
6-foot-5, 6-6, so it's something that really helps us in so far as
getting up and down the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is a natural foil for Sprewell, who almost
single-handedly destroyed the Hawks in the playoffs. Jackson
shoots, passes, rebounds, goes to the hoop. He lacks Sprewell's
startling explosiveness, but he ranks much higher on the
reliability scale and he is regaining the spontaneity that allowed
him to play the point earlier in his career and made him such a
dangerous backcourt partner for Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit down at night and think about the last three years where
I really haven't been able to grow as a player because I've been
limited to certain things. ... It takes some time to get back to
playing the kind of basketball I know how to play. But Lenny's
giving me that confidence where if you're on the court and you have
a shot, you take it or you set it up. He's puts me in situations
were I can be successful and I can only grow from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is a good fit with his new coach. ``He's interesting in
that he allows you to be as professional as you should be. To come
out here and work hard and do the things that you can. You have the
freedom to go out on the court and play the kind of game you are
capable of playing. For a guy like me who hasn't had that freedom
it's a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jackson simply wants to fit in and he hopes the Hawks like
what he gives them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look around. Watching ESPN the other night I saw something
on Marshall Faulk. He had a great year in Indianapolis and he was
told he wasn't needed. He went out and played every game and did
what the organization asked and now they wanted a change. Well that
affects you. You give your sweat, your blood, your tears for an
organization where you think they have your back and they want to
help you out, that takes something away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes something away from the game because you've given of
yourself. I wanted to win and I felt that was a good situation (in
Portland), long-term for me, and I put my trust where I try not to
and it showed me what kind of business this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Here he goes again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
