<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-JACKSON-COX     10-30 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JACKSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackson attempts to bring system to Lakers
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Jackson's indoctrination to Los Angeles came a few months
after he accepted the task of elevating the underachieving Lakers.
It came early one Saturday morning, totally unexpected, like an
epiphany. Only it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   As the coach rested in his bed, things around the room started
to move and bang together. No, it was not Shaquille O'Neal rumbling
down the hallway, but an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make Jackson wonder what he was doing in plush
Playa del Rey in Southern California instead of his home in the
picturesque mountains of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like this,'' Jackson said, extending his arms,
``grabbing my bed frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, including Jackson, survived the quake. But he learned
quickly that there would be more uneasy times in Los Angeles before
the good times become routine. The team he inherited from Kurt
Rambis, who took over from Del Harris, has talent. But it is
deficient in areas of the game on which Jackson is unshakable:
cohesion, discipline, unselfishness.
</P>
<P>
   So, the coach of the six-time champion Chicago Bulls, who quit
after the final title run in 1998, is rebuilding the Lakers from
within. Deep within _ their psyches.
</P>
<P>
   He nixed in an instant the notion of the Lakers acquiring the
New York Knicks' Latrell Sprewell. ``Latrell hasn't really wanted
to fit in anywhere,'' Jackson said. ``One of the things we try to
do is have people who want to be part of what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Lakers seem to welcome a part in Jackson's grand
plan. The star players _ O'Neal, Kobe Bryant, Glen Rice _ have had
individual success of varying degrees. But their teams have
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   A residual of coaching Michael Jordan and winning a half-dozen
titles is that Jackson commanded respect when he first walked into
the locker room _ even with the Lakers, who failed to honor Harris
and essentially ignored Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   That's not happening now. O'Neal showed the respect he has for
Jackson last summer, when he was in Montana for a charity event.
Across the lake, Shaq was told, was Jackson's home. The 7-foot,
330-pound O'Neal climbed in a boat and sailed across to meet his
new coach. Jackson's wife, June, was home alone. He and June went
karaoke singing. The duet sang ``Red, Red Wine,'' ``Purple Rain''
and ``I Believe I can Fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, O'Neal returned to Jackson's home, and the
coach was there. O'Neal stayed just 10 minutes, but Jackson used
that time to let his all-star center know he expected him to become
a leader and a consistent force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same thing my father tells me,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jacksonare on the correct path. Here's O'Neal: ``Before
you succeed, you must learn to fail. For me, it has been seven
years of failing. It hasn't been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is playing under Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're at a military school, and you heard about
this certain military guy,'' O'Neal said. ``There's a certain
respect when you come in. Last year or the year before, we had guys
talking and (messing) around. But with Phil, everybody knows his
resume and knows who he is. A couple of the guys had trouble with
the drills, including me. It's like basic training.''
</P>
<P>
   The basis of Jackson's scheme is the triangle offense, an
approach that emphasizes teamwork. The Bulls mastered it in
Chicago, and one of the stabilizers for the Bulls was guard Ron
Harper, whom the Lakers signed to a two-year contract near the end
of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson believes Harper's expertise and experience will go a
significant way toward the Lakers' jelling. Harper can be a
positive influence on Bryant, the immensely skilled guard whose
major shortcoming has been playing within the framework of a team.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who did not seem comfortable in the triangle offense
during practice before breaking a bone in his hand, and O'Neal did
not always get along last year. Bryant's penchant for one-on-one
play bothered O'Neal. But the two have been on the mend. Bryant
invited O'Neal to his birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teamwork is the key,'' O'Neal said. ``If there was a way for
one person to do everything by himself, I would've had five rings
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers need Bryant to provide scoring and for Rice to hit
from the perimeter. They also need to find a reliable power forward
and for the other pieces to fit snugly. But if they are to reach
the apex of Jackson's expectations, O'Neal has to be the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make a prediction regarding him,'' Lakers
executive vice president Jerry West said. ``I think he's going to
be the Most Valuable Player in the league this year. I see a
tremendous enthusiasm on his part. He's as happy as I've seen him
since he has been in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have to believe an awful lot of that is that he believes
in what his coach is trying to do, and more importantly, he feels
that this system will allow him to reach his goal _ and that's to
win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   To do so, Jackson's offense must be assimilated. Precision is a
necessity. ``Eventually,'' Bryant said, ``the offense will come to
the point where it's not a matter of reading one another; it's a
matter of all of us reading the defense. It's not that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``You have to find a way to figure out your own
game in it. If you're a good player and a professional, you'll be
able to do that. This is not that difficult to do. I make people
adjust to what we're doing rather than adjusting my system to who
they are. Right now, I'm just in the process of trying to bend
their will to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal will be the axis. ``Now you have a dominant-sized person
in the post where you can always throw the ball,'' Jackson said.
``We used to manipulate to get Michael to the post by taking our
post guy out and bringing Michael in to give him open spaces to
work in the post. Now it's simply, get the big guy down the court,
get the ball inside and give him operating space to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ball, O'Neal has to determinewhen to score, when to
pass. And it's not like he's been heralded as a great assist man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to drop it off to my guys for assists, I don't mind
doing that,'' O'Neal insisted. ``Because in this lifetime, in this
sport, it's all about winning. When you're winning, nothing else
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   How the Lakers develop will be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be very interesting,'' Harper said. ``One thing I know
is that we have the coach to get us there. We'll have to see how
these kids respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
