<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-NBATREND-COX     10-30 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBATREND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New rule against hand, body checks tilts balance for offenses
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There will be unmistakable change in the East. Change in the
power structure, change in the way teams are put together and
change in the way the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   The old Neanderthal style has been legislated out of existence.
Thugs will no longer rule the paint. Speed and quickness and daring
will be rewarded in the new NBA, and change will be more keenly
felt in the East where the likes of Bill Laimbeer, Rick Mahorn and
Charles Oakley once ruled through sheer intimidation and a modicum
of athletic skill.
</P>
<P>
   The league decided in June that the paying customers had had
enough and that a game that penalized skill and rewarded loutish
behavior would be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The results are palpable. Coach Rick Pitino was right two years
ago when he brought a trapping, running game to Boston. Pitino
lacked the players and his system went too far, but his instincts
to speed up the game were right on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   What the Knicks accomplished in the playoffs, making it to the
Finals with the athletic Latrell Sprewell, Allan Houston and Marcus
Camby, only put the concept of speed ball over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 1/2 months after being routed by New York, the Hawks have
seven new players and junked their stilted halfcourt offense by
ejecting guards Mookie Blaylock and Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   At Detroit, they are so committed to the fast break they brought
in an assistant coach, Mo McHone, to teach it. A face from the
1980s, McHone honed his philosophy in San Antonio at the end of an
era during which Doug Moe and Stan Albeck coached a jack rabbit
running game.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando junked three-fourths of its team. Cleveland dumped coach
Mike Fratello and his chess board attack. Milwaukee will run
without a true center as anchor. The New Jersey Nets will latch on
to Stephon Marbury's flying sneakers. And we all have seen the
havoc Allen Iverson can wreak in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The rules now are about players like Iverson, their great speed
and enormous athletic skills and about something called Personal
Foul Rule 12, Section B.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what it says: ``A player shall not hold, push, charge
into, or impede the progress of an opponent by extending a hand,
forearm, leg or knee or by bending the body into a position that is
not normal.... Contact that results in the re-routing of an
opponent is a foul which must be called immediately. Contact
initited by the defensive player guarding a player with the ball
is not legal. This contact includes, but is not limited to,
forearm, hands, or body check.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: You can't ride an opposing player off a pick or
push him away. You can prevent an opponent from setting a pick. You
can't bump an opponent if he's going through the lane. Hands off.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to read Rule 12 again because the few sentences
have changed the way basketball is played in the East, reformatting
the game to the Western style best implemented by the ``Showtime''
Lakers, Cotton Fitzsimmons' old Phoenix Suns and Moe's old Denver
Nuggets. They would play defense, but they wouldn't have to knock
you down to do it. And once they had the ball, they would run so
fast that shoes would smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetics of the new game appeals to Charlotte coach Paul
Silas. ``I like it very much,'' he said. ``For too long, coaches
have tried harder to stop their opponents from scoring than scoring
themselves, and that philosophy needed to change. What bothers me
is this: If you can't touch him, how can you stop Allen Iverson?''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Pitino asks, ``If you're guarding Stephon Marbury in the
open court, how are you going to stop him if you can't put your
hands on him?''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should you penalize talent and quickness?'' Hawks general
manger Pete Babcock said. ``Those are qualities that should be
rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino says there is no question the advantage has shifted to
offense. ``Every coach, in their minds, thinks the new rules are
going to change the game, and what you have to do is speed it up to
take advantage. Everybody is playing racehorse basketball to get
them in the open court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to stop (scorers) is to play five on three, three on
one, but still, the heavy, heavy advantage is open-court offense.
If you're guarding Brevin Knight and you can't put your hand on
him, how do you stop him? You have to stop him with multiple
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dikembe Mutombo of the Hawks says you stop people ``by using
your feet, by making your rotations and getting help. If you're not
going to move your feet, you aren't going to stop anybody because
you can't put your hands on them. That's what coach (Lenny Wilkens)
has been preaching to us. That's what we worked on in camp.''
</P>
<P>
   But change has been painful throughout the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is getting used to no hands on defense,'' Silas
said. ``It's kind of unnatural. They're used to using the forearm,
the hand-checking, for so long.'' He said he will help his players
deal with it, that after watching film from the '70s he is
``appalled'' by the brutality he saw in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the brave, new world of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
