<HEADER>
A3401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-RIDER31-COX     10-30 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RIDER31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider: `I never harm anyone'
 &HT;    'By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Isaiah ``J.R.'' Rider wants something from this town.
He wants a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't judge me until you know me, Rider says. Don't make
assumptions about me.
</P>
<P>
   Rider admits he's no angel. Trouble follows him as surely as
rain follows heavy clouds, only in Rider's case it's an annoying
drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   He has a record of misdemeanors, not felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not now, nor have I ever been, a gang-banger. I've never
committed a serious crime. I've never hurt anyone with the mistakes
I've made. The harm is self-inflicted,'' he said. ``There are
players in our league who have done more than I have, got caught
with a lot more than a half a joint of marijuana, so...
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I've made my mistakes. I would like to judge me on what
I do now.''
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Rider wants you to know he's never done heavy drugs, never
been arrested or DUI. He doesn't hang out in the clubs. ``I don't
have children all over the country. I'm single and I don't have
children.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants you to know that at 28 he is a bright young man, that
he has an intellectual curiosity. He grew up poor in Oakland and he
climbed out of poverty alongside his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family is successful,'' he said. ``I have two brothers and
three sisters who are successful.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Michelle, has a master's in economics from
Northwestern. She is in marketing with Coca-Cola and does some work
for Rider. A brother, Lamond, has a college degree. Another
brother, David, played football a year for the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Rider wants you to know he's a regular guy. ``I never turned my
back on my friends when I became successful. Is that bad? I don't
hide in a mansion up in the hills. Is that bad? I got into some
stuff young guys get into, OK. I made mistakes young guys make. I
admit that. But I feel I've grown from that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He still has a problem with punctuality, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm late a lot, but it's something I'm working on. But I never
harm anyone else. People need to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Better still, Rider does good for people. If you don't know
that, it's because he has never made much of an effort to tell the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought the media cared about what I do in that
regard,'' he said. ``I never wanted it out because when I do
something it's not for the attention. It's not so people will like
me or so I can get a big basketball contract. I've got money and if
I want to spend some of it helping people, that's between me and
them. I do it because it makes me feel good. I do it from my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, Rider has entered in partnership with Oakland Mayor
Jerry Brown to build and equip two recreation centers so
poverty-level youth have some place to go. He said he will coax
Portland Trail Blazers owner Paul Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft,
to donate computers for his rec centers. ``We want to set up
after-school programs, places to study.''
</P>
<P>
   While playing in Portland, Rider bought a bus and used it to
transport 30 kids to every Blazers home game, where they used
tickets he paid for. He worked out a deal with a local McDonald's
and a Mexican restaurant to feed them. Now that he's in Atlanta,
Rider said he and the Hawks are going into partnership, supplying
25 tickets each game to kids, and he hopes to have his bus shipped
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going in with the Boys (&AMP; Girls) Club or any other
organization. I want to pick the kids myself,'' he said. ``I want
to bring some happiness to poor kids, kids who have holes in their
jeans and holes in their shoes. White kids, black kids. Doesn't
matter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, he became unofficial big brother to young
Sheena McCullum, who had lost her mother. He helped her become a
Blazers ball girl. With pride, he notes, ``She's 16 and class
president and a good basketball player. Financially, when she needs
something, I look out for her.''
</P>
<P>
   So, balance this with the Rider who can't show up on time, who
has a record for skirmishes, and decide how the scales weigh out.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates admire Rider
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Rider teammate, or an ex-teammate, you give him more
than the benefit of doubt. You give him admiration for his skills,
loyalty for his friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been knowing J.R. since we were in high school, from Nike
camp,'' former and current teammate Jim Jackson says. ``It's sad
that his mistakes are what everybody talks about because he's a
good person, bright and funny and a great player. If he's on your
team, you've got to admire him.''
</P>
<P>
   Celtics guard Kenny Anderson, who playedtwo seasons with Rider,
describes him as ``a guy who really gets it done. He commands a
double team and he's a really good passer. He was great to play
with because of that. He's the ultimate `two' guard in this league,
as far as I'm concerned. He doesn't have anything to prove. He's
already up there with the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Richmond of the Wizards was a Rookie of the Year guard
with Golden State when he befriended Rider, then a high school
senior ineligible to play ball because he lost interest in his
studies. Richmond had been a star at Kansas State and he knew his
school was recruiting Rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out he was in Oakland so I tracked him down,''
Richmond said. ``We hit it off. I used to take him to a bunch of
scrimmages some of the Warriors and guys out in Oakland would have
in the summertime. He was up against some good players, guys like
Sarunas Marciulionis, and he held his own.''
</P>
<P>
   His senior year in high school, Rider loved being recruited. ``I
enjoyed it so much I stopped paying attention to classes,'' he
said. ``That's why I couldn't go right to K-State. I had to go to
junior college.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent a year in Kansas, averaged 31 points at Allen Community
College, and realized he didn't really want to be in the nation's
heartland, far from his friends and family. He transferred to
Antelope Community College in Southern California, averaged 33.6,
and went on to Nevada-Las Vegas. As a senior, he averaged 29.1.
Minnesota grabbed him with the fifth pick of the 1993 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't ready for me,'' Rider said. Nor was he ready for
them. The stormy relationship ran three years. The team was losing
and Rider was wandering into trouble off the court while playing
well for a terrible team. The Wolves swapped him to Portland. ``I
don't have to put up with this'' anymore, said an exasperated Kevin
McHale, the Wolves' general manager, after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Rider's record of off-court contretemps continued, but this time
he was part of a winning organization and last season the Blazers
went to the Western Conference finals before San Antonio demolished
them in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Success triggered Rider's best instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I was a guy who needed to be with a winner,'' he
said. ``Scoring 25 points a game didn't matter to me. I didn't need
that. I needed winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Loved playing in Portland
</P>
<P>
   Jackson noted the change. ``We both realized that if we
sacrificed, we would be successful,'' he said. ``When that happens,
you learn a lot. You learn how to carry yourself and how to be
professional and how to win basketball games. Deep down inside,
J.R. realized that was his ultimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider wanted so much to remain in Portland that he refused to
exercise his option for free agency, accepting the seventh year of
his contract at $5.4 million. The Blazers seized on that chance to
move him at minimal risk to the buyer, and Rider and Jackson became
Hawks in exchange for Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The trade weighed heavily on Rider. He says he was two days late
coming to training camp because of his doubts about the Hawks,
their commitment to winning and their ability to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of that. I had sacrificed my game to win in
Portland,'' he said. ``I had become part of a winning team and,
look, I know all about how this is a business. But for me it got
very personal. And now, I wasn't part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He still isn't sure this will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we have enough scorers to go with me and J.J.
I know don't know if Coach (Lenny Wilkens) is willing to play us
together like I want him to because that's our best team. So,
there's a lot we have to find out about, see how it works. But,
yeah, I feel a lot better about it than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   And he looks forward to the challenge of being in the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing against (Latrell) Sprewell. I've had some of my
biggest games against him. And against Mitch because he's my
mentor. He's a friend of mine. Allan Houston, Vince Carter coming
into his own, Reggie Miller. I want to show the East Coast what a
West Coast guy has.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
