<P>
   CENTRAL DIVISION
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE HORNETS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 26-24.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Paul Silas, 1st full season, 22-13 as interim coach in
1999; 4th season overall, 100-181.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft -- Baron Davis (3rd), Lee Nailon (43rd); free
agent -- Todd Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Chuckie Brown (San Antonio).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Elden Campbell, Derrick Coleman, Ricky Davis, Eddie
Jones, Anthony Mason, Brad Miller, Bobby Phills, Eldridge Recasner,
David Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Tough inside, able to score quickly and from the wings,
the Hornets can be very good. Certainly, they are headed back to
the playoffs, and they have a real chance to overhaul Indiana for
the division title.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA PACERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 33-17, eliminated in third round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Larry Bird, 3rd season, 91-41.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Trade -- Jeff Foster, Jonathan Bender.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Antonio Davis (Toronto), Fred Hoiberg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Travis Best, Austin Croshere, Dale Davis, Al Harrington,
Mark Jackson, Derrick McKey, Reggie Miller, Chris Mullin, Sam
Perkins, Mark Pope, Jalen Rose, Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Old and older. This is the last dance for the Pacers.
Bird's leaving, and Jackson, Miller, Perkins, Mullin, et al. are in
the declining years of their careers. Although still a factor, they
have missed their chance at a championship.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND CAVALIERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 22-28, missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Randy Wittman, first season as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft -- Andre Miller (8th), Trajan Langdon (11th);
trade -- Lamond Murray; free agent -- Mark Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Corie Blount (Phoenix), Derek Anderson (LA Clippers),
Johnny Newman (LA Clippers).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Andrew DeClercq, Danny Ferry, Cedric Henderson, Zydrunas
Ilgauskas, Shawn Kemp, Brevin Knight, Wesley Person, Bob Sura.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Can Ilgauskus play a full year without injury? Can
Kemp diet? Can Wittman coach? If those and other questions are
answered in the affirmative, the Cavs have a chance to be the
surprise of the East.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA HAWKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 31-19, eliminated in second round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Lenny Wilkens, seventh season with Hawks, 282-178; 27th
season overall, 1,151-927.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft -- Jason Terry (10th), Cal Bowdler (17th),
Dion Glover (20th); trade -- Bimbo Coles, Jim Jackson, Isaiah
Rider, Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Tyrone Corbin (Sacramento), Grant Long (Vancouver),
Mookie Blaylock (Golden St.), Ed Gray (Portland), Steve Smith
(Portland).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Chris Crawford LaPhonso Ellis, Alan Henderson, Anthony
Johnson, Roshown McLeod, Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Unsettled at the point, unable to sustain a
half-court offense in the preseason, the Hawks could struggle early
and then come on with a rush in the second half of the season -- if
they come on at all.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 28-22, eliminated in first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: George Karl, 2nd season with Bucks, 28-22; 13th season
overall, 531-348.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Trade -- Dale Ellis, Danny Manning; free agent --
Darvin Ham, J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Dell Curry (Toronto), Michael Curry (Detroit), Chris
Gatling (Orlando), Armen Gilliam (Orlando).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Ray Allen, Sam Cassell, Vinny Del Negro, Ervin Johnson,
Glenn Robinson, Tim Thomas, Robert Traylor, Scott Williams,
Haywoode Workman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Bucks remain very soft in the middle. Typical of
a George Karl team, they have perimeter offense and a knack for
running, but they have to be tougher inside defensively. Still a
fringe playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO RAPTORS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 23-27, missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Butch Carter, second full season with Raptors, 28-55.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft -- Alek Radojevic (12th); trade -- Antonio
Davis; free agent -- Dell Curry, Muggsy Bogues
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Paul Rogers, Micheal Williams, John Wallace (New York)
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Dee Brown, Vince Carter, Doug Christie, Sean Marks,
Tracy McGrady, Charles Oakley, Michael Stewart, John Thomas, Alvin
Williams, Kevin Willis
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Raptors aren't going to take a great leap without
a very good guard. Unless Radojevic is ready, the depth at power
forward -- Willis, Oakley, Stewart, Davis -- will spill into the
middle. A real playoff chance, however.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT PISTONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 29-21, eliminated in first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Alvin Gentry, 2nd full season with Pistons, 45-42; 4th
season overall, 60-63.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: free agents -- Michael Curry, Terry Mills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Bison Dele, Joe Dumars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Jud Buechler, Bison Dele, Grant Hill, Lindsey Hunter,
Christian Laettner, Eric Montross, Don Reid, Jerry Stackhouse, Loy
Vaught, Jerome Williams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Two starters retired, and the Pistons are learning
how to run. It's hard to see them as much better than last season's
No. 5 finish in the East. The forwards can rebound, but can the
guards shoot?
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO BULLS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 13-37, missed playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Tim Floyd, 2nd season with Bulls, 13-37; 2nd season
overall, 13-37.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft -- Elton Brand (1st), Ron Artest (16th),
Michael Ruffin (32nd), Lari Ketner (49th); trade -- James Cotton,
Hersey Hawkins, Chris Anstey; free agent -- B.J. Armstrong, Fred
Hoiberg, Will Perdue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Ron Harper, Keith Booth, Mark Bryant (Cleveland), Bill
Wennington (Sacramento), Brent Barry (Seattle), Andrew Lang (New
York).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Corey Benjamin, Randy Brown, Kornel David, Toni Kukoc,
Rusty LaRue, Dickey Simpkins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Bulls have gone to ruin, and the fans, locked in
on season tickets and suites, are growing restless. Bringing back
Armstrong and Perdue won't make a significant difference in the
standings.
</P>
