</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA CAPSULES
 &HT;    MIDWEST DIVISION
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO SPURS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 37-13, won NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Gregg Popovich, fourth year with the Spurs, 110-86.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Free agents _ Terry Porter, Samaki Walker, Felton
Spencer, Chucky Brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Will Perdue (Chicago).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Antonio Daniels, Tim Duncan, Mario Elie, Sean Elliott,
Jaren Jackson, Avery Johnson, Steve Kerr, Jerome Kersey, David
Robinson, Malik Rose.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Duncan was so good as the Spurs won their first title
that they were able to disguise a very ordinary backcourt. Porter
helps a little, but it will take another magnificent year from
Duncan to get close to a championship.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 37-13, eliminated in second round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Jerry Sloan, 12th year with the Jazz, 582-271, 15th
year overall, 676-392.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft _ Quincy Lewis (19th), Scott Padgett (28th);
free agents _ Olden Polynice, Pete Chilcutt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Shandon Anderson (Houston), Greg Foster (Seattle), Todd
Fuller (Charlotte).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Howard Eisley, Adam Keefe, Karl Malone, Jeff Hornacek,
John Stockton, Greg Ostertag, Bryon Russell, Jacque Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The bell may have tolled for this bunch, but they
will make one more magnificent run at it. However, this is probably
the end for the Jazz. Rebuilding will be a long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON ROCKETS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 31-19, eliminated in first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Rudy Tomjanovich, ninth year with the Rockets, 353-219.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft _ Kenny Thomas (22nd); trade _ Steve Francis,
Don MacLean, Tony Massenberg, Carlos Rogers, Walt Williams, Kelvin
Cato; free agent _ Shandon Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Scottie Pippin (Portland), Antoine Carr (Vancouver),
Michael Dickerson (Vancouver), Othella Harrington (Vancouver),
Brent Price (Vancouver), Sam Mack, Pig Miller.
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Charles Barkley, Matt Bullard, Bryce Drew, Eddie
Johnson, Matt Maloney, Cuttino Mobley, Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: This latest reincarnation of the Rockets presents yet
another last chance for Barkley to get a title. They're going to
join the new NBA roadrunner club. Anderson, Francis, Williams and
Cato will help.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA TIMBERWOLVES
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 25-25, eliminated in first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Flip Sanders, fifth year with the Timberwolves,
130-146.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft _ Wally Szczerbiak (6th), William Avery
(14th).
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Dennis Scott (Vancouver), James Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Terrell Brandon, Kevin Garnett, Dean Garrett, Tom
Hammonds, Bobby Jackson, Sam Mitchell, Radoslav Nesterovic, Andrae
Patterson, Anthony Peeler, Malik Sealy, Joe Smith.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: The Wolves can't advance unless they get stronger in
the middle, and center Dean Garrett will miss part of the season
with injury. Szcerbiak and Avery make this a very deep team on the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER NUGGETS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 14-36, missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Dan Issel, fourth year with the Nuggets, 96-102.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft _ James Posey (18th), Chris Herren (33rd);
trade _ Popeye Jones, Ron Mercer, Dwayne Schintzius; free agents _
George McCloud.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Trade, Danny Fortson (Boston), Eric Washington (Boston),
Eric Williams (Boston).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Cory Alexander, Chauncey Billups, Keon Clark, Raef
LaFrentz, Antonio McDyess, Bryant Stith, Johnny Taylor, Nick Van
Exel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: This is an interesting team, as Issel retakes the
coaching reins. With Mercer joining Van Exel, the Nuggets have
undeniable fire power. If they can keep a steady course, they'll
challenge for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER GRIZZLIES
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 8-42, missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Brian Hill, third year with the Grizzlies, 27-105;
seventh year overall, 218-209.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Draft _ Obinna Ekezie (37th); trade _ Antoine Carr,
Michael Dickerson, Othella Harrington, Brent Price; free agents _
Grant Long, Dennis Scott, Robert Werdann.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Steve Francis (Houston), Tony Massenburg (Houston), Lee
Mayberry (Orlando), Makhtar Ndiaye (Orlando), Rodrick Rhodes
(Orlando), Michael Smith (Orlando).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Shareef Abdur-Rahim, Mike Bibby, Felipe Lopez, Cherokee
Parks, Bryant Reeves, Doug West.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: They have improved, but not enough to make a
significant difference in their standing in the West.
Realistically, the Grizzlies will meet you in St. Louis long before
you see them in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS MAVERICKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: 19-31, missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Don Nelson, third season with Mavericks, 35-81; 22nd
season overall, 886-710.
</P>
<P>
   _ Newcomers: Trade _ Leon Smith, Sean Rooks; free agents _ Greg
Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone: Samaki Walker (San Antonio), A.C. Green (Los Angeles),
Chris Anstey (Chicago).
</P>
<P>
   _ Back: Shawn Bradley, Cedric Ceballos, Hubert Davis, Michael
Finley, Steve Nash, Dirk Nowitzki, Robert Pack, Erick Strickland,
Bruno Sundov, Gary Trent, John Williams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: In his final year as coach, Nelson wants them quick
and lean. Sounds good, but the Mavericks have a very weak front
line, and it will prevent them from winning more than 40 percent of
their games.
</P>
<P>
