<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-OSLO-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AFTER A GALLOP, MIDEAST LEADERS FEAR THE TALKS HAVE
STALLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak steamrolled into office
with grand plans of forging a permanent Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreement by next September. Stopwatches were set at the blow of
his whistle. And then, after an uplifting summit meeting early this
fall, almost two months yawned by without a single official
negotiating session.
</P>
<P>
   For a peace effort interrupted so many times by spasms of
violence, a little lull might not seem cause for concern. So much
is happening so quickly on the ground: Israel's transfer of land,
release of prisoners and opening of a safe-passage route between
the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, U.S. officials, and even
some Israelis have begun worrying that peacemaking momentum is
slowing from a gallop to a saunter. Barak's ambitious aspiration to
reach a framework agreement for a final status by February _
resolving huge discrepancies on sensitive issues ranging from
settlements to Jerusalem _ may soon appear foolhardy, they say.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, even though Barak's Jerusalem office and Arafat's
Ramallah office lie 10 miles apart, the two Middle East leaders are
jetting off to Oslo to meet President Clinton for a chat by the
fjords on Monday and Tuesday. Clinton is once again being handed a
catalytic role in the peace process, through a tacit agreement
between three parties whose motivations are all different.
</P>
<P>
   The president wants to secure a legacy as the arbiter of a final
Israeli-Palestinian peace. Barak, despite his desire to convert the
trilateral relationship to a bilateral one, wants the United States
to feel central so that a reluctant Congress will release $1.2
billion in promised aid. And Arafat, whose ties with the United
States were profitably strengthened under Barak's right-wing
predecessor, does not see an advantage to being alone at the table
with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no real negotiations in Oslo, no possibility
of a new agreement and little likelihood of a crisis. Instead, the
meeting will serve as one more confidence-building session between
the parties, resonantly synchronized with a memorial service on
Tuesday for Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister who was assassinated
four years ago by a right-wing Jewish extremist.
</P>
<P>
   With transparent symbolism, it will also be a return to Oslo,
where the original peace accord was forged and where Rabin, Arafat
and Shimon Peres, now the minister of regional development,
received the Nobel Peace Prize five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, although he is happy to ``exchange views,'' did not
initiate the meeting and does not consider it essential to the
process, his spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton can be very helpful, but let's remember the
basic facts,'' Gadi Baltiansky, the spokesman, said. ``The dates
were set by Barak. He decided. He doesn't need anyone to push him.
On the contrary, people criticize him because he is running too
fast, pushing others too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, by contrast, speak about the need to
``revive'' a broken-down peace effort once more. In fact, they have
dropped their public expression of good will toward Barak, which
reached a peak with the signing of a new deal in Egypt in early
September. While Barak has fulfilled some of his obligations, they
say, he has also ``spit in our faces,'' as one official said, by
authorizing new construction at many settlements in the West Bank
and legitimizing some new outposts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything possible to restore our partnership and our
trust,'' Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian official, said on Friday
night, his voice exuding irritation. ``And not only have the peace
talks not begun, but we are witnessing an unprecedented escalation
of settlements and land confiscation activity that makes such talks
meaningless anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the very scheduling of the three-way meeting seemed to
spur action, if not reconciliation. This week began poorly.
Tensions flared over sovereignty in Jerusalem as Israeli security
officers, who were denied access to a British-Palestinian
diplomatic meeting, ringed the American Colony Hotel in the Arab
part of the city. A three-day battle between Palestinian youths and
Israeli soldiers raged in Bethlehem, beaming worldwide the old
images of renewed conflict.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, Barak, with the deadline of Oslo upon
him, finally appointed a chief negotiator, Oded Eran, the
ambassador to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian negotiator, Yasser Abed Rabbo, whom the Israelis
consider incendiary, scoffed at Eran's appointment as ``not
serious.'' But by Friday, the two were ensconced in a suite at the
King David Hotel in Jerusalem, from which they emerged to announce
that a first formal negotiating session would be held on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   In the routine damping of expectations that precedes summit
meetings, most officials are saying that just such a result might
ensue after Oslo too: the scheduling of yet another meeting date,
this one at Camp David early next year. Additionally, a road map or
timetable might be established for the months ahead. But the real
purpose of the gathering, they say, is to work, once again, on the
intangibles, the trust between the parties that is essential to
transverse chasms on so many issues.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The situation is complex. Barak, a former general who operates
with military precision, does little unintentionally, and many find
it difficult to believe that he delayed the start of final status
negotiations unwittingly. Rather, he is marching with deliberation
to his own rhythm, tuning out Palestinian anxieties with the
certainty that they will understand his good intentions in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did spend _ ``waste,'' one of his ministers said _ a good
deal of time trying unsuccessfully to arrange legal grounds to
appoint a private attorney, Gilad Scher, to head the final status
talks.
</P>
<P>
   But his lack of haste reflected a tactic, too. Barak chose to
negotiate with Israel first, his advisers say. He sought to avoid
the traps that snared Rabin, his mentor. He wanted to move more
cautiously and moderately toward the same goal: the ``peace with
security'' of a general turned peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   On the settlements, for instance, he secured the unprecedented
cooperation of the settlers themselves to dismantle 12 illegal
hilltop outposts. In exchange, he agreed to legalize 30 others. He
considers it the price of building a constituency to support a
final peace agreement that will involve concessions many Israelis
consider wrenching. But the Palestinians, outraged, see it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digging in settlements means deepening the occupation at the
very time we are negotiating on the basis of exchanging land for
peace,'' said Nabil Shaath, the planning minister. ``I believe
Barak is a serious person and totally different from his
predecessor. So far the implementation has gone on schedule, if a
bit late. But on this we don't see eye to eye. I call it a
bittersweet situation, whereas it was all bitter before.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In four meetings with his ministers in the last two weeks, Barak
has led a volatile philosophical discussion on the future
relationship between Israel and the Palestinian entity. The
ministers have debated what they call a final separation from the
Palestinians, a concept that worries both the Americans and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose advisers now routinely quote him quoting Robert
Frost, repeatedly says that ``good fences make good neighbors.'' He
wants to build security zones, with literal fences, between Israeli
and Palestinian populated areas. This would be to protect Israel
from both terrorism and ordinary crime like car thefts. Barak also
thinks the Palestinian territories should be connected by a complex
series of bypass roads, with an elevated highway linking the West
Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Barak supports what sounds like a Palestinian state, with its
own currency and its own trade relationships with other countries.
There could be a free trade zone with Israel, he says, and a goal
to reduce the number of Palestinian laborers in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The debates about separation are laying the groundwork for
Israel's positions in the final status talk. The Palestinians are
not publicly preparing any working papers on the issues, which
their public understands as fixed positions that have not changed.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Barak repeatedly stresses, the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict is 100 years old, and each party's positions are well
established and well known to the other. To reach a framework
agreement, he says, essentially takes some cold-blooded
decision-making by the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need months for that,'' Baltiansky said. ``You need
courage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
