A3434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICH-JUVENILE-TRIAL-6     10-30 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-JUVENILE-TRIAL-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER TRIAL OF 13-YEAR-OLD SPOTLIGHTS MICHIGAN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Two years to the day after an 11-year-old boy
fatally shot a stranger walking out of a convenience store, opening
statements were made Friday in his trial on a charge of
first-degree murder, in a case that is drawing attention to
Michigan's tough 3-year-old juvenile justice law.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Nathaniel Abraham, who is now 13, is being tried as an
adult here in this northern suburb of Detroit. Prosecutors say that
he has a surprisingly long history of encounters with the police
and had talked about shooting someone.
</P>
<P>
   But court-appointed psychologists say that Nathaniel has
below-average intelligence and emotional difficulties, notably in
controlling anger.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel's lawyers contend that the shooting was an accident.
In any case, they say, the boy was not mature enough to understand
the seriousness of shooting someone, much less plan a killing.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel, a slim boy of about 5 feet, sat quietly in Oakland
County Circuit Court during opening statements, wearing a green and
white checked shirt and dark trousers.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, he could be sentenced to life in prison without
parole, although prosecutors have expressed a willingness to seek a
lesser sentence in which he would be confined in a juvenile
detention center until the age of 21 and then resentenced if he
showed inadequate signs of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening statements in the family division of the court,
prosecutors portrayed Nathaniel as a calculating criminal who told
a girl at school that he would kill someone and then did so.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel, who has been held in a juvenile detention center
since the shooting, is also being tried on a charge of assault with
intent to murder. Prosecutors say he fired a borrowed .22-caliber
rifle at a neighbor four hours before going out on a steep hillside
with the rifle and fatally shooting the stranger, Ronnie Greene
Jr., who was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel appears to be the youngest child ever charged as an
adult with murder in Michigan, and one of the youngest ever in the
United States, although children as young as 7 were tried as adults
in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel's case is also one of the most unusual to reach a
courtroom since Republican lawmakers in Michigan adopted one of the
toughest juvenile justice laws in the nation in 1996. The law
allows prosecutors to seek judges' permission to try any juvenile
as an adult, no matter how young. Prosecutors sought and received
this permission in Nathaniel's case.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1996 law, Michigan had required that juveniles be at
least 14 before being tried as adults with a judge's permission.
The state has long required that youths of 17 or older be tried
automatically as adults, unlike many states or the federal
government, which set 18 as the age for automatic consideration as
an adult in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Republicans had not expected a child as young as
Nathaniel to be tried as an adult for murder when the law was
enacted, said Thomas Ginster, the criminal-justice policy
coordinator for Gov. John Engler, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were doing the research,'' Ginster said, ``we found a
few scattered 13-year-olds committing capital crimes, but I don't
think we ever saw an 11-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Fieger, Nathaniel's lawyer, said Friday in court that
the boy had been shooting at trees in the fatal shooting as well as
when the neighbor came under fire. Though Fieger acknowledged that
Nathaniel had fired the shot that killed Greene, he contended that
the distance of the shot, at least 200 feet, was too far for
accuracy with the battered, low-caliber weapon missing its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger also contends that the prosecution may be partly
motivated by race, an accusation denied by prosecutors. Nathaniel
is black, as was Greene. A 14-year-old white boy is said to have
been shooting with Nathaniel when bullets flew past the neighbor,
but was not with Nathaniel at the time of the fatal shooting and
has not been charged with any crime. The boy is expected to testify
for the prosecution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jury selection took nearly two weeks, partly because a
prospective juror in the first pool of 75 said he recalled a
``run-in'' with Nathaniel. The pool was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac police records show that by age 11, Nathaniel had been a
suspect in nearly two dozen crimes, including two beatings with
metal pipes, an arson incident and a burglary, and had twice been
placed in special programs after using guns to threaten other
elementary school students.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are expected to ask the judge in the case, Judge
Eugene Moore, to instruct the jurors that they can find Nathaniel
guilty of lesser offenses than first-degree murder. But Fieger said
in an interview Friday that he would ask that the jury not be given
that option, adding that he expected all charges to be dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
