<P>
   IRAN _ TEHRAN, Iran _ For Iranians, the takeover of the U.S.
Embassy 20 years ago this week (Nov. 4) is their Bunker Hill; their
Boston Tea Party. It galvanized their revolutionary fervor as they
took on the ``Den of Spies'' that had helped install and support
the brutal, dictatorial Shah. The takeover symbolized a revolution
that changed the atmosphere of the Middle East and helped create
now-familiar buzzwords like ``Islamic fundamentalism'' and
``Hezbollah.'' And, it shocked the West into realizing that
religion was still a force in world politics. (Just a year before
the revolution, Jimmy Carter called Iran ``an island of
stability.'') Today in Iran, the takeover highlights the country's
identity crisis. Any criticism of the takeover is still
controversial. But the radical fervor has long been cast aside as
most Iranians who seek a new pragmatism and freedom. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service)..
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REFORM _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Some of those involved in the
embassy takeover, and President Mohammad Khatami, have tried to
move U.S.-Iranian relations carefully forward. The gift shop that
sold souvenirs fromn the takeover has long ago closed and many of
the former hostage takers are risking their freedom now trying to
open up the closed Iranian system that the embassy takeover helped
create. A profile of a former hostage taker. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
