<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORLEANS-CASINO-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASINO IS A HIGH-RISK ENTERPRISE FOR NEW ORLEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Nev., N.J., Conn.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The first of the nightly Mardi Gras parades wound
its way through a vast new windowless casino on Thursday night, its
costumed stilt walkers dancing past the carefully re-created French
Quarter and Garden District, past Pete Fountain and his clarinet
and buffet tables heaped with jambalaya, but hundreds of people
never even looked up.
</P>
<P>
   If it was merriment they wanted, the old playground of the real
French Quarter was only steps away, outside the building. But in
their high-stakes games of baccarat and blackjack, they had found a
new, more absorbing form of adult entertainment in New Orleans, and
the city is fervently hoping that they bet again and again, 24
hours a day, every day of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi, watch out!'' cried Mayor Marc Morial in a
ribbon-cutting warning to the nation's other casino homelands, just
before the new Harrah's casino opened its doors to the public late
Thursday. ``Las Vegas, watch out! Atlantic City, watch out!
Harrah's New Orleans is here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Full-scale gambling, in the city's first permanent land-based
casino, has indeed come to New Orleans, wedged perfectly into a
large downtown lot between the French Quarter and the Mississippi
River, a few blocks from the convention center. But the mayor's
need to make an audacious declaration of permanence underscored
just how difficult it has been to get those doors open, and how
much of a risk has been taken by the city and the casino's owner.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows if the 11 million tourists who visit New
Orleans each year will want to gamble, or if the extravagant
evocation of the city's flamboyance inside the walls of the $345
million Harrah's will distinguish it from the growing glut of
riverboat casinos, Indian casinos and resort casinos around the
country. No one knows whether it will settle into the city's
business landscape as a major employer and attraction, or whether
it will in some way alter the delicate character that has drawn
visitors to New Orleans for ages.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling's recent history in the city has raised some doubts
about its future. The state Legislature first approved a single
land-based casino in New Orleans in 1992, a few years after it
allowed riverboat casinos, video poker machines and a state
lottery. While Harrah's began building its permanent structure in
1995, it opened a temporary casino in the city's Municipal
Auditorium, to great fanfare. Before seven months were out, the
owners realized that revenues were only a third of the necessary
$33 million a month. In a humiliating bankruptcy, the temporary
casino closed in November 1995, and work on the new building
halted.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's now says the failure was the result of the auditorium's
out-of-the-way location, next to a public housing project, and says
the new casino's premier site and opulent interior will improve its
fortunes. But three riverboat casinos that were moored near
downtown have also failed, raising the question of whether New
Orleans can ever be a wholehearted gambling town.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't come here to gamble,'' said Raphael Cassimere, a
history professor at the University of New Orleans who is an expert
on the city's past. ``They come here for a convention, or to go to
the restaurants and the French Quarter. The big gamblers go where
there are lots of casinos, like Las Vegas or Atlantic City. I think
it's far from settled whether this casino will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   During the reorganization of the local holding company that owns
the casino, of which Harrah's Entertainment Inc. is a 43 percent
shareholder, several large casinos opened on the gulf coast of
Mississippi, drawing heavily from nearby New Orleans. Those
casinos, as well as casinos in Nevada and Atlantic City, N.J., have
something the local Harrah's does not: luxurious attached hotels,
restaurants and nightclubs that add a sense of entertainment to
gambling. To get past the objections of New Orleans' powerful
restaurateurs and hoteliers, the Louisiana Legislature required
Harrah's to build a stand-alone casino, with no attached rooms and
limited food service. (A nightclub may eventually open in the
building's second floor.)
</P>
<P>
   It also required $100 million in state tax payments every year
and more than $10 million in annual rent to the city. Gambling
analysts say the casino will have to make about $260 million a year
to pay its taxes and its 2,800 employees, which translates to
14,000 patrons a day losing an average of $50 each. That revenue
projection is about half of what a major casino like the MGM Grand
in Las Vegas takes in every year, but 14,000 gamblers a day would
equal fully half of New Orleans' daily tourist population.
</P>
<P>
   The economic burden is heavy, and Harrah's officials, who will
manage the casino, acknowledge feeling handicapped by the taxes and
rules, compared with the relatively free hand they have at other
casinos. But they are nonetheless convinced their investment will
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have an attached hotel, but we have something the
others don't: New Orleans,'' said Gary Loveman, chief operating
officer of Harrah's Entertainment. ``We're a virtual monopoly here,
and we're the only casino between the East Coast and Nevada with
facilities for our high-end customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the casino's three elaborate Mardi Gras floats, wrought
iron balconies and hand-painted murals are lush private rooms for
gamblers willing to spend $10,000 or more a day on card games,
craps or $500 slot machines. The 100,000-square-foot casino is
already adjacent to the city's most expensive hotels _ whose rooms
will be reduced in price for high rollers _ and nationally known
restaurants are not far away.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the hope for the casino is a general sense that New
Orleans, with its bars, jazz clubs and loose-limbed spirit, already
attracts people who might be prone to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it _ New Orleans is not Orlando,'' said Warren
Reuther, who owns several paddle-wheel tour boats and other tourist
enterprises downtown. ``It's already perceived as an adult city, a
let your hair down and have a good time place. It won't be easy for
them to make money, but I think New Orleans is their biggest
hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a third of the casino's revenues are expected to come
from local residents, Loveman said, meaning the casino will have to
entice millions of the conventioneers and other visitors who come
to the city for other reasons. Some of the tourists gawking at the
starlit purple ceilings on Friday said that they might very well
spend a few hours playing some of the casino's 2,900 slot machines,
which, as in most casinos, dominate the floor. Thousands of
visitors, in fact, crowded into the building on its opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' asked Dr. Morton Weyler of Westbrook, Conn., who
was in town with his wife on a group tour. ``It's all part of the
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics fear that the city is sacrificing a slice of its
authenticity to pay for government services without raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of people enjoying the real sights of New Orleans,
they're asking people to go inside a closed building and look at a
fake New Orleans,'' said C.B. Forgotston Jr., a lawyer who has been
an outspoken opponent of the casino and who predicts it will
eventually beg the state to reduce its tax burden. ``Why would
anyone do that? And if they did, they would just take money away
from existing small businesses. It's no way to run a government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1405EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
