<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-FRIENDS-ART-1110     10-30 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FRIENDS-ART-1110(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE IS FINDING INSIDER IMAGE TOUGH TO SHAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Vice President Al Gore uprooted his campaign
headquarters from K Street and moved to Nashville, Tenn., the
change was intended to distance the campaign from the city's famous
avenue of influence where many of the vice president's advisers
have earned millions of dollars in lobbying fees.
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself was worried that the campaign was perceived as
being too closely connected to several highly paid lobbyists _
lobbyists whose success appeared to be inextricably linked to the
vice president's political fortunes, several senior Gore advisers
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the symbolism of this month's move off K Street,
Gore's closest confidants _ the lobbyists Tom Downey, Peter Knight
and Roy Neel _ have continued to play central roles in his 2000
presidential campaign, even while they have continued to
aggressively lobby members of the administration and, in some
cases, Gore himself, on behalf of their corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   His close relations with lobbyists are part of a deeper
political problem that the vice president faces in his campaign, as
the Democratic challenger, Bill Bradley, continues to portray
himself as a Washington outsider and champion of campaign finance
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a son of a senator who lived in a hotel on Massachusetts
Avenue, and a candidate who is still trying to dispel criticism
about his 1996 fund raising, has been portrayed as a consummate
Washington insider who symbolizes the capital's tolerance for
influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that many of the Gore campaign's leaders, and the vice
president's senior advisers, are connected to K Street and the
capital's culture of money, power and influence has made it hard
for the vice president to shake that image.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, a friend of Gore for nearly 25 years, was investigated
repeatedly by congressional Republicans for his lobbying
activities, including an accusation that he used his influence to
persuade the Federal Communications Commission to move its
headquarters to an office complex owned by one of his clients.
Knight was never charged with any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting the campaign headquarters on K Street was just plain
dumb,'' said a senior Gore adviser who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``You cannot pick a worse place to put the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's senior advisers said that the ``K Street problem'' had
become obvious in recent months, mostly because Gore's campaign
headquarters was within walking distance of the lobbyists' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Downey, known as the vice president's ``first friend'' since
they served together in the House of Representatives, tried more
than once to lobby Gore personally on issues that are important to
his corporate clients, a roster that includes Microsoft and Merck &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been there when Downey has come up to the vice
president to lobby him on some issue,'' recalled another senior
Gore adviser. ``And the vice president had to literally put up his
hand and say, `Tom, I don't want to hear it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Downey did not return several phone calls to his office last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, the press secretary for the campaign, said: ``Tom
has served with Al Gore in the Congress, and he is one of his close
friends. He has on occasion raised specific issues with the vice
president. But the vice president has not taken action as a result
of their conversations that he would not have otherwise taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said that the move to Nashville was more than symbolic.
``It was a real move that represented a real change in direction
for this campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the change of address and direction, Gore's coterie of K
Street friends is still playing an influential, though quiet, role
in his campaign. Many of them raise money for his election effort.
At the same time, they are hired by corporations seeking advice on
how to navigate the legal and regulatory battles they are waging
with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But they are sensitive to the criticism that their private
dealings raise conflicts of interest, and two of the lobbyists have
made arrangements to limit or end their lobbying activities next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the first Democratic debate, in
Hanover, N.H., on Wednesday night, Downey helped prepare the vice
president for the showdown with Bradley, a former senator from New
Jersey. In debate rehearsals, Downey played the role of Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, another close friend of Gore, is overseeing the
campaign's fund-raising activities while he continues to represent
an array of corporate clients, including Bell Atlantic, Lockheed
Martin and Leap Wireless. But in an interview, he said that he
planned to disband his lobbying firm at the end of the year to
allow him to assist Gore's campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been his friend for 23 years,'' Knight said. ``So
putting myself in a position to help out in any way that I can is
the least I can do to help him become president.''
</P>
<P>
   A former chief of staff to Gore, Neel is the president of the
U.S. Telephone Association, where he lobbies the White House on
behalf of the Baby Bells. At the same time, Neel advises Gore and
his staff on telecommunications policy. But Neel said he would also
devote most of his time next year to assisting the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends of Al Gore, and we are not manipulators,'' said
Neel, who makes $500,000 annually as the president of the telephone
association. ``I think I can speak for the entire group. Our
careers, our day-to-day jobs, are important to us, but I don't
think anyone in this group would work on anything that would put Al
Gore at risk, or put him in a bad situation, or do anything that
would reflect poorly on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the potential for conflict of interest is clear, although
Knight and Neel say they are careful not to mix their clients'
interests with their work as campaign volunteers for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign's other two leaders also have some continuing
private business ties. Tony Coelho, the campaign chairman, has
severed his ties with most of his corporate clients, campaign
officials said. Questions had been raised about Coelho's management
of the United States' participation in the 1998 World Exposition in
Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   And Carter Eskew, the campaign's media consultant, has a
continuing role at a public relations firm, though he recently
severed his ties with a controversial client, Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gore was assisted by two political
consultants who had continued to represent corporate clients _
Robert Squier, an adviser, and Mark Penn, a pollster. But both have
left the campaign since Gore's move to Nashville.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent Democrats, including a former White House
adviser, Paul Begala, have urged Gore to demand that his aides
curtail their private dealings and lobbying because of the
appearance that private interests were seeking to influence the
vice president through his kitchen cabinet of lobbyists. Most of
these Democrats applauded the Gore campaign's move to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Gore's lobbyist-friends have clients interested in
issues that have also interested the vice president, like
technology, health care and environmental matters.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of their lobbying reports shows that Knight, Neel
and Downey often do get what they ask for _ from the
administration, the Federal Communications Commission and the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's firm, which represents Lockheed Martin, has lobbied the
administration to continue its $1 billion deal with Lockheed to
help Russia launch commercial rockets. The White House has said
that it is considering terminating the deal to discourage Russia
from selling ballistic-missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Knight, who worked for Gore for 13 years in
the House and Senate and was the manager of the 1996 Clinton-Gore
campaign, said that most of his firm's lobbying, on behalf of
Lockheed and other companies, had been handled by his partners. And
Knight said he had been careful not to discuss his clients'
interests with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Knight's critics contend that clients hire him because of
his insider's knowledge of the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Peter Knight calls an agency for help, it's almost as if
the vice president or his staff calls,'' said an investigator for a
Republican House member. ``He might as well be Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Downey lives not far from Gore, and they often play basketball
together on weekends. After Downey, a Democrat from Long Island,
N.Y., was defeated for re-election to the House in 1992, he founded
a lobbying firm with former Rep. Rod Chandler, a Republican from
Washington, and the firm has been very successful. According to a
study by Legal Times, Downey Chandler earned $1.7 million in fees
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On his lobbying reports, Downey acknowledges that he has
directly lobbied the office of the vice president on behalf of most
of his clients, a list that includes Boeing, Merck &AMP; Co. and Fuji
Film Co.
</P>
<P>
   One adviser to Gore denied that Downey had won most of his
fights, saying that Gore excoriated the U.S. pharmaceutical
industry at a recent campaign appearance in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the extreme price differentials between the
Canadian and U.S. markets, Gore used a 60-tablet package of Zocar,
a medication used to control cholesterol that is manufactured by
Merck &AMP; Co., a Downey client.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hammered Merck,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Former White House officials are barred by law from lobbying
other senior administration officials for one year. And the Clinton
administration's own ethics rules bar former administration members
from lobbying the White House for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Neel, who was the vice president's first chief of staff until he
left the administration in late 1993, waited until this past winter
before he began lobbying members of the administration about
telecommunications policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That five-year prohibition ended last winter, and I have had
discussions with the vice president in general terms on
telecommunications policy and telecommunications politics,'' Neel
said. ``But I do not lobby him on any single issue related to our
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
