<SLUG> BC-MISS-GOV-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., La.)  
 MISSISSIPPI RACE CENTERS ON FAMILY VALUES _ OR LACK OF THEM  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ Only three states had governors' races scheduled
this year: Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisiana contest last Saturday turned out to be a bit of a
political yawner when Gov. Mike Foster, a Republican, easily
brushed aside 10 challengers to win a second term.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kentucky contest, on Tuesday, looks like another yawner,
because about the only thing in doubt is by how much Gov. Paul
Patton, a Democrat, will win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Mississippi contest, also on Tuesday. This one
is different.
</P>
<P>
   It looks to be close, with final polls showing the two top
candidates, Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove, a Democrat, and former U.S.
Rep. Mike Parker, a Republican, running neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the issues.
</P>
<P>
   For years, candidates for governor in Mississippi have been
debating what to do about the state's persistently low-ranking
schools and its persistently low-paying jobs. Musgrove and Parker
are no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest issue may be the phantom issue: Kirk Fordice,
Mississippi's current governor.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrove and Parker are not running against just each other.
They are also running against Fordice, using him as a foil, without
mentioning him directly, for competing campaign pitches and
feel-good television commercials that focus on family values, one
of the hottest political issues of the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no issue is hotter in conservative, Bible-belt
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Fordice, a Republican who is not eligible to
run for a third term under state law, has been making headlines
with his efforts to divorce Pat Fordice, his wife of 44 years, so
he can marry an old high school flame he has been publicly
courting. He wants Mrs. Fordice to decamp the Executive Mansion
(she refuses to go), and he has had a number of loud and unpleasant
exchanges with reporters assigned to cover him.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mississippians, Republicans as well as Democrats, say they
are fed up with the story of marital infidelity in the Executive
Mansion, coming as it has on the heels of the story of marital
infidelity in the White House (Fordice called frequently for
President Clinton's resignation). They say they are embarrassed for
their state.
</P>
<P>
   John Grisham, the Mississippi lawyer turned best-selling
novelist, is a Musgrove supporter. But he said the other day that
``after eight years of Kirk Fordice'' just about any ``decent
person'' of whatever political ilk would do as a successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' Grisham said, ``Jesse Ventura would look good, or
Hulk Hogan, or anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Musgrove and Parker are trying to outdo each other over
how much more money to pour into Mississippi's schools and what
bait to use to lure more high-paying industries to the state, so
they also are trying to outdo each other when it comes to their
commitment to family values.
</P>
<P>
   When Fordice showed up the other day for a Parker fund-raiser,
at which Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was the headline speaker, he
was given a seat in the back row, as good a measure as any of how
much distance Parker is trying to put between himself and the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   When Musgrove and Parker are out on the campaign trail, their
wives often accompany them, standing prominently on the podium.
Both candidates are running television commercials featuring family
members.
</P>
<P>
   One of Musgrove's advertisements shows his son, Jordan, in a
classroom, raising his hand to ask a question. Another has Musgrove
chatting warmly with his wife, Melanie, and their daughter, Carmen
Rae.
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign speeches, Musgrove talks of ``tax relief for
families'' and of how better schools make for stronger families.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Parker's advertisements show him fishing and hunting
with his children and talking to his mother about dirty campaign
tactics. In another, he tells of courting his wife, Rosemary, and
at the end he gives her a loving hug and says:
</P>
<P>
   ``She's smarter than I am and I'm smart enough to know that. I
think she'd make a great first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Musgrove, who is 42, and Parker, 50, sound in their
speeches and commercials as if they are delivering each other's
campaign spiels, perhaps no great surprise given that Mississippi
is one of those Deep South states in which Democrats are coming
more and more to resemble Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised debate here on Monday night, Musgrove said, ``We
have to improve our schools and upgrade our economic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker countered, ``What Mississippians want is good education
and good-paying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two men have their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrove accuses Parker of voting to cut health and Social
Security benefits while in Congress. Parker, who did not run for a
sixth term last year, counters that he voted only to balance the
budget and calls Musgrove's accusations ``disingenuous''
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Parker has been hitting the family-values issue harder
than Musgrove, particularly in his television commercials. Any
discernible results?
</P>
<P>
   When Parker started his campaign early last summer, he trailed
Musgrove by a dozen or so points in the polls. Since then, he has
steadily closed the gap and in the most recent survey was several
points ahead of Musgrove, although the race was still essentially a
dead heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0174 </DOCNO>
