<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE VULTURE CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So I was watching the Marilyn auction with my
sister.
</P>
<P>
   She observed that it was sort of creepy, since the star did not
know all her stuff would be sold, or even know the seller _ Anna
Strasberg, the second wife of Lee, Marilyn's mentor.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed obscene that Mrs. Strasberg hauled in a good portion
of the $13.4 million netted from the auction of Marilyn's most
intimate things: her bustiers and baby-doll nighties and oven mitt
and makeup and pots and pans and snapshots of her dog, Maf, and
those sad little notes to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if my plane went down,'' my sister wondered, ``and people
came into my home and pawed through everything? I wouldn't want
them forming an opinion of me by a pair of shoes or jeans or some
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Di and Jackie and Elvis and J.D. Salinger and the duke and
duchess of Windsor and Marlene Dietrich and Garbo and Marilyn _
celebrity detritus is all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   But what if Christie's and Sotheby's run out of the flotsam and
jetsam of the rich and famous? What if they start rooting around in
the drawers and closets of the indebted and anonymous?
</P>
<P>
   I decided I had better prepare myself for the inevitable
reductio ad absurdum of the vulture culture. Why not enjoy the
profit of my own remains? If one Marilyn wooden hanger could fetch
$4,370, the possibilities seemed limitless for my Hammacher
Schlemmer clothes steamer. So I began busily drafting the auction
catalog for my many priceless effects.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 5: A pair of gray sweat pants worn while watching ``Some
Like It Hot.'' Estimate: $4 to $9.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 7: Three volumes of the Starr Report, with annotations,
written in blue ink, e.g., ``Wow!'' ``No way!'' Estimate: $40
million to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 8: Pair of brown suede stilettos, with a Ferragamo label,
worn when it suddenly hit me in 1992 that Ross Perot was a complete
nutcake. Estimate: $250.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 10: One box of Biore pore strips, used before the Gridiron
dinner in 1998. Estimate: $1 to $2.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 12: Collection of frothing letters from American Express.
Best of lot, sent on Oct. 15, 1999, reads: ``If you do not send
$3,567.80 immediately, we will take steps that will amaze you.''
Estimate: $3,567.80.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 25: Vintage fur-trimmed sweater worn in 1994 to an Easter
Mass at Blessed Sacrament, where I gave the ``handshake of peace''
to Pat Buchanan. Estimate: $8,000 to $10,000. Sold to benefit World
Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 44: Letter from Kato Kaelin complaining about the way I
wrote about him in a column. Letter reads, in part, ``I must say,
in regards to the `shaggy blond pool boy-moocher' (are you sure
it's not, smoocher?), if I was any smarter, I'd be insulted!''
Estimate: $2 to $3. Proceeds to Literacy Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 91: A Strom Thurmond letter opener given to me by Strom
Thurmond when he was only 91. Estimate: $91.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 100: Fork with sticky curry residue from the Bombay Club,
nervously clutched as self-defense weapon when Monica Lewinsky
confronted me at the restaurant to ask why I wrote such tart
columns about her. Estimate: $25.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 110: Books sent to me by friends who are writers. Spines
uncracked. Estimate: $2.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 111: First editions of Marilyn Quayle's ``Embrace the
Serpent,'' Richard Gephardt's ``An Even Better Place'' and John
Kasich's ``Courage Is Contagious.'' Estimate: 50 to 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 116: Partially erased tape of my only guest appearance on
ABC's ``Nightline,'' critiquing President Bush's first State of the
Union address. The performance was singled out in a book on Ted
Koppel as the worst show in ``Nightline'' history. Estimate upon
request.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 125: A Marilyn Quayle key chain. Estimate: $1.99.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 150: Pink phone message that reads ``Warren Beatty is
holding.'' Estimate: $20.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 173: Printouts of encouraging e-mails from readers calling
me ``Witch,'' ``Sick,'' ``Slut'' and ``Lickspittle,'' writing
``drivel'' and ``piffle.'' Estimate: $500.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 200: Letters from my mother with guidance on bald tires,
antifreeze, the Value of a Dollar, Soup in a Cup and married
suitors, here referred to only as ``old goats'' and ``long-tailed
rats.'' Plus a newspaper clipping headlined, ``Going to Church May
Be Good For Health.'' Estimate: Priceless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3455 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-30 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE LAST 100 DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know how Al Gore will do in the upcoming race. I think
he's got a lot more substance than the press has given him credit
for. But if Gore's candidacy does go down early, it could have one
interesting side effect. It might actually free up the Clinton
administration to govern in its final months without worrying about
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Having missed out on its first 100 days _ due to a variety of
scandals and mishaps _ the Clinton administration could be the
first in history to be known for its last 100 days. Imagine if the
president, unconstrained by any campaign, actually felt free to do
only the right things in foreign policy with his last 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the speech Clinton would give:
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, I intend to use these last 100 days to
make up for some of the mistakes in the previous 2,820. The first
thing I will do is something I never did in foreign policy _ set
some clear priorities. My last 100 days are going to focus on the
two biggest relationships we have _ Russia and China _ because
unless we manage those right, the rest won't matter. With Russia I
did the wrong thing and with China I failed to do the right thing.
Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's start with Russia. We never had it in our power to
determine how the democratic experiment in Russia would come out.
We did have it in our power, though, to make Russia a less
dangerous place and a less angry and isolated place _ no matter how
its experiment evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, driven by a need to win Polish votes in the
Midwest, I opted to do just the opposite. We expanded NATO, which,
in one fell swoop, alienated the Russian elites, undermined our
moderate, pro-Western allies inside Russia, and so angered the
Russian Duma that it refused to ratify the Start II treaty, which
would have cut Russia's long-range nuclear arsenal in half.
Madeleine and Strobe kept telling me we could expand NATO and get
START II. But it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics of arms control say: `No problem. We don't need
Start II. Our strength will protect us.' What these guys don't
grasp is that it's not Russia's strength that threatens us. It's
Russia's weakness. I'm not worried about Russia using a nuke. I'm
afraid of it losing a nuke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is not that a strong Russia will launch a missile
at us, but that in a weak Russia one will fall off the back of a
truck and end up in Iraq. And the way to reduce that threat is by
making Start II and Russian integration in the West our top
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therefore, on this eve of Russian presidential elections, I am
announcing the following: The United States will support bringing
Russia into NATO and the EU by 2010, provided Russia meets a
specific set of democratic, legal, arms-control and economic
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the top politicians in Russia today are just corrupt
old Bolsheviks, but by the next election in 2004, you are going to
have a new generation running that gets it. I want to empower these
young Russians in their internal fights with Russia's old guard by
laying out a clear, strategic pathway for them. I want these young
Russians to know, and to be able to say, that if they make the
right choices, Russia will get what it wants and what we should
want _ that it become part of a free and undivided Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for China, we don't have the power to transform China. But
we do have the power to make it a more open, rules-based society.
We have a great tool for doing that _ bringing China into the World
Trade Organization, which would force upon it a set of legal norms,
and a degree of openness, that would be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a WTO deal, U.S. Internet firms would be much freer to
invest in China and the Chinese would have many more ways to
interact with the world _ without having to go through their
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a huge mistake last April when I let John Podesta, Gene
Sperling and Bob Rubin talk me out of finishing the WTO deal with
Zhu Rongji when he was here. We could have had it. But after all
the support we had gotten from House Democrats on the Monica thing,
my aides didn't want to rile up the Dems and the unions by pushing
through WTO for China. So I let the deal go. I regret that, and I'm
going to fight to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, every time I did the politically hard thing _
Kosovo, NAFTA, the Middle East _ I made history. And every time I
did the politically expedient thing, I made trouble. I'm going to
use these last 100 days to fix both China and Russia. And while I
am at it, I'm going to lift the embargo on Cuba too. I never did
like Florida anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
