<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-AMERICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAIR OF PAIRS INSPIRE EACH OTHER AT SKATE AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NANCY GAVILANES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ The reigning world pairs champions,
Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze, were the heavy favorites
going into this weekend's Skate America competition, but after
Friday night's short program the Russians were a surprising fourth.
Not that they were worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be skating our whole life without some problems,
without some mistakes, it's not possible,'' said Sikharulidze after
Berezhnaya fell on the pair's side-by-side triple toe loop and
stepped out of the throw triple loop. ``Tomorrow, we will keep our
attention, and we'll try to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That positive attitude is something the pair has absorbed from
their coach, the legendary Tamara Moskvina. She is a firm believer
that skaters can sometimes learn more after skating a rough program
than a clean one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make it a tragedy,'' Moskvina said Friday night,
``we'll gain something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moskvina isn't worried about the team's less-than-flawless start
because Skate America is, after all, their first competition of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sikharulidze, the mistakes in the program will just
motivate them to skate better and guard against complacency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're leader, it's very difficult to go forward every
time,'' he said, ``and you just want to just keep what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, the pair will get motivation not only at competitions
but also in their own backyard, Ice House in Hackensack, N.J.,
where they share the practice rink with Kyoko Ina and John
Zimmerman of the United States. Also in Moskvina's all-star lineup
at Ice House are Artur Dmitriev and Natalya Mishkeutonok, the 1992
Olympic pairs champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good atmosphere,'' said Moskvina who coaches all
three pairs with her husband. ``They support each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation inspires Ina, who with Zimmerman, stands fifth in
the Skate America pairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get much better than training with world and Olympic
champions every day,'' said Ina. ``It's also like we're traveling
with our teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only Ina and Zimmerman's second season together, and
their inexperience may have contributed to their mistake on a lift
at the end of their short program Friday night. According to
Zimmerman, the timing was off on their footwork entering the lift.
Instead of putting Ina at risk of a dangerous fall, he opted to set
her down early.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, the Americans skated a clean program that
included solid side by side triple toes, a double twist and a throw
triple salchow. Still, Ina and Zimmerman have more modest goals for
Skate America than Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no expectations,'' said Ina, who won two U.S. titles
with her former partner, Jason Dunjen, and finished fourth at the
Nagano Olympics in 1998. ``We're just going to start the program
and hopefully finish on a high note.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Moskvina has higher hopes for the Americans, who
finished second at last year's nationals. ``He's a very handsome
boy and she's very tough cookie,'' she said. ``Together, they'll go
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my best to have them become the best couple in the
States and one of the best couples in the world,'' said Moskvina,
who coached Dmitriev and Mishkeutonok to Olympic gold in 1992 and
Dmitriev and Oksana Kazakova to gold in 1998. ``That is not our
dream,'' Moskvina said, referring to Ina and Zimmerman, ``it is our
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the leaders after Skate America's short program,
which counts for 33 percent of the total score, were Jamie Sale and
David Pelletier of Canada. The Canadian team nailed their throw
triple salchow, side-by-side triple toe jumps and their double
twist. Peggy Schwarz and Mirko Muller of Germany and Sarah Abitol
and Stephanie Bernadis of France are in second and third place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
