</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION ISSUE RAISES RED FLAGS  
 CONSUMER'S GUIDE TO THE CANDIDATES 
SEEKING NEW RULES FOR A CAMPAIGN TOOL 
MAKING PEACE, MISSOURI-STYLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine., Mo.)  (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By definition, political advertisements are one-sided.
Sometimes, if they are outrageously inaccurate or tasteless, they
may be rejected by a newspaper or broadcast station. But most news
outlets determinedly avoid censorship of political advertising,
leaving it to the aggrieved candidate to cry foul or to news
reporters to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   But things are different this fall in Maine, where on Tuesday
voters will decide whether to ban a late-term procedure that
opponents call partial-birth abortion, one of the most contentious
issues in politics.
</P>
<P>
   In four instances in recent weeks, television stations WCSH and
WMTW of Portland and WLBZ of Bangor have refused to run
commercials, both pro and con, that deal with the proposed ban or
have required that the spots be modified. The stations said the
commercials were either inaccurate or in questionable taste.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, station executives questioned the accuracy of one
advertisement that said late-term abortions were never necessary
and another that contended the issue was moot because Maine law
already prohibited late-term abortions. The executives argued that
under Maine law, exceptions were sometimes made for late-term
abortions, such as when the health of the mother was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   In other instances, station executives rejected advertisements
on the grounds that they were too visually provocative for young
viewers or left the impression that abortions routinely involved
healthy late-term fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's governor, Angus King, a political independent, worries
that rejecting political ads or requiring that they be modified
interferes with ``the battle of ideas,'' especially during
campaigns in which the issues are particularly hot and both sides
are trying to compress complicated arguments into 30-second ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stations are taking unto themselves a heavy burden,'' he
declared last week after the latest rejection. ``It raises
troubling questions that they're making political decisions. I
would err on the side of open conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer's Guide To the Candidates
</P>
<P>
   A Web site called Selectsmart.com, which normally serves up
facts and figures and specifications to help consumers make buying
decisions about such things as cars and wines and dogs, has
branched out into some fun with presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of all those newspaper stories and television reports
about Election 2000? Tired of talking heads telling you how to
think and vote?
</P>
<P>
   Click onto www.Selectsmart.com, answer a dozen or so questions
about tax policy, election reform, Social Security and the like,
click again, and Selectsmart will tell you which one of 18 White
House hopefuls, including Warren Beatty and Ralph Nader, comes
closest to matching your hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking New Rules For a Campaign Tool
</P>
<P>
   Few things have had more influence in recent years on the way
political campaigns are run in this country than the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the effect has been so great that the Federal Election
Commission thinks it is time to set some rules and guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates, parties and political action committees have
apparently concluded that the Internet is a powerful campaign tool
with the potential to significantly influence the outcome,'' the
commission said in a statement issued on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, there are few guidelines to follow as the nation
crosses this new frontier, as the commission called the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates now raise money, spread their messages and organize
via the Internet. Just about every candidate has a Web site and
hardly a campaign manager can be found who is not pondering some
even more inventive use.
</P>
<P>
   So the commission is asking for comments on how _ and, for that
matter, whether _ it should regulate the new tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission is grappling with the new area of technology
and the application of campaign law to it,'' Scott Thomas, the
chairman, said in calling for questions, suggestions and
observations from campaign workers and the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be well served,'' he added, ``to get the questions
answered as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Making Peace, Missouri-Style
</P>
<P>
   In the Missouri Senate race, one of the most mean-spirited
elections in the country, both candidates professed last week to
want peace.
</P>
<P>
   And then they got into an argument about what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   So it has gone for months now, ever since Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
moderate Democrat who cannot seek re-election under state law,
decided to try to unseat the state's junior senator, John Ashcroft,
a Christian-right Republican up for a second term.
</P>
<P>
   In a contest that is considered a toss-up and could be among the
most pivotal in determining control of the Senate, the two men have
tangled so far over the death penalty, abortion and race, with the
last issue playing out all last week and into the weekend after
Republicans began spreading around a 1960 photo of Carnahan
participating in a blackface minstrel show.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a threat to his hold on the state's large, traditionally
Democratic black vote, Carnahan issued a speedy apology for having
taken part in ``this kind of theater'' and insisted he had
``grown'' in the intervening 39 years. But the Republicans would
not let the issue die, and a contest that was already ugly began to
grow downright nasty as charge and countercharge were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, the chairmen of the Missouri Democratic and
Republican Parties were calling for a truce, a call that quickly
degenerated into a battle of faxes and press releases. Whereupon
the governor and senator began trying to reach each other by phone
to set up some kind of peace parley.
</P>
<P>
   Or so their aides said, though one of them, Steve Hilton of the
Ashcroft staff, went a step further, and probably came closer to
the truth than anyone else, when he observed that such a highly
publicized peace effort ``inevitably has the air of, perhaps, a
gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, on Friday, the senator and the governor had their
peace talks, though argument, it appears, would be a better word.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said afterward, through Hilton, that the talk had been
``even and businesslike'' and that he had made the point that there
would be no peace between him and the governor until the governor
and his fellow Missouri Democrats demonstrated good faith by ending
their practice of ``hate politics.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Carnahan replied, via fax:
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress will not be made if every conversation we have is
merely a new chance to level old accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Scary Halloween Masks
</P>
<P>
   This being Halloween, herewith the percentage results when Fox
News pollsters asked 705 people which of the Election 2000
presidential contenders would make ``the scariest Halloween mask:''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan 27, Gore 22, Bush 10, Forbes 10, McCain 6 and Bauer 4.
</P>
<P>
   Margin of error: Plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
