</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FLYFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: BOOKS FOR FANS OF FLY-FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Austin Francis has carried his fascination with the wondrous
trout streams of the Catskills and the region's seminal role in the
development of fly-fishing in the United States to a celebratory
level with his ``Land of Little Rivers'' (The Beaverkill Press,
hardcover, 276 pages, illustrated, $100).
</P>
<P>
   A business communications consultant and an ardent
fly-fisherman, Francis is the author of ``Catskill Rivers,
Birthplace of American Fly Fishing'' (Nick Lyons Books-Winchester
Press, 1983), a title every Catskill trout-stream buff should own.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of his latest book. Immersed as he is in the
region's history and magic, Francis evidently felt _ and I hope he
will pardon me for this gratuitous excursion into his motivations _
that a traditional history, albeit often inspired, of the
Catskills' streams didn't capture their natural beauty. Hence the
birthing of ``Land of Little Rivers,'' a visually stunning
achievement. Printed in Italy by Stamperia Valdonega and
distributed by W.W. Norton &AMP; Co., most of its color photographs
were taken by Enrico Ferorelli, a contributor to National
Geographic and Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``A Story in Photos of Catskill Fly Fishing,'' this is
a big, handsome picture book with historic and literary punch, a
felicitous blend of illustrations and text. The photographs convey
the glories and mystery of the streams, and the author's graceful
text _ photographs and sparse captions can never do it all _
provides a look at the lives and contributions of key figures in
the world of fly-fishing who dwelled in the region or were drawn to
it because of their inclinations or their callings.
</P>
<P>
   To get just the book he wanted, Francis said he was also its
creative director and publisher. (The address of the Beaverkill
Press is 55 E. 76th St., New York, N.Y. 10021.) ``To be the
publisher,'' he wrote in response to my query in September, ``I had
to invest my own and other people's money _ soon to be more than
$400,000 _ before the first receipts started coming in.'' If
quality determines the economic success of his effort, he need not
worry about receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Lively, Updated History
</P>
<P>
   An updated edition of Paul Schullery's ``American Fly Fishing''
has been issued by the Lyons Press (hardcover, illustrated, 282
pages, $40). This is a carefully researched, well-crafted, lively
history _ the best of its genre and scope _ of the development of
both fresh and saltwater fly-fishing in the United States. In his
afterword, new in this edition, Schullery examines the changes in
attitudes toward fly-fishing and all recreational angling in this
country. He cites the once firmly entrenched notion that trout
waters set aside exclusively for fly-fishing give the fish, when
released, a better chance of survival than released fish caught on
spinning lures. Recent studies, he notes, have shown that this is
not so. Fly-fishing-only regulations, he adds, appear to have only
social arguments _ some might call it selfishness or snobbery on
the part of fly-fishers _ to support them.
</P>
<P>
   A Wealth of Useful Suggestions
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1994, J. Kenney Abrames' ``Striper Moon'' (Frank
Amato, paperback, illustrated, 48 pages, $15.95) deals
provocatively with fly-fishing techniques when wading and flies for
striped bass in estuaries, rivers, bays and surf. A former
charter-boat skipper and a liturgical artist, sculptor and writer,
Abrames, a Rhode Islander, is an intense observer of water,
currents, baitfish and stripers. He constantly ponders the meaning
of what he sees, striving to refine his presentation of fly to
fish. There are enough suggestions in this little book to keep an
accomplished striper fly-fisherman busy all season. It was from
reading ``Striper Moon,'' for example, that I learned that a
marvelously effective way to catch striped bass was by simply
casting my fly from the beach into the alongshore current of
Vineyard Sound off Martha's Vineyard and letting it swing about,
without retrieving it, until it straightened out below me. It
became even more productive when I understood under what conditions
it worked best: when the bass were simply stationed in the current
waiting for food to be swept to them, rather than slamming about in
all directions after schools of terrified baitfish.
</P>
<P>
   Handy Guide to Casting
</P>
<P>
   Ed Jaworowski, who studied fly-casting under the ebullient and
talented Lefty Kreh and now holds casting clinics of his own across
the country, has written a splendid little fly-casting book,
``Troubleshooting the Cast'' (Stackpole Books, paperback,
illustrated, 78 pages, $12.95). In the book, aided by drawings, he
describes 32 common casting problems and tells how to deal with
them. Although a beginner will certainly benefit from this text, it
is probably the more experienced fly-fisher who will reap the
greatest reward. You've got to have a certain degree of competence
before specific deviations consistently emerge from the welter of
ineptitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
