<HEADER>
A3480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-N     10-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: ALL-CENTURY TEAM BECAME ALL ABOUT ROSE AND GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those watching the introduction of the all-century team last
Sunday before Game 2 of the World Series surely hoped it would stir
emotions similar to those created at last July's lovefest for Ted
Williams before the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out to be a stilted ceremony consisting of the 18
living players standing up, moving across a platform and sitting
down.
</P>
<P>
   The only real excitement was the huge ovation for Pete Rose, the
career leader in hits and pariah of official baseballdom.
</P>
<P>
   The best possibility of enlivening the ceremony for those
observing it from home was to speak to the players without delaying
the game for long.
</P>
<P>
   But there were few warm and fuzzy moments _ and then it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   That was when NBC correctly went to its reporter, Jim Gray, to
ask Rose if this first step onto a major-league field since he was
banned from the game in 1989 for gambling would lead him to confess
to gambling on baseball. But Gray took on the role of hard-nosed
prosecutor, unrelentingly questioning Rose even as the former
Cincinnati Red demonstrated he would not confess to Gray on
national TV.
</P>
<P>
   The only other NBC interview of one of the 18 living members of
the all-century team, with Hank Aaron, came after a commercial
break.
</P>
<P>
   Having stretched the first pitch by five minutes to 8:10 p.m.,
neither NBC nor major-league baseball wanted to delay the World
Series game any further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked NBC to do more interviews, but we felt
pressure to get the ceremony done in the given time,'' said Patrick
Courtney, a spokesman for major-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and baseball, knowing how badly the Rose interview went,
should have acted quickly to delay the game another 10 minutes to
speak to Stan Musial and Willie Mays or Ken Griffey Jr. and Warren
Spahn. So the lasting memory of the all-century ceremony was Gray
vs. Rose and the ensuing backlash of phone calls, letters, e-mails
and sports radio venting by fans, leading Gray to apologize to the
aggrieved and overwrought.
</P>
<P>
   The Gray-Rose contretemps made a side issue of legitimate
questions about some players voted on and left off the all-century
team. A panel of 21 experts, whom baseball will not identify,
fashioned a list of 100 players, of whom 25 were chosen in
balloting sponsored by Mastercard International.
</P>
<P>
   Fan voting often produces uneven results in an All-Star Game,
but balloting on 100 years of history is fraught with more
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The major problem was the ballot: It contained no statistics,
only the years of the players' careers. Fans who received their
ballots in copies of Sports Illustrated could have clipped out
accompanying supplements with statistics. Those voting at
major-league baseball's Web site were also able to access
statistics. But ballots at stadiums and Kmarts contained no
numerical aids.
</P>
<P>
   About one-half of the 2.5 million ballots returned to Mastercard
were from sources without immediate statistical references, said
Chris O'Neill, a Mastercard spokesman. How many of those voters
consulted statistical sources is unknown. But how many people carry
``Total Baseball'' to the ball park?
</P>
<P>
   You don't need statistics to vote on no-brainer choices like
Babe Ruth or Lou Gehrig. But a ballot without context skews voting
toward the popular (Cal Ripken Jr. as the top shortstop over Honus
Wagner?), the contemporary (Nolan Ryan as the best pitcher?), or
the contemporary and the flat-out wrong (Roger Clemens as the
fourth-best pitcher, over Bob Gibson and Walter Johnson?!?).
</P>
<P>
   A ballot with statistics would have required more space. But,
then, less space on the ballot is given to player names than to an
order form for the all-century team book and a rebate offer for
Microsoft's ``Baseball 2000'' game.
</P>
<P>
   A ballot with statistics would have revealed that four pitchers
with a combined 1,409 victories were deemed unworthy by the fans of
being on the all-century team's six-pitcher staff. Warren Spahn,
No. 10, had 363 victories, the most of any left-hander; Christy
Mathewson, No. 14, and Grover Cleveland Alexander, No. 16, each had
373 victories, and Lefty Grove, No. 18, won 300.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Musial finished 11th in the balloting for the nine
outfielders _ behind Rose, who got the fans' nod as the ninth and
last outfielder. Musial, of course, had 3,630 hits, a .331 career
batting average and 475 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's selection meant that the fan plebiscite not only had
judged him better than Musial, but also better than Roberto
Clemente, Joe Jackson, Reggie Jackson, Tony Gwynn, Carl Yastrzemski
and Frank Robinson, whose resume includes 586 home runs, the
fourth-most in history, and 2,943 career hits.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-ribbon panel, which was empowered to name up to five
players it felt were unfairly omitted by the fans, added Musial,
Wagner, Spahn, Mathewson and Grove. But Robinson, as well as Josh
Gibson and Satchel Paige, whose Negro League statistics are
difficult to tabulate, did not get special dispensation.
</P>
<P>
   Like all lists of this kind, the debate over the all-century
team's selection process will soon be forgotten. The Gray-Rose
incident will fade, too.
</P>
<P>
   For Mastercard, the experience was quite favorable. It got a few
months of publicity, which sponsors covet dearly. ``In a bizarre
way, through all the calls and e-mails, it became like a giant
focus group,'' O'Neill said. ``Through it all, people knew
Mastercard was baseball's partner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-30 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LESSONS OF FLEETING FAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you heard that Michael Jordan's restaurant, the burger-fare
establishment on North LaSalle Street in downtown Chicago, is
reinventing itself? Soon it will become Sammy Sosa's, switching
identities in midflight, from slam dunk to grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   There must be a moral to this menu manipulation that relates,
primarily, to the transitory nature of fame, when its underlying
motive is greed.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's people say it's merely a business dispute _ now in
court _ with the people to whom he sold his naming rights years
ago. The restaurateurs have dared to claim that the retired
legend's popularity has gone into decline. If ever there was
evidence that the National Basketball Association now belongs to a
new generation, there you have it.
</P>
<P>
   Magic has turned 40. Larry is already winding down as Coach
Bird. Charles Barkley says he's quitting after this season, and
might even mean it. Patrick Ewing has devolved into a set prop for
24-hour SpreeTV. Scottie Pippen's latest role is Cub Scout leader
in Portland. John Stockton and Karl Malone ceded control of the
Western Conference, wearing down last time around after 50
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan, most valuable player in last June's finals, is the
best player in professional basketball. It is up to Kevin Garnett,
among others, to make the case against an opinion so widely shared.
</P>
<P>
   Step up, as the coaches say, Allen Iverson, Ray Allen, Stephon
Marbury, Vince Carter, Grant Hill, Shaq and Kobe, Jason (Kidd) and
Jason (Williams). Prove us wrong. The new rules inhibiting defenses
from Rileying you to death should help.
</P>
<P>
   But the selling of the game is not just about hand-checking and
jump-shooting, and hasn't been since David Stern took over the
corner office at Olympic Tower. There is a challenge for the new
crop of NBA sneaker pitchmen.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Stern's marketing miracle is clearly at a junction,
if not the crossroads. The sport may be in danger of returning to
the third-class status behind football and baseball that it
previously held, before Stern forged a scratch-my-back partnership
with the networks and shoe companies, helping his players become
endorsement and promotional tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   Commercially speaking, no one in the history of professional
sports was bigger than Jordan, and few have had the capacity, or
audacity, to so consistently live up to the hype. As much as we all
miss him, Jordan's level of fame _ achieved primarily through
performance on the playing field _ must, in the end, be ephemeral,
especially when measured by the jersey-buying, burger-consuming
youth.
</P>
<P>
   Is it coincidence that Jordan's camp began promoting the idea
for the restaurant on North LaSalle to cater more to the more
mature, well-heeled diner who wouldn't so soon forget six Bulls
championships in eight glorious years?
</P>
<P>
   Basketball isn't baseball, a sport fueled by nostalgia. Lately,
even adult Jordan-worshippers I know have begun to ask, in so many
words, how many buzzer-beaters has Michael made lately and, anyway,
what serious adult would co-star with Bugs and Tweety in commercial
and film?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's star power was always predicated on his coming through,
then cashing in. He never attached himself to a cause that might
enhance his legacy in post-playing years, in a social or political
vein. He never leveled with the public on the hot-button Nike
issue. Apart from his indomitable skill and will, what I remember
most about Jordan as I compare him to other 20th century sporting
icons was his refusal to endorse an African-American candidate,
Harvey Gantt, in a North Carolina Senate race against Jesse Helms.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by Sam Smith in his 1995 book, ``Second Coming,''
Jordan told a friend, ``Republicans buy shoes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else could have got away with the cynical marketing ploy
_ switching from No. 23 to 45, supposedly in the name of his dead
father _ that Jordan foisted upon his public when he returned from
his sabbatical. The new jerseys happened to be on the racks that
week. I Exist, Therefore I Earn _ that was Jordan's
career-governing principle, guided brilliantly by his agent, David
Falk. This wasn't a crime; it was just who Jordan was.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be instructive to his heirs as the league moves
on and tries to reshape its image and rebuild its ratings. No
matter how popular he may be with desperate Knicks fans, a
self-absorbed, defiant personality like Latrell Sprewell will never
restore the NBA to where it was.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980s stars, Magic and Larry, had the original feel-good
formula. They raised the visibility of the sport so that Jordan
could emerge to become its first boardroom ballplayer. But too many
of Jordan's peers across this decade wanted to Be Like Mike, and
couldn't, because they could never be anywhere near as good.
</P>
<P>
   The league for years existed as one man's promotional vehicle.
Everyone else came off as overpaid, overindulged. This was not
always fair, when there were players like David Robinson, who for
years in San Antonio has been a graceful, philanthropic presence.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has certainly been a great role model for Duncan. In
New Jersey, Marbury and Keith Van Horn should pay close attention
to Jayson Williams, who can't say no to a kid and just last week
donated $2.1 million to his alma mater, St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is a lot to expect of these young men, when you also
consider that the corporations they work for are no more
accountable and often more selfish. The players are packaged and
sold more as individuals, though, than as part of teams. That is
the game, the source of their wealth, and the burden that comes
along with it.
</P>
<P>
   And it is their league now, to make of it what they will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
