<HEADER>
A3510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-700(2TAK     10-30 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK: CUNNINGHAM'S TURNAROUND; EMULATING
STEINBRENNER; RAMS CHASE PERFECTION; FAVRE TO TIE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Mo., Wis.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Last week against the San Francisco 49ers, quarterback Jeff
George, now oddly the savior of the Minnesota Vikings, threw a
rocket pass to the superstar wide receiver Randy Moss. It had been
a long time since Moss saw a football aimed for him, in game
conditions, that was flying at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Moss stood by his locker and was asked about the
difference between George's arm and that of the Vikings' previous
starter, Randall Cunningham. ``The ball,'' Moss said bluntly, ``is
carrying a little faster.''
</P>
<P>
   After hooking up with Moss, George connected on an 80-yard pass
play with Matthew Hatchette, becoming the first Viking to throw a
touchdown pass of more than 50 yards in his first start. Thus the
George era, which actually started at halftime the week before in a
loss to the Lions, had officially begun. On the sideline was
Cunningham, taking notes and, for the first time in his career,
charting plays.
 &UR;  &LR;  Cunningham on the bench? Charting plays? Wasn't this the same
All-Pro quarterback who last season led the Vikings to a National
Football League-record 556 points? Cunningham, without much of a
fight, has gone from hero to bench warmer in one of the most abrupt
turnarounds for a record-breaking quarterback in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't ask me to chart them, but I felt I would to help
George,'' Cunningham said. He added: ``It wasn't tough to sit
Sunday because the timing made it happen. When you are sitting,
there are so many things that go through your mind. All I can do is
keep praying that guys stay healthy, and that we put points on the
board and hopefully get turnovers. That's my job now. I'm a praying
man now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has handled the awkward situation with class. Still,
the question remains: What happened? The answers are not easy. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The quick-read theory. Last year, teams were afraid to
constantly blitz Cunningham because he would simply lob the ball to
Moss. Teams studied the Vikings in the off-season and figured the
best way to stop him was to force him to make quick reads. One
defensive coordinator who has planned strategy against Cunningham
this season called it ``Randall-izing the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   This season the Vikings saw a lot more zone blitzes and
switch-ups in the secondary. Cunningham was often confused.
</P>
<P>
   _ The friendly face theory. Brian Billick was the team's
offensive coordinator last year, and he had a close relationship
with Cunningham. Billick sometimes told him before the play exactly
where to throw the ball.
 &UR;  &LR;  In fact, Cunningham relied heavily on a trio of people. Besides
Billick, there was the quarterbacks coach, Chip Myers, and the
backup quarterback Brad Johnson, who constantly counseled
Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, Billick left to become head coach of
Baltimore, Myers died of a heart attack and Johnson became the
starting quarterback at Washington. Although Cunningham was
hesitant to characterize how important Billick was to the team,
Moss was not. When asked if the current offensive coordinator, Ray
Sherman, did a solid job in his game-planning for the 49ers, Moss
said: ``Is he a hero? No, I think if we call anybody a hero, it
would be Jeff George. He's just a coach. Our hero is gone. Our hero
is down in Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The cotton candy theory. A small number of people on the
Vikings and around the league feel that Cunningham, 36, has simply
turned soft. When he was demoted from the starting position,
teammates were surprised at Cunningham's attitude, which was not
anger, but relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is sure,'' Cunningham said at the time of his
benching. ``The offense is not being run the way it should be run
with me in there, which is why Jeff should be in there. I did
everything I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that coach Dennis Green's decision to bring in
George as a backup last spring was one of the smartest personnel
moves in the league this season. Other teams, like the Jets, wish
they had a player like George now, no matter how wacky and
inconsistent he has been during his 10-year professional career.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to Cunningham now? He will stay on the bench. Green
is doing a good job of keeping Cunningham's spirits up, because the
Vikings do not know when they will need him again.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Football Steinbrenner?
</P>
<P>
   After the Washington Redskins fell to the Dallas Cowboys last
Sunday for the second time this season, the Redskins' owner, Daniel
Snyder, dragged coach Norv Turner into the trainer's room and
scolded him for almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   That was embarrassing enough, an owner yelling at his coach,
with the players forced to treat their injuries in other parts of
the cramped locker room. But the chewing out did not stop there.
After the Redskins' plane landed at Dulles airport in Virginia,
Snyder resumed his chewing out of Turner and then began scolding
the defensive coordinator, Mike Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   It is only a matter of time before Snyder fires Nolan. It may
happen one week from now or at the end of the season. Snyder is
turning out to be one of the most aggressive owners in the league's
recent history, which is both a good and a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, along with his smart personnel guru, Vinny Cerrato, is
trying to make the Redskins winners again. Since becoming head
coach in 1994, Turner is 36-49-1.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of Snyder's taking such an aggressive, public stance,
though, is that he can undermine the head coach's position with the
players. What do players think when they hear an owner screaming at
the coach in the next room? At some point they stop listening to
the coach, thinking he won't be around long.
</P>
<P>
   A Chance to Run the Table
</P>
<P>
   Could one of the traditionally worst teams in the NFL actually
go undefeated in what is quickly becoming a watered-down league?
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams are 6-0 and have two solid tests coming up.
They face 5-1 Tennessee in Nashville on Sunday and play the Lions,
now 4-2, in the Silverdome next Sunday. The rest of the St. Louis
schedule is: home against Carolina, at San Francisco, New Orleans,
at Carolina, at New Orleans, the Giants, Chicago, and at
Philadelphia. The current combined record of these late-season
opponents is 18-34.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, if the Rams can somehow win their next two games,
they will indeed have a realistic shot at going 16-0.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cleveland Browns could become the first team in
league history to go 0-16 if they do not win what seems to be their
only winnable game, at New Orleans on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Week After Week After Week
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, when Green Bay plays host to Seattle, Brett Favre
will make his 116th consecutive start, tying him with the former
Eagle Ron Jaworski for most starts in a row by any quarterback in
NFL history. Favre, 30, will most likely play at least five more
years, so he will probably greatly extend the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I've managed to last this long is beyond me,'' Favre said
recently. ``Man, I hold nothing back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaworski's record has been more than a match for all
quarterbacks but Favre. Trent Dilfer's consecutive-game streak will
end at 70 Sunday when he is benched by Tampa Bay. Injuries have
halted streaks by Dan Marino of Miami (46) and Steve McNair of
Tennessee (34).
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh quarterback Kordell Stewart is second to Favre among
current quarterbacks with 39 straight starts.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as Favre's streak is, it still pales compared with
the accomplishment of the Minnesota defensive lineman Jim Marshall,
who played in 282 consecutive games. That record, set in 1979, may
last another 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DISABLED-DANCER-ART-2     10-30 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-DANCER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAPLEGIC DANCER REDISCOVERS HIS ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marc Brew clutches the barre with one hand, and
elegantly raises the other. Suddenly, his arm stops in midair,
frozen in space as if held there by scaffolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to me,'' his teacher says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a spasm,'' Brew replies, waits it out, and brings
his arm down to rest.
</P>
<P>
   A dancer since he was 7, Brew, now 22, is in a familiar setting:
a ballet studio, with mirrored walls, smooth shiny floors, and a
barre running the length of the room, like a spine. A paraplegic
for two years, he is in a familiar position: curled in a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   It is the marriage between the two that is brand-new.
</P>
<P>
   He twists right, then left, then right, in his chair. ``I feel
like I'm quite restricted,'' he says. ``I still feel like I want to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Brew's future seemed starry: he had just signed a
contract with the State Theater Ballet Company of South Africa. But
there, a drunken driver plowed into a car carrying him, his
girlfriend, her brother and another young man. Only Brew survived.
His ability to walk did not.
</P>
<P>
   He returned home to Australia, and languished. Then fate offered
a compensatory grace: two friends of Brew's visiting New York met
Kitty Lunn, a dancer who broke her back after slipping and falling
on ice in 1987 but who resumed dancing five years later.
</P>
<P>
   She studies classical ballet with able-bodied dancers. She
founded a dance company, Infinity Dance Theater, again with
nondisabled dancers, in which she performs in her wheelchair and on
the floor. A luminous woman with red hair, she balances other
dancers on her back. She does handstands, with help. She moves on
the floor as if she could get up and walk off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   In Brew, she saw a student for her technique, a companion in her
struggle. And at 49, with her body increasingly resistant to the
demands of performing, she also saw someone who might be able to
sustain the concept she had nurtured: that a person incapable of
walking could still create beauty.
</P>
<P>
   She bought him a ticket to New York, saying she would try
training him for her company's three performances this weekend at
the Theater of the Riverside Church. She gave him room _ in a
wheelchair-accessible hotel on the Upper West Side _ and board. On
Nov. 1, he would return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that he finds out he has a life to
live, whatever that is for him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as she did. Over eight years, she has tried to bend not
just her frame to her will, but also the perception that she is a
``spunky cripple,'' in her words, but not a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   To be a dancer in a paraplegic's body is to have your soul crave
movement, and your body resist it. For the next seven weeks, Brew
would struggle to build a bridge between the two.
</P>
<P>
   _ It is Sept. 15, five days after Brew got off the plane from
Australia and met Ms. Lunn for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mails to her had nearly shouted with excitement, but
today, the laborious reality is upon him. He is in ballet class for
only the third day, struggling to stay upright in his chair, to
reach his arm to the end of his knee. He has a month and a half to
prepare for his role in the ballet ``Gilchrist's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   He is extremely thin _ the accident took half his pancreas and a
fourth of his stomach _ and extremely pale, with spiky blond hair.
His upper body is a dancer's: lithe and toned, with arms that are
long and lean. His legs are a paraplegic's: limp, atrophied, and,
when a spasm hits, prone to shaking beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he will learn how far he can go. For now, he is trying
to transfer a dance regimen instilled since childhood to his upper
body. In a traditional plie, the legs contract, bending and rising.
Today, Brew must transfer that movement upward, gracefully bending
and straightening one arm while the other clutches the barre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soften at the back of the knee,'' Ms. Lunn says, gesturing at
the inside of his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correlate the body parts,'' she says. The upper arm becomes
the thighbone. The heel of the hand becomes the heel of the foot.
The attention to form and detail is taxing, but imperative. These
exercises will turn into fondus, pas de deux, frappes, all done
with the arms and a body able to bend only partly.
</P>
<P>
   Brew is breathing heavily. ``I'm getting all confused with
everything,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Lunn says ``arch your foot,'' he instinctively
bends his wrist. His muscles, he realizes, have memory.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A week later, he takes his first class with other dancers.
Seated in his chair, he is surrounded by a forest of muscled legs.
</P>
<P>
   Brew bends his head as they bend their bodies. When they turn,
he whirls his wheelchair around. His teacher, Peff Modelski,
invokes body parts that no longer have meaning for him: ``open the
thighbone, lengthen the hamstring.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he confesses his self-consciousness. ``I felt like
everybody's eyes were on me.'' But that is a small price for what
Brew says next: ``I am feeling like a dancer again.''
</P>
<P>
   For every challenge in class, there is one outside it. Ms. Lunn
moves with as much ease as a paraplegic can throughout the city,
cruising down sidewalks, mounting buses, pulling herself up stairs,
and often, when she encounters an obstacle, waging a legal battle
for access.
</P>
<P>
   Brew grew up in a small country town, Jerilderie, New South
Wales, in Australia. New York is daunting enough, let alone trying
to navigate it in a wheelchair. At first, nervousness structures
his routine: he will not go to class alone. He will not take the
bus. He will not leave Broadway, where both his hotel and the dance
studio are located. He has brought a friend, Matthew Emond from
Australia, and is never without him.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the wheelchair. ``Everyone stares at me,'' he says
as he rolls down the street. ``I wonder what they're thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, another young man in a wheelchair pulls up next to him
and nods. ``Let's race, man,'' the man says. Brew offers a weak
smile, but ignores the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He does not want to mix with people in wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Marc, not a wheelie,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also has trouble accepting himself as a wheelchair dancer.
``I look at myself in the mirror, and I think, this isn't how I
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lunn is sympathetic, to a point. ``The hardest part for Marc
is to give up the image of what he looked like standing up, but I'm
not going to spend time fighting that image,'' she says.
``Self-loathing or self-pity isn't an option.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sept. 24, she yells at him in rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I look stupid,'' he says. ``I feel foolish. I hate
this _ I hate being in this chair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' she responds. ``You're going to be in this
chair. You can either begin to make friends with it, or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lunn wonders if he is trying to dance too soon after his
accident. She wonders if he is simply too young. ``He is too young
even to have figured out things standing up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least for the time being, ain't none of us getting out of
this chair,'' Ms. Lunn says. ``Nobody says he has to like it, but
the alternative is that you become a very bitter, broken person.''
</P>
<P>
   The things she can no longer do as a dancer _ point her feet,
hold her stomach in, let alone pirouette outside a wheelchair _ are
painful to her. Not dancing, she says, is more so.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Brew is apparently reaching a similar conclusion. On Monday, he
is back in class after a weekend off, studiously avoiding looking
at the wheelchair in the mirrors that line the dance studio.
</P>
<P>
   But Oct. 11, the two-year anniversary of his accident, looms. In
the days before, Brew begins spending more and more time alone,
withdrawing. On the day itself, he relives the accident over and
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask questions all the time: Why?'' he says. ``There are no
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   He wonders, as well, if he will ever find love again. ``Who
wants someone in a wheelchair?'' he asks. ``I'm not in a hurry, but
I do get lonely.'' Today, he says, ``I feel really, really
lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, the dancer's constant quest for
improvement and perfection propels him forward. And so, gloom or
not, there is class.
</P>
<P>
   He bends to the floor, and comes back up, gripping the
wheelchair. His arm languidly flutters out, and curves. A smile
curves as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, the Australian Ballet is scheduled to arrive in
New York. Brew studied with many of the dancers, who helped raise
money for his trip here. They are friends _ but also the most vivid
reminder of what he was, and what he is.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, the dancers of the Australian Ballet leap and crouch
and climb and entwine in liquid, fluid motions. In the darkness,
Brew watches, fidgeting and shifting in his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception at the Australian Consulate after the
performance, he is embraced enthusiastically. He tries to explain
what he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do professional training, ballet class every day,'' he says.
``I just feel like my career is going in a different direction,
less toward the classics, more experimental. I'm doing a lot of
movement; I'm using my legs, even if I can't feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   The faces mingle love and pity and skepticism. ``There are no
words to describe it,'' Brew finally says, and encourages them to
see the performances, now less than two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  At another rehearsal, he pulls himself across the floor, using
only his arms. His legs seem more lead appendages than limbs. Sweat
soaks his hair, and a ghostly pallor suffuses his already pale
skin. He is playing, with eerie acumen, a wounded warrior on the
verge of death.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the floor, as dancers leap and fall around him,
he reaches up, then falls, reaches, rolls over _ carefully moving
each leg into place before he does so _ sits up virtually straight,
pointing, arches his back like a cat, then prays before collapsing,
dead.
</P>
<P>
   He is so bony, so prone to bruising, that to rehearse on the
floor, he must be padded as heavily as the Michelin Man. He can
break a bone easily because he has no feeling in his lower body.
During one rehearsal, he does not realize that he is being held up
in a handstand until he looks in a mirror and sees his legs in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   His arms, on the other hand, ache from the exertion of pulling
lifeless legs across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are just over a week away. He is exhausted, but
excited.
</P>
<P>
   His sense of humor is back. ``I would point for you,'' he says,
showing off new black ballet slippers at dress rehearsal, ``but I
can't.'' His friends from the Australian Ballet have come to see
him rehearse, and finally grasp what he is trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   The only cloud is the Nov. 1 return ticket. Brew wants to stay;
Ms. Lunn knows it. But he has no source of income, and no home: she
cannot continue paying for a hotel, nor can she accommodate him for
long at her and her husband's one-bedroom apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Like many young people before him, he sees the city, which he
now moves about with relative comfort, as a place of infinite
opportunity, and his home in Australia as a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether I'm happy, but I'm busy here,'' he said
last week. For the first time, he has direction, focus _ and
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance comes from within, the feeling of expression, of
movement,'' Brew said. ``That's still there. I didn't give up
dancing _ it was taken from me without my choice, and there is the
feeling of not having finished. There's nothing else I want to do.
It's in my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Ms. Lunn agrees that Brew can stay six more weeks,
at her apartment, or somewhere else if she can find it. He will go
home for Christmas, then try to pay his way back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Brew performed before an audience for the first
time in two years. He did his crawl across the floor; he looked
strong. In concert with Ms. Lunn, he glided and pirouetted in his
chair. It looked effortless. Then he took a bow, just able to bend
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God,'' he said he thought as he sat onstage, applause
swelling around him, ``they're actually clapping for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
