<HEADER>
A3516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-EARBITING-SHOOTING     10-30 0204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EARBITING-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S EAR BITTEN OFF IN FIGHT WITH CABBY, WHO IS THEN SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An off-duty security guard shot a livery-cab driver
in Brooklyn early Saturday, after the driver bit off a large
portion of the guard's ear, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The security guard, Gary Theis, 38, had just returned from work
and was parking outside his home in East Flatbush when he heard the
livery-cab driver, Gene Leveque, 36, sounding his horn to signal a
passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Theis found the honking obnoxious at 1:30 a.m., but Leveque
argued that it was perfectly appropriate, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument quickly escalated into a brawl, and during it,
Leveque bit off a large section of Theis' left ear, police said.
They said the fight ended when Theis pulled his handgun, for which
he has a license, and shot the driver once in the left torso.
</P>
<P>
   Officers found both men bleeding in front of Theis' apartment
building at 2021 E. 41st St. The combatants were taken to Kings
County Hospital Center, where they remained in stable condition
Saturday, police said, noting that Leveque, of 5515 Avenue M,
Brooklyn, and Theis both face charges of first-degree assault. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKEE-GAP-NYT &LR;      10-30 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEE-GAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-SEASON CHALLENGE: HOW TO BEAT THE YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gord Ash thought he saw a glimmer of vulnerability. ``I believe
there was a bit of a stumbling block this year,'' the Toronto Blue
Jays' general manager said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had lost all three games to Boston in a September
series at Yankee Stadium, and now they were in Toronto, having lost
the first game, their lead over the Red Sox down to three and a
half games. In the eighth inning of the second game, the Blue Jays
led, 6-1, but then, Ash said the Yanks ``became rejuvenated.''
Bernie Williams hit a grand slam, Paul O'Neill duplicated it in the
ninth, and all was right with the Yankees again. They won that
game, 10-6, then the next three and nine of 10. They didn't stop
winning until last week, when they ran out of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   So can anyone beat the Yankees? ``It doesn't look like it,'' Ash
said. ``Not in the postseason anyway. They have so many veterans
who rise to the occasion at that point in the season. They are
tough to beat. They play very disciplined, very unselfishly. That's
a very unique and formidable combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette, whose Red Sox finished second to the Yankees in
the regular season and in the league finals, felt his team at least
narrowed the gap this year. ``They were not as terrific as they
were a year ago,'' the Boston general manager said. ``We played
them 17 times this year. We won nine, they won eight. They won the
four that counted the most. But we're closer now to challenging the
Yankees than we were a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   As challengers, though, Duquette said, the Red Sox and anyone
else have to be better to supplant the Yankees. ``They're the
reigning world champions,'' he said. ``It's like a heavyweight
fight. You can't just beat them if you're the challenger; you have
to knock them out. We got close this year, and they skipped away
and beat the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was not fooling himself about the distance to be
covered. ``Whoever's going to beat the Yankees has their work cut
out for them,'' he said. ``They have three great players in the
middle of every game _ Williams, Jeter and Rivera _ and they have
some good years ahead of them. They also have a veteran team, a
stable team, good depth, good pitching depth and good depth to
their bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to beating the Yankees in the postseason, he said, is
the presence of a Pedro Martinez. ``If you have a top pitcher and
your top pitcher can pitch a few games in a series against them,
that could make a difference,'' he said. Unfortunately for the Red
Sox, Martinez couldn't pitch until the third game and his ensuing
victory was too little too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep trying,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   So are the Texas Rangers, but they have more ground to make up
than the Red Sox. In six playoff games against the Yankees the past
two seasons, the Rangers have scored a total of two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play well as a team, they really do,'' said the Rangers'
general manager, Doug Melvin, about the Yankees. ``They were great
in the postseason. They have pretty good depth with their pitching.
Whatever button Joe Torre punched, it worked. Last year he played
Shane Spencer, and he won some games for him. This year he played
Chad Curtis, and he won a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Hunsicker, the Houston general manager, watched the World
Series from the stands after his team failed to get past the first
round of the playoffs for the third successive season. Hunsicker
talked about what the Yankees have working for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that really stood out for me was what a good
situational hitting team they were,'' Hunsicker said. ``It was
especially impressive because that's been one of the main problems
our club has had getting out of the first round. When you get into
the postseason, you're going to face quality pitching every day.
Unless your team is willing to change its approach, it's going to
be tough to win. They do that better than any team I've seen all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin added a view of the Yankees that has rarely been heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a club you can like,'' said Melvin, a former Yankees
minor-league pitcher and front-office employee. ``Some Yankee teams
in the past you weren't fond of. You didn't want them to win. I'm
in the American League trying to beat them, but it's easy to root
for these guys because of Joe Torre, Brian Cashman, Gene Michael.
The players show a lot of class, too. It's class and
competitiveness, too. They play the game hard. They're a team you
can like even if you're competing with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's impossible to talk about the Yankees' success without
talking about the money behind it. Officials of other clubs don't
begrudge the Yankees the money they have available, but they wish
they had it, and many of them know they won't be able to compete
with the Yankees unless they do have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, I think there are only a handful of teams that
at the start of the season have a chance to beat the Yankees,''
Gerry Hunsicker of Houston said. ``It comes down to money. Nobody
wants to talk about money. People suggest that's an excuse, but
it's a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The major-league payroll isn't all that enters into the
championship picture, Hunsicker added.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more organizations are not able to compete in
scouting and player development,'' he said. ``Not that they're not
capable, but they don't have the money and the resources. The
Yankees do a terrific job with their resources. You have to give
them credit for that because a lot of organizations have egg on
their faces because they've spent a lot of money and have little
show for it. More and more clubs are being shut out of competing
for players. Latin America is a good example.''
</P>
<P>
   Latest case in point: In an ongoing auction for the latest Cuban
defector, a 22-year-old pitcher, Danny Baez, the bidding is said to
have reached $10 million (signing bonus, three-year contract), and,
an executive of another club said, the Yankees appear to be the
front-runner, just as they were with El Duque, Orlando Hernandez,
an older Cuban defector.
</P>
<P>
   Also, earlier this year, the Yankees signed Willy Mo Pena, an
outfielder from the Dominican Republic, to a five-year, $3.7
million contract after he was declared a free agent. The Mets had
signed him for $6,000, but it was discovered that the scout who
signed him signed his father's name on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Yankees drafted Drew Henson, a high school third
baseman, and gave him a $2 million signing bonus, the most money
ever given a third-round pick, even though he planned to throw
passes for the University of Michigan football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have the money; it's another thing to be
able to make big money mistakes and just keep making them because
the additional money is there,'' Hunsicker said. ``I can't go out
and spend a million dollars on a Latin player to begin with. But if
I could, it would have a major impact. Our whole signing bonus
budget, domestic and international, last year was $3 million. It
doesn't take a genius to know if you sign one player for $1
million, you wouldn't have much left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
