</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-CENTURY FALLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALL-CENTURY TEAM FALLOUT I
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose, 10 years later, apparently continues to labor under
misapprehensions. Just because the agreement under which he was
suspended in 1989 said he could apply for reinstatement after one
year, a provision that merely followed baseball rules, he seems to
think that meant he would be reinstated after one year. His
advisers might have led him to believe that, but Fay Vincent,
deputy commissioner then, said no such promise or suggestion was
made.
</P>
<P>
   Rose believes Commissioner Bart Giamatti double-crossed him by
saying publicly he believed Rose bet on baseball when no such
finding was included in the agreement. Rose's people, Vincent said,
had been told what Giamatti would say if he were asked what he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-CENTURY TEAM FALLOUT II
</P>
<P>
   Those who concocted the idea for the team decided to have a
maximum of 30 players (25 elected by the public, a maximum of five
added by a panel) to simulate the 30-man roster that is used for
the All-Star Game. But the All-Star Game features two 30-man
rosters. Had 50 or 60 players been selected, the honor might have
been reduced for the 30 who were named to the team, but the extra
places would have avoided the huge hurt inflicted on the Latin
American community over the absence of Roberto Clemente, not to
mention the problems with other oversights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the methodology was ridiculous when you're considering
the greatest players of the century,'' said Tom Reich, a player
agent and member of the board of directors of the Clemente
foundation. ``If they were voting publicly on 25, an oversight
committee properly balanced should have been empowered to name at
least another 25 people. You're talking about a 100-year span.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich said the absence of Clemente, Frank Robinson, Josh Gibson,
Satchel Paige, Juan Marichal and Roy Campanella was especially
grievous. ``The five players added,'' he said, ``were eminently
qualified, but there were at least 20 or so more than absolutely
had to be named.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Reich said, was the public voting that could be
done on the Internet. How many members of the black and Hispanic
communities, he asked, go on the Internet compared with white
users? Six black players were elected. No Hispanic players made the
team either by election or selection.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig said he was ``extremely sensitive'' to
the angry reaction to Clemente's absence. ``I understand their
concern,'' he said. ``Roberto Clemente would have made my team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
