<HEADLINE>
MARBURY-VAN HORN DUO MAY BE UP WITH THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Granted, they were only preseason games, but in them, Scott
Layden watched the New Jersey Nets' Stephon Marbury and Keith Van
Horn twice dominate the New York Knicks in ways that provoked
thoughts of some of basketball's most revered duos.
</P>
<P>
   Layden, the Knicks' first-year general manager, knows plenty
about outstanding twosomes, having been largely responsible for
matching John Stockton and Karl Malone in Utah. Now just a casual
car ride away from the Meadowlands, Layden fears he may have
transplanted himself into a geographic rivalry with a comparable
point guard-power forward tandem that, like the Jazz's pair of
future Hall of Famers, could stamp its imprint on an entire era of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marbury and Van Horn are so gifted and so multi-talented,''
said Layden, who worked with the Utah Jazz for 18 years before
joining the Knicks. ``I watched Keith for four years at the
University of Utah, so I'm one of his biggest fans. And Marbury
might be the best guard in the league. So you've got these two
guys, who obviously are going to play a long time together, and
they're going to do very well. If they get as good as Stockton and
Malone, that'll be something. Frankly, it's a little frightening
when you're sitting across the river from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons, some legitimate and some absurd, are always being
made in the National Basketball Association, so it is inevitable
that Marbury and Van Horn will be likened to Stockton and Malone.
Of course, the list of superstar tandems that once seemed destined
to duplicate Stockton and Malone is long and distinguished, but for
reasons ranging from personality clashes to free-agent wandering,
none have lasted.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hardaway and Shaquille O'Neal split after three seasons in
Orlando. Shawn Kemp, who demanded a trade, left Gary Payton in
Seattle while both were in their prime. And Marbury himself forced
his way out of Minnesota, despite forming a devastating duo with
his good friend Kevin Garnett. And in 1991, Kenny Anderson and
Derrick Coleman teamed up for the Nets amid huge expectations, only
to have their well-documented problems on and off the court keep
them from accomplishing anything significant. Eventually, both were
traded.
</P>
<P>
   The current Nets are in a different situation. Benefiting from
the league's new collective bargaining agreement, which put a cap
on the amount of money players can earn, the team signed both
Marbury and Van Horn to six-year extensions worth just over $70
million, meaning that the duo should be together at least until the
2004-05 season.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, both players want to play in New Jersey. Neither
tested the free-agent market before signing a contract and both are
happy with the makeup of the club. Marbury, a Brooklyn, N.Y.,
native, seems to have a strong enough personality to endure being
close to home, and Van Horn is content living with his wife and two
children in Franklin Lakes, N.J. So the early indication is that
the two young Nets will be together for the prime of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   When Marbury and Van Horn are compared with Stockton and Malone,
it is in terms of their potential impact on the game, not their
style of play. Although Marbury, like Stockton, is excellent at
penetrating, drawing defenders and finding the open man, he shoots
and scores much more than the Jazz playmaker. Van Horn can run the
floor like Malone, but his inside game is not nearly as strong. His
outside shot, however, is better than Malone's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good parallel, not that Stephon plays exactly like
Stockton or Keith like Malone,'' said Jim Lynam, a Nets assistant
who has more than 10 years of NBA head coaching experience. ``But
in terms of being absolutely high-high-level players, I think the
Stockton-Malone parallel is right on target, because these two guys
complement one another. Each makes the other better because of
their own unique talents, and both have great competitive
instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury and Van Horn have worked hard to harmonize their games.
Because Marbury's play is at times unorthodox, with no-look and
behind-the-back passes, Van Horn has had to study his point guard
to know when to expect a feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephon's very good at passing in the air, so when he gets up
in the air, I usually don't just stand there,'' Van Horn said. ``I
try to reactto it because I know if somebody gets in his face,
he's going to find someone quickly. A lot of times when a point
guard gets in the air, he scrambles and doesn't know what to do
with it. But Stephon always seems to find somebody at the last
minute, so I've become accustomed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury believes he and Van Horn are ``playing on a string'' _
his term for in sync _ and that with more practice together, they
will only get better. He is not afraid to compare the two of them
to the standard by which today's point guard-power forward
combinations are judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get in a groove, we look like Stockton and Malone when
they were in their prime,'' Marbury said. ``Playing with Keith is
great because he can do so many different things. I didn't know he
was this good. When I got a chance to play with him, I was like,
`Wow, this guy is one of the best players in the NBA!'''
</P>
<P>
   With two young, high-scoring players who are used to being the
first offensive option, the possibility for conflict always exists.
The Nets hope each player's desire to win will quell any problems.
Yet already there have been signs in the preseason that shot
distribution could be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has set up his teammates with numerous open looks,
Marbury has shot far too much, averaging a whopping 23.5 shots a
game. That was eight more than Van Horn averaged in the preseason
and nearly two more than Philadelphia's Allen Iverson averaged last
year. Van Horn says Marbury's gunning is not a problem, but great
duos have been destroyed over less, as Nets General Manager John
Nash noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to be the high scorer on the team?'' Nash said.
``Is it going to be Keith Van Horn or Stephon Marbury? If either
guy cares that badly, then we've got a problem. The answer is
whoever's open should get the shot, and let's win the game. Each
guy averaged 21 points and change a year ago. Who's going to score
the most points is not what this should be about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can these two be like a Stockton-Malone tandem? In time. I'm
not ready to anoint them because those two guys are Hall of Fame
plus. But there's a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
