<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-RESIDENTIAL-REAL-7     10-30 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RESIDENTIAL-REAL-730(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HOUSING MARKET, INVENTORY IS DOWN AND PRICES UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By some accounts, the house on New Rochelle's Van
Meter Fenway was a mess, the sort of home that should have gone for
a relative pittance to anyone who was ready to stomach perhaps
$100,000 in repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The house, according to real estate agents, needed everything: a
shoring up of its foundation, a new kitchen, new flooring, new
landscaping, a hard-core paint job on the outside and a new roof to
replace the one that had caved in over the screened-in porch.
</P>
<P>
   In a less frenzied real estate market, the house might have
taken a year or more to sell. But within a week of being listed at
$265,000 early last summer, it had more than 30 offers.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the house sold for $335,000, and little wonder: In
New Rochelle, as in many communities within the New York
metropolitan area, homes for sale, many brokers say, seem to have
simply vanished.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the problem appears more severe in certain
communities and for homes within certain price ranges. And real
estate agents report that there are still houses that are taking
months to sell, usually because they are unusual properties that
have highly specialized features, or because they are seriously
overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, the New York metropolitan area
appears to be in the midst of an inventory drought that many real
estate professionals say they have never seen before. As a result,
they say, homes coming on the market are more often than not
spurring bidding wars that frequently leave both buyer and seller
gasping in disbelief. In New Rochelle, for example, overnight price
increases of 25 percent are no longer uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not negotiating here _ it's like an auction,'' said
Hiedi Ross, a sales agent for the local Century 21 King David
office. She said that one of her current clients, a couple who have
a mortgage commitment of $650,000, can't seem to land a house
because they are persistently outbid by at least $20,000 every time
a house comes up within their price range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen the market like this,'' said Gerald Ziering,
president of the Century 21 King David office. ``In most markets
you usually have an inventory surplus that keeps moving along with
the market, but in this case the surplus was eaten up about a year
ago, so now there's nothing that we're carrying forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much of the inventory crunch can be pegged to a
strong economy, as well as years of relatively low interest rates.
But real estate brokers cite other factors as well.
</P>
<P>
   First, because of rising land values, new-home construction is
virtually nonexistent in many areas of suburban New York and the
city itself, especially the most desirable sections; for the same
reason, many homeowners are deciding to stay put and renovate
rather than move.
</P>
<P>
   A contributing but statistically untrackable factor, brokers and
others knowledgeable about the market say, is that the flush
economy is spurring homeowners, mostly in the suburbs, to try to
sell homes on their own rather than listing them with a broker and
paying a subsequent fee.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, meanwhile, are reacting to the inventory crunch by
increasingly asking that listings be considered exclusives rather
than sharing listings with their peers.
</P>
<P>
   All this has already fostered a mountain of anecdotes. There are
tales of brokers who used to routinely have dozens of listings at a
time but now are hard pressed to come up with enough to count on
one hand; open houses that have long lines of potential buyers
snaking out the door, and brokers who are slashing commissions _
perhaps by half _ to get listings.
</P>
<P>
   There are stories of smaller real estate firms that have gone
out of business for lack of listings, as well as sellers who have
become so overwhelmed by multiple bids for their homes that they
have whisked them off the market. And finally, there are examples
of how dispirited many potential home buyers have become.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last three sales that I've had, the first question I
was asked was how long had the house been on the market,'' said
Katy Anastasio, the founder of Anastasio Associates Inc. Realtors
in Huntington, which has been in business since 1980. ``It seems
that if a house is on the market for longer than a week, then
people wonder if there is something wrong with it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In some communities, the current inventory drought apparently
has less to do with fewer houses coming on the market overall, and
more to do with lightning-fast turnover, which has caused so-called
standing inventory to reach dismally low levels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Linda Hodge, a broker at the Greenwich, Conn.,
office for Preferred Properties, said that brokers in her area
actually had slightly more listings for single-family residential
properties _ 1,910 listings vs. 1,899 _ through the first eight
months of this year than they did for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that inventory is low, as it is responding to
market turnover,'' said Ms. Hodge. ``It's a turnover situation
because houses that were once just satisfactory are moving faster
than before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebie Wood, regional manager for Houlihan Lawrence in Pound Ridge
and South Salem agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have the same amount of homes coming on to the
market as in the past, but now they're coming on at time where
there are a lot of serious buyers who are not lingering when they
see a house that meets their needs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many real estate agents report that they are actually
seeing far fewer listings than before. Moreover, they report that
the drought doesn't appear to be tied to the fact that fall is a
time when generally fewer houses go on the market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Anastasio said that in her area, which is the
north shore of western Suffolk County, there are currently only
about 150 listings of houses for sale, as opposed to 350 at the
same time last year. Ms. Ross added that over the last six months
of this year, brokers in New Rochelle had only 182 listings, a
number that traditionally would have been perhaps 500 or 600.
</P>
<P>
   Certain types of homes appear to be especially scarce. For
example, a year ago, Evelyn Atanas, the founder of the 15-year-old
Atanas Realty in Williston Park had some 20 homes to show in
central Nassau County that were priced in the low $200,000s. But
now her least expensive home is a ``tiny'' house in Mineola, for
$249,000; most of her listings are priced at $279,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the supply of town houses and condominiums that
are relatively close to New York City is especially tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a healthy market we would probably have about five months
of town-house inventory, which means we would have 75 listings for
every 15 reported sales,'' said Jacelyn Botti, regional vice
president for Weichert Realtors in central New Jersey. ``But now we
have less than a 30-day supply of such homes, which means we have
fewer listings than we do reported sales.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Manhattan?
</P>
<P>
   In general, ``we've been in a low inventory situation for
years,'' said Lawrence Sicular, an appraisal analyst for Brown
Harris Stevens, which handles mostly blue-chip properties.
Nevertheless, Sicular added that supply _ relative to demand _
appears to be substantially tighter for certain types of properties
vs. others, and is now generally tightest for larger apartments,
which have also experienced the largest price jumps over the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Since April, Sicular has conducted a monthly inventory survey
for his firm of the most expensive sections of the Upper East Side
and Central Park West. And he cautioned that his results are often
based on relatively small sample sizes, because certain types of
apartments for sale, such as prewar six-room units, are relatively
rare to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in his most recent survey, taken last week, he
found that there are now roughly 28 percent fewer Classic Six
prewar co-op apartments _ with two bedrooms, a dining room and a
maid's room _ for sale in those neighborhoods than there were in
April. On the other hand, he said, the supply of similar postwar
apartments in those neighborhoods has grown 110 percent, while the
number of 1,500-square-foot or more lofts downtown has grown 34
percent since July.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, Sicular suspects that the inventory crunch
in Manhattan has eased a bit since Labor Day, for seasonal reasons
and possibly because a jittery stock market has put some potential
buyers at bay.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Manhattan, ``We're in a situation where demand for
one- to four-family homes has far exceeded supply,'' said Kenyatta
Punter, the founder of a real estate firm with the same name. ``We
started to see signs of an inventory problem in the fourth quarter
of 1998, and it's been a tight market since then.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how tight the situation has become, Punter, who
is also president of the Greater Harlem Real Estate Board, said
that open houses in his area now bring, on average, 50 to 75
attendees, whereas in 1997 attendance might have been 15 to 20
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Monday, it's not atypical now to receive 10 offers from an
open house, whereas in 1997 you might solicit just two or three
offers,'' he said, adding that the inventory crunch has also caused
prices in his area to rise 20 percent to 25 percent since January.
He said that a brownstone in the Hamilton Heights area near City
College that had an asking price of $500,000 in February is now in
contract for $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the brownstone communities surrounding Brooklyn Heights,
Cobble Hill, and Park Slope, Christopher Thomas, director of the
Brooklyn offices for the William May Company, said that there is
currently less town-house inventory available, compared to last
fall, but that the number of co-op apartments for sale has probably
stayed about the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in prices here has been driven heavily by the
lack of inventory,'' Thomas added. According to his figures,
Brooklyn town houses that were selling for between $1.7 million and
$2 million this time last year are now available for $2.3 million
and up. As for co-op apartments, prices have risen, on average,
some 15 percent since January, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory crunch may, however, be easing, according to
Jeffrey G. Otteau, president of the Otteau Appraisal Group in East
Brunswick, N.J., who said that a sharp drop in the number of sales
contracts in New Jersey suggests that buyers may be resisting
paying the higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the buying resistance, Otteau said, is seasonal: Most
local buyers tend to buy in the spring and summer months, so that
they can move before school begins. Nevertheless, he added, his
firm is now seeing cases of sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are looking at significantly higher prices for less
desirable homes than what we had available six months ago, and that
has created price resistance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Otteau added that the resistance helps explain why home sales in
New Jersey _ as measured by signed contracts _ appear to have
dropped dramatically since last summer _ some 40 percent _ as well
as why prices appear to have peaked. By comparison, Otteau said,
sales from the summer to the fall last year dropped between 15
percent and 20 percent, less than half the rate for this year.
</P>
<P>
   The only exceptions to the sharp drop in sales, he said, appear
to be entry-level houses that cost less than $250,000, and homes in
so-called secondary markets, those markets that consumers tend to
settle for when they can't afford the more desirable primary
markets. According to Otteau's figures, housing prices in New
Jersey's primary markets have jumped between 15 percent and 20
percent over the last year, but they have risen only 5 percent to
10 percent in the state's secondary markets
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hodes-Stempler is a home shopper frustrated by the price
jumps in her area, as well as the dearth of inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her husband, 2-year-old son, and brother, Ms.
Hodes-Stempler now lives in a rented five-bedroom, three-bathroom
house in Fresh Meadows, Queens. After four years of renting, the
family is ready to buy a home. But Ms. Hodes-Stempler and her
husband couldn't afford to buy the home they live in _ a house that
went on the market this fall for $389,000 and that received a
successful bid, for $375,000, in just two weeks. Nor can they
afford anything else in Fresh Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the couple are now looking on Long Island, where
they hope to find a home that costs roughly $300,000, to balance
the higher taxes there.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hodes-Stempler has seen dozens of houses since August,
through a dozen different real estate agents. Still, she feels as
though she is being shown the same recycled inventory. ``Agents are
acting like all their listings are fresh, but usually when they
call, I've already seen the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-October, Ms. Hodes-Stempler did hear of one house that
fit her needs: a four-bedroom Cape on a large lot in New Hyde Park
that was listed for $299,000, and that would have had an annual
real-estate tax payment of just $3,900.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time her broker was finally able to get her an
appointment to see the house, it was too late: the owners had
already accepted a bid. Still, Ms. Hodes-Stempler liked the house
enough to send the owners a check for $1,000, to hold her own bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a mad land grab here, but it is sort of desperate,''
she said. As an example, she pointed to 30 or so real estate agents
and their clients who were parked on the lawn of her rented home
when she came home from work one day a few weeks ago. They were
waiting to see a house that Ms. Hodes-Stempler thinks would have
sold for roughly $100,000 less just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers say Ms. Hodes-Stempler's experience isn't
unusual. Indeed, they claim that many consumers have become
unusually aggressive at getting the house they want.
</P>
<P>
   Take the couple who attended an open house that Ms. Atanas, the
Williston Park broker, recently sponsored in Mineola. The open
house was for a three-bedroom Colonial that was priced at $235,000,
a rarity, by any measure, in central Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ms. Atanas, the first day the house was on the
market, its owners received three offers, all full-priced. In the
end, however, the owners accepted a bid from a couple who refused
to leave the house until they knew they had it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Atanas called a mortgage broker that she works with, who
preapproved the couple's mortgage on the spot. Meanwhile, the
couple arranged to have an engineer inspect the house Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract went out on Tuesday, and within a week it was
signed, sealed, and delivered,'' she said. ``That's how fast this
couple worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every home is moving at such speed, of course. Ms. Wood, for
example, can think of one home in northern Westchester that was
recently put on the market by its owners _ an estate _ for
$550,000, but which she thought should have been priced at
$495,000.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after it went on the market, the house received two bids,
for $480,000 and $485,000, but the estate turned both offers down.
After several months of paying carrying charges for the property,
however, the estate reduced the price of the home to $475,000, and
eventually sold it for $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   In this market, if that house had been priced properly, it would
have sold immediately,'' Ms. Wood said. ``Sellers should remember
that their home will probably sell for less than it would have sold
for if it had gone to market at the right price, and while this is
usually a real-estate truism, it's especially true in a very active
market such as what we now have.''
</P>
<P>
   But Otteau also urges sellers not to get too greedy. Based on
what he has recently noticed within the New Jersey real estate
market, he thinks that homeowners who want to sell their homes over
the next three or four months will need to price them more
competitively than was necessary six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Betsy Goss, a sales agent at Prudential Connecticut
Realty in Darien, urges sellers to remember that the fall and
winter months often bring in a different kind of buyer than do the
spring months. ``Often these buyers have been looking and looking,
and are educated enough to know the market,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What about buyers? Ms. Goss advises them to get preapproval for
a mortgage before they start looking, and to come see the house as
soon as they can with checkbooks in hand. As for Ms. Ross, the real
estate agent in New Rochelle, she urges buyers to take a reality
check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the asking price no longer gets you the
house,'' she said. ``If it's a good house, you've got to go over
that price immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
