<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUGBY-WORLDCUP-NYT &LR;      10-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUGBY-WORLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA BEATS SOUTH AFRICA IN WORLD CUP RUGBY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ South Africa had never lost a game in the rugby union
World Cup, and when their stocky fly-half Jannie de Beer sent an
improbable 40-meter penalty kick through on the last play of
regulation to send Saturday's semifinal against Australia into
overtime, it appeared that the Springboks might not leave
windswept, rainswept Twickenham Stadium a loser either.
</P>
<P>
   There was a whiff of destiny about de Beer's oscillating kick
into the wind; a whiff of the sort of good fortune that had helped
the South Africans win the last World Cup on their own soil and
spark a national celebration and a powerful, if ephemeral,
rapprochement between the black majority that never much cared for
rugby because of its links with the apartheid regime and the white
minority that could not get enough of the rough and tumble game.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, de Beer's kick was only a perfectly timed
tease. There will be no chance to repeat the memorable victory
embrace between Nelson Mandela, the former South African president,
and the Springbok captain. Not this year. The Australians, slightly
more constructive and creative throughout this bone-rattling
encounter, made sure of that by scoring nine points to the South
Africans' three in the 20 minutes of overtime and then walking off
the field drenched and delighted with a 27-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians will now face the winner of Sunday's semifinal,
between the tournament favorite, New Zealand, and this year's most
prominent underachiever, France.
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult for any of the remaining games to match the
suspense of this one. It was a game without tries (comparable to
touchdowns in football), but a game in which the players never
stopped trying their best: tackling ferociously and scrambling for
loose balls and precious meters inside and outside the aptly named
scrums and rucks and mauls that are the rough and equally rough
equivalent of line play in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a roller-coaster ride, a great sporting game,'' said
South African coach Nick Mallett. ``There are two ways you can be
disappointed: because you let yourself down or because of the
result. This team has not let itself down. It gave its best and has
nothing to be ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa and Australia know each other well. They play
against each other annually in the Tri Nations tournament along
with New Zealand. They are the best the Southern Hemisphere has to
offer, and the Southern Hemisphere remains the center of power in
this sport that was invented, like so many other of this century's
most popular games, by the British.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand won the first World Cup in 1987; Australia the
second in 1991; the South Africans the third in their return to
international competition after being banned from the first two
because of their political system.
</P>
<P>
   The Springboks experienced another tumultuous stretch in 1997
and 1998 in which the specter of racism on their team resurfaced
and coach Andre Markgraaff and federation president Louis Luyt
resigned. They experienced a disquieting stretch earlier this year
when their 17-game victory streak came to a halt and they were
beaten by Wales, trounced twice by New Zealand and once by
Australia, in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Springboks and Mallet, their uncommonly cosmopolitan
coach, managed to grind out a much-needed 10-9 victory over the
Australians in the return match in South Africa in August and then
proved that they had recovered their balance and confidence by
defeating England in last week's World Cup quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The key to that victory was de Beer's five drop goals _ a record
_ and a tactical flourish to which the English could find no
riposte. But it was clear early Saturday that the points would not
come as easily for de Beer or his team. De Beer missed his first
two drop goal attempts and the third was blocked. He ended up one
for five.
</P>
<P>
   His place-kicking was much more accurate, however, and he and
Australia's designated kicker, fullback Matt Burke, engaged in an
afternoon-long duel. Burke finished with 24 points on eight penalty
kicks, de Beer with all 21 of South Africa's points on seven
penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic came in the final seconds of injury time in
the second half with Australia leading by 18-15 and agonizingly
close to celebrating. South Africa had possession inside
Australia's half, but the Australians only needed to avoid errors,
contain the Springboks and let the clock run out. Instead,
Australian forward Owen Finegan was called for a penalty after
handling the ball in a ruck, which might sound innocuous to an
uninitiated American but was anything but to Welsh referee Derek
Bevan.
</P>
<P>
   De Beer took a swig of water and made his difficult 40-meter
penalty kick from an angle to send the game into overtime, which
consists of two 10-minute periods with the teams changing sides
between periods. After the first, the score was still even at
21-21, but the Australians knew that if it finished that way, they
would be the team to reach the final because of the tie-breaking
rules in use here (the South Africans had had a player expelled
from a match during this tournament; the Australians had not).
</P>
<P>
   The Springboks needed the points. The Australians would end up
getting them, first on a surprise drop kick from 45 meters by their
own fly-half Stephen Larkham in the 13th minute of overtime. The
kick looked as spontaneous as it was straight, and Burke would add
the final three points with a penalty kick in the 18th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Australians have the chance to win their second World
Cup this year in Britain. Their cricket team won the first this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
