<HEADER>
A3528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT     10-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE PARCELLS' HEADSET, SIGNALS ARE SCRAMBLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you may be wondering: is all this misery finally too much
for Bill Parcells, and is he going to pack it in after this season?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no. Well, at least not necessarily _ that is, if
you listen to him, try to interpret it, and guess what it all
means.
</P>
<P>
   His team is 1-6 (although without too much stretch of the
imagination, it could be 3-4 or 4-3). With a bye week, he has a
rare Sunday at home to reflect on how difficult this season has
been. And during the week he went through the emotional trauma of
losing his good friend and longtime agent, Robert Fraley, in the
plane crash that claimed the lives of golfer Payne Stewart and four
others.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the future, Parcells said last week that he can
only concentrate on the next game _ next Sunday against the Arizona
Cardinals at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   But if he was going to hang 'em up, why is he worrying about
next season's backup quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point,'' he also said last week, ``I'm going to have
to find out whether it's Rick Mirer or Ray Lucas _ it won't be Tom
Tupa _ as Vinny Testaverde's backup next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I do something to improve my chances at the position
next season? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   This much Parcells has said about retirement: He wants it to
happen by the time he is 60. He will not be 60 until 2,001.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel my health is an issue, I'll retire,'' he has also
said.
</P>
<P>
   And how is his health?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' he said just the other day.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that when time for retirement comes, ``There'll be
no shame in that.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite quotation of his is borrowed from Marv Levy, his
former colleague in the coaching fraternity who had a long run of
success with the Buffalo Bills. ``When you're thinking of
retirement, you're already retired,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there is this to wonder about: the sale of the club.
Parcells' $2.4 million-a-year contract will still be in force next
year. But how much is Parcells worth to any billionaire who will
shell out about $500 million _ and will, no doubt, want to keep the
coach who turned around the franchise? Certainly, it would seem
that incentives for Parcells to stay would be in the millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But this area is murky, too. What the average fan thinks a
Parcells is worth to a franchise, a potential owner may not.
</P>
<P>
   One recent buyer, who backed away because he thought the team's
price would be too steep, considered the Parcells effect in
purchasing the team. The businessman, who is also active in sports
but did not want to be identified, suggested the following: ``If
you asked me six months ago, I'd give you a different answer. They
were headed for the Super Bowl then. That said, Parcells is good,
but is he the difference in buying a team? I don't think so. The
deal is so expensive, it's not based on people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have a problematic lease in that the money they take in
falls far short of what other franchises, with their own stadiums,
have been able to amass.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur looked at it coolly when asked whether he, or
any buyer, would raise Parcells' $2.4 million salary to keep him,
if that is what it took. ``You'd sweeten it,'' he said. ``But it's
hard to sweeten it for only eight games.'' He meant, of course,
that the Jets play eight home games at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   His players have been wondering for weeks whether Parcells will
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he'd want to go out on a note like this,''
linebacker Chad Cascadden said. ``We were talking about it and we
came to the conclusion he'd want to go out a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   And Testaverde plans to speak to Parcells after the season about
returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him back,'' the quarterback said.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde will tell him that many of the major components,
which Parcells had refined in the past off-season, will remain in
place next season. Indeed, the Jets on paper were a significantly
better club this year than last season, when they came a few
fumbles from winning the American Conference title and going to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells knows that he will face serious cap issues next
season because of the number of high-salaried players. And the team
has yet to sign Pro Bowl linebacker Mo Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask everyone here,'' said a high-ranking team official
who, like almost everyone in the organization, does not want to be
quoted by name, ``to a man no one knows. He just hasn't let on. I
wish I knew, but I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official said of Parcells' style, ``He won't know it
until 20 minutes before he knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill goes by how he feels,'' said left tackle Jumbo
Elliott, who had a long stint with Parcells on the Giants before
hooking up with him again on the Jets. ``When he knows, you'll
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime Parcells player whose relationship began back
in New England, running back Curtis Martin, merely said, ``I hope
Bill does what makes his heart sing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
