<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATE-AMERICA-KWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN IS ENJOYING THE TWISTS OF HER DOUBLE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SKATE-AMERICA) 
(lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS _ On weekdays, when anonymity swallows her up
in the stampede of 24,000 UCLA undergrads hustling to get to class
on time and struggling to stay awake once they get there, Michelle
Kwan's mandatory accessories are books and a baseball cap. On
weekends like this one, when world-class competition calls to her
like a siren, it's back to Spandex, sequins, and a Mona Lisa smile
for the inevitable celebrity spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   This double life that Kwan, the two-time world champion and
three-time national champion, has opted to live, so far has proven
more restorative than distracting. Here at Skate America, the first
significant test of the season, Kwan blithely skated into first
place after Friday's short program with a performance that
expressed a duality befitting its creator.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Kwan hone in like a technician on all eight
required elements, she gave Lennon-McCartney's ``A Day in the
Life'' an air of brooding reverie that transformed a compulsory
test into a work of art. Kwan later supposed it was her karmic
connection to the Beatles (her father named her for their song
``Michelle'') that enabled her to ``let it rip.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, it was that moment of freedom when, just as visions of
homework flitted into her consciousness, she was able to tell
herself that all she had to do for the next two minutes was skate
to perfection. It felt like a release instead of a responsibility.
It felt right.
</P>
<P>
   Now that skating has become her other dimension instead of her
only dimension, Kwan, at 19, could be undergoing a rejuvenation.
After a disappointing 1998 Olympics, where she was upstaged in
Nagano by Tara Lipinski (who immediately abandoned her amateur
career upon pocketing the gold medal and some $10 million in
attendant endorsements), Kwan took her silver medal and began
taking stock of herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I thought I could never be happy with just
a silver medal; when I watched the Olympics on TV, I remember I
always pitied the person who got the silver,'' Kwan said over a
post-practice cup of tea, having sworn off the ice cream, fries,
and pizza that added a treacherous 3 pounds to her sylph-like frame
after just one week at college. Kwan said even that tiny quantity
of extra ballast made the two-year-old stress fracture in her toe
start to throb and caused her usually unflappable coach, Frank
Carroll, to exclaim, ``Oh, my God!'' the first time he saw her
after she'd started school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all that late-night studying, sitting there on your
fanny,'' said Kwan, who pulls all-nighters like the rest of the
inmates, but has tempered her snacking and her studying technique.
``I keep myself moving,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is tempting to assume that Kwan has elected to attend
college and retain her Olympic-eligibility because she's fixated on
coming away from Salt Lake City with a gold medal in 2002, she
hopes that isn't her only reason for making a ``pivotal'' lifestyle
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I could stay amateur just for 2002; that's so
far away, and who knows what's going to happen there,'' Kwan said.
``I want to be there with all my heart, but I don't think that's
why I'm doing this. It's not tangible; it's more for the everyday
challenge of skating, of competing, of trying to figure out why, if
I've done that triple a million times in practice, how can I miss
it in competition? How can you say that six minutes at the Olympics
is going to tell you that you'll be happy for the rest of your
life? That's insane.''
</P>
<P>
   So is studying until 4 a.m. in an unair-conditioned dormitory
cubicle while stereos compete for the airwaves and unofficial
football games rage in the hallway, especially when you have to
wake up at seven for a skate and then hustle back to take a quiz.
But for this quarter at least, Kwan is reveling in the frenzy.
She's soaking in ``the whole 9 yards'' of the college experience,
and doing it in sync with her contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me I should wait until I'm 21 to go to school,''
said Kwan, who instead took her cues from her brother and sister
(at California-Irvine and Boston University, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   ``I know school could wait, but the experience I wanted
couldn't. I was ready to have my mind not thinking about skating
100 percent; it can drive someone crazy. Believe me, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she also had the positive examples of Olympic medalists
who went the academic route: Dick Button, a Harvard man, won gold
in 1948 and '52; Tenley Albright graduated from Harvard Medical
School after winning gold in '56, and Debi Thomas was attending
Stanford when she won bronze in '88.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm going to succeed 100 percent at combining
school and skating; at times I may fail, but hopefully not
miserably,'' said Kwan, who has noted a connection between her
attitude toward skating and studies. ``I'm pretty extreme; I expect
so much from myself: Why do things halfway?''
</P>
<P>
   Just before this competition, Kwan was fretting about receiving
a B on a quiz, a mark that left her father, Danny, unperturbed.
``He told me what's wrong with a B, B's are good,''' said Kwan.
``But I wanted an A. I guess it's just innate in me that I want to
be better.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kwan, who picked up another record-breaking 6.0, her 21st
in Olympic-style skating, for presentation here on Friday, leaves
unsaid is that she'd like to be best; according to her coach, she's
already there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got millions; she doesn't need to work a day in her life
if she doesn't want to, and if she walked away from skating right
this minute, I still feel she'd go down as one of the greats,''
said the 61-year-old Carroll, who has vowed not to retire until
Kwan does.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she's not through with it yet. She's intellectual enough
that she knows where she draws her satisfaction from, and it's not
money or medals. It's simply the beauty of skating, and the
competing. Before she started at UCLA, she had the feeling she was
wasting time, wasting her life just on skating, and she did
something about it. She knew she can't be doing double axels until
she's 50, but that education is something you have forever, until
you're dead. Now that she's challenging her mind, the skating has
become a joy again. We'll have to wait and see where that goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ICE CHIPS:
</P>
<P>
   Just behind Michelle Kwan in the short program was 14-year-old
Sarah Hughes of Great Neck, N.Y., with Russia's Elena Sokolova in
third. The men's standings heading into tonight's long program,
worth two thirds of their score, had Alexei Yagudin of Russia, the
two-time world champion who is also defending this title, in first
place. Michael Weiss, the 1999 United States champion, was second,
and 19-year-old Timothy Goebel, who last year became the first man
to land a quadruple salchow in competition and Friday night became
the first to land the jump in a short program, was third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT-HOME-REAL-825&AMP;ADD-     10-30 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO CHECK CHIMNEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's flue season. Has your chimney had its annual checkup?
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend that people have their chimneys inspected at
least once a year,'' said Julie Reynolds, a spokeswoman for the
nonprofit National Fire Protection Association, based in Quincy,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Reynolds said that of an average 8,800 home fires each year
because of faulty or improperly used fireplaces, about 5,500 are
caused by fires in the chimney itself.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in most chimney fires, she said, is creosote _ a
chemical substance formed from burning wood _ which builds up
inside the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a lot of creosote, it can actually ignite,'' Ms.
Reynolds said. ``And having a fire in your chimney is a lot
different than having a fire in your fireplace.''
</P>
<P>
   With a chimney fire, she said, dangerous amounts of smoke can
back up into the house, creating a potentially deadly hazard for
occupants. And if the fire in the chimney gets hot enough, it can
end up setting the house on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason for having an annual chimney checkup, Ms.
Reynolds said, is to ensure that the lining of the flue is in good
shape and will keep smoke and dangerous gases out of the living
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have loose bricks or cracks in the chimney lining, you
can end up with carbon monoxide seeping into the house,'' she said.
``And while we recommend that people consider installing carbon
monoxide detectors, that is no replacement for making sure your
chimney is working properly.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if you don't use your fireplace? Is an inspection still
necessary? And what if you don't even have a fireplace to use?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you don't have a fireplace, doesn't mean you
don't have a chimney,'' said Ashley Eldridge, technical director
for the National Chimney Sweep Guild, an industry organization
based in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Eldridge explained that just about any house that has to vent
combustion gases _ whether from a fireplace, a wood stove, an oil
furnace, a gas furnace, or even a gas water heater _ will have a
chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, houses that have more than one source of
combustion _ for example, a house with a fireplace and a gas
furnace _ will usually have two separate flues running inside the
chimney. That means that if a homeowner decides to use electric
logs in the fireplace this year, the chimney still needs to be
inspected, because it will be venting the exhaust gas from the
furnace.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, inspecting the chimney by crawling into the
fireplace and shining a flashlight up toward the roof is hardly
going to reveal the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flue from the fireplace might look fine while the flue
from the furnace could be collecting debris,'' he said. One of the
most common causes of heating-system ventilation problems, he said,
is debris that has accumulated at the point where the vent from the
furnace enters the chimney. And while an oil- or gas-furnace flue
is not likely to have problems related to a buildup of creosote,
both are prone to problems of their own.
</P>
<P>
   An oil-fired furnace that is not properly adjusted can cause a
buildup of soot on the interior walls of the chimney. If allowed to
accumulate, Eldridge said, that soot can clog the chimney, thereby
further reducing the efficiency of the furnace. Or the soot can
fall off the lining walls to the bottom and clog the vent itself.
</P>
<P>
   And while gas-fired furnaces burn cleaner and cooler than oil
furnaces, they can cause even more trouble than an oil furnace if
they are not vented correctly. ``There's not a lot of smoke with a
gas appliance,'' Eldridge said. ``But there could be a lot of
condensation.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that since most chimneys were built to accommodate
the exhaust that high-temperature gases produce when coal or oil is
burned, they are not properly sized for exhausting the cooler gases
produced when gas is burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem that bigger is always better, but that's usually
not the case when a new gas furnace is vented into an old
chimney,'' Eldridge said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that since chimneys work because rising hot air
creates the draft necessary to keep everything moving up and out,
problems can arise if the gas in the chimney cools too soon _
something that often happens when low-temperature appliances are
vented through flues designed for high-temperature exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   And when the exhaust from a gas appliance cools too soon,
Eldridge said, condensation forms on the inside walls of the
chimney, setting the stage for major problems down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The condensate can be acidic,'' he said, explaining that when
water comes in contact with the byproducts of combustion that line
the interior walls of the flue, one of the resulting substances is
hydrochloric acid. ``The acids can actually destroy the chimney by
eating away at it from within.'' In other words, he said, even a
chimney that looks fine from the outside could have some serious
internal problems.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   George Infantino, the owner of Chimney Tech, a chimney
inspection and cleaning company based in Island Park, N.Y., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't call me until something goes wrong,''
Infantino said. The most common signs of chimney problems that
homeowners notice are furnace malfunctions, smoke in the house or
loose bricks or masonry on the floor of a fireplace. ``And by the
time things have gotten to that point,'' he said, ``they usually
have a major problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, he said, the only way to avoid serious
chimney damage is to identify and repair small problems before they
become big ones. And the first thing a reputable company will do is
to determine whether the chimney itself is appropriate for the
appliances that are being vented through it.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, while a 50-year-old chimney with an
8-by-8-inch flue might have been appropriate for a coal furnace, a
smaller flue is likely to be required for a high-efficiency gas
furnace. If that is the case, he said, the size of the flue can be
reduced by inserting a stainless steel liner inside the existing
opening. The cost of relining a chimney in a two-story house, he
said, runs from about $1,200 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   If the existing flue is determined to be the proper size, it
still needs to be inspected. And while it is possible to inspect
the interior of a chimney using high-powered lights and mirrors,
the most accurate chimney inspection is obtained by means of a
video camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camera gives you the ability to go down inside the flue
and see things you'd never be able to see with lights and
mirrors,'' said Tom Urban, the owner of Estoban Corp., a Fairfield,
Iowa, company that manufactures and markets Chim-Scan, a video
system used by chimney inspection companies across the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Chimney inspection companies that use the Chim-Scan system,
Urban said, typically make a videotape of the inspection so that
the homeowner can see the condition of the interior of the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a great way for people who are buying a house to
check the condition of the chimney beforehand,'' he said. Urban
said video inspections of chimneys can run from under $100 to
several hundred dollars, depending on the size and location of the
chimney and the number of flues to be inspected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
