<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOAT-AMERICA'S-CUP-NY     10-30 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN BOAT SPEEDS AHEAD ON MONEY, LUCK AND TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an old, telling story about Italy's first America's Cup
challenge, in 1983. One could always foresee an Italian tack, it
was said, when the crewmen, in unison, tossed their freshly lighted
smokes over the side.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, observers found the game, but inexperienced, Azzurra
bunch to be a source of great mirth. But no one is laughing at
Italy's latest ensemble. For at the conclusion of the first round
of the Louis Vuitton Cup challenger trials last Thursday, the
Milan-based Prada Challenge sat firmly atop the standing with a
10-0 record. The second round of trials begins on Saturday, Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by the wealthy Bertellis of global fashion renown,
Prada's budget reportedly ranges between $50 million and $70
million. Along with cash, they have talent: Doug Peterson, the
naval architect who helped create the last two cup-winning boats
sailed by Bill Koch's America3 syndicate and Team New Zealand,
commands a design effort that includes German Frers, the legendary
Argentine.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie cup afterguard, led by Francesco de Angelis, the
internationally tested big-boat skipper, and the Brazilian-born
tactician Torben Grael, a three-time Olympic sailing medalist, have
proved that they can compete with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   And in the first round-robin, the Italians also enjoyed a
priceless intangible _ sweet, dumb luck. Twice they encountered
critical matches with American challengers also sporting
unblemished records: first against the San Francisco-based America
One crew and, a day later, with the New York Yacht Club's Young
America contingent.
</P>
<P>
   In both races, the U.S. team was winning with the finish line in
sight. Incredibly, in each contest, the American boat came undone
when an identical spinnaker shackle failed, the equivalent of
lightning striking twice. The Italians capitalized on the gaffes to
remain undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   With duplicate 8-2 marks, Young America, skippered by Ed Baird,
and Paul Cayard's America One are tied for second and have joined
Prada in the elite ranks of the 11 challenging syndicates. All
three squads are now heavily favored to advance to the six-team
semifinal challengers round next January. But the remaining three
spots are wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday a much-anticipated race between the two top
American syndicates proved anticlimactic when America One, unable
to hoist its mainsail because of rig damage, retired after two
legs. In 18 to 20 knots of breeze, Young America sailed the course
uncontested to record the victory, worth one point. In the next
round robin, each victory will be worth four points.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter stages of the first round, stiff winds and broken
gear became continual refrains. On one windy, bewildering day that
seemed more like a demolition derby than a regatta, six of eight
scheduled races turned into one-sided fiascos because of a litany
of miscues. Meanwhile, on an adjacent course, the two Team New
Zealand yachts conducted a flawless heavy-air practice session, a
sight the Louis Vuitton spokesman Bruno Trouble called
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   The weather, which in the early going brought nearly breathless
conditions before freshening to the more seasonly spring gusts, has
not been the only surprise. Dawn Riley's coed America True
campaign, also based in San Francisco, has showed flashes of
downwind brilliance and is holding fourth place. Japan's Nippon
Challenge, which rallied after a poor start, is fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a half-point penalty imposed by an international jury
for a prestart collision during a race with America One, Dennis
Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes trails the Spanish Challenge, in sixth,
though both teams are deadlocked at 5-5. The incident, which sent
America One into the shed for repairs to its stern, was partly
responsible for several days of postponed racing. In assessing the
penalty, the jury appeared to be sending a hard-line message to the
fleet regarding future contact between competitors.
</P>
<P>
   John Kolius' Honolulu-based Abracadabra, the French yacht Le
Defi Francais, and Young Australia were all off the pace in Round
1. As is the case with Prada, Young America, America One, and the
Nippon Challenge, Kolius has a second new boat at his disposal and
may hold an ace up his sleeve. The others must tinker and try to
eke more speed from their lone entries.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the Swiss boat Be Happy, the only challenger
that failed to win a race in the first round. With limited backing,
the Swiss are to be commended for trying something different. But
their radical yacht _ which reportedly employs two keels and
fore-and-aft rudders _ is dreadfully slow and a nightmare to steer.
</P>
<P>
   The British sailing journalist Tim Jeffrey has suggested that
the Swiss add a three-word preface to their boat's name. Already a
handful, No Reason to Be Happy would also be a mouthful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
