<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FEDBUD-$ADV31-1STLD-C     10-30 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDBUD-$ADV31-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE THAN DOLLARS SEPARATE CLINTON, CONGRESS IN BUDGET END GAME
 &HT;    EDS: Updates after 4th graf with Saturday developments.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 31.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of heated rhetoric and partisan
maneuvering, President Clinton and congressional leaders are poised
to wage the final skirmishes this week in their fight over the 2000
budget.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of money, the Democrats and Republicans are not far
apart. They are squabbling over a difference of about $10 billion
in a budget whose tax and spending proposals total $1.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides have staked out sharply different positions on
several important issues, including education and foreign policy.
While funding disputes are often settled by splitting the
difference, compromises on policy are harder to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has signaled his willingness to bend on some of these
issues _ ``I never thought I'd get 100 percent of what I wanted,''
he said last week _ but aides insist he will not give them up
completely.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the two sides promised to work together even as
they traded barbs.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter House leaders sent to Clinton _ it was signed
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois, Majority Leader Dick Armey of
Texas, Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas, and J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, the House Republican Conference chairman _ they
complained their efforts to reach a budget agreement have been
blocked by Democrats out ``to advance their political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written response, White House Chief of Staff John Podesta
accused Republicans of pushing proposals that would jeopardize the
financial stability of the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   The political stakes are making the negotiations difficult. Each
party hopes to make points that will carry them to victory in next
year's presidential and congressional elections. Currently, the GOP
controls both houses of Congress. But the margin in the House is
only 222-211, with one Democrat-leaning Independent and one
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security surplus has emerged as the battleground that
underlies all the combat.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats have agreed to depart from 30
years of budget practice and reserve surplus Social Security taxes
_ projected to hit $147 billion next year _ to reduce the $5.7
trillion federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has already accused the other of trying to renege.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to requests from Democrats, the Congressional Budget
Office reported last week that under its own spending assumptions,
the Republican budget would gouge $17 billion out of next year's
Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly got the CBO to state that under the more
flexible accounting rules used by GOP appropriators, the surplus
would not be tapped. In contrast, they said, it is Democrats who
want to spend the surplus for unneeded programs.
</P>
<P>
   To make their own budget add up, House Republicans last week
approved a 1 percent across-the-board cut in discretionary
spending, excepting some defense programs. Discretionary spending
is the one-third of the federal budget not mandated as payouts to
veterans, retirees and Medicare and Medicaid recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are asking federal agencies to do is what single moms
and single dads, working moms and dads all over the country do on a
weekly basis,'' House Republican Conference Committee chairman
Watts told PBS on Friday. ``For someone to say that we can't find
one penny, one penny of every dollar that comes into the government
in savings, seems to be a bit of a stretch to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House countered that the plan would cut into the
marrow of needed programs. Discretionary spending, points out White
House spokesman Barry Toiv, has already fallen over the past eight
years from 8.7 percent of the country's total economic output to
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point,'' said Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, ``at
which you can die of a thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Clinton is expected to veto the GOP plan for
across-the-board cuts. The plan is likely to be passed by the
Senate early this week and sent to Clinton's desk after he returns
Tuesday night from a trip to Norway.
</P>
<P>
   That trip will spotlight his fight for increased funding of a
host of his foreign affairs priorities. He and his congressional
foes are roughly $3 billion apart on his request for money to help
pay back dues the United States owes to the United Nations, Third
World debt relief and aid Clinton has promised to Palestinians and
Israelis as part of their efforts to secure peace in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who agreed to Republican increases in the $268 billion
defense spending bill, wants his foreign aid requests funded in
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that, you know, I've worked with them. I signed that
defense bill ... and I think they ought to work with me so that we
can have a balanced national security policy,'' Clinton said in an
interview. ``I feel very strongly about it, and I'm going to fight
hard for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Clinton has dug in his heels on money to hire new
teachers to reduce the size of elementary school classes. Congress
wants to lump the education money into block grants that states can
spend as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, Clinton on Friday signed a third
temporary spending bill that will government operating without a
formal budget until Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   He said he remains optimistic that he and his Republican foes
can wrap up this contentious season of budget wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, as much as I fight with these Republicans, it's
amazing, if we just sit down and talk and spend a few hours
together, normally we can work it out,'' Clinton said in an Oval
Office interview Wednesday. ``You actually have to work hard not to
make an agreement with me _ if we can do it in good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
