<HEADLINE>
SUIT BY MAN ACCUSED OF AIRLINE ATTACK IS DISMISSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ People are always filing lawsuits seeking to
vindicate their constitutional rights, but a judge says a Manhattan
lawyer went too far in a suit having to do with air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no constitutional right to separate the shoulder of a
flight attendant on a delayed flight,'' U.S. District Judge John S.
Martin Jr. wrote in an opinion released Friday that dismissed the
case. He said he was considering sanctions against the lawyer,
Howard Gotbetter, for filing a frivolous suit.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said Gotbetter and a woman he was traveling with
became angry that their plane was in a holding pattern before a
landing.
</P>
<P>
   While Gotbetter's companion _ ``a woman with an apparently
limited vocabulary,'' as the judge put it _ screamed ``gutter
epithets'' at a flight attendant, Gotbetter grabbed the crew member
by the shoulder and shook her so violently that she suffered a
partially separated left shoulder and an injury to her rotator
cuff. She was out of work for six months, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not surprisingly,'' Martin continued, Gotbetter and his friend
were later removed from the plane ``to the apparent delight of
several of the other passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the government later opened administrative
proceedings against Gotbetter under a Federal Aviation
Administration rule that says ``no person may assault, threaten,
intimidate or interfere'' with a plane's crew. The lawyer was
trying to block those proceedings with his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Saturday by phone, Gotbetter said, ``Judge Martin's
opinion is totally contrary to fact.'' He denied assaulting the
attendant on the American Airlines flight from San Francisco to New
York in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gotbetter said an administrative judge with the FAA found
earlier that he had touched the flight attendant for 14 seconds,
which had constituted assault. He contended that she had backed
into a ski magazine he was holding. He also said the FAA judge
found that he had not threatened, intimidated, or interfered with
the attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Gotbetter argued in his lawsuit that the regulation was
``unconstitutionally vague'' because it ``does not give a person of
ordinary intelligence a reasonable basis to know what is
prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martin said even someone of ``limited intelligence'' would
grasp the idea. ``One does not have a right to take out one's
frustration over the vagaries of air travel by assaulting the crew
of an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the regulation protected crew members from ``unwarranted
assaults by antisocial airline passengers whose egos are so large
that they have no concern for the rights of others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
