<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PUERTO-RICO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ISLAND BOMBING RANGE  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 31:
</P>
<P>
   A presidential panel created by Defense Secretary William Cohen
recommended earlier this month that the Navy cease all training
activities on the island of Vieques near Puerto Rico in five years.
In the interim, the Navy would be allowed to use the island for
live bombing exercises. That phase-out plan is not fast enough. The
Navy should discontinue the shelling right now and promptly return
the land to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   About 9,300 people live on Vieques, a small island six miles off
the coast of Puerto Rico. The Navy controls two-thirds of its
33,000 acres. Aerial bombing and naval gunfire over the past two
decades have degraded the environment and stymied efforts to
increase tourism and maritime jobs. Angry protests from local
residents, who are U.S. citizens, and the Puerto Rican government
erupted in April when a civilian guard was killed at the Naval
range in a bombing accident. Live fire exercises have been
suspended pending a final decision by President Clinton. Meanwhile,
Sens. Charles Schumer and Frank Murkowski have introduced a bill
calling for the immediate removal of the Navy from the island.
</P>
<P>
   This controversy goes back to the 1970s, when the Navy ceased
using the neighboring island of Culebra for weapons training after
mortar fire landed on a beach where children were playing. Training
exercises were transferred from Culebra to Vieques, despite intense
opposition from the governor of Puerto Rico and the island
community. In 1983, the governor and the Navy secretary signed an
agreement in which the Navy promised to help with economic
development, address safety and environmental hazards caused by the
shelling, and keep the use of live fire to an absolute minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential panel found that the Navy has not lived up to
those commitments. The percentage of live fire used in relation to
inert ammunition actually doubled from the late 1970s to the 1990s.
No real effort has been made to deal with noise and health
concerns, and relations with the community have deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy says it cannot perform combined combat exercises
anywhere on the East Coast. But separate components of the
exercises, such as aerial bombing, artillery training and ship
gunfire training, can be conducted at ranges elsewhere. The panel
noted that the availability and convenience of Vieques may have
influenced the assessment of other sites. The panel's
recommendation that an alternative be found in five years suggests
that military readiness need not be compromised by using other
venues and other training methods. The people of Vieques should not
have to wait that long before the Navy clears out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
