<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     10-30 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS PRESSING TO GET OUT VOTE IN SAN ANTONIO 
GIVING VANCOUVER A CHANCE 
HORNETS HAVING THEIR PROBLEMS 
THE LAKERS' MISSING PIECE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Duncan has threatened to leave, via free agency. The owner,
Peter Holt, is implying that he may move the team. Even the
gracious David Robinson has joined the gallant fight to make the
people of San Antonio pay for a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Warning the citizenry of the great catastrophe at hand if they
fail to vote for a referendum on Tuesday, Robinson said: ``If they
don't want the team there, that's fine. But they have to realize
what comes with that or what goes with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA champions have suddenly become politicians as they open
defense of their title. At issue is a proposed hotel and car rental
tax that would raise a projected 84 percent of the money needed for
a new $175 million arena to replace the cavernous and outdated
Alamodome. Residents of Bexar County, Texas, will vote on the
controversial referendum on the same day the Spurs will open the
season and raise their championship banner.
</P>
<P>
   Without a new arena _ and the extra revenue that comes with
luxury boxes, food courts and other amenities _ the Spurs have
intimated that they won't be able to sign Duncan, the game's most
accomplished player who can become a free agent at the end of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arena is a big part of it,'' Duncan told The Chicago
Tribune earlier this month. ``If there is a possibility they're
going to move, I don't want to be stuck in a city I don't want to
be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt also has hinted at the possibility of moving the franchise
should the referendum be rejected. Despite winning the
championship, the Spurs claim they lost $12 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The current deal has Holt only putting up $28.5 million of the
expected $175 million price tag for the new arena. In late
September, Citizens for Responsible Spending conducted a survey of
500 likely San Antonio voters from the hospitality industry.
According to the data gathered, 48 percent opposed the plan, 41
percent approved and 11 percent were undecided. Hence, the campaign
trail blazed by Robinson, Duncan and even Sean Elliott, who
underwent a kidney transplant in August.
</P>
<P>
   During the lockout, Michael Jordan baited Washington Wizards
owner Abe Pollin into a verbal sparring session by suggesting that
Pollin should sell his team if he could not make a profit on it.
Pollin, the league's senior owner, had a right to be angry. He had
spent $200 million for a downtown arena and paid Juwan Howard $105
million the past four years. He did not ask the District of
Columbia for financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Spurs try to gouge their city for a new arena
reminds us that for all the feel-good emotion a championship team
can bring, what it really wants back is not your applause or
worship. It's your dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Vancouver a Chance
</P>
<P>
   After St. Louis billionaire Bill Laurie and his wife, Wal-Mart
heiress Nancy Laurie, purchased the Vancouver Grizzlies last month
from John McCaw, the franchise was all but headed to the Midwest.
The Lauries own the St. Louis Blues and the Kiel Center in which
the Blues play, so the idea of the Grizzlies moving by the
2001-2002 season did not seem farfetched, despite David Stern's
bluster over the league's owners wanting to give Vancouver a better
chance as an NBA city.
</P>
<P>
   But at a board of governors meeting in New York on Friday, the
league's financial advisory committee considered the proposed
transfer of ownership and decided it was not prepared to recommend
approval of the deal as it is currently structured.
</P>
<P>
   The committee expressed concern that the two years remaining
under the expansion agreement might not provide a sufficient
opportunity for Vancouver to demonstrate that it can support an NBA
team.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the committee, the Suns' owner, Jerry Colangelo,
had much to do with the decision. Under the expansion agreement
under which the Grizzlies entered the league in 1995, the team
cannot be moved until the 2001-2002 season _ at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in Vancouver as an NBA marketplace then and I still
do,'' Colangelo said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie needs a two-thirds majority of the board of governors to
approve his purchase. Both parties will resubmit their request
after further discussion, but it appears the league's owners are
not going to sign off on a franchise move in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hornets Having Their Problems
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silas knows he has enough talent in Charlotte to contend
for the Eastern Conference championship. He also found out last
week that he has enough potential turmoil to wind up in the
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Derrick Coleman was charged with driving while
intoxicated after an accident. Guard Eldridge Recasner, a passenger
in Coleman's vehicle, will miss at least six weeks of the season
because of a broken shoulder and collapsed lung.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who suffered only minor bruises, was charged after he
apparently tried to make a left turn in front of an oncoming
grocery delivery truck. He refused a Breathalyzer test after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Silas has seen much of Coleman's self-destructive behavior _
from his eating binges in Charlotte and Philadelphia to his
nonchalant work ethic with the Nets, where Silas was an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he's going to have to think hard about and deal
with,'' Silas said. ``If you have a problem _ I'm not necessarily
saying he does have one _ you've got to admit it and deal with it.
There's only so much we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Missing Piece
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson may have inherited a talented team, but he is
already campaigning for the acquisition of the Lakers' missing
piece: a bona fide power forward to take some of the pressure off
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry has been hurt and looks lost in the triangle
offense, A.C. Green is nearing 37 years old and Travis Knight
leaves much to be desired as a stopper. Among the possible
solutions: Bison Dele (the former Brian Williams), who played for
Jackson's 1997 champion Bulls team but shocked the Pistons by
retiring recently, and Dennis Rodman, who starred for Jackson's
Bulls but has not played since being waived by the Lakers last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a special relationship with Brian Williams,'' Jackson
said. ``I don't know Bison Dele. I've never met him. If Brian
Williams tells me he wants to talk to me about playing basketball,
and he comes and tells me he's Bison Dele, yes, we'll have a
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with the news media last Monday,
Jackson also mentioned Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we haven't addressed that Dennis question,''
Jackson said, ``but it's there and it ultimately has to be
addressed at some level. But we hope that it's not something that
we'll jump into as a sign of desperation for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
