<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-ELECTIONS _ GUATEMALA CITY, Guatemala _ Guatemala's
shakey hold on peace will be tested Nov. 7, when the country holds
its first presidential election since the 1995 peace accords ended
the 36-year civil war. Public interest in the election seems low,
despite the fact that one of the major candidates ? a guy whose
nickname is ``The Gruff Chicken'' ? recently admitted murdering two
men years ago while he lived in Mexico, a crime for which he was
never prosecuted. We profile the candidates and the country's
efforts to find stability after decades of war. (Williams, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-BOX _ The main candidates: Alfonso Portillo of the
Guatemalan Republican Front and Guatemala City Mayor Oscar Berger
of the National Advancement Party. (Williams, Cox News Service). 1
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN _ TEHRAN, Iran _ For Iranians, the takeover of the U.S.
Embassy 20 years ago this week (Nov. 4) is their Bunker Hill; their
Boston Tea Party. It galvanized their revolutionary fervor as they
took on the ``Den of Spies'' that had helped install and support
the brutal, dictatorial Shah. The takeover symbolized a revolution
that changed the atmosphere of the Middle East and helped create
now-familiar buzzwords like ``Islamic fundamentalism'' and
``Hezbollah.'' And, it shocked the West into realizing that
religion was still a force in world politics. (Just a year before
the revolution, Jimmy Carter called Iran ``an island of
stability.'') Today in Iran, the takeover highlights the country's
identity crisis. Any criticism of the takeover is still
controversial. But the radical fervor has long been cast aside as
most Iranians who seek a new pragmatism and freedom. (Kaplow, Cox
News Service)..
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REFORM _ TEHRAN, Iran _ Some of those involved in the
embassy takeover, and President Mohammad Khatami, have tried to
move U.S.-Iranian relations carefully forward. The gift shop that
sold souvenirs fromn the takeover has long ago closed and many of
the former hostage takers are risking their freedom now trying to
open up the closed Iranian system that the embassy takeover helped
create. A profile of a former hostage taker. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Oct. 27 in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-US _ WASHINGTON _ Nov. 4 marks the 20th anniversary of the
takeover of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran, an event that doomed the
Carter presidency and led to an enormous rupture in Middle East
politics. How did the 444-day ordeal change America? (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Wed., Oct. 27 in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WACO-MILITARY _WACO, Texas _ Images of the military's
involvement at Mount Carmel still wind through our collective
memory six years later. Bradley Fighting Vehicles and Abrams tanks
roamed the landscape outside Waco in 1993 from one edge of the TV
screen to the other. Behind the scenes, there were caches of
generators, gas masks and night vision equipment. But documents
released to Cox Newspapers under the Freedom of Information Act
show the military was for the most part a reluctant participant.
After a bitter internal struggle, it scaled back its assistance to
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms as the agency prepared
to raid the Branch Davidian compound and during the siege refused
to sign off on the FBI's tear gas assault. (England, Waco
Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   JIMMYDEAN _ CHAFFIN'S BLUFF, Va. _ Entertainer and sausage baron
Jimmy Dean, who makes his home in a James River mansion just south
of Richmond, became famous with his 1961 song ``Big Bad John.'' Now
he's stirred up a ruckus among some Virginians who claim he's
throwing his sausage money around trying to win a contest for a new
state song. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
