<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-RENEW-REAL-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTIAL LIFE IS RETURNING TO ATLANTA'S DOWNTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Gould said he felt like an urban pioneer when he
stepped through a kudzu-shrouded doorway nine years ago into his
new home.
</P>
<P>
   The 25,000-square-foot brick building dated to the 1880s when
Standard Oil of Kentucky built it for a barrel-making operation;
more recently it had been an automobile-parts supply house and a
junk dealer's warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Just beyond the back yard lay a railroad yard, while next door
were other industrial buildings, also empty, also hidden by kudzu
vines. And yet this industrial no man's land stood at the edge of a
growing downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, a photographer, envisioned loft apartments, spaces for
artists like himself to live and work in at a reasonable cost.
</P>
<P>
   Now 39, Gould is a pioneer no more.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of residential units, in new high rises and conversions
of industrial buildings, have been built in the last few years as
developers have discovered a heady market for living in downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The two-square-mile downtown had long been overlooked in favor
of fancier midtown addresses or the even-more elegant Buckhead
area, both to the north. Families tended to trek farther out to
suburban enclaves in neighboring counties, subdivisions that sprawl
for miles across the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary out here,'' said Gould, whose Allied Factory
Warehouse now includes eight apartments and work space for more
than a dozen artists. ``The area had almost returned to
wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   He was attracted to the site first by a love of industrial
buildings and then by a cobblestone street at the rear, a rarity
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about Atlanta that doesn't appeal to me is
everything is new,'' he said. ``We've been tearing down buildings
since the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Atlanta is a place where new is revered. High rises
were built only after smaller, older buildings were demolished in a
steady progression beginning in the 1960s and continuing until the
early 1990s. One of Atlanta's best-known companies, Coca-Cola Co.,
left downtown in 1919 _ the year that Ernest Woodruff bought it for
$25 million _ for a campuslike setting in midtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1976, Cable News Network opted to buy a
1.5-million-square-foot building at the edge of downtown for its
headquarters. The building is now nestled between two new
civic-related developments, Centennial Olympic Park, built for the
Olympics, and Phillips Arena, home to Atlanta's Thrashers hockey
team and its Hawks basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The arena was built by Ted Turner, founder of CNN; Philips
Electronics North America paid for the right to have it named for
the company and to have its huge sign on the building.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, $1 billion has been invested in downtown Atlanta.
Much of the money was spent on Olympics-related construction, such
as the park and Turner Field, used for the Olympics and now home to
the Atlanta Braves, and landscaping along downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   In that same period, 2,690 housing units were built downtown,
according to a report for the Centennial Olympic Park Area, a
private, nonprofit organization founded to guide development around
the 21-acre park.
</P>
<P>
   One of the agency's first projects is a three-acre site at the
northeast corner of the park that is to include about 100
condominium units, 200 rentals, retail spaces and, possibly, a
children's museum. The agency paid $6.5 million for property, which
is to be developed by a private developer sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the park, Legacy Property Group expects to
break ground next month on a 10-story residential condominium at
the rear of the Embassy Suites Hotel. Called Centennial Park West,
the units will range in price from $200,000 for 1,000 square feet
of space with one bedroom to $1 million for 4,000 square feet and
four bedrooms, according to John Pauli, an architect whose firm,
Stang &AMP; Newdow, is designing the interior. The firm of May &AMP; Pinska
of New York City designed the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Most developers here credit the Olympics with not only making
the city more attractive but also with spurring the first projects
that brought people back to the city. Some of the games' sponsors
subsidized projects to convert three downtown office buildings into
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   One, the 89-unit Metropolitan, once the home of the First
National Bank, is now being sold as condominiums, ranging in price
from $50,000 to $120,000. The other two _ the 65-unit Muses and
114-unit William-Oliver _ are still rental apartments, according to
a report by Dale Henson Associates, a real estate consulting firm
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a mild to severe case of condo-mania,'' said Dale
Henson, a real estate consultant here. ``There is a frantic effort
to get into the market before it gets too filled out or we have an
economic setback.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the office-building conversions, several
industrial buildings close to Gould's property in the Marietta
Street area have been converted into lofts and many of them have
been sold as condominiums. The site of a former gasket manufacturer
was turned into 30 units that sold for $145,000 to $337,000, while
a seed company's building was transformed into 18 condominium units
ranging in price from $137,000 to $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gould said he had decided to rent out space because his
development proceeded one unit at a time, without bank financing.
Now that the renovation is nearly complete, he is considering
selling the units as condominiums.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another area seeing a surge in residential development is the
Fairlie-Poplar neighborhood, once a high-crime area of bars and
rundown hotels. Several buildings have been converted to loft
condominiums, while the first new residential construction downtown
in many years is taking place at what will be 123 Luckie St., now
the site of a parking lot. Prices for the 49-unit condominium will
range from $190,000 for a one-bedroom to $550,000 for four
bedrooms, said Pauli, the project's architect.
</P>
<P>
   Henson noted, however, that while the market looked vibrant the
actual number of units recently completed or under way is less than
a thousand.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many does it take to create a community?'' he asked.
``There's not enough to create an environment that will make a
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a downtown like Atlanta's certainly poses challenges,
Gould said. The area could be considered in its infancy for
residents, meaning few restaurants open at night and only one
grocery _ a Kroger Supermarket across the street from the State
Capitol _ anywhere close.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is a perception that crime is worse here than in
the outlying areas. But Gould, as well as city leaders, say that is
perception, not reality. Reported crime has decreased since the
police increased street patrols and put neighborhood precincts in
storefronts across the city.
</P>
<P>
   The city has made attracting downtown residents a priority as
well. The need for a vibrant middle class was highlighted in a 1998
report issued by the Atlanta Renaissance Program, which called its
absence ``missing rungs in the ladder to progress.'' The report
showed that the city had become home to the poor and the wealthy
and set goals such as improving education and transforming
deteriorated areas to attract more middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   John A. Williams, chairman of Post Properties and president of
the Atlanta Chamber of Commerce, said the city was working hard to
solve those problems so that it could be home to others besides
empty-nesters, young marrieds and singles.
</P>
<P>
   One element that city leaders see as crucial to this end is
keeping Macy's open on Peachtree Street in the heart of the city.
Williams' company has offered to buy the six-story building, lease
the ground floor to Macy's and put offices on the second and third
floors and 150 residential units on the top three floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to a vibrant downtown is people,'' he said. ``The city
is now very popular, a response to rebellion against sprawl that
has infected Atlanta. The customer is making a choice to live in an
environment different than suburbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
