<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS-PANTHERS-     10-30 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-PANTHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home's not sweet in nightmare year
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _There is a point in at least every other Falcons season
when everybody becomes numb. If it hasn't happened already, a loss
today at home to Carolina (2-4) might be the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (1-6) won every home game last year, and brought an
11-game home winning streak into this season. But remember, this is
a team that has never in 33 previous years had back-to-back winning
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So what's happened?
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have lost all three home games, including 17-14 to
the Vikings when Atlanta had a minus-three turnover deficit and
Morten Andersen missed two field goals.
</P>
<P>
   There was the 13-3 third-quarter lead they blew in a 19-13
overtime loss to Baltimore. And the 41-13 thumping by the Rams
remains an open wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's gone right, absolutely nothing,'' said quarterback
Chris Chandler. ``It's been one screw-up after another. It's pretty
much been a total nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there is hope. In '97, the Falcons began the season
1-7 but went 6-2 the rest of way, catapulting themselves toward
last year's Super Bowl run. So maybe they can start another run one
game earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If today's the magic day, the Falcons must:
</P>
<P>
   1. Get the running game going. If it means trying running back
Winslow Oliver, or using wide receiver Tim Dwight more, do whatever
it takes.
</P>
<P>
   The line needs to hold blocks longer. Ken Oxendine and Byron
Hanspard need to stop missing holes, and drag a few tacklers for a
change. Monday night at Pittsburgh, Atlanta running backs carried
21 times for 36 yards. Fifteen of those carries went for 2 yards or
less. Five went for 2 yards. Four went for 1 yard. Three went for
no gain. Three lost yardage. Nobody can win that way.
</P>
<P>
   2. Do a better job of picking up blitzes, and make the Panthers
pay when they blitz by hitting a couple big plays. Carolina doesn't
mix up its rush packages as much as last year, when the 3-4 was its
base defense. But everybody blitzes more against the Falcons,
who've yet to demonstrate they can stop it.
</P>
<P>
   3. Keep Carolina tight end Wesley Walls from finding seams in
the secondary. He's had some huge games against the Falcons, and
with wide receiver Rae Carruth out, and Patrick Jeffers injured and
possibly out, quarterback Steve Beuerlein is likely to look even
more at Walls. 4. Win the turnover war. The Falcons have scored 10
points off six takeaways, and surrendered 63 points off 17
turnovers. That's a recipe for 1-6.
</P>
<P>
   5. Get the lead first, and keep it. The Falcons have held the
lead for 33 minutes, 10 seconds all season _ out of a possible 422
minutes, 29 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
