<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-PANTHERS-COX     10-30 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PANTHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Success comes to Muhammad
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing in the NFL can sometimes be a game of timing. Carolina
receiver Muhsin Muhammad was plagued by injuries his first two
seasons, but he enjoyed a breakout season in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad's durability was still a factor when the former
Michigan State star and the Panthers couldn't agree on a contract
extension before training camp. Six games into his fourth season,
Muhammad probably stands to earn a lot more money.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 217-pound native of Lansing, Mich., ranks first in
the NFC in receiving yards (593) and fourth in receptions (34).
Muhammad, 26, is on pace to shatter Carolina's single-season record
for catches (69) and receiving yards (1,024), set by Raghib Ismail
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a great player here since the beginning of last
year,'' Panthers quarterback Steve Beuerlein said. ``He had a real
solid year for us last season and I always felt that if he could
stay healthy, he would really establish himself as a premier
receiver. He took the first steps toward doing that last year, and
I think he's just backing it up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad, who was drafted in the second round in 1996, was a
late bloomer at Michigan State. He had only 28 catches his first
three seasons, but 41 catches for 696 yards as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Against LSU in the 1995 Independence Bowl, Muhammad had nine
receptions for 178 yards, including a 78-yard touchdown. That
performance drew comparisons to former Spartans star Andre Rison
and improved Muhammad's value in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great receiver,'' said Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan,
who will cover Muhammad today. ``I've been watching him grow the
past three years. Last year, I thought he did a pretty good job. He
just needed to get the ball thrown to him. This year, he's come
into his own. I respect the guy. He can make a lot of plays out
there. Steve Beuerlein has been putting a lot of faith and trust in
throwing the ball to him.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in Muhammad's first two seasons. As a
rookie in 1996, he missed both games against the Falcons because of
shoulder and hamstring injuries. He finished with 25 catches and
one touchdown in nine games, including five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad missed four games in his second season because of a
broken left wrist. He finished with only 27 receptions and no
scores. Last season, he finally stayed healthy and started all 16
games. He posted career highs with 68 catches, 941 receiving yards
and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been able to go out and produce on a weekly basis,''
Beuerlein said. ``I think he'd be the first person to tell you, and
I'd agree with him, that he's just going to get better as he gets
more reps and more confidence. As we as players and coaches learn
to use him better, he'll do nothing but get better.''
</P>
<P>
   With his gaudy statistics, Muhammad's attractiveness as a free
agent is soaring. Contract talks between the Panthers and his
agent, Ajili Hodari, have resumed. Muhammad will become an
unrestricted free agent in February if a deal isn't reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really focusing and concentrating on playing the games,''
Muhammad said. ``The contract will take care of itself if I come
out and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Height, weight: 6-2, 217.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 26.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: East Lansing, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   College: Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Career highlights: Muhammad posted career highs with 68 catches,
941 receiving yards and six touchdowns last season. ... He missed
10 games in his first two seasons because of injuries. ... Muhammad
was drafted in the second round by the Panthers in 1996 out of
Michigan State. ... Muhammad's first name is Arabic for
``charitable'' or ``one who does good deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
