<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-HKN-RHODES-COX     10-30 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RHODES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rhodes does not panic
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He has been, for the last two games, exactly what the
general manager envisioned. A goalie who can steal a game. A goalie
who can put a fledgling franchise in position to win a game. A
goalie who doesn't panic when it seems the players around him might
be doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I can do that,'' Damian Rhodes said. ``I think I
can play even better than I have at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to a preseason marketing campaign, central to the
Thrashers' hopes in their first season, Rhodes will make his eighth
start in 10 games tonight when they play host to the Ottawa
Senators at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   That Rhodes spent his last three and a half seasons in the
Canadian provincial capital and left there after being on a
goaltending yo-yo with Ron Tugnutt under coach Jacques Martin
provides some added incentive tonight for the 30-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nerves will be up a little bit,'' Rhodes said. ``No matter
what terms you leave a team on you always want to play well against
them and show that you really are a player. But I think the reason
I had to leave was my contract was up and they couldn't afford to
pay two goalies.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes was the first player under contract to the Thrashers. He
was acquired from the Senators in a trade just before the expansion
draft but would have landed here either way. General manager Don
Waddell was set to take him off Ottawa's roster because the
Senators were likely to protect Tugnutt (who was under contract) in
the draft. Martin also had a closer relationship with Tugnutt than
he did with Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes says he isn't bitter about his stay in Ottawa. ``We got
better every year, I got better every year,'' he said. ``You have
to take the positives out of it.'' But after six seasons in Canada
(Toronto, then Ottawa), the Minnesota native was anxious to get
back on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe Ottawa, Rhodes said, ``Cold.'' There, he
rented an apartment, although the inability of a mortgage interest
write-off in Canada for a U.S. citizen partly was the reason. Here,
Rhodes owns a home with his wife, Lara, in Sugarloaf Country Club
on the third tee.
</P>
<P>
   He says he feels ``more comfortable here'' than in the hockey
fishbowl of Ottawa. On the ice, it shows. Last Tuesday, he stopped
30 of 31 shots by Calgary, including 14 in the third period, to
preserve a 2-1 win. The next night in Toronto, he blanked the
high-powered Maple Leafs on 16 shots in the first but, abandoned by
his teammates, eventually fell victim to a 37-shot assault and lost
4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can say he got off to a slow start, although
maybe the Buffalo game (when the Sabres rallied for two goals in a
5-5 tie) he was a little bit off,'' Waddell said. ``But certainly
the last two games he's been great. He has given us a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes has faced an average of 31 shots per game. In Ottawa, he
faced only 26 per game last year, and generally less quality
chances. No problem, says Rhodes, who added, ``I don't think I've
hit my stride yet but it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, he might even be recognized. He has yet to be stopped
on the street, a stark contrast to Canada, where ``if you're a
hockey player, you get noticed. Here, I even come off the ice in my
goalie equipment and kids don't know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
