   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 10/30/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ANN ARBOR, Mich. -- Oct. 30, 1999 --
CRUISES-MEDICAL-CARE, 10-30 -- Elizabeth Carlisle of Ann Arbor,
suffered a ruptured appendix and an infection while on a cruise
with her parents, Darcy and Kristopher Carlisle. When it comes to
medical care, the cruise ships to which millions of Americans flock
every year are free of any U.S. regulation. There is no
international oversight of medical care because maritime law does
not require cruise ships to provide any for passengers. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- DISABLED-DANCER-2, 10-30 --
Mark Brew, 22, two years after he lost the use of his legs in a car
accident is preparing for his rebirth as a dancer in the ballet
``Gilchrist's Dream,'' at the Theater of the Riverside Church. In
1997, Brew's future seemed starry: he had just signed a contract
with the State Theater Ballet Company of South Africa. But there, a
drunken driver plowed into a car carrying him, his girlfriend, her
brother and another young man. Only Brew survived. His ability to
walk did not. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- DISABLED-DANCER-1, 10-30 --
Two years after he lost the use of his legs in a car accident, Mark
Brew, 22, is back on stage in the ballet ``Gilchrist's Dream,'' at
the Theater of the Riverside Church. To be a dancer in a
paraplegic's body is to have your soul crave movement, and your
body resist it. ``I do professional training, ballet class every
day,'' he says. ``I just feel like my career is going in a
different direction, less toward the classics, more experimental.
I'm doing a lot of movement; I'm using my legs, even if I can't
feel it.'' (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- BBA-YANKEE-BATBOY, 10-30 --
Luis Castillo, 17, a New York Yankees batboy. Castillo who had
always been a Yankees fan was overcome by the depth of his
experience when the Yankees won the 1999 World Series on Wednesday.
The players, coaches and manager Joe Torre have always treated the
batboy respectfully and graciously and made him feel like one of
the family. Castillo and Yankees ace David Cone, worked together so
often that one day, while Cone and Castillo played catch, relievers
Mike Stanton and Tony Fossas began chanting, ``Little Coney.''
(Aaron Lee Fineman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- SENATE-ENVIRONMENT, 10-30
-- Sen. Robert C. Smith, R-N.H., with his press secretary, Karen
Hickey, is one of two pro-business candidates for the chairmanship
of the Environment and Public Works Committee. Whether Republicans
choose Smith or James Inhofe of Oklahoma, they will break the
environmental mold filled by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., who died
Oct. 24. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- GORE-FRIENDS, 10-30 --
Peter Knight, one of Vice President Al Gore's closest friends and a
lobbyist for major companies, at a Congressional hearing two years
ago. Gore's closest confidants, the lobbyists Tom Downey, Peter
Knight and Roy Neel, have continued to play central roles in his
2000 presidential campaign, even while they have continued to
aggressively lobby members of the administration and, in some
cases, Gore himself, on behalf of their corporate clients. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) REHOBOTH, Mass. -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- WICCA-MOVEMENT-3,
10-30 -- Len Laframboise, during a Wiccan ceremony in Rehoboth.
Encouraged by federal court rulings recognizing witchcraft as a
legal religion, an increasing number of books related to the
subject and the continuing cultural concern for the environment,
Wicca, as contemporary witchcraft is often called, has been growing
in the United States and abroad. It is a major element in an
expanding ``neo-pagan'' movement whose members regard nature itself
as charged with divinity. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) REHOBOTH, Mass. -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- WICCA-MOVEMENT-2,
10-30 -- Joined by a neighbor's black cat, Isis, local covens
gather at a sundown ceremony in a backyard in Rehoboth. In the
rite, the assembled witches are asked to form a ``circle of
energy'' and vow to ``change the future through tolerance,
education and through love.'' Wicca, as contemporary witchcraft is
often called, has been growing in the United States and abroad. It
is a major element in an expanding ``neo-pagan'' movement whose
members regard nature itself as charged with divinity. (Evan
Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) REHOBOTH, Mass. -- Oct. 30, 1999 -- WICCA-MOVEMENT-1,
10-30 -- Cheryl Sulyma-Masson, a high priestess of one coven in
Rehoboth, wields a sword and leads fellow withces in a seasonal
ceremony. Wicca, as contemporary witchcraft is often called, has
been growing in the United States and abroad. It is a major element
in an expanding ``neo-pagan'' movement whose members regard nature
itself as charged with divinity. (Evan Richman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
