<HEADER>
A3568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SUBWAY-MURDER-TRIA     10-30 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-MURDER-TRIAL-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S ABSENCE AT TRIAL UNDERSCORES MENTAL ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During each day of the trial of Andrew Goldstein, the
schizophrenic man accused of pushing Kendra Webdale in front of a
subway train, Ms. Webdale's mother and sister have sat resolutely
in the courtroom's second row, just behind prosecutors. But the
rows behind Goldstein have remained empty.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's mother, Barbara, a former secretary who lives in
Little Neck, Queens; his father, Edmund, a Maryland doctor, and his
brothers, Douglas, a Manhattan optician, and Richard, have never
appeared in court.
</P>
<P>
   They have refused all interview requests from the media and have
declined to testify at the trial in Goldstein's defense. They have
even refused to speak with an expert psychiatrist working with
defense lawyers to save their son or brother from 25 years to life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   A jury continued deliberating Saturday afternoon in his murder
trial at State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Those who might look for signals in the absence of the family of
Goldstein, a 30-year-old man with a decade-long history of
schizophrenia, could reach contradictory conclusions: either that
Goldstein's family is callous and uncaring, or that he is himself,
and has driven his family away.
</P>
<P>
   But according to other schizophrenics and their families,
neither extreme is likely to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The gulf between Goldstein and his relatives is familiar to most
families with schizophrenic members, medical experts say. Studies
have shown that 95 percent of schizophrenics fail to have regular
contact with their families. The Goldstein family's absence from
court, other schizophrenics and their families say, may not reflect
their judgment of him as much as their own exhaustion and
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen MacNamara, a 54-year-old woman from Albany whose
estranged son Jeff is mentally ill, said she understood how a
mother could both desperately love her son and desperately not want
to see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he lived here, he threatened me with a knife,'' Ms.
MacNamara said, her voice choked with emotion. ``He threatened to
kill me. I'm afraid of him now. I know he couldn't live in my house
and we can't be together, but I love him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks of detailed testimony that covered intimate
parts of Goldstein's life, his relationship with his parents, who
divorced when he was 8, and his siblings remains a mystery.
Prosecutors paint a picture of abuse so intense that it eventually
sparked a murderous attack from Goldstein. Defense lawyers portray
a family so frustrated by dealing with a dysfunctional state mental
health system that they were simply forced to give up.
</P>
<P>
   One revelation at the trial seized on by prosecutors is that
Goldstein carried out the fatal attack on his mother's birthday.
Assistant District Attorney William Greenbaum has argued that
rejection from his family, particularly his mother, fueled the rage
that led Goldstein to kill Ms. Webdale.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein told acquaintances before the attack that his mother
gave him some money in mid-December and told him not to bother her
during the holidays. His father, he said, came to New York to
celebrate New Year's with Goldstein's brothers, but had not invited
him.
</P>
<P>
   In a far more serious allegation, Goldstein told psychiatrists
that his father beat him in 1998 because he believed Goldstein had
given his medication to his father's dogs. The dogs apparently were
sleepy. Goldstein also said that before his parents divorced, his
father regularly beat him and his mother.
</P>
<P>
   With Goldstein's family declining to be interviewed, it is
impossible to determine to what extent the stories are true, if at
all. Goldstein may have simply made everything up.
</P>
<P>
   The family's decision not to testify in his defense could also
reflect a decision on their part to protect him. Under
cross-examination by prosecutors Goldstein's mother, father, or
brothers could have been forced to disclose damaging information
about him that could weaken his case.
</P>
<P>
   His defense lawyers, Harvey Fishbein and Jack Hoffinger, have
highlighted the parts of the medical record that portray
Goldstein's relationship with his family as destroyed by a cruel
and incurable mental disease. Fishbein has repeatedly recited to
the jury a note written by a Bellevue Hospital social worker in
1997, eight years after Goldstein began cycling in and out of
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The social worker wrote that Goldstein's mother said in a
telephone conversation that she ``has since given up because she
says she is unable to deal with him anymore after so many years.
She feels like she has a lost a son. He is a completely different
person.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goldstein's relationship with his mother first began to crumble
in 1989 after his schizophrenia forced him to drop out of the State
University of New York at Stony Brook, medical records show. He
moved in with her, but in an ugly confrontation, he shoved her and
threatened to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   A note in his medical records detail his delusions at the time.
``He is threatening to kill her,'' it says, ``because she gave him
poisoned food and there is poison in the air and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's mother took him in again after he was released from
the hospital. But weeks later, she again called an ambulance after
he stood in his room in a catatonic state for several hours, not
moving or responding to questions. After he was released from the
hospital yet again, his mother, who may have been frightened of him
at this point, refused to take him in.
</P>
<P>
   There is also evidence in the record of an early effort by
Goldstein's father to aid him. In 1992, he moved to Delaware to
live with his father. There, Goldstein tried to re-enroll in
college.
</P>
<P>
   He took classes at a local community college, he told
psychiatrists, but his father was disappointed with his grades.
After several months, he said, he was ordered out of his father's
home and retreated to New York, he said. There, his mother refused
to take him.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein was able to find rooms to live in at that point. His
parents appear to have intermittently given him money over the next
several years and there was at least one other brief visit to his
father. But he told psychiatrists and friends that he continued to
feel rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Nuza, one of Goldstein's roommates, quoted Goldstein as
telling him in 1998 ``that his family pretty much disowned him,
that his parents didn't want anything to do with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But medical records show that his mother made an effort to help
him only two weeks before the killing. A note states that his
mother went to North General Hospital in Manhattan, where Goldstein
was from Nov. 15 to Dec. 10 last year, and asked that he be
admitted to Creedmoor for long-term care. Her efforts failed and he
was released onto the street. He killed Ms. Webdale two weeks
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0253 </DOCNO>
