<HEADLINE>
INDY'S BIG THREE REMINISCENT OF COWBOYS' TRIPLETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Colts quarterback Peyton Manning is in
commercials with Michael Jordan and has a cameo role with wide
receiver Marvin Harrison in an episode of ``The Jersey'', a
children's cable television series. Along with running back
Edgerrin James, Manning and Harrison are the toast of local sports
talk radio. ESPN is calling them ``Team 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   So at least they are getting the headlines, like a certain set
of triplets who've been the class of the 1990s. But before
comparing Manning, Harrison and James to the Cowboys' triumvirate
of Troy Aikman, Michael Irvin and Emmitt Smith, Colts coach Jim
Mora says to take a good look at his fingers and then think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any Super Bowl rings yet. Those guys have
three,'' Mora said last week. ``Those guys with the Cowboys have
done this a long time. Our three guys are basically pups. To
compare us to them, uh, we need to have some success. That is
measured by what you do over a long period of time. You just can't
compare us to them until we've done something. We haven't won
anything yet, not even a division title.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but as the Colts (4-2) prepare to face the Cowboys (4-2) at
the RCA Dome today, notice how the new triplets look like the old
ones when the 1990s began: young, talented, and confident.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Beastie Boys rocking the Grammys, the Colts' three-man
band took home a trophy case full of NFL awards in September. In a
Week 3 victory against San Diego, Manning had a club-record 404
passing yards, two touchdown passes and one rushing TD, and was
selected the AFC offensive player of the week. James was NFL
offensive rookie of the month on the strength of 75 carries for 276
yards and two touchdowns. Harrison was AFC offensive player of the
month after he had 28 receptions for 422 yards with six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is third in the league in passing yards (1,679) and
second in touchdowns (13). Harrison is second in yards (709) and
second in receptions (45). James is third in rushing yards (520).
Hey, maybe they'll never win a Super Bowl. But at least the
foundation appears to be set to keep the Colts competitive for the
next decade and beyond, Miami Dolphins coach and AFC East rival
Jimmy Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've surrounded \RManning\S with a better supporting cast
than what I did in Dallas,'' said Johnson, who coached the original
triplets from 1989-93. ``Troy really struggled for the first couple
of years and really started to come on about his third year. But I
think Peyton has come on stronger than what Troy did.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning has started all of his 22 NFL games and has better stats
than Aikman had in his first 22 starts, including 1,653 more yards
passing and 22 more touchdown passes. Manning has thrown touchdowns
in 19 consecutive games, and on six occasions he has led the Colts'
offense to 20 points in a half.
</P>
<P>
   Colts offensive coordinator Tom Moore said Manning, son of
former New Orleans Saints great Archie Manning, ``is like a coach
on the field,'' because he is so astute with Moore's playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, however, credits his improvement this season to lessons
learned from his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year I'm doing a better job of throwing it to
different spots on the field,'' Manning said. ``You always try to
get the ball to your playmakers. But last year, I was just throwing
the ball to the outside receiver on the right or on the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I'm using my layoffs better. I'm taking \Rtight
end\S Ken Dilger, who a lot of times may be the third read, or
Edgerrin James. When defenses see that, they can't just cover the
outside guys. They know they have to cover everybody.'' \Nsubheds:
The receiver Usually, Manning ends up throwing to Harrison. The
fourth-year pro from Syracuse is the go-to-guy for Moore, the
Pittsburgh Steelers' receivers coach when they had Lynn Swann and
John Stallworth. Moore was also offensive coordinator of a 1995
Detroit Lions team that was the first in NFL history to have two
wide receivers catch more than 100 passes each.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, who missed the last four games of 1998 with a shoulder
injury, has started 18 games with Manning and caught 15 touchdown
passes. At 6-foot, 181 pounds, he is not as big as Irvin but he is
just as productive. He has four games of 100 or more yards
receiving this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' second-year receiver Jerome Pathon said, ``Peyton
and Marvin are one of the best tandems in the league. Everyone else
\Rother Colts receivers\S is just trying to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Manning describe his rapport with Harrison, and you'd
think it's Aikman talking about Irvin in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvin and I have a bond, a feel that's hard to describe,''
Manning said. ``We go to dinner. We hang around. We spend extra
time on the practice field. Even when Marvin's the second or third
read, I know I can count on him to be open. If it is an 18-yard
route, I know he's going to go precisely 18 yards. He knows the
ball is going to be in the air before he turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison may get all the passes. But unlike Irvin, Harrison is
quiet and unassuming in the locker room. Outside the locker room,
he doesn't get the publicity that Manning and James get.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all right,'' Harrison said. ``It's something I've been
living with all my life. Even coming out of Syracuse, \RPatriots
wide receiver\S Terry Glenn was at Ohio State. I was always
overshadowed. Now you've got Terry and Keyshawn Johnson in my
division. But I believe my time will come.'' \Nsubheds:The running
back
</P>
<P>
   James, whom general manager Bill Polian selected out of Miami
instead of former Texas back Ricky Williams, believes his time has
come. Like the Cowboys in Smith's early years, the Colts have been
a one-horse show. James is the only running back Manning has handed
off to this year. And with 149 carries, he is on pace to break Eric
Dickerson's team record of rushes in a season (388 in 1988).
</P>
<P>
   He has more rushing yards (520) than Smith had (319) in his
first six starts. Yet despite the early success, James, who has
lost two costly fumbles, said he knows he has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be like Terrell Davis or Michael Jordan,'' James
said. ``Right now, I'm just another guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And James, Harrison and Manning may be just like any other
threesome in the game. But somehow, you get the feeling that they
may be more, that the next great trio is in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look around the league over the past years,
there's always been a combination of quarterback, receiver and
running back,'' Harrison said. ``I think we have that here.''
