<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3593 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-PHIL-JACKSON-TEX     10-30 2405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PHIL-JACKSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD ZEN: PHIL JACKSON'S COACHING YEN TAKES HIM TO LA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Richie Whitt 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``To: clashingegos &LR; WHATAWASTE.com(Los Angeles
Lakers)''
</P>
<P>
   Turn down your Walkmans, turn over your Pokemons and tune in
your new coach, Phil Jackson. He owns eight rings, a spiritual
grasp of the mysterious Triangle, inner peace from Zen Buddhism and
a vision of depth in bubble wrap. The only things deep about you
are your pockets and your trouble. While you were holding your own
Fight Club the last two seasons, the less-talented Utah Jazz and
San Antonio Spurs made you their personal BackSweep Boys. So
please, listen up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't get their attention,'' said former Lakers star
Magic Johnson, ``nobody will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To: den o'zen &LR; WAYOUTTHERE.net(Phil Jackson)''
</P>
<P>
   You certain that Eight Isn't Enough? And, isn't it kinda creepy
that you're working for two Jerry's again? Whatever, don't go to LA
expecting a smooth Boyz II Men brainwash. These kids have scars
from Shaq being jealous of Kobe's fans, Kobe being envious of
Shaq's money, owner Jerry going over president Jerry's head to sign
Dennis, Del getting fired, Dennis getting fired, Kurt getting
fired, and a dysfunctional unit with more cliques than a high
school cafeteria. Be patient. It will take time for your wacky
wisdom to penetrate the cell phones and hard heads of stars who
would rather be leading scorer than leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll have to go to their Web pages and e-mail them,''
joked Jackson, who took over the Lakers on June 16 after a one-year
coaching hiatus preceded by him walking away from the most
successful sports dynasty of the 1990s. ``I'd say the key word here
isn't `sacrifice,' but `submit.' These players are going to have to
change not only the way they play the game but also the way they
approach it. They've tried to win with `me'; now, we're going to
try as `we'.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel Jackson, meet the Hollywood Squares.
</P>
<P>
   While arguably the NBA's most-talented team _ with All-Stars
Kobe Bryant out front, Glen Rice on the wing and Shaquille O'Neal
in the middle _ unraveled in a four-game sweep to the
eventual-champion San Antonio Spurs last spring, Phillip D. Jackson
was riding his Harley, fly-fishing in Alaska and stumping for close
friend, former teammate and presidential candidate Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year removed from his second three-peat with the Chicago
Bulls, already one of the league's 10 greatest coaches, with the
NBA's best winning percentage in the regular season (73.8, 545-193)
and playoffs (73.0, 111-41), and owner of eight championship rings,
the 54-year-old has nowhere to go but down.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, have his Jackson Five starting lineup of
motivation, beginning with a five-year, $30 million contract from
owner Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the opportunity to finally coach a dominant center
in O'Neal, and the challenge to mature the adolescent,
underachieving Lakers, whom Jackson said made him ``cringe'' with
their stagnant offense and late-game mental collapses in the '99
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major limitation is their attention span,'' Jackson said.
``It comes from too much rap music and agents whispering in their
ears. We've got to develop interlocking components of compassion
and selflessness to find peace. And that's difficult with these
kids, because their focal points last about as long a TV
commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also is back to erase that little stigma at the bottom
of his bio. It's written in invisible ink, but screams out like a
blood-curdling Halloween victim: ``Never won a championship without
Michael Jordan!''
</P>
<P>
   He, like former Jordan sidekick Scottie Pippen, shrugs off the
asterisk though those close to him say it eats at Jackson like that
upstairs leaky faucet at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil wants to prove he can win without Michael, sure,'' said
Charley Rosen, Jackson's close friend of 26 years. ``You betcha
it's a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there is the inevitable urge. No matter how many
times Jackson meditates on his black pillow, he is and always will
be a hoops junkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the Zen thing about being in the hills and
breathing fresh air,'' said veteran guard Ron Harper, signed as a
liaison between old Bulls and new Lakers. ``But Phil can do that
being retired. The thing about him is he loves coaching basketball,
being in the gym. He's a coach first. All the psychological stuff
comes later.'' \Nsubheds:Now and Zen As a player, Jackson was a
crafty 6-foot-8 forward nicknamed ``Bones'' who butted heads with
Boston Celtics-turned-Mavericks coach Don Nelson for the New York
Knicks' championship teams in '70 and '73.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, he exudes the aura of a man who knows something you
don't, and is so intellectually and spiritually superior you don't
even dare ask him about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes Phil,'' whispered the teen-ager in a No. 8 Bryant
jersey to his buddy in a No. 32 O'Neal jersey before a recent
exhibition game at the San Diego Sports Arena. ``Dude, he's ... the
... man.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a rowdy class coming to order at the arrival of their
teacher, fans who were only seconds earlier screaming wildly for
player autographs suddenly grew silent. It was an eerie,
fascinatingly reverent treatment usually reserved for serial
killers or priests.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to teach us to respect him,'' O'Neal said.
``That came automatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lakers president Jerry West, ``He'll speed up our mentality
and our maturity. He's one of the most intellectually stimulating
people I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Deer Lodge, Mont., to Pentecostal ministers, Jackson
lived in the basement of a church and didn't go to his first movie
until he was 17. While an All-American at North Dakota, he turned
on to Zen Buddhism through his brother Joe, who was studying
psychology at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While learning basketball from coaches Red Holzman with the
Knicks, Jackson lived in the loft of an auto repair shop in order
to learn from the Zen owner, Hakin, seeking enlightenment through
meditation and intuition rather than in scripture. While playing
for the Knicks he took yoga classes, studied the teachings of the
Lakota Sioux and often retreated to the Rangers hockey locker room
to meditate for 45 minutes before Knicks games.
</P>
<P>
   As coach of the Bulls from '90-98, Jackson decorated his office
with spiritual trinkets including a bear claw necklace and the
middle feather from an owl. He preached oneness over one-on-one,
often mixed in clips from The Wizard of Oz or Full Metal Jacket
into game film, wore Grateful Dead T-shirts to workouts and began
and ended each practice with a sacred circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to life than basketball,'' Jackson wrote in his
book, Sacred Hoops. ``And there's more to basketball than
basketball. It's not focusing on winning or losing, just on what's
happening at this very instant.''
</P>
<P>
   Said veteran John Salley, who played for Jackson in Chicago in
1995-96 and signed with the Lakers this past off-season, ``One
night we'd lose a game, the next day we're sitting on a pillow
holding hands. And you know what, there wasn't one smirk in the
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing purple-framed glasses and sipping iced tea before an
exhibition game at The Great Western Forum, Jackson claimed his
one-year absence from nightly game tension and daily pressure
dealing with Jerrys Reinsdorf and Krause has re-booted his energy
and enthusiasm. He's building a 6,000-square-foot home on the beach
in Santa Monica, Calif., and promised his wife, June, not to fall
into the reclusive traps that led to stress-related gout and
problems with his thyroid, kidney and liver in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life became pretty much just basketball,'' Jackson said of
his decade with the Bulls. ``And even though I had my reading and
other interests, to have that down time to protect myself I
excluded people even in my own family life. I've made some personal
goals here to be with people, to get out more. Get on my bike, my
Porsche, my motorcycle, go to concerts. Don't wall off people and
be defensive, because they can be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   With a Triangle offense to install and new personalities to
learn during training camp, Jackson said he hasn't yet opened up
personally or begun to deliver the Zen tactics that became his
Bulls legacy. In Chicago he often gave players books to read on
long trips, once offering an angry Pippen author Langston Hughes'
Ways of the White Folks and Beavis and Butthead to Stacey King.
\Nsubheds:Livin' L.A. Vida Loco It's going to take more than
Jackson quoting Ghalib (''For the raindrop, joy is entering the
river'') or Rudyard Kipling (''The strength of the pack is the
wolf, and the strength of the wolf is the pack'') to mesh L.A.'s
talented five fingers into a hand.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's 31-19 record, Del Harris, Dennis Rodman and
Kurt Rambis each failed to survive with the team and O'Neal was so
peeved at Bryant after the Game 4 loss to the Spurs in the Western
Semifinals that he wouldn't join the post-game huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years we've had incidents and scenarios and
personalities that have clashed,'' guard Rick Fox said.
``Everything seemed to be a fight against ourselves. It was
sickening. For now, that's all stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The healing has begun. So, more importantly, has the learning.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal shocked Lakers management and surprised Bryant by
attending his 21st birthday party Aug. 23. O'Neal now refers to
Bryant as his ``little brother'' and Jackson said he's seen no
signs of outward jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Phil will have to be a mediator,'' said Bryant,
sidelined until the end of November with a broken right hand. ``I
don't see any problems between the two of us, really. Some of it
was inevitable. We both put ourselves before the team and learned a
hard lesson from it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has embraced Jackson's spookiness and system. He's
co-existed with Bryant, tried to think ``pass-first'' in the
Triangle and, incredibly, managed to somehow become an even worse
free-throw shooter (35.3 percent in the preseason compared to 54
percent last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a good free-throw shooter, but everything else I do is
perfect,'' O'Neal said. ``Whatever Phil wants me to do, I'll do it.
I don't want to ruin his perfect resume. I have an array of passes
that you haven't seen before that will make the difference in my
game this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said West: ``Shaq will be the MVP this season. He's the happiest
I have seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   With $50 million committed to his top six players, Jackson
predicts 60 victories in the regular season while also
acknowledging pressure to get the Lakers back to the Finals for the
first time since '91. Sensing the power struggle between the
27-year-old O'Neal and 21-year-old Bryant, he ordered new pre-game
warm-ups with bland white pants and jackets void of players' names.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big gulp,'' Jackson said of the lack of direction.
``There's some leadership that has to be developed here. It's a
maturation point. It's a responsibility that each of them has.''
</P>
<P>
   But the burden to teach the Lakers how to play defense, and how
not to bog down on offense in crunch time, is all on Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   So how did he begin Basketball Maturation 101? His first two
training camp practices in Santa Barbara included no ball or any
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rule No. 1 is that there is one ball and five players,''
Harper said. ``It's called sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   With as many as 24 options off one pass, there are no Cliffs
Notes to Jackson's Triangle offense that Michael Jordan derisively
called ``the equal opportunity system'' when introduced to it in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is ideal for this offense, but he's got to get in his
head that he's a feeder first, then a scorer,'' said Triangle
innovator and former Bulls-turned-Lakers assistant Tex Winter. ``We
don't have Michael, but we've got more overall talent here than we
had in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``When it's running smoothly, it's like a five-man
tai chi where nobody is thinking. Where playground ball is like
John Coltrane and jazz music, the Triangle is more like Mozart and
Bach.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, however, Jackson said the key change in L.A. will
be on defense. After a week of practice, he assessed that the
Lakers ``have no clue'' about what kind of intensity it takes to
play ``honest defense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was that guys didn't want to commit to being
on the same page, but more that we never really had a page to
follow,'' guard Derek Fisher said. ``Now we've got a handbook we
know works.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson realizes his team will be far from polished by the time
the Lakers debut in the new $400 million glass-and-steel downtown
Staples Center Wednesday against the Vancouver Grizzlies. Bryant is
out, Buss was unwilling to pay the price to acquire Pippen, it took
the Bulls a year-and-a-half to master the nuances of the Triangle,
and 36-year-old former Maverick A.C. Green or undersized Robert
Horry will be the starting power forward. (Jackson only winks and
smiles when asked about a possible return of Rodman).
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe by December we can judge whether they are going to be
champions or not,'' said Jackson, who has brought in veterans
Harper, Salley and Green and former Bulls assistants Winter, Frank
Hamblen and Jim Cleamons to smooth the transition. ``But these guys
have been in remedial reading for a month. Now we're in junior high
school and then they'll get their secondary education in pro
basketball. We have to teach them new skills. They have to learn a
new system and we have to correct bad habits.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Jackson's memory of the past, grasp of the present,
vision of the future and awareness of all planes in between, he
sees winning as a matter of ``when'' rather than ``if.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in being the savior has been presented to me,'' Jackson
said. ``It's a weird feeling to have, but a good one. I came here
to win a championship and I cannot expect anything less.''
</P>
<P>
   To: tallgreedybrats &LR; PAMPERED.com(Rest of the NBA)
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers may have failed chemistry. But if they can master
Phil-osophy and strategic geometry, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of chaos, we'll build a team and a family,'' former
Mavericks coach Cleamons said. ``If our marquee players are willing
to sacrifice their egos, this can be a dominant team. The talent
has always been here. Now they've got direction.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
