r s BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX     10-30 2268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLIAN IS THE OLD GUY DIRECTING THE YOUTH MOVEMENT IN INDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There is something special here, and it has
nothing to do with the $8 million renovations done to the Colts'
practice facilities. Walk into the plush locker room and see the
youth and one might think this is what the Cowboys locker room must
have looked like in 1991: Talented, but still unsure of how good
they'll be, and not taking life so seriously.
</P>
<P>
   There is Colts quarterback Peyton Manning, whose locker is among
the linemen's lockers, joking around with tackle Adam Meadows.
There is defensive tackle Bernard Whittington and tight end Marcus
Pollard taking note of the amount of media around their cubicles.
There is running back Edgerrin James, telling you that his mom and
Deion Sanders' mom talk on the phone frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, youth is good. But to know why the 4-2 Colts have the
potential to be one of the great teams for years to come, one must
find the old guy with the big office. It's a short walk outside the
locker room, around the corner past the huge posters of Lenny Moore
and Johnny Unitas and Raymond Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Colts president Bill Polian, 56, has a winning resume as thick
as his Bronx accent. He is unafraid to make the big deal that could
make a mediocre team average, or an average team great.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is aggressive,'' Colts coach Jim Mora said. ``One of his
best qualities is that when he makes a decision, he is like, `Let's
go forward.' He's not afraid to make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This team became a winner the day \Rteam owner\S Mr. \RJim\S
Irsay decided to hire Bill Polian,'' said Colts linebacker
Cornelius Bennett, who has also played for the Bills and Falcons
after being originally drafted by the Colts in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In Polian's first major job, as general manager of the Buffalo
Bills from 1984-92, he drafted or signed 13 players who have
combined to make 31 Pro Bowl appearances. One of those players, of
course, was Bennett, whom Polian acquired from the Colts as part of
the three-way Eric Dickerson deal in 1987 involving the Rams and
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Polian became general manager of the expansion Carolina
Panthers. And with a combination of free agents and draft choices,
the Panthers knocked off the Cowboys in the 1996 divisional
playoffs to make the NFC Championship Game. Eight players drafted
or signed by Polian have combined to make 13 Pro Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Polian came to Indianapolis in December 1997, as the Colts were
finishing a 3-13 season. In 21 months, he has hired a new coaching
staff and brought over much of his scouting department from
Carolina to help with personnel decisions. On the field, only 12
players remain from his first day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   He has made three deals that could have blown up in his face:
Drafting Peyton Manning over Ryan Leaf. Chasing off Pro Bowl
running back Marshall Faulk. And taking running back Edgerrin James
over Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Polian looks smart. Leaf, who had problems on and off
the field in 1998, hasn't played a down in 1999 and could wind up
in NFL Europe. Faulk is having a nice season in St. Louis, but his
replacement, James, has more rushing yards (520 to 403) and
touchdowns (4 to 0) than Williams, who has been slowed of his
rookie season injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worry about what people think about the decisions we
make,'' said Polian as he leaned back in the big leather chair in
his office. ``Sometimes, it is out of your hands. One of the best
picks I thought we ever made in Carolina was \Rrunning back\S Tim
Biakabutuka. Now, up until this season, he was viewed by the media
and some in that organization as a failure. He's a great player,
but he's been injured. You just can't control those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Polian has had better luck with the situation in Indianapolis, a
situation he compares to the one he had in Buffalo. ``We had to
rebuild both clubs from scratch,'' he said. ``The only difference
is the salary cap.''
</P>
<P>
   He has built the Colts with a mix of youth and experience. Ten
of the 11 starters on offense have not been in the league more than
four years. Fifth-year tight end Ken Dilger, 28, is the old man of
the unit. On defense, 10 of the 11 starters have been in the league
at least five years.
</P>
<P>
   Polian is confident that the mix, as long as Manning, James, and
wide receiver Marvin Harrison remain the key ingredients, will
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we on schedule? Yeah,'' Polian said. ``Are we there yet?
No, not by a long shot. But we'll get there. I'm sure of that.''
 &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons, (817) 390-7237
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Holmgren makes his first return to Green Bay
 &LR; subheds:SPOTLIGHT: Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren On ``Monday Night
Football,'' Mike Holmgren will return to Green Bay for the first
time since he left there last winter to takeover as coach and
general manager of the Seahawks. Here is a question-and-answer
session on how Holmgren feels about the club he led to consecutive
Super Bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You left because you had a chance to be a general manager.
How hard was it to leave Green Bay?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was very difficult. My two youngest daughters grew up
there, graduated from high school there. We made life-long
associations there. \RLeaving\S was more of a business decision
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you expect the Green Bay fans to react to your return?
</P>
<P>
   A: They'll root for Green Bay. I'm no longer a Green Bay Packer.
They are rooting hard now for \Rhead coach\S Ray \RRhodes\S. At
\Rformer defensive coordinator\S Fritz's \RShurmur's\S funeral, I
saw some of the players, most of the players that were highly
critical of me. And it went OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How big would a win against your old team be?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you can compete with the Green Bay Packers and the top
teams in the league, then you can kind of measure where your team
is. We're too early in this thing to say we've arrived. But again,
I'll equate it to when we \Rthe Packers\S beat San Francisco in
that game in 1995. That really put a stamp on our team and that was
a launching point for us. This is too early for that but it
certainly would be something.''  &LR; subheds:NFC NOTES  &LR; subheds:Moss'
hero  &LR; agatea:Even though his team finally broke through offensively
by scoring 40 points against the 49ers last week, Vikings wide
receiver Randy Moss still isn't sold on Vikings offensive
coordinator Ray Sherman. When asked last week if Sherman was a hero
in the wake of the 49ers game, Moss said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he a hero? No. I think if we can call anybody a hero, it
would be Jeff George. But as far as Ray Sherman being a hero, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RSherman's\S just a coach, man,'' Moss said as his team
prepared to face the Broncos today. ``Our hero is gone. Our hero is
down in Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss was speaking of former Vikings offensive coordinator Brian
Billick, who helped guide the club to an NFL record 556 points last
year.  &LR; subheds:Grass or turf  &LR; agatea:It is the last day of October
and the undefeated St. Louis Rams will be playing their first game
on grass this season when they play the Tennessee Titans. Will the
surface affect the club's undersized defense and quick,
skill-position players on offense? ``I don't think it makes one bit
of difference,'' Rams coach Dick Vermeil said. ``In fact, I asked
them, `if we went out and practiced three days, would you rather
practice inside on AstroTurf or outside on grass?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said they'd rather practice on the natural grass,''
Vermeil said. ``Because it makes them feel better, the bumps and
bruises and everything else.''  &LR; subheds:The said, sad, sad Saints
 &LR; agatea:Maybe rookie Saints running back Ricky Williams has been
hit in the head too many times. Despite a 1-5 start, Williams
thinks the Saints will make the playoffs in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll finish the season with a winning record,''
Williams said. ``I think we'll make the playoffs this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Saints offensive lineman Willie Roaf, meanwhile, was much more
realistic about the Saints' situation. ``It doesn't look like \Rthe
end of the tunnel\S is in sight right now,'' Roaf said. ``It can't
get any worse than it is right now. And the thing is, we've got a
lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Saints coach Mike Ditka acknowledged that he might be
fired after the season.
</P>
<P>
   It is, ``a possibility,'' Ditka said. ``I don't control that.''
 &LR; subheds:Briefly  &LR; agatea:Former 49ers great Joe Montana, who was
nominated last week for induction into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame, was asked if he thought 49ers quarterback Steve Young should
retire because of his concussions. ``It's hard to tell any athlete
what to do, but when you start looking at the brain, you have to
think about going out. He's had a long, great career.'' It's
interesting to note that Montana admitted Young has had a, ``great
career,'' for the two have barely spoken to each other since Young
replaced Montana at the beginning of the decade. ... Reggie White,
who had his number retired by the Packers this month, has told
safety LeRoy Butler that he might try for a comeback next season.
``Me and him have talked about it,'' Butler said. ``He said,
`LeRoy, I've been thinking about coming back.' ''  &LR; subheds:AFC
NOTES Brotherly love  &LR; agatea:Despite their different last names,
Broncos cornerback Dale Carter, 29, and Vikings wide receiver Jake
Reed, 32, are brothers. Both have the same mother and father. Why
the difference in the last name? Reed was born before their parents
married and kept his mother's maiden name.
</P>
<P>
   They'll face each other for the third time. The last time, in a
1996 game, Reed says Carter didn't play fair.
</P>
<P>
   He tickled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running down the field and \RDale\S puts his fingers in my
side trying to tickle me as I'm running the route,'' Reed said of
Carter, who was then a cornerback with the Chiefs. ``I kind of hate
to say this, but I don't really like playing against Dale. We have
a lot of fun, but I think he likes to play around a lot with me out
on the field. I try to be more serious about the game, and he's
trying to get me off my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carter: ``I'm going to pop him. Nah, I'm not going to try
to hurt my brother. I'm not going to purposely go out and let him
beat me, and he's not going to let me get the best of him. Whatever
happens, happens, and we just laugh about it after.''  &LR; subheds:Joy
to Stingley's heart  &LR; agatea:The Jets signed Derek Stingley to their
practice squad last week. Stingley, 28, is the son of former
Patriots wide receiver Darryl Stingley, who was paralyzed from the
neck down after he was hit by Oakland's Jack Tatum in a 1977
preseason game. Derek Stingley, who was 7 at the time of his
father's injury, has played Arena Football the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited, very elated,'' said Darryl Stingley about his
son getting a chance to play in the NFL. ``Naturally, this elation
was brought about because most people are aware of what happened to
me some 21 years ago. Derek was a very young kid then.''
</P>
<P>
   Stingley, in a conference call with the local media, was asked
whether he thought Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin (spinal
condition) and 49ers quarterback Steve Young (concussion) should
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us who ever played the game are true warriors,''
Stingley said. ``As long as you can breathe, you think you have an
opportunity to go out and play. But I think these guys ought to use
a lot of common sense. They've both had great careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take a logical approach and say, `I had a great time
doing it. I had a great career. Now it's time to go in another
direction, be with family, friends and do something for your
community.''  &LR; subheds:Gogan by the bay  &LR; agatea:When the Dolphins
play the Raiders today, Miami guard Kevin Gogan returns to the Bay
Area for the first time since the 49ers traded him last spring for
salary cap relief. At least that's the reason Gogan was given, but
Gogan isn't buying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really understand the whole deal behind it,'' he
said. ``I understand the team was $25 million over the cap, but
it's not like dumping Kevin Gogan is going to relieve $1.9 million.
They saved $400,000 with me, which is pennies under the cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Gogan said he didn't think 49ers GM Bill Walsh or offensive line
coach Bobb McKittrick liked him, though he respected McKittrick for
his honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobb never lied to me, he always told me he didn't like me,''
Gogan said. ``I respect Bobb for telling me the truth. Bobb hated
me and my 300-pound body.''  &LR; subheds:Games of note  &LR; agatea:Dolphins
at Raiders: The Dolphins are going to start Damon Huard in place of
the injured Dan Marino. And you know Raiders cornerbacks Eric Allen
and Charles Woodson are daring Huard to throw in their directions.
Raiders quarterback Rich Gannon (hand) is hurting, but the game's
best rushing offense should be enough for a minor upset. Raiders
20, Dolphins 16
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks at Packers: Mike Holmgren comes back for a ``Monday
Night Football'' visit to the town in which he has a street named
after him. Problem is, Holmgren's team isn't quite ready for Prime
Time yet, and after the game, Holmgren will wish he was still a
Packer. Packers 35, Seahawks 14
</P>
<P>
   Rams at Titans: This is the Rams' first game on grass and so
perhaps their quickness on offense could suffer. The Titans have
already handed the Jaguars their only loss and would love to do the
same thing to the Rams. Another minor upset in the making. Titans
20, Rams 17
</P>
<P>
   Last week: 2-1. Season: 11-9.
nn
</P>
