<SLUG> BC-BBO-BAYLOR-CUBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cubs' tradition wins over Baylor
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Baylor has accepted an offer to become manager of the
Chicago Cubs, a hiring that will be official today. Baylor agreed
to a four-year deal worth $5.2 million, for an average of $1.3
million per season.
</P>
<P>
   He returns to the managing ranks after a season as hitting coach
for the Braves. Baylor was fired from the Colorado Rockies last
year after managing them for their first six years and taking them
to the playoffs in 1995 _ the fastest any expansion team has
reached the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor also considered offers from Anaheim and Milwaukee, which
were competitive with the Cubs in money and length of contract, but
the lure of working for the storied Cubs and staying in the
National League was too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not that many opportunities you have to manage the
Braves, the Yankees, the Cubs, the Dodgers,'' Baylor said Saturday.
``It's a great move for me to make. I've been in the league now for
six years as a manager and (two) as a coach. I know the league now.
In the American League, I don't know as much, watching the
slugfests over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who played his entire 19-year major-league career in the
AL, has his strongest ties in that league with the Angels, with
whom he won the MVP award in 1979 among his six seasons there. He
makes his offseason home in La Quinta, Calif. But Baylor didn't
feel comfortable with the state of the Angels organization when
they made their offer on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an awkward feeling,'' Baylor said. ``You're negotiating
with the president of the team, not the general manager. It's for
sale, too. Too many variables. The stability of the Cubs and
Wrigley Field won me over.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians general manager John Hart wanted to interview Baylor,
but he never seriously considered that job.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs fired manager Jim Riggleman after they finished last in
the NL Central with the third-worst record in baseball (67-95),
ahead of only the Marlins (64-98) and Twins (63-97). This came on
the heels of a 1998 NL wild-card berth in a season highlighted by
Sammy Sosa's MVP award and 66 home runs in his chase with Mark
McGwire and the rise to stardom of pitcher Kerry Wood.Baylor's
impact on Braves hitters was undeniable. Chipper Jones, a switch
hitter, credits Baylor with helping him change his approach from
the right side on his way to hitting a career-high 45 homers and
setting the stage for winning this year's NL MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
