<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING HARDHEADED ISN'T ALWAYS SAFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEION SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders' column, as told to staff
writer Clarence E. Hill Jr., will appear in the ``Fort Worth
Star-Telegram'' every week during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever misplaced a set of keys? An important document? A
pair of glasses? Or forgot where you parked your car at the
shopping mall?
</P>
<P>
   These things happen on a regular basis. I would even understand
if you forgot to pick up your child from school, practice or a
friend's house, because my momma did so when I was a shorty.
</P>
<P>
   But how could you forget where you are on a Sunday afternoon
around 12:30. I don't drink, smoke or get high, so what's the
excuse? Let me share with you the experience of the second
concussion of my 11-year NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta. I caught a punt off a bounce during a game in 1990. I
shook two guys but the second one stuck his arm out and hit me on
the top of my helmet.
</P>
<P>
   I ran for about 5 more yards and sort of fainted with no one
close to make the tackle. It was hilarious to everyone on the
sideline but me. I probably would have laughed also if I had known
what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   The concussion against Washington on Sunday was different.] I
was so hyped up to play this game for many reasons, and I knew the
Lord would allow me to make a big play, especially after certain
players spoke against me.
</P>
<P>
   I was back speaking to the Lord as I always do when I'm waiting
for a punt on fourth down. I was saying things such as: ``Use me,
Lord; use me right now, Lord. I'll give you the glory Lord. I'll
praise you.'' That's what I'm saying when you see me dancing around
waiting to receive the punt.
</P>
<P>
   I fielded this punt as I would any other. I danced by one
defender and spun in the middle of field, which is a big no-no as a
punt returner. I recall getting hit head-on then I saw a blur of
assorted colors. I then held my hands up hoping one of my teammates
would help me as usual because this time I literally couldn't help
myself up.
</P>
<P>
   Soon as they helped me, I spotted trainer Jim Maurer half way on
the field so that told me which way to go. They sat me down and
peppered me with questions to see if I was OK. I tried my best to
dance around the questions, but I couldn't tell you what they asked
me.
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall going in the locker room or taking X-rays, but
slowly I'm starting to come back. Dr. Z \RJ.R. Zamorano\S stayed
inside and continued the questions, which I tried to avoid. I was
flunking like I flunked honors Algebra in high school. He said,
``This is it for you today, my man.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime I felt like I was OK. I still didn't recall what
happened, but I was having no problems recognizing and remembering
anyone. I knew where I was, and I knew I badly wanted to play.
</P>
<P>
   I told Emmitt Smith what I was going to do. I waited until
everyone was gone back out, and I started to pray and pray and get
loose. Michael Irvin had come in with his son to eat some hot dogs
and clown me. He was laughing as hard as he could about the
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   I told him to come out and watch me. But he just kept laughing.
I said, ``Don't come out, but listen to the roar of the fans in a
minute.'' I didn't know what was going on the first few plays. And
my neck was killing me.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a few minutes later came the punt return. I did my
prayer and the Lord answered them. You know I wanted to dance when
I got the end zone, and I'm sure everybody expected me to do
something, especially considering all the trash talking. But the
Lord made this possible. He allowed me to come back and make a big
play for the team.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of the battle, I must tell you it's hard to make
decisions. I was only thinking about the team. I was out there for
my team and because of my intense competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, my mother was in the luxury box crying,
and my wife and kids were worried sick.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, I don't know if I did the right thing. But I have
faith in the Lord. I believe he will always take care of me and
point me in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   I put the decision in his hands. And as always, whatever he
touches turns out right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me.'' _
Philippians 4:13
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Jesus loves you! Ask Deion ``E-mail your questions to
cehill\Nstar-telegram.com. This week's question:'' You've played in
a number of different cities and media markets: Atlanta, San
Francisco and Cincinnati. How does playing here compare? ``DS: What
trips me out most about this place is the media. That's probably
the strangest thing because the Cowboys are it down here. With
apologies to the Rangers and Stars, the Cowboys are the biggest
attraction down here by far. But the media down here constantly try
to tear us down over and over. That's what baffles me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
