<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURLEDE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players find it easier to play after service
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For Payne and in pain. It's been that kind of a
gut-wrenching week.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a week for Tiger Woods to tear up Champions Golf Club
and be torn up emotionally. On his way to a seventh PGA Tour win in
1999, Woods has a three-stroke lead in the $5 million Tour
Championship at 13-under-par 200.
</P>
<P>
   No other play
</P>
<P>
   er has matched Woods on the leaderboard, but after Friday's
gut-wrenching services in Orlando for Payne Stewart, they all
seemed rejuvenated during 27 sometimes rainy holes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind was a lot more at ease today than it was any time
during this week,'' Woods said, ``because it was nice to finally
put an end to it and have some kind of resolve and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Woods said ``I just lost it and started bawling'' when
Tracey Stewart, Payne's wife, walked through the line of PGA Tour
players at the service and grabbed his hand, he channeled the
strength she displayed as a way of handling the
</P>
<P>
   mental hurdles of a return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you, seeing Tracey get up there and speak
from the heart,'' Woods said, ``if she can have that kind of
strength, then we can, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be pretty difficult to bet against Woods finishing off
the $900,000 win today. In his previous 11 times with at least a
share of the lead after 54 holes, Woods has won 10 times and on 10
straight occasions. With the American Express Invitational in Spain
remaining next week, the 23-year-old Woods is trying to equal
Johnny Miller's record of eight PGA Tour wins in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods wins today, including the Deutsche Bank Open in Germany
in May, it would be seven victories in his last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet numbers to be sure for everyone's player of the year, but
this one, following the emotional turmoil from Stewart's death in a
bizarre plane crash Monday, won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do win tomorrow, the victory probably will be a nice
thing to feel, but I don't think I'll feel quite as high just
because of what went on this week,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III, who had led Woods by a stroke
through the 27 holes that were played prior to Friday's suspension,
played 27 more Saturday and is still at 7-under par, but now trails
Woods by six shots.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry, who is second at 10-under 203, wore a piece of
plaid fabric on his cap, in addition to a black ribbon, in memory
of Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is truly going to be missed,'' said Perry, who met Stewart
when he was first on tour, in 1986. ``I think he's going to change
a lot of people's lives because of what happened. I know he's going
to change mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 29 players, the PGA Tour's top moneywinners, felt a
similar flood of relief Saturday following formal funeral service
for Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like going to Orlando yesterday gave everybody a
little bit of closure,'' said Tom Lehman. ``It was a little easier
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton also felt a rush of strength from at least finally seeing
Tracey Stewart and her children, Chelsea and Aaron. Watching from
Houston, unable to comfort those grieving in Orlando, brought it's
own type of mental burden. On Friday he told Tracey how much his
friendship with the 1999 U.S. Open champion and fellow Ryder cup
teammate had grown in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I only wish I had a chance to tell him how much of a
friend he was,''' Sutton said. ``She said, `He's right here. Just
tell him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sutton felt even more burdened at having to play the
first round immediately after Thursday's emotional ceremony at
Champions, even Saturday his thoughts remained scattered. When his
score was added up afterward and it totaled 64, Sutton said,
``Really? I don't even know it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a little better leaving there,'' said Stuart Appleby,
who lost his wife in a car accident 15 months ago, ``but it's very
hard switching to trying to tear it up on the golf course after
being so sorrowful. We're all just really playing for Payne this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see TOUR, E4
</P>
