<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOUR NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    Tiger is still in charge
 &HT;    Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Well, one thing is certain. Tiger Woods obviously did
no serious damage through his botched Sergio Garcia impersonation
Thursday in the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of treatment following a shot where Woods tried
to hit through a fist-sized rock and suffered a ``stinger'' in his
neck and shoulder, Woods emerged healthy enough Saturday to start
sprinting away from the field, taking a three-stroke lead at
13-under par 200 entering today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would make the same decision if facing the shot
again, Woods said, drawing laughter, ``I'd do it differently. I'd
hit it (the rock) harder and get the ball back to the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said his left shoulder stiffened somewhat at the end of
Saturday's 27 holes, but moreso because Houston's warm, muggy
weather changed from rain, to cool and breezy in a matter of
moments at mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we didn't have was an ark go through No. 8,''
said Woods. ``I think we had everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   With such an incredible run this year _ he's gunning for a
seventh win in his last 10 starts today _ Woods was asked to
measure whether he can possibly improve on his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could predict the future, then I'd be able to answer that
question, but I can tell you this,'' said Woods, who has won more
than $4.7 million this year. ``I will continue to work just as hard
as I have been. I've been very patient with the changes I've made
in my golf swing. . .. How much better can I get? Only time will
tell . . Hopefully, I'll continue to get better. Everybody's goal
out here is to improve each and every year, and so far I've been
able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Orlando for the Stewart funeral, Woods picked up a
replacement 60-degree wedge for the one gouged by the rock shot
Thursday. ``It was not USGA-legal, that's for sure,'' Woods said. .
. .David Duval is tied for 10th at 5-under, eight shots behind
Woods. . . Canadian Mike Weir is 29th at 4-over-par 217. . . Hal
Sutton jumped from a tie for 23rd to a tie for fourth. . . Andy
Martinez, Lehman's caddie, wore a Payne Stewart-type cap as a
tribute.
</P>
<P>
   _30 _
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
