<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNST-ILLINOIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE BEATS ILLINOIS, 27-7  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAMPAIGN, Ill. _ Last week, Rashard Casey was spitting blood
after taking a hit to the chest in the third quarter against
Purdue. Saturday, he drew blood in the third quarter on three
frenetic plays that stopped Illinois' valiant attempt for an upset.
When the unpredictable half of Penn State's two-quarterback
rotation was done, the Nittany Lions had scored 20 points and
dumped the Fighting Illini, 27-7.
</P>
<P>
   Casey did it with his arm. He did it with his legs. He did it
with his heart, which apparently was not damaged last week when
Purdue linebacker Willie Fells laid a helmet on him, resulting in a
chest bruise.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions were in trouble before Casey was inserted into
the game with little more than four minutes left in the third
quarter. Casey had played sparingly in the first half and the
Nittany Lions clung to a 10-7 lead; the 50,014 at Memorial Stadium
were beginning to believe that, like last week against Michigan, an
improving team was poised to knock down a football giant.
</P>
<P>
   But Casey let them know immediately that it was not going to
happen. First, he rolled right at the Illinois 43-yard line,
stopped and drilled the ball 27 yards down the field to John
Gilmore. The pass was so hard it knocked down the 6-foot-4-inch,
253-pound tight end at the Illini 16-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions called the play again, but Casey was chased
down the line by Danny Clark. The quarterback made a pump fake, and
the linebacker jumped. That gave Casey enough room to fire the ball
into the end zone, where another tight end, Tony Stewart, was
waiting, giving the Nittany Lions a 17-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence earned Casey a place in the huddle again after the
Nittany Lion defense forced Illinois to punt from its end zone.
Once more, he rolled right, but this time Illinois linemen Rameel
Connor and Mike McGee were right behind him. Connor took his shot;
Casey ducked and turned back left. McGee swooped into him. Casey
spun and turned up the field. Safety Asim Pleas dived and missed.
So did two more Illinois defenders. Casey never looked back and
went 34 yards for a touchdown and a 24-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Travis Forney kicked a 39-yard field goal _ his
second of the day _ Casey had rushed for 75 yards, thrown for
another 49 and kept Penn State (9-0, No. 2 in the New York Times
and the Associated Press rankings) in the hunt for the national
title.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, the Memorial Stadium crowd roared in appreciation
as the Illini stormed off the field. Both players and crowd sensed
that an upset could be at hand on this sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois defense had given up 232 yards, and the Nittany
Lions had driven into Fighting Illini territory four times. But
three first-half sacks, two interceptions and 40 yards of Penn
State penalties had the teams tied at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Illini defense had something to do with Penn State's sloppy
play. In the second quarter, Illinois held Penn State on
fourth-and-3 at the Illini 25-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as time was running out in the half and the Nittany Lions
were threatening from the Illinois 12-yard line, a persistent pass
rush forced quarterback Kevin Thompson to throw his second
interception. Thompson pumped once but was wrapped up by the legs
as he overthrew a desperate pass to Tony Stewart that Illinois
cornerback Tony Francis gathered in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Illini offense hoped to keep up a scoring binge that began
late in the third quarter last week against Michigan and allowed
Illinois to come from 20 points down to upset the Wolverines.
Again, quarterback Kurt Kittner propelled the Illini down the
field. In a five-play, 89-yard drive, he got 33 yards when he
lofted a pass down the middle of the field that tight end Josh
Whitman took to the Nittany Lions' 34. On the next play, halfback
Rocky Harvey streaked inside his left tackle and breezed untouched
into the end zone to put the Illini ahead, 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   It was Thompson, the starter in Penn State's banged-up
quarterback rotation, who moved quickly to answer. Although he
threw two touchdown passes last week in the Nittany Lions' narrow
escape at Purdue, Thompson is still bothered by soreness from a
separated shoulder that he sustained two weeks ago against Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   With Casey sitting on the bench in the first half, still tender
from the shot to the chest he received in the Purdue game, Thompson
played all but four minutes of Saturday's first half. On
second-and-8 at the Penn State 18, Thompson called a quarterback
draw and lumbered 33 yards up the middle to the Illinois 49-yard
line. Thompson then went back to the air, finding wide receiver
Chafie Fields for a 13-yard gain. Thompson and Fields capped an
84-yard march by hooking up on an arcing fade pattern 13 yards to
the corner of the end zone to tie the score at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
