<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3605 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-ODOM-LBPT     10-30 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM MAKING IMPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You know the pose, Clipper fans. Head bowed, eyes
closed and one jittery hand on the bible (The Sporting News NBA
Register).
</P>
<P>
   But this time, put the other hand on Clipper jersey No.7. Right,
the work shirt of rookie Lamar Odom. Buy it for a song at the
Staples Center team shop.
</P>
<P>
   Feel the power of no-look passes, the infectious grin, the
ankle-breakin', ACL-takin' spin moves and relentless,
coast-to-coast assaults on the hoop? What if we throw in a
hallelujah? You may not be healed, but the traditional lottery pick
may slip a few notches.
</P>
<P>
   OK, to accrue evidence that the 6-foot-9 Odom the Clippers'
choice with the fourth pick in the June draft is far more than
another New Yorker who moved to L.A. with a great production deal,
we'll go for the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' says teammate Maurice Taylor. ``I love him. I
keep him around me 24-7. He's a special kind of player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a feel for the game you don't see very often,'' says
Lakers talent sage Jerry West. ``He could be the steal of the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most spectacular thing I've ever seen,''
assistant coach Jim Todd says about an Odom pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has to learn to play defense and offense in our
system,'' says coach Chris Ford, who's paid to keep us grounded.
``Rookies don't just come into this league and take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's resume the less-subdued testimony. You're up, Scott
Brooks. Let's hear about last Sunday's exhibition moment vs.
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a timeout, Lamar said `I'm going to pick up my game
right now!' Then he went out and dominated the second half,''
Brooks, who was released by the Clips earlier this week, says of
Odom's 19-point, 14-rebound, 6-assist effort. ``It was like a
called shot. He's my new hero.''
</P>
<P>
   It's teammate Eric Murdock's turn at the pulpit, and you might
want to brace yourself for what sounds like grand hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already dubbed him Magic Johnson with more athletic
ability,'' says Murdock, a veteran of eight NBA seasons. ``He's
that good.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd better open your eyes on that one. Magic Johnson with more
athletic ability?
</P>
<P>
   Let's downshift a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The ditches lining every road to NBA glory are fertilized by
words touting the ``next'' Jordan, or the last white guy with
enough chutzpah to conjure the name Bird. Or another tall, lanky
kid who handles the rock and hands out more passes than a lounge
lizard down the home stretch of happy hour.
</P>
<P>
   The next Magic? That one's awfully tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard comparison to live up to,'' says Odom who has
attempted to integrate the court awareness of Johnson and Larry
Bird into his game. Through such assimilation, he's become more
versatile than a Swiss Army Knife. ``If that's what people see,
then I'm flattered. I don't consciously go out and try to play like
him, but it's really an honor to be even mentioned with Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he certainly jumps higher and jets around the court in
less elapsed time than the ex-Laker great. Dribbling? Forget it.
Magic was functional, textbook; Odom has those next-millennium,
schoolyard handles. Defense? Odom while still guilty of system
mistakes has the length, quickness and desire to play it; Magic
couldn't guard a rhino in an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Odom's shooting needs work, but Johnson who lacked
this kid's ability to square and shoot off the dribble wasn't
exactly William Tell when he arrived in L.A. 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Magic began his Laker journey with that emotional victory
over the 76ers in San Diego, he was an old man of 20. Odom, who
leads the Clips in scoring and rebounding through seven exhibitions
games, will turn 20 next week.
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson, Odom seeks and delivers the spectacular pass, but
an ability to match this boyhood idol for wisdom in his decisions,
and the knack for overpowering any coming adversity will determine
if he can carry the weight of yet another ``next Magic''
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is right-handed, Odom is a lefty. Leave that one for the
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's something else. Your move, Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Magic came in,'' said Anderson, another new Clipper,
``the Lakers already had Kareem, Jamal Wilkes, Norm Nixon ... ''
</P>
<P>
   What Anderson, in a boldly, self-deprecating way, was
emphasizing is the modest caliber of running mates Odom has joined.
While Anderson, Taylor and center Michael Olowokandi are swell
prospects, they don't provide the caliber of comfort zone, the
margin for error, the aforementioned Lakers gave Johnson. In
return, Johnson helped give the Lakers five championships.
</P>
<P>
   So let's not even start on franchise histories. Aw, why not?
Well, we know Odom while happy to be where he is didn't have a
destination choice, but propelling a Magic sequel while employed by
L.A.'s flip-side team could be harder than duplicating Paul
Revere's ride on the back of a mechanical pony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bulls weren't very good when Jordan got there,'' Odom
says. ``Every team has to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his greatest hurdle is personal history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson entered the draft after leading Michigan State to the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Odom certainly excelled during his Rhode Island cameo, but his
circuitous, sometimes-confounding route from New York City prep
legend to Clipper rookie has invited critics to overlook his
enormous skill and label him a can't-help-but-miss prospect.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems he was as reluctant to enter the NBA as Johnson was
to leave it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that if I don't do well,'' Odom says, ``I'll be
criticized because of my past. But I think I can handle that,
because the pressure I put on myself is so much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   That self-imposed challenge includes clearing a path for the
next phenom whose youthful uncertainty grows a field of red flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that all the time,'' Odom says. ``You know, if I
do well, it might be easier for the next guy. It might be someone
from my own neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest assist may come in passing the torch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day,'' said Brooks, ``we're going to be comparing guys to
Lamar.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen, Clipper fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
