<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-RULES-LADN     10-30 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-RULES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, IT'S A RULE OF FLAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rick Fox can hardly contain himself. He's about to
verbally unload on the NBA's new, call-every-apparent-foul policy
when the TV monitor five feet away makes his point for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch, right !ital!here!off!. Look! Look!'' he says excitedly
as the videotape shows Phoenix Suns rookie Shawn Marion glide by
Fox, through the paint and straight to the hoop, unmolested, for an
easy one-hand jam.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, Marion would have had an elbow in his gut three
steps into his drive. Not now. Not with the NBA cracking down on
what it perceives as too-rough defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   The league hopes the crackdown, combined with a handful of new
rules, will reverse a 10-year scoring decline and return the league
to a more aesthetically pleasing offensive game. Rather than the
bruising, offensive-to-the-eyes game it had become.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working. Per-game scoring this exhibition season
rose to 97.4 points per team, up from 90.7 last exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   That's all fine for owners and NBA marketing agents. But for
many players and coaches, the new edicts amount to a
criminalization of basic defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've started letting people go,'' rather than risk a foul, Fox
said, explaining Marion's highlight-reel flight. ``Normally, as he
drove, I would have got right into him. He had me beat, but I could
do something about it before.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Not without drawing a whistle. And Fox's matador act
with Marion is essentially what the league wants. More fast breaks,
more wide-open play. And points, points, points.
</P>
<P>
   NBA teams last season averaged just 91 points per game _ the
lowest since the shot clock was introduced in 1954-55. Only the
Sacramento Kings averaged more than 100 points per game. By
comparison, in the 1989-90 season, only one team !ital!didn't!off!
average 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes the NBA's point perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game was getting too physical,'' said Rod Thorn, NBA vice
president of operations. ``The grabbing, clutching, impeding
progress, chucking _ those things were becoming rampant in our
game, and the consensus is overwhelming that we had to do something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution takes several forms, not all of them aimed at
defense. First is the directive to officials to better enforce
what's already on the books. The second step was to adopt four new
rules for the 1999-2000 season:
</P>
<P>
   _A prohibition on hand-checking and forearm checking, except
between the baseline and the free-throw line (imagine it extended
across the court). Self-explanatory.
</P>
<P>
   _The Mark Jackson/Charles Barkley rule. A player dribbling the
ball below the free-throw line, his back to the basket, must shoot
or pass within five seconds. This eliminates the awful, plodding
strategy of backing a defender into the paint while the other eight
players stand around plotting investment strategies.
</P>
<P>
   _The shot clock will be reset to 14 seconds rather than 24 under
certain circumstances. Again, play will be sped up, mathematically
ensuring more possessions per team and, presumably, more points.
</P>
<P>
   _A modification in the arcane illegal-defense rules. (No
explanation will suffice. Just trust the league on this one.)
</P>
<P>
   Only the first two rules have drawn any substantial criticism.
The Pacers' Jackson, naturally, objects to having his
bread-and-butter play taken away, saying, ``People may say it's
boring . . . (but) it's simple in its purest form, getting a team
at a disadvantage and then exploiting it. I don't agree with (the
rule), then at the same time, five seconds to make a move is plenty
of time.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, the five-second rule has only resulted in a blown
whistle ``three or four'' times, according to Thorn. ``The players
immediately adjusted to that during the whole preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting to the hands-off defensive rules has been tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to change the mentality and develop some
techniques and tactics . . . that still are going to allow us to be
a good defensive team,'' said coach Pat Riley, whose Miami Heat
squads have earned a reputation for aggression. ``I think (the new
policy) has taken the edge off of the defense allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Intuitively, it all seems to point to more fouls called, more
stoppages of play, more free throws and longer games. The Lakers
played a three-hour exhibition that included 105 free throws and 75
fouls.
</P>
<P>
   But players have indeed adjusted. On average, teams attempted
30.3 free throws per game this exhibition season, which is in line
with the past few seasons. Teams have been called for 28.5 fouls,
an increase of a foul per game, per team.
</P>
<P>
   The average game time of two hours and 16 minutes also is close
to past marks, Thorn said, and the league is ``guardedly
optimistic'' that the new rules are working to increase scoring
without negative consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson has had his complaints, particularly
over the lack of consistency in officiating, but he believes the
league's approach makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for the new rules because I think it creates
lanes in which people can cut,'' he said. ``We have an offense
that's not a motion offense, but it's movement with purpose. We'd
like the ability for players to cut, not get jammed up, not get
held, not get tackled.''
</P>
<P>
   To balance the restrictions on defenders, officials also are
calling more offensive fouls, primarily on illegal screens, but
also for charging. The league also has vowed to call players for
``carrying'' the ball more often.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on the whole the new rules seem to favor the play of
quick-footed slashers like New York's Latrell Sprewell,
Philadelphia's Allen Iverson and the Lakers' Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   That's great for ``SportsCenter'' producers, but it's all a bit
distasteful to players who have made a living on the small bumps
and taps that make them good defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been discouraged, because I've always prided myself
defensively,'' Fox said. ``Now they're telling me I can't play the
way I've played the last 15 years. It's frustrating, because it's
not basketball. You're basically asking the defensive player to
give the offensive player free reign to the basket. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't we just go up and down the court, and I let you
score, and you let me score, and I let you score, you let me score.
Where's the defense?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
