<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH CURES WHAT AILS MISSOURI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ There was really no reason for Texas Tech to don
costume in observance of the weekend's macabre holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The team of a thousand faces merely came to Missouri dressed as
itself _ The Phantom of the Soap Opera.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of two consecutive games for the first time this season,
the Red Raiders were thoroughly dominated, 34-7, by a Missouri team
that was winless in four Big 12 games and had been shut out last
week by Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Tech coach Spike Dykes said. ``It is a mystery
that we play so good at times ... over our heads at times and
underachieving at other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating. It starts at the top. I've had a hard read
on getting these guys to play at the same level with the same kind
of intensity week after week. The buck stops here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's game _ both offensively and defensively _ stopped at the
line of scrimmage. Missouri (4-4, 1-4) held the Raiders (4-4, 3-2)
to a season-low 169 yards total offense, 9 rushing, while racking
up six sacks. Meanwhile, sophomore backup tailback Zain Gilmore
gouged Tech's middle behind a bullish offensive line for a
career-high 165 yards and three touchdowns on a school-record 45
carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders were penalized 13 times for 109 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore's previous best was 139 yards against Western Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practiced against an eight-man front, so when they did
that, it didn't matter,'' said Gilmore, who celebrated his 20th
birthday. ``I said all week I could get outside, but it was kind of
easy running between the tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech's lone touchdown came on an 86-yard fumble return in the
first quarter by safety Kevin Curtis. Curtis also caused a fumble
that halted a Missouri drive at the Tech 12 late in the first
quarter. But the Raiders' defense finally began to sag after
holding the Tigers to a pair of early field goals when it couldn't
slow the Missouri rush and got no help from its offense.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri coach Larry Smith said he challenged his team both
mentally and physically after the 21-0 loss to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat the heck out of these guys in practice this week,'' he
said. ``I was afraid they'd be tired, but the key is to work our
butts off in practice and do the same in a game. This is the best
whole game we've played all year. It was a fantastic effort by the
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech gained 67 of its 87 yards total offense and its only four
first downs of the first half on a drive that ended on
second-and-goal at the Missouri 1 when Tigers nose tackle Cedric
Harden tipped a Rob Peters pass and teammate Pat Duffy intercepted
four seconds before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just bad luck,'' Peters said. ``We got what we wanted _ a post
to the back side. The linebacker blitzed and \Rwide receiver\S
Darrell Jones was wide open. The defensive lineman just got his
hand up in the right place at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders tight end Tim Winn had dropped a first-down slant pass
to the other side after fullback Sammy Morris had gotten to the lip
of the goal on a 24-yard pass-run play with 12 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After the interception, Tech went in at the half down 20-7 and
no more in the game than it had been before that drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key to the ballgame, really. Though I doubt if
Missouri would think so,'' Dykes said. ``If we score right before
the half, it makes a different ballgame out of it and we go in with
our heads up instead of down.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not try to punch it in with two timeouts left?
</P>
<P>
   ``Time wasn't a factor,'' Dykes said. ``We had been pretty good
on those little angle passes and thought that might have been the
way to do it. In retrospect, I wish we had punched it in.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, however, Tech had a hard time even making a fist.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
