<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-DEALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNEAU HOPES FOR WINNING DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems safe to forget any thoughts of collusion in the NHL.
Remember when the Bruins cut Dmitri Khristich free and his agent,
Larry Kelly, made less-than-veiled references to possible collusion
among club owners? His guy had been dropped, he said, and if no one
stepped up with an offer . . . blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   We know the rest of the story. Khristich found a pot of gold in
Toronto worth maybe $10 million over four years. Ulf Samuelsson
picked up $4.55 million with the Flyers. Last weekend, ex-Bruin Joe
Juneau signed a pact with Ottawa that could bring him the same kind
of money Samuelsson is making over two years. Slowly, perhaps
reluctantly, clubs are still willing to pay for certain
high-profile free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I had a few offers, I was just waiting for the
right team,'' said Juneau, who is also represented by Kelly. ``For
a while, there just wasn't a club that interested me. I'd said all
along, if I was going to take a little less money than the last
three years and keep playing, then I was going to go with a club
where there was a real chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Along came the Senators, jilted by Alexei Yashin (with one year,
$3.5 million left on his deal) and hindered by the loss (until
around Christmas) of Daniel Alfredsson. Juneau, a free agent after
finishing last season as a rent-a-player with Buffalo, drove the 4
1/2 hours from his home in Quebec and signed on the dotted line. He
was expected to make his Senator debut Saturday night at home
against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the feedback I've gotten from agents and the (Players
Association), it's easy to believe that something's been
happening,'' said Juneau, asked if he thought collusion was at play
this fall. ``But we'll never know for sure. In my case, I think
I've proven that I play to win, and I've always played hard in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 31 years old, Juneau entered the NHL with the Bruins
following the '92 Olympics, arriving as one of their most promising
forwards of the '90s. When his production began to slip some and it
became clear his contract demands would escalate, the Bruins
shoveled him to the Capitals at the March '94 trading deadline for
Al ``The Planet'' Iafrate. He quickly became a multimillionaire in
Washington, where he averaged well in excess of $2 million a year
for about five years.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the best thing that ever happened to Juneau was
getting out of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's true, for sure,'' said Juneau. ``The first time
I saw Harry Sinden after I signed my contract (in Washington), he
said to me, first thing, `You never would have gotten that here.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, said Juneau, he would have been willing to swap
some of that money for a different environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I made some good friends and money in Washington,''
he said. ``But I would have traded some of that money _ it's tough
to say _ maybe for a chance to win, and maybe to be in a place
where hockey was more in the spotlight, like Boston. It's tough to
go to a place like Washington, where it's not really a hockey town.
I've got nothing against Washington, but I think everyone would
admit it's not a hockey town _ that's why I'm so happy to be in a
place like Ottawa, where everyone cares so much about the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Juneau, who got his degree in aeronautical engineering at RPI,
pilots his own airplane. He uses it mostly for fishing trips in
Quebec, popping in and out of lakes in the summer, flying from one
to the other to land the catch of the day. As with any pilot, this
year's airplane accidents that killed John F. Kennedy Jr. and Payne
Stewart have caught his attention. The day Kennedy's plane went
down off Martha's Vineyard, Juneau was flying around Quebec, the
humidity high and conditions often foggy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visibility wasn't good where I was, and I'm sure it was
worse over the ocean than in Quebec,'' he said. ``It's hard at
night with that kind of visibility. It's almost like you're in a
cloud. What must have happened to him _ and I'm not
instrument-certified, and maybe I'm not the best to ask _ but when
you get in that situation, you have to forget your senses and just
trust the dash(board) and what the instruments are telling you.
Whatever it is, you have to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Juneau flies his puddle-jumper, he rarely exceeds an
altitude of 6,000 feet. Stewart's Learjet was capable of cruising
at 35,000 feet or higher, and Juneau suspects that something
``broke down, exploded, or malfunctioned.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``They'll figure it out, but something major went
wrong. At that altitude, with no pressure and that severe cold, no
one could survive that. They had to die right away, fall asleep, or
freeze to death.''
</P>
<P>
   None of it, said Juneau, has led him to consider taking himself
out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad it happened to them, but there are always
accidents,'' he said. ``For some reason, in these cases it happened
to people who were well-known. If something like that happened to
someone else, you probably wouldn't have heard about it. The truth
is, on a percentage basis, there are more accidents on the road.
Flying is a very safe means of transportation. I think if you fly
your own plane and keep it up yourself, it's very easy to be
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago blues
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's 0-4-4 start not only earned it the dubious distinction
of being the last NHL team this season to get a win (1-0 over
Montreal Wednesday night), it also equaled the Blackhawks' worst
start ever, in 1953-54. So much for last season's strong finish.
The Blackhawks haven't recovered since the August 1996 trade that
sent Jeremy Roenick to Phoenix after they were unwilling to meet
Roenick's contract demands. They went 94-119-42 after the deal,
missed the playoffs twice, and went 2-4 in their lone round of
postseason play (1997). Roenick will average $4.4 million over
these next three seasons. It ranks up there with Montreal's
dismissal of Patrick Roy as the worst deals of the decade . . . You
know the heat's rising in Montreal when head coach Alain Vigneault
benches Trevor Linden, only to make it worse by ordering the
29-year-old center not to talk to the media. In Montreal, that's
tantamount to changing Linden's number to 911 and setting his hair
on fire. Right now, Vigneault, Lorne Molleken in Chicago, and John
Muckler in New York (Rangers) lead the race for first coach to be
sacked. In each case, they're working with the mess handed down
from above, but that rarely prevents the executioner's song from
being sung . . . Who knows whether it will last, but it's fun to
see Los Angeles with an entertaining product on the ice once again.
The deal to bring in Ziggy Palffy was key, of course, but head
coach Andy Murray is getting strong, accountable performances up
and down the lineup, including the continued hot hand of Luc
Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Prime real estate
</P>
<P>
   Bruins owner Jeremy Jacobs found an extra $6 million sitting
around the office and plunked it down for the famed Butler Mansion
in Buffalo, right there on the corner of Delaware and North _ not
far from Marine Midland Arena. He has yet to figure out what he'll
do with the grand piece of architecture, which includes acreage and
carriage house, and undoubtedly room for a few butlers . . . Group
2 free agent Bill Guerin, looking for $3.5 million a year, still
hasn't come to terms with the Oilers, each day increasing the odds
that he'll get dealt. Guerin, an ex-Boston College Eagle, has some
grit, but he never has scored more than the 64 points he collected
last season. At his asking price, there won't be many takers. Even
the insatiable Rangers have to stop somewhere (although they've
offered Manny Malhotra and a draft pick for Guerin) . . . Speaking
of the Blueshirts, they were back on the ice Saturday night in
Montreal, looking to end a horrendous skid of three straight
shutouts _ their worst scoreless stretch since the '20s (214
minutes 31 seconds and counting). Lavish free agent acquisitions
over the summer boosted the New York payroll to a league-high of
some $60 million, but thus far more money has brought only more
losing. Once again, it's not necessarily how much you spend, but
paying the right people the right money. General manager Neil Smith
invested too much in players who were too old, bringing the
all-too-predictable results (including a league-worst 4 for 55 on
the man advantage prior to Saturday night) . . . Ex-Bruin Tim
Taylor continues to travel the unlucky trail in Manhattan. His most
recent setback: As he prepared for a faceoff, a two-inch splinter
from his own stick pierced his glove and then his hand, ultimately
leading him to the hospital. Earlier this season, Taylor missed
time after an emergency appendectomy and then a concussion. ``I've
never seen a person so unlucky in all my life,'' said Muckler.
``He's just jinxed.'' . . . Ex-Bruin Steve Leach signed for the
rock-bottom price of $200,000 to keep his career going and is
getting a decent amount of fourth-line duty with the Penguins. It's
yet another sign that some veterans slowly are willing to take some
serious discounts for the sake of making what most people would
still consider outrageous dough. To wit: Veteran winger Dave Lowry,
also an unrestricted free agent, signed a one-year deal with San
Jose for $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers game
</P>
<P>
   Just over two weeks ago, when the expansion Thrashers were in
Uniondale, N.Y., to face the Islanders, the announced attendance
was around 5,300. Truth in numbers: The turnstile count was only
3,062. OK, so the Yankees were in the Bronx that night, facing the
Red Sox in the American League Championship Series, but a number
that low is a huge embarrassment, and at some point the league has
to force a resolution here (i.e., put up a new building with a
legitimate franchise or get the thing sold and moved) . . . In a
lackluster 4-3 loss to the Predators, the struggling Sabres allowed
an ungodly five-on-one breakout (rub eyes here), with only Jean-Luc
Grand-Pierre left to defend in front of Dominik Hasek. The next
day, the Sabres summoned goalie Martin Biron from the minors, and
it was Grand-Pierre who got dished back to Rochester. The Sabres
still appear hung over from their disappointing loss to Dallas in
the Cup finals _ clinched on Brett Hull's disputed goal. One
measure of the malaise: At one point last week, the Sabres'
celebrated checking line of Dixon Ward-Michael Peca-Vaclav Varada
was a dumbfounding minus-20, and Varada was still looking for his
first goal since January . . . Biron's brother, Mathieu, a
6-foot-6-inch defenseman, was considered a throw-in for the
Islanders in the deal that sent Palffy to the Kings. But right now
the 19-year-old Biron is factoring prominently in the Islander
defense. He has great size and great enthusiasm, the latter perhaps
the most important ingredient on a team that is a living train
wreck . . . When you just know things are going bad: The Flames
outshot the Lightning, 36-9, last Saturday night and lost, 2-1. On
the upside for the Flames, Valeri ``The Other'' Bure carried nine
goals into Saturday night's game in Toronto, giving him four more
strikes than famed brother Pavel. Couldn't the Canadiens use
Valeri's touch now? Remember, the Habs dished Bure to Calgary late
in the 1997-98 season for Jonas Hoglund (now in Toronto) and Zarley
Zalapski (he of ZSC Zurich last season). Just another of the
front-office bunglings that have helped make the Habs the '66
Yankees of hockey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
