<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-IOWA-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ESCAPES IOWA STATE ON LAST-SECOND KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Perhaps fearing there might be something amiss in
America's heartland this weekend, Texas coach Mack Brown tossed his
troops the perfect cautionary reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them,'' he said, ``that in order to win a
championship, you've got to win some ugly games on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-ranked Longhorns (7-2, 4-1 Big 12) won a monster
yesterday, dispatching Kris Stockton to boot an 18-yard field goal
for a 44-41 victory as time expired, finally, on the Iowa State
Cyclones (4-4, 1-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we sure got their `A' game,'' said wide receiver Kwame
Cavil (11 catches, 106 yards), ``but I guess you expect that when
they schedule you for homecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying a battlefield on which 60 passes were launched to
produce 636 yards, Brown said, ``This was sure a showcase for
quarterbacks and receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was also a showcase for runners and kickers, as
Hodges Mitchell (33 carries, 158 yards) carried seven consecutive
times as the clock wound down toward nil, advancing the ball from
the Cyclones' 34 to the lip of the goal and leaving Stockton at
point blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, meanwhile, was on the sidelines, swishing the kick
successfully in his mind, aloof from all else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hoping Hodges would score on that last run \R10
yards to the one\S so I wouldn't have to go through this,'' he
said. ``But I wasn't that worried. I've done it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to look the guys in the face at that moment, and
I don't like doing practice kicks into the net. I don't want to go
onto the field if I've just made a bad kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton was perfect on the sideline and drilled the real one,
deflating most of the 37,218 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   With Major Applewhite (30-for-40, no interceptions) throwing for
345 yards and two touchdowns, the Texas offense was its normal
frisky self. But the defensive game plan went askew quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The prime objective was achieved, as Darren Davis, the nation's
third-leading rusher, was limited to 67 yards on 24 carries. But
quarterback Sage Rosenfels threw for 291 yards and made a mess of
the Texas plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns were also bedeviled by a 5-foot-6 explosive device
named J.J. Moses, who had 249 yards on pass receptions and kickoff
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas victimized him once, after scoring on a pass from
Applewhite to Montrell Flowers to take a 31-27 lead late in the
third quarter. On the ensuing kickoff, Moses was unhinged at his
11-yard line by Maurice Gorden, the ball popped loose, and Beau
Trahan scooped it up at the 5 and ran it in for a sudden 11-point
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Horns added a fourth-quarter field goal to make it
41-27, Moses ran the kickoff back 80 yards to the 20, and the
Cyclones quickly cut it to seven points.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas stalled, Rosenfels was back _ throwing 34 yards to
Michael Brantey, setting up Davis' 1-yard score to cap a 66-yard
drive with 3:20 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At which point, Brown figured he liked the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give Major Applewhite 3:20 with three timeouts left, he's
gotten it done almost every time,'' Brown said. He just always
thinks he's going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the final drive, Applewhite hit Ryan Nunez
for 38 yards to move it to the ISU 34, and Mitchell did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called that pass earlier and hit Kwame for about 16
yards,'' said offensive coordinator Greg Davis. ``Actually, I
thought he was going to throw it to Kwame again, but he did a
perfect job of reading what the safeties were doing, and he made
the right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown admitted that the Longhorns _ fresh off victories against
Oklahoma and Nebraska _ were ambushed, and he was happy they
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were supposed to run, not throw,'' Brown said. ``But
gosh, that guy \RRosenfels\S threw it as well as anyone. Sometimes,
when you're coming off a big, publicized win like we were, you
forget to respect the next opponent. But they sure earned ours
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Davis said he thought past experience may have been the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trailed both OU and Nebraska, but we came back, and you
learn something from that that you can use later,'' he said. ``It's
like putting a CD in the bank _ it draws interest and it's there
when you need it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
