<HEADER>
A3655 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-STEWART     10-30 2338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-STEWART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASTING IMAGE OF A TRUE CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a moment he probably had been dreaming about for six
years, ever since that September day at The Belfry when the United
States had last won a Ryder Cup. And as Payne Stewart joined his
teammates in celebrating minutes after the dramatic rally past
Europe at The Country Club a month ago, I found myself watching
him.
</P>
<P>
   There were thousands of people off the 18th green and in front
of the men's locker room, there was so much going on, and you could
barely move. Yet in that sea of chaos, Stewart's was the only face
I noticed for quite a while. He had made such a big deal out of
returning to the Ryder Cup, so sure that he could help reverse the
losses of 1995 and 1997 _ years in which he had not played, he
would remind you _ that I focused on him, curious to see his
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, his smile as wide as possible, placed one hand on each
side of Justin Leonard's face and urged the crowd to salute the
hero of the match. Thousands responded on cue, and Stewart kissed
Leonard once, twice, then hugged the kid as tightly as he could.
</P>
<P>
   The cheering went on, the celebration moved to the balcony above
the men's grill, and Stewart remained right in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   He had to be the most satisfied of all, I found myself thinking,
and it was impossible not to feel good for him. He had stuck his
neck out about making the team at a time when most felt his career
was on the downturn, just as he had accepted the challenge of
another US Open a few months earlier, to the snickers of the
critics who were telling anyone listening that Stewart would find a
way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart won that US Open, of course, and he played a leadership
role in doing what he had talked about passionately: winning back
the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not many people in this world who have guts. But I
saw that a lot in him,'' said Tommy Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan is a former club professional from Milton who got into
the clothing business many years ago and had the license to sell
and merchandise the Payne Stewart Collection. In that capacity,
Riordan in recent years came across a lot of people who doubted
Stewart's ability to return to the top of the sport. There had been
some seasons of complacency, and as Stewart turned 40, he surely
did not have the fortitude to bounce back, skeptics thought.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart dedicated 1999 to making that Ryder Cup team, and in
accomplishing that goal, he silenced his critics. ``It was as if he
crossed all the T's and dotted all the I's,'' said Stewart's golf
coach, Chuck Cook, at Friday's memorial service in Orlando, Fla.,
for the player, who was killed in an airplane accident Monday in
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart showed courage on the golf course (he may have been the
best US Open player of his era, and please never forget the grace
he showed in his Ryder match with Colin Montgomerie) and even more
of it in life, for he recognized the flaws he had as a person and
strived each day to get things right in his life. By all accounts,
he succeeded _ and how many of us can say that?
</P>
<P>
   So, for me, the lasting image will have nothing to do with
knickers and caps, US Open championships, or the sweetest golf
swing my eyes have ever witnessed. It will be of a man standing in
front of thousands of people and, despite having gone 0-2-1 in the
Ryder Cup, wearing the biggest smile. The team had won, and he was
very much a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have dreams,'' William Payne Stewart once said. ``The
funny thing is, sometimes you get to live them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scary moments
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Stewart was killed, Ian Woosnam revealed that a
twin-engine plane he was in had begun depressurizing as he traveled
to this week's Volvo Masters in Spain. Oxygen masks dropped, and
the pilot was able to dive and equalize pressure. ``It was scary,''
said Woosnam, ``but I don't want to make a big thing about it,
especially after the tragedy of Payne.'' . . . Reporters could have
found a more suitable person to ask about the Stewart tragedy than
John Daly. Yet there he was the other day, saying how the plane
disaster scared him so much that he drove six hours _ rather than
take a one-hour flight _ to get to the PGA Tour stop in
Mississippi. An understandable sentiment in light of the disaster,
but how silly it was to have Daly talk about the safety of
automobile travel. This is a guy who a few weeks ago talked openly
about taking a few six-packs with him for a drive from Memphis to
Arkansas . . . When the Southern Farm Bureau Classic was cut to 54
holes out of respect for the Stewart memorial service, it put more
pressure on those players trying to make the top 125 on the money
list, and thus gain exempt status for 2000. Or make that the top
131. Since six non-American PGA Tour members (Jose Maria Olazabal,
Sergio Garcia, Paul Lawrie, Lee Westwood, Montgomerie, and Jean Van
de Velde) are high on the list thanks to the influx of World Golf
Championships money, the cutoff drops accordingly . . . Remember
Justin Rose? He nearly won the 1998 British Open as an amateur,
then spent his first year as a pro playing Thursdays and Fridays,
but never weekends. But he breezed through the second stage of
European Tour qualifying and will try to secure his card for 2000
at the finals Nov. 17-22.
</P>
<P>
   Payback pairings
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is responsible for the pairings on the European Tour has
a sense of humor. At last week's Belgacom Open, Mark James was
paired with Robert Karlsson. In the opening round of the Volvo
Masters, James drew Bernhard Langer as a playing partner. As
European Ryder Cup captain, of course, James had overlooked both
Karlsson (11th in points standings) and Langer (14th) and chose
unheralded Scotsman Andrew Coltart (12th) as a captain's pick. ``It
was a bit tense,'' said Karlsson, ``especially the first few
holes.'' Karlsson went on to win in Belgium, a result he credited
indirectly to James. ``Probably, if I'd played the Ryder Cup,'' he
said, ``I wouldn't have been fresh to win.'' James no doubt did not
ask Karlsson for his opinion, but if he had, the Swede would have
told him that the captain had erred. ``I'd have picked Bernhard
Langer if it had been me,'' said Karlsson . . . Langer, a devout
Christian, led the moment of silence that European players held in
memory of Stewart at the 18th green following Friday's second round
. . . Quite a back nine for American Bob May in the first round in
Spain. He made a double bogey at the 10th and closed with a
three-putt bogey from 15 feet on the 18th, but in between he made
six birdies and a par to shoot 70 . . . Overshadowed by Montgomerie
and unheralded because he plays mainly in Europe, South African
Retief Goosen has put together a splendid season. He flirted with a
59 in the Volvo opener Thursday before settling for a 62. Goosen
has one win, four seconds, and six other top-10 finishes and is
fourth on the Order of Merit . . . Latest golfer to pay the price
for not knowing the rules: Westwood. He slammed his second shot on
a par 5 at the Volvo Masters into a pile of loose grass clippings
near a bush and didn't have much of a shot, his ball barely
visible. Free lift? No, he was told. He got angry with a rules
official and hastily took a foolish swipe, barely moving the ball.
On his fourth shot, the ball trickled out of the cuttings, and
Westwood ended up with a double bogey, sinful on such a short par
5. When he discovered later that he could have scraped the cuttings
away since they were considered loose impediments, Westwood at
first got mad at the rules official (who was under no obligation to
offer this option to the player, though had Westwood not been so
rude, perhaps he would have), and then he conceded it was his
fault. ``If I'd known the rules better,'' he said, ``I'd have saved
at least two shots.'' Not to mention embarrassment to the poor
rules official.
</P>
<P>
   Captain promoted
</P>
<P>
   It was an important story in the golf world as of noon Monday.
By 2 p.m., though, the appointment of Curtis Strange as 2001 US
Ryder Cup captain was lost amid the Stewart tragedy. During his
press conference, Strange covered a wide range of Ryder Cup
opinions _ from his belief that the event has not become too
intense (``When you are growing, there are going to be growing
pains; certainly there are instances that need to be addressed and
will be'') to the question about whether wives should be inside the
ropes (``It's exactly where they should be''). Strange, 44, played
on five Ryder Cup teams (1-3-1) and said being named captain was
``truly one of the most exciting days of my life.'' Some other
Strange thoughts: Don't look for him to get as involved as Ben
Crenshaw was, right down to clothing. ``All of them are going to
get six pair of khakis and a dozen white shirts,'' he said. ``I
told Tiger (Woods), if he plays well, I'll give him a red shirt for
Sunday.'' He expects Sam Torrance to be the European captain. ``A
wonderful pick,'' said Strange. ``I've known Sam for 23 years. He's
well-respected and well-liked.'' On the compensation issue: ``I had
mixed emotions all this year when it came up. In 1983 and '85, the
PGA of America lost money. Now they're putting on a heck of a show,
and the players are not getting anything out of it. I can
understand where the players are coming from.'' On the players'
responsibility to restore dignity to the event: ``We're all grown
men, and we have to respect each other.'' On his heralded
competitive fire: ``I've always said that if you think you're good
enough to win, you have to have the guts to lose.'' Whereas
Crenshaw had two assistant captains, Strange said he will have one.
In addition, he will bring along his sons, Tom, 17, and David, 14.
``I would never think about not taking them,'' he said. Strange's
work with ABC has helped his relationship with the younger players.
But he still plays a hefty schedule and, he said, ``I hope they see
me as a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour finally in her cards
</P>
<P>
   Pam Kerrigan quietly secured her LPGA Tour card for next year,
tying for second last week at Daytona Beach, Fla., in the final
stage of the qualifying tournament. The Franklin native will give
up her teaching job at the Mike Adams Academy in Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., but she hasn't mapped out her schedule for 2000.
``We were supposed to have a rookie meeting, but they canceled it
(because of a lengthy seven-player playoff for the final three
spots) and left us on our own,'' said Kerrigan. ``I was exhausted,
so I haven't looked at the schedule.'' The graduate of Colby-Sawyer
made folks take note, and not just because of her steady golf
(73-68-72-74). At 34, she is the oldest rookie to graduate to the
LPGA Tour next year. Although many of her qualifying opponents were
teenagers or recent college graduates, Kerrigan doesn't pay much
attention to the age factor. ``I started playing later than most of
them,'' she said, ``and I had the sense that for some of the kids
there, it is life and death. Not for me. It's a great job and I
love to play, but I'm just going to go out and play as well as I
can.'' It was her sixth trip to the qualifying tournament, the
third time she made the final stage. ``I played solid the first two
days, but I didn't hit it well the last two,'' said Kerrigan. ``I
kind of survived. But I'm happy and looking forward to next year.''
Her joy was tempered somewhat by the fact that her good friends and
fellow Bay Staters _ Kevin Johnson and Fran Quinn _ fell short of
earning their PGA Tour cards during the Nike Tour Championship.
Johnson, 14th on the money list entering the event (the top 15 got
cards), shot 83-80 on the weekend and fell to 16th. Quinn, needing
a top-five finish, started the final round birdie-birdie to tickle
the top of the leaderboard, but couldn't finish strongly and
dropped to 18th on the list. Still, said Quinn, there is a bright
side. Both he and Johnson, by virtue of being in the 16-25 range on
the money list, get to skip the second stage of qualifying and will
be at Doral Nov. 17-22 for the final stage. ``It's a great golf
course,'' said Quinn. ``I've played there a few times.'' The first
of six second-stage events in this annual torture gets under way
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   URI in the swing
</P>
<P>
   The University of Rhode Island men's team was in Baton Rouge,
La., this weekend, completing its fall schedule with the LSU
Invitational. Freshman Michael Carbone of Brewster did not make the
trip, however, as his left hand is still not completely healed from
an Oct. 5 car accident. Carbone was driving home in a rainstorm,
said URI coach Tom Drennan, when the accident occurred; he was
spared more serious injury because he was wearing a seatbelt. URI
recently won the New England Intercollegiate at New Seabury as all
five Rams _ Michael Sims, Josh Hillman of Greenfield, Jim Salinetti
of Stockbridge, Justin Thompson, and Michael Lucas of Framingham _
broke 80 in typical fall weather (cold, windy) at the seaside
layout. Salinetti, the Massachusetts Golf Association Player of the
Year for the second time in three years, has placed in the top 10
in all five events this fall, said Drennan, while Sims, who hails
from Bermuda, has done so four times. Carbone's injury allowed
Lucas, a transfer from the University of North Carolina, and Dave
Vetelino of Rockland to crack the lineup for a few events . . .
Monday is the last chance to vote for what you believe is the
greatest golf moment of the 20th century. You can cast your ballot
at www.thegolfchannel.com. The cable service will announce the
results Nov. 21-22. My vote goes to the drama at The Country Club,
and I don't mean last month's Ryder Cup matches. Here's a vote for
Francis Ouimet's 1913 US Open triumph over Ted Ray and Harry
Vardon, which went a long way in bringing the game to the masses. A
close second is Bobby Jones's 1930 Grand Slam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
