<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BC-SYRACUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC THRILLS IN SPILLING SYRACUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ It had everything you could have wanted from a
Saturday matinee cliffhanger. There was a shocking start that had
you leaping from your seat. There was a richly layered plot that
churned your stomach with each twist and turnover. And there was a
gripping finish that had everyone on edge.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Boston College's sixth victory of the season, a 24-23
triumph over Syracuse before a Carrier Dome crowd of 48,487
Saturday, proved as taut a thriller as ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   DuJuan Daniels, subbing on the kick-return team for injured
freshman William Green, got the game off to a stunning start when
he returned the opening kickoff 100 yards for a touchdown. It was
another in the series of firsts for Daniels, who scored on his
first varsity play in high school, hauled in a 64-yard touchdown
against Navy on his first collegiate play, and scored the first
time he ever handled a kick return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deja vu No. 3,'' said Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Then John Matich, who missed a critical 33-yard field goal in
the fourth quarter of last week's gut-wrenching 31-28 loss to
Miami, converted a 34-yarder to rally BC from a 23-21 deficit with
2:57 left. Matich's only attempt of the game trumped the three
successful tries by Syracuse's Nate Trout, who converted from 34,
31, and 36 yards before missing a 40-yard attempt to the right with
9:08 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, myself, more than anyone else on this team, feel
redeemed,'' said Matich. ``It's been a long season for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior linebacker Frank Chamberlin provided the gripping finish
when he made a game-saving ankle tackle on Syracuse quarterback
Madei Williams, stopping one him 1 yard shy of converting a
fourth-and-13 play. It punctuated a huge day for Chamberlin, who
had 24 tackles (14 unassisted), 1 1/2 sacks, and a 26-yard
interception return. But he saved his best and biggest tackle for
last when he brought down Williams to clinch it with 1:09
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what you do when you have the will to win,'' said
BC coach Tom O'Brien, who is assured of his first winning season
following back-to-back 4-7 seasons at The Heights, as his team
improved to 6-2 overall and 3-2 in the Big East. ``These kids came
in here and that's all we talked about this week. We challenged
them at halftime. I didn't know who was going to win, but I was
going to grade the film on effort. I wanted to know who the
warriors were in this football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had some warriors, they were going to show up in the
second half. At the end of the first half, we had guys starting to
feel sorry for themselves. It was the same ol' BC, but if we were
going to be different, we were going to have to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. Not against a Syracuse team intent on redeeming
itself after a 62-0 thrashing two weeks ago at Virginia Tech. So,
after they were staggered by Daniels's return, the Orangemen went
on a 19-play, 70-yard drive that consumed 9:30. The Eagles gave up
only a field goal, however, and held on to a 7-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Troy Nunes, who started the day at quarterback, gave the
Orangemen a 10-7 lead when he scored on a 5-yard run. Television
replays showed Nunes's knee touched down at the 1, but officials
let the score stand.
</P>
<P>
   Junior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck got the Eagles back on top
when he capped a nine-play, 80-yard drive with an 11-yard run. The
march was highlighted by Hasselbeck's 40-yard pass to fullback Ryan
Burch on the first play.
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck accounted for 213 of BC's 269 yards of total offense.
He led all Eagles with 11 carries for 52 yards and completed 6 of
13 passes for 161 yards, averaging almost 27 per completion.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse took a 17-14 lead into the break when running back Dee
Brown, operating at quarterback, scored on a 9-yard keeper.
Chamberlin then chased Nunes from the game in the third quarter
with his interception that gave BC the ball at the Syracuse 37. Six
plays later, Cedric Washington scored on a 1-yard plunge for a
21-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, who scored on five of their first seven
possessions while converting third-and-longs at will, trudged 51
yards in 12 plays for a 31-yard field goal by Trout with 4:47 left
in the third that cut BC's lead to 21-20.
</P>
<P>
   After Hasselbeck fumbled at midfield, giving Syracuse possession
at its 49, BC's defense forced the Orangemen to settle for another
field goal by Trout with 11:43 left in the fourth after a 14-play,
33-yard drive fizzled at the 18.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 23-21, the Eagles averted disaster deep inside their
own territory when Keith Bulluck's apparent interception return for
a touchdown was ruled an incompletion. It was the break the Eagles
needed to survive the cliffhanger, and Matich's field goal sealed
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the time off because whatever we had, we used up,''
said O'Brien, eyeing next week's open date. ``Obviously, we're
extremely happy to come back after the game last week. We
resurrected ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in the nick of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
