<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PITINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO'S CONCERN IS NOTHING HEAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM _ There are few things more important than conditioning
for any player on a Rick Pitino team. And 48 hours before the
Celtics open the 1999-2000 season, the coach says his marquee
player, Antoine Walker, is not quite where he wants him to be.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said Saturday Walker is ``85 percent'' of what he should
be, mainly in the weight department. According to the coach, Walker
has already lost 10 pounds and needs to lose another 6 or 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in bad shape. He's in good shape. He needs to get in
great shape,'' Pitino said. ``At the five- to six-minute mark, he
breaks down. We need to get him to the eight- or nine-minute mark.
In another week to 10 days, he'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has looked tired at times during the exhibition games,
most noticeably on Thursday in Springfield, the second of
back-to-back games with the Washington Wizards. In the 102-101
loss, Walker was 1 for 8 from the field and watched from the bench
for almost the entire fourth quarter as the second unit got the
team back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said his ankle, which he badly sprained last April, is
not a major concern. He also said he didn't think there was
anything wrong with his condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was in bad shape, I would be hurt,'' he said. ``That's
not a factor. I don't understand why everyone talks about that. I'm
playing basketball. I'm fine. I'm playing. I'm happy. That's not a
question for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino thinks Walker is at an acceptable weight to play power
forward, which is where he will spend most of his time the next two
months as Danny Fortson recovers from foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight is fine (for power forward),'' said Pitino, who
added Walker rarely comes off the floor in practice. ``He needs to
bring it down and tighten it up.''
</P>
<P>
   By dropping another 7 pounds, the coach feels, Walker will be
able to move seamlessly between the forward positions. Walker has
dismissed such talk as recently as nine days ago, when he said
making the move to small forward was, in his mind, not a matter of
weight.
</P>
<P>
   But wasn't all this supposed to be a non-issue with the lockout
over? Wasn't Walker supposed to hire a personal trainer this
summer? Weren't the Celtics going to be on top of him _ and his
teammates _ to make sure they were on the right conditioning
programs and were meeting offseason goals? Isn't that what the
lockout prevented?
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys go on vacation,'' Pitino said. ``We did (stay on top of
everyone) to a certain degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he wasn't even certain Walker had hired a trainer _
Walker said he had one until the end of August _ and added that his
captain never should have come back last May after suffering the
ankle injury. Pitino also said Walker isn't the easiest person to
find in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough to monitor,'' Pitino said. ``He plays a lot of
basketball. Some guys don't play and live in the weight room. In
the middle is the truth of it all _ Paul Pierce.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Walker, ``I had the trainer and he was fine. A local guy
(in Chicago). He really helped me get my ankle stronger. It really
helped me a lot. But I played on it in the process of getting it
stronger, so I don't know if that helped it or hurt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said his ankle bothers him only a little, mostly on
back-to-back games. (The Celtics have two sets this week.)
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it's been fine,'' he said. ``It's been easy
for me to jump, cut, and move. It's getting to the point where it's
not a factor anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible aid _ having his ankles taped _ is a no-no, Walker
said. Most players get their ankles taped. Most trainers advise
their players to tape their ankles. Walker doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to play with tape on,'' he said. ``I just feel it
holds me down. I like my shoes to be tight on my feet. If you put
on tape and extra socks, it takes away from that. I don't feel
right doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Celtic center and coach-without-portfolio Dave Cowens was
at practice. Cowens recently moved back to the Boston area and
could do some scouting for the San Antonio Spurs. The NBA Hall of
Famer was in to work with what's left of the Boston front line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in to work with our big men _ offense, defense,
post-up, positioning,'' Pitino said. ``For our guys who are
undersized at the center position, and at power forward, he's
probably the perfect undersized guy who's played the game at that
position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
