<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PATRIOT DRAMA LIKELY TO UNFOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ If you're an avid Patsologist, you undoubtedly
circled  &UR; today &LR; 's date on your calendar the moment you laid eyes on
the 1999 NFL schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps you're new to this whole deal. Perhaps you're a
transplant. Perhaps you're new to football. Perhaps you don't
realize that each of the three previous Patriots-Cardinals games
played in Sun Devil Stadium have been quasi-surreal experiences for
Patriots fans. It kind of makes you wonder what delectable
spectating treat is in store for us Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The first Patriots excursion to the Valley of the Sun took place
Nov. 25, 1990. The Rod Rust Pats were 1-10 and losers of nine
straight when they lined up against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The big issue all week was who would be the starting
quarterback, Marc Wilson or Tommy Hodson? Steve Grogan had been
KO'd by the Eagles a few weeks earlier. Coach Rust, who was born to
operate behind a closed door with a full stack of videotapes at the
ready, and who was as ill-suited to be a general as he was to be a
disc jockey, had made this bit of NFL minutiae into a major affair
by stubbornly refusing to identify his starting quarterback, right
up to Sunday morning. Quipped colleague Frank Dell'Apa, ``Rust
guarded the starting quarterback announcement like the Enigma
code.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the crafty Rust opted for Hodson. The rookie acquitted
himself quite well, guiding the Patriots to a 14-14 standoff at the
half. He would finish 17 of 29 with 189 yards, two touchdowns, and
no interceptions, but the Patriots would be outscored, 21-0, in the
second half. Rookie Junior Robinson _ how's that for a forgotten
trivia item? _ would fumble away two kickoffs in his NFL debut.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of the times, it was just another gruesome road
game during the Victor Kiam regime. But it did showcase the
astonishing conservatism and indecisiveness of Rust, who, when it
was over, refused to commit to Hodson for the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason to depart from the procedures we've
followed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those procedures got him a 1-15 record. He has never had another
head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   The next visit to Tempe will always be remembered as the day the
Patriots turned the Cardinals' Tom Tupa into a combination of Otto
Graham, Johnny Unitas, Joe Montana, and David Copperfield during a
24-10 loss Sept. 29, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The 312 yards and three touchdowns are in the books forever. Tom
Tupa! Oh, but it was infinitely more embarrassing. The Patriots
should be thankful no one makes an annual perusal of third-down
yardage stats, because they would almost undoubtedly be the
one-game reverse record-holders.
</P>
<P>
   In this game, Tupa was third and long 13 times. He responded
with nine double-digit conversions for _ get this _ 217 yards,
seven first downs, and two touchdowns. Way to buckle up, guys!
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them third and 20 and they made it, for Christ's
sake,'' moaned defensive coordinator Joe Collier. Also third and
10, 11, 12, and just about every other number between 13 and 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' only touchdown? A 99-yard kickoff return by Jon
Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   But the news hasn't always been bad out here.
</P>
<P>
   In the oft-bizarre annals of this truly unique NFL franchise, it
can be difficult to cite Example A or Example B as the
best/worst/most/least of anything, but the deciding play in the
Patriots' 23-21 victory Oct. 10, 1993, occupies a special niche. It
remains the most improbable winning play in team history.
</P>
<P>
   Situation: Patriots trailing, 21-16. First and 10 on their own
16. Just under five minutes left. Scott Secules, replacing the
injured Drew Bledsoe (sprained knee on a Ken Harvey hit 13 seconds
before halftime), connects with fullback Kevin Turner at the 20.
Turner legs it up to the Cardinals' 19, where he is grabbed by the
ankles. Before he goes down, he laterals (actually hands off) to an
oncoming Leonard Russell, who lugs it to the Cardinals' 2. Secules
then finds Ben Coates in the end zone for the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Let's back up a bit. No sooner had Russell been brought down
when a flag was thrown. Every Patriot, every Patriot coach, every
Patriot fan, and, of course, every member of the media, assumed the
play would be brought back. After all, weren't these the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to bring it back,'' reasoned Pat
Harlow, by then a typical battle-scarred Patriot. ``I thought it
was a good lateral, but it's the Patriots, man.''
</P>
<P>
   After a full-scale officials powwow, the amazing decision was
rendered: The play stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure they were going to take something away from
us again,'' said Russell. ``I knew I was behind Kevin when he took
the ball, but I figured it was 50-50 that this could happen to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being on the other side. Turner was looking around for
help for a long time. Where were all the other Cardinals? Coach Joe
Bugel sure wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seven or eight guys watching the play and three holding
an ankle,'' marveled the Cardinals' mentor.
</P>
<P>
   And how about Secules? This guy had spent six years not playing
behind Dan Marino. He signed with the Patriots as a free agent and
then watched as they drafted Bledsoe. This was his Big Moment, too,
as he finished his one great half of play 12 for 20 with 214 yards
and the touchdown pass. ``I'd like to introduce everybody's
All-American, Scott Secules,'' joked then-coach Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. This was the first Tuna Triumph as a Patriots
coach. Not that he wanted to make too much out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team that we didn't win the Rose Bowl today, but
this was a long time coming,'' Parcells said. ``I'm just happy to
get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds are, even the Tuna would have to remember the Great Lateral
among the thousands of plays he's witnessed during his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird play,'' decided Russell. ``It's one of those
things that probably only happens once in your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably?
</P>
<P>
   We haven't even mentioned the 115-degree temperature on the
field and the players needing halftime IVs in '91. It's just not
normal here. You'll see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
