<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-INJURIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING KNOCK ON NFL INJURY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Teddy Atlas hears about Deion Sanders sustaining a
concussion and then coming back into the game and returning a punt
for a touchdown on a play he later said he remembered nothing
about, the first thing that comes to mind is not thoughts of
bravery. The first thing that comes to the mind of the veteran
fight trainer is that boxing gets a bum rap.
</P>
<P>
   To a lot of people in boxing who hear stories of NFL players
going back into games after concussions or other serious injuries _
as Sanders did a week ago for the Cowboys _ there is no comparison
between the violence in prizefighting and the long-term
debilitating effects of what football players are asked to endure.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when he thinks about how the NFL looks at concussions,
it makes Atlas's head hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing has the reputation of being the most barbaric sport
there is, but if a fighter gets knocked out _ which is what a
concussion is _ he's out for 45 to 90 days,'' said Atlas. ``He
can't go back into the gym without a CAT scan. He don't just get up
and go back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries in football are much more rampant and much more
severe than in boxing. Neck injuries. Paralysis. Concussions.
Crippling injuries these guys have to deal with at the end of their
careers. You don't have that in boxing very often. It happens, but
nothing like in football. Incorporate high school and college
football and your mind would be boggled at the number of serious,
serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing doesn't get nearly the serious injuries football does.
It's incredible the numbers every Sunday when you're watching, but
you just don't hear about it because football is much more
corporate. It's a well-run machine. Football dresses up its
violence better. Nobody says anything about what goes on in pro
football until someone like Steve Young gets a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ain't going back and playing this weekend, but how many
other guys are? If Steve Young is a lineman who got those
concussions, would they be treating him the same way? No they
wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas's point is well taken. Every Sunday, handfuls of players
get knocked out in NFL games; they just don't call it a knockout.
Who can forget the rolled-up eyes of ex-Charger quarterback Stan
Humphries after he got KO'd against the Patriots a few years back?
A couple of weeks later, he was back in the saddle (although not
for long).
</P>
<P>
   But players don't get knocked out in the NFL. Oh, no. They get
``dinged,'' a harmless-sounding term.
</P>
<P>
   Dinged. Like when you flip your finger against the side of a
metal pan.
</P>
<P>
   Ding.
</P>
<P>
   Harmless, no?
</P>
<P>
   Atlas and others will tell you otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think football is finally realizing what we realized a long
time ago,'' said Mark Ratner, executive director of the Nevada
State Athletic Commission and a college football referee on the
West Coast. ``It's a dangerous, dangerous occurrence. Boxing has
always been careful about head injuries. Football has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chuck Minker was the executive director here and I worked
for him, we used to talk about that all the time. How can they let
guys go back in and play football? I've seen it myself at the
college level, and it's wrong. We just had it last week at UNLV
against BYU. They had a player get a concussion and play the whole
game and not remember a thing about it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing would never do that, but the two sports are looked at
so differently. The fact is boxing is medically regulated better
than any sport, including football. Head blows are common in
boxing, but the very thought of sending a fighter back out after
being knocked out is anathema to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you remember the fight when Buster Douglas got hit after
the bell by Louis Monaco and got knocked out, there was some
discussion about giving him a five- or 10-minute rest and then
restarting the fight. They didn't do it for one reason: because it
was crazy. But they do it in the NFL every week and no one says a
thing about it until someone like Steve Young goes down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not always proud of boxing, but I am on this point. Steve
Young and a lot of others are playing with fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers quarterback has not played since being KO'd Sept. 29
by Arizona cornerback Aeneas Williams without even being hit in the
head. The body blow he took snapped his head back so hard that he
was out cold before he hit the ground. It was his fourth concussion
in three years, by his accounting, or his seventh if you believe
his agent, Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue is whether Young will play again. Although he says
he no longer is suffering from postconcussive problems such as
headaches, memory loss, and blurred vision, he has yet to find a
neurologist who will clear him to play. Were he a professional
fighter who suffered as severe a knockout, he would not fight again
until January at the earliest, yet two weeks ago Young was
petitioning to get back into a game.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe this is a ploy and Young will retire after the
season, saving the 49ers serious salary cap consequences. Perhaps,
but Sanders will play Sunday and so will Patriots running back
Terry Allen, who sustained a concussion last Sunday against the
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Allen didn't get ``knocked out,'' of course. He got ``dinged.''
He didn't return to the game, either, but he'll be back Sunday
against the Cardinals. The Patriots will tell you that Allen was
never unconscious, which is true, but that doesn't mean he wasn't
concussed.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, coach Pete Carroll called Allen's concussion
``mild.'' A mild concussion is like ``minor surgery'': It means
you're not the one going through it.
</P>
<P>
   Allen will be back 45 days before a boxer would be allowed to
return after visiting what is called ``the black lights.''
</P>
<P>
   To boxing people such as Atlas, that reasoning borders on the
criminally insane. ``You try to do that in boxing,'' he said, ``and
somebody would have you arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching his son play Pop Warner football in Staten
Island, N.Y., for three years, Atlas pulled the boy out of the
sport, directing him toward baseball and golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I didn't want my own son to play football, people got a
kick out of that because I'm a boxing trainer,'' said Atlas. ``But
I saw how hard they got hit. You can only get hit from one
direction in boxing. Football is not a sport for your son if you
want him to stay healthy. You have to be lucky in football. You
have to be very blessed to play for long without getting a major
injury. It's not, `Will you get hurt?' it's just the degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``In boxing, at least you have some control over how you get hit
and they're only throwing one limb at your head from one direction,
not their whole bodies from every direction. I laugh when you hear
these football coaches talk about dingers. There's no dingers in
boxing. You get knocked out, you're out of the game. And you should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas recalled his own football experience, when he got a dinger
and walked to the wrong sideline. ``I couldn't find my way back to
the right sideline,'' he said. ``Somebody had to lead me over
there. I wasn't on the floor, but I was out. And they put me back
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is a strong supporter of Young, who he said ``is so
bright and so well-equipped he'll know what's right. I know how
Steve is. I know he's talked to the top people in the country about
his condition, and if they leave him alone, he'll make the right
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll also knows that Atlas and Ratner may have a point.
``When I was playing defensive back (in college), there were times
I'd hit a guy and I couldn't see,'' Carroll recalled with pride in
his voice. ``Lawyer (Milloy, the Patriots' knockout safety) and I
were talking about that, and he's had the same thing happen. You
can't see but you still can play. He had it happen earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably one play from being gone, but you can play
when you sort of feel like you can't see. It's wild but you can do
it. There is some of that warrior mentality now that goes beyond
the norm. You have to guard against that. After three or four
times, I imagine it's not too good for you.''
</P>
<P>
   I imagine not.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine what they'd be saying if we were talking about a
prizefighter instead of a prized football player.
</P>
<P>
   Does the term ``criminal charges'' ring a bell?
</P>
<P>
   Brotherly love is lacking
</P>
<P>
   Word is circulating that all is not peaches and cream in
Philadelphia. Eagles owner Jeff Lurie and director of football
operations Tom Modrak engaged in a desk-pounding, expletive-filled
argument at Veterans Stadium three weeks ago, and the animus
lingers. Modrak claims it was an effort to clear the air and things
have been smoothed over, but that's not what the word is around the
NFL. Modrak can walk on his five-year deal at the end of the
season, and if things don't improve, don't be surprised if he does.
Modrak was never in favor of hiring Andy Reid as head coach over
his candidate, Jim Haslett _ although he publicly denies that _ and
he remains angry that the new stadium and practice field he was
promised more than a year ago have not been started, which makes it
difficult to recruit free agents . . . When Tony Banks takes the
first snap for the Ravens  &UR; today &LR; , he will be coach Brian Billick's
third starting quarterback this season. Billick came into the job
this year saying he was responsible for the development of numerous
top quarterbacks over the years. Apparently he's trying to double
the number in one season. Stoney Case and Scott Mitchell were the
starters before Banks. All three are healthy . . . When the new
rule concerning footballs for kickers was announced this year, many
speculated that it was a response to Minnesota punter Mitch Berger,
who was a legend for doctoring balls. Well, maybe it wasn't that
simple. Berger is averaging 50.8 yards a punt, with a net of 41.8
yards, both best in the league. He may really explode Sunday,
kicking in the thin air of Denver's Mile High Stadium . . .
Everyone in New Orleans is disappointed over the Saints' 1-5 start,
but five-time Pro Bowl tackle Willie Roaf is so infuriated that he
called himself the team's best trade bait and said he did not know
how much longer he wanted to stay in New Orleans. He's not alone.
After last Sunday's 31-3 shellacking by the Giants, coach Mike
Ditka went up to club president Bill Kuharich and told him he
should fire the entire coaching staff. You get the feeling Ditka
doesn't want to do this anymore? Kuharich says he does not intend
to get rid of either . . . Kicking has always been an inexact
science that bordered on the mystical. A case in point is in
Arizona, where Scott Player has risen to fifth in the NFC in
punting after a dreadful start. What's the difference? According to
Player, it's that he no longer punts on Thursdays. Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp finds strength
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think that a 40-pound weight loss has helped the
play of Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp, consider this: His
seven sacks are as many as he had in 16 games last season . . .
Rams offensive line coach Jim Hanifan experienced chest pains
Wednesday night and was taken by ambulance from the team offices to
a local hospital, where he underwent an angioplasty. When head
coach Dick Vermeil got to the hospital to check on him, Hanifan was
on a gurney, working on the run-blocking schemes for this week's
game plan . . . Rams director of personnel Charley Armey believes
the success of quarterback Kurt Warner is attributable in part to
playing in the fast-paced indoor Arena League for several years.
``He sees everything and reacts so quickly mentally,'' Armey said
of Warner, whose 131.5 quarterback rating and 72.8 completion
percentage are the best in the NFL. ``After six straight weeks, his
performance is no fluke.'' . . . The Rams hoped small electronic
earplugs would help their offensive linemen block out the noise at
Tennessee's Adelphia Coliseum, but the league prohibited their use.
The Titans learned of St. Louis's plans on the Internet and
notified the league. An angry Vermeil said, ``I thought innovation
was part of the game.'' . . . These are tough times for Bill
Parcells. His predicted romp to the AFC championship with the Jets
has collapsed into a weekly march toward defeat and more injury,
and he is now as absurdly criticized by the New York media as he
was once absurdly praised by them. Drew Bledsoe was asked recently
to reflect on his time with Parcells, and his assessment was not
much different from that of another ex-Parcells quarterback, Jeff
Hostetler. ``There was never a situation where I felt he was unfair
or overly harsh,'' Bledsoe said. ``I've never said that, nor did I
believe it. But he was not a fun guy to play for except when what
he was saying wasn't directed at you. I did recognize there was a
method to his madness, though. It's very easy to define greatness
in football: winning football games. He's won every place he's
been. He's the only guy to take three teams from losers to winners,
from losers to the Super Bowl.'' Which makes him a great coach
regardless of what happens with the Jets this year . . . Bills GM
John Butler has a surprising choice for Coach of the Year through
the first half of the season. ``Parcells has done a remarkable
job,'' Butler said. ``He's a great coach. Great coach. He's done a
great job with that team. They lost so many players and they're
still in every game. A lot of that is coaching.'' Someone should
remind the New York media that great coaching often doesn't equal a
great number of victories. In fact, it's often the opposite because
great coaching is maximizing your talents and minimizing your
weaknesses, not merely winning when you have the most talent.
Parcells has done the former as well as anyone in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
