<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODY HELPS PATRIOTS MAKE UP GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Damien Woody grew up in the hot, muggy conditions
of Beaverdam, Va., so the dry heat of Arizona won't even enter his
mind Sunday as the Patriots take on the Cardinals in what has the
potential to be New England's first blowout win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost on the big center's mind will be making sure the
Patriots string together two straight weeks of top-level
run-blocking, finally ending the questions that have haunted the
offensive line this season.
</P>
<P>
   Woody isn't used to such criticism. In his days at Boston
College, Omari Walker and Mike Cloud ran quite well behind the big
line, and Woody took it for granted that things would be even
better at the pro level.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until last week that New England's veterans caught
up to Woody, who has turned out to be a gem of a pick (17th
overall).
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Denver, the offensive line began opening
holes, the runners found them, and the Patriots amassed a
season-high 133 yards rushing, 106 of them from Terry Allen, who
scored two rushing touchdowns while rookie Kevin Faulk added
another in a 24-23 win.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the success came up the middle, the area Woody patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasized the run last week, and we've got to keep
emphasizing it,'' said Woody. ``Our success last week, I think, was
all because of the rushing attempts (28) we had. We kept with it.
We had a lot of 1- or 2-yard gains, but we stuck with it and hoped
the bigger gains would come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is to get it established, maintain it, and then make
it better and just see where it goes. What we don't want to do is
take a step backward with it. It's got to be in our mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time the line had set its mind on positive
run blocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the emphasis for us quite a bit,'' said Woody, ``but
then we'd get away from the run, and it would be difficult to get
into that rhythm you need.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some talk last week that the Broncos had ``allowed''
the Patriots to run, preferring to avoid their explosive air
attack, but Woody and coach Pete Carroll didn't feel that was the
case.
</P>
<P>
   This week, they would like to leave no doubt. Another reason to
establish the run is to win the time-of-possession battle, which
not only saves wear and tear on the receivers but also keeps the
defense on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helps you get a breather when the offense holds on
to the ball and they have longer drives because they're running
it,'' said cornerback Ty Law. ``If it's the other way, that's fine,
but it's a plus. It helps the whole team when that happens. That
would help us a lot this week in a hot climate because you don't
want either side to be out there more than they have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who has been cleared to play after sustaining a mild
concussion in the fourth quarter last week, would fit nicely behind
this line if it can drive the Cardinals' big linemen back enough
for him to hit the hole and then make his cuts in the secondary.
The Cardinals have had huge problems stopping the run; they are
ranked 30th overall, allowing 136.5 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the good things a running game can do for us, so maybe
we'll keep trying to emphasize it,'' said Woody. ``I think that's
what everybody here is trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody has worked on some things the past few weeks, including
his shotgun snaps, which had been erratic for two or three games.
Now he's giving Bledsoe at least belt-high snaps, where before they
were ankle-high, which is tough for a 6-foot-5-inch quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's going pretty good for me right now,'' he said.
``I'm pretty comfortable on the field. It's just been a smooth
transition for me from college to the pro game. There are still
things I need to get better at, like recognition things, technique
things, but those things will come with experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody thinks he helped himself greatly by reporting in mid-May,
on the first day that draft picks were scheduled to arrive to team
headquarters. It got him off and running with the playbook, and it
got him accustomed to the pro life and to Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation I came into was really good,'' Woody said.
``Guys around me helped me out and made the transition a lot
smoother. It makes it tough when you don't have that. People always
keep me up even when I make mistakes. Coming out in my first year,
I couldn't have asked for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carroll, ``This guy is really holding his own. He's done a
tremendous job in certain areas for a young center. We're excited
to see how much better he's going to be the second half of the year
and how he progresses from his first year to his second year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
