<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS AND LEETCH END ONE DROUGHT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A struggling Rangers team faced an equally inept
Montreal team Saturday night. The result was an entertaining
contest, one that ended in a 2-2 tie, but at least the Rangers
scored.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a remarkable effort from Brian Leetch, it was far from
an offensive explosion from either team at Molson Center. But it
might have seemed like one to the Rangers, who had been shut out in
three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch scored his first goal of the season and assisted on
another. And Mike Richter (29 saves) turned in a brilliant effort
in his 500th National Hockey League game. On the downside, the
Rangers (4-7-2 and without a victory in five games) again struggled
on the power play, going 0 for 4, and they are now a woeful 4 for
59 on the year.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring drought finally ended at 19 minutes 2 seconds of the
first period _ a total of 253:33 over the last five games _ when
Leetch fired a slap shot from the left wing circle past Montreal
goalie Jeff Hackett, tying the game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Leetch _ long considered one of the finest
offensive defensemen in the game _ ended the scoreless streak. It
broke one for Leetch, too. The goal was Leetch's first of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the goal was set up by a harmless shot by Mike York
on the previous shift. With the Rangers in the midst of a line
change behind the play, York wheeled and fired the puck on net in
the Canadiens' zone, before turning back for his bench. Hackett
inexplicably covered the rebound of his easy stop, setting up a
face-off in his zone.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Taylor won the draw from Saku Koivu, pulling the puck back
to Leetch, who went backhand-forehand-backhand with the puck before
skating around a confused Brian Savage into the open. Leetch then
blasted the Rangers' 12th shot of the evening past Hackett, and
more than 12 periods of frustration was over.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rangers' team records of four straight scoreless games
and 341:42 without a goal still stand from 1928, the year the
Rangers won their first Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch's goal negated a Martin Rucinsky tap-in from the left
post on a Montreal power play 6:22 into the game. The Canadiens'
power play was the second-worst in the league, behind only the
Rangers. After tying the score, Leetch set up Mike Knuble's score
at 17:07 to give the Rangers their first lead in 254 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had last led on Oct. 19 against San Jose, the last
time they had scored a goal. Since then, they have had to answer
questions about their lack of production. Leetch, as captain of the
team, had answered many of the questions. So it was not surprising
that Leetch seemed like he was on a personal mission Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Richter matched Hackett save for save, as both goalies kept
their teams in the game. And then Kevin Stevens gobbled up a
turnover in the Rangers' zone and skated to neutral ice. Stevens
curled at the red line along the left wing boards and passed to
Leetch at center ice. Leetch, who had four shots in the second
period, skated in with Knuble on Hackett on a 2-on-1 with Eric
Weinrich back attempting to defend the play.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Leetch chose not to shoot. He slid the puck over to
Knuble, who was skating down right wing, and Knuble's wrister beat
Hackett's glove to the right corner of the net for his second goal
of the season. It was the first time in five games the Rangers had
scored more than one goal.
</P>
<P>
   The lead did not last long, however. Koivu blasted a one-timer
past Richter from the top of the circles just 30 seconds into the
final period to give the Canadiens another power-play goal and tie
the score at 2-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
