<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS BEAT DEVILS, 5-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Flyers played without Eric Lindros and with
their backup goaltender, but they still managed a 5-3 triumph over
the Devils, who collapsed in the second half of the last period
Saturday night at First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took a 3-2 lead about midway through the third
period, when the rookie John Madden scored his first goal of the
season. But the Flyers then erupted for three goals and also missed
a penalty shot by Valery Zelepukin, who shot wide to the right of
Martin Brodeur with 2 minutes 24 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the lead and we wanted more instantly instead of
settling down and trying to control the tempo,'' said Bobby Holik
of the Devils (6-4-1).
</P>
<P>
   Along with the game, the Devils may lose Krzysztof Oliwa for a
few days and Randy McKay to a possible suspension by the league for
an infraction against Ulf Samuelsson, the defenseman for the
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers took the lead just 51 seconds after the opening
face-off when Sandy McCarthy's crossing pass from the left side hit
the left skate of Devils' defenseman Lyle Odelein standing alone in
front of his goal and sailed past Brodeur. It was the second goal
of the season for McCarthy and it started with Daymond Langkow
winning a face-off from John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Sharifijanov tied it for the Devils with his first goal of
the season with 4:42 left in the first. Odelein started the play
with a long pass to Jay Pandolfo, who had only Brian Boucher to
beat. The Flyers' rookie goalie, making only his second appearance
in the league, stopped Pandolfo but only temporarily because
Sharifijanov followed the play and leaped on the loose puck.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Recchi, who is leading the Flyers in scoring, gave the
Flyers a 2-1 lead with his sixth of the season on a deflection in
the low slot off Langkow's shot from the right point with 4:42 left
in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils came out strong in the third period and tied the
score at 2-2 on Petr Sykora's second and Madden's first, 6:20 into
the period. Sykora took a pass from Scott Gomez from behind the
goal and was allowed two chances to beat Boucher from close range
in front.
</P>
<P>
   Madden gave the Devils a 3-2 lead 8:47 into the period, when he
beat Boucher with a shot from near the blue line. But that lead
lasted only 28 seconds because Mark Creig jammed the net and scored
his second of the season from a rebound off a shot by Simon Gagne
at 9:15. What made it worse for the Devils was that Dan McGillis
gave the Flyers the lead with his second goal of the season with
6:01 left and John LecLair scored the final goal of the game with
2:49 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils benched Patrik Elias and Denis Morrison for what they
termed precautionary reasons. Elias played his first game of the
season in Friday's victory at Carolina after signing his contract
hours earlier. He missed all of training camp along with Brendan
Morrison, who was scratched again nursing a swollen left foot from
a shot by Ken Daneyko in Friday morning's skate before the Carolina
game.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros missed his second game in a row because of a virus
infection that has resulted in a low blood count.
</P>
</TEXT>
