</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANES BEAT ISLANDERS, 4-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The talent hasn't been there, but now the
energy is gone, too, and the Islanders are sinking.
</P>
<P>
   They came into Saturday night's game against the Carolina
Hurricanes with the fewest points in the National Hockey League and
succumbed quietly in a 4-0 loss before 8,944 at Nassau Coliseum.
For the first time this season, the Islanders were roundly booed by
the home fans as they left the ice after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing went right for the Islanders (2-6-1). Passes did not
connect, shots missed their mark and the special teams were
completely ineffective. The Islanders' power play went 0 for 5 and
the penalty killers allowed three goals on four chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is very frustrating,'' said Coach Butch
Goring, who sharply criticized his team for the first time this
season. ``It hurts when you're never even in the hockey game. I'm
going to make life a lot more difficult for the guys. We're just
not committed right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's Eric Fichaud, the Islanders' former ``franchise''
goalie, was the best player on the ice Saturday night. He made 24
saves for his first shutout of the season. Felix Potvin made 27
stops for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Fichaud was one of the Islanders' hottest
prospects. But the Islanders landed a better prospect in Roberto
Luongo while Fichaud was having problems with nagging injuries.
Disheartened by Fichaud's lack of progress, the Islanders traded
him to Edmonton, and after a stop at Nashville, he is now
Carolina's backup to Arturs Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not ask for a better scenario,'' Fichaud said. ``First
I get the win, second I get the shutout, and it's especially great
against this team in this building.''
</P>
<P>
   Fichaud faced an Islander team that was coming off its worst
defeat of the season, a 6-3 loss last Wednesday to Pavel Bure and
the Florida Panthers. That game was not nearly as close as the
score was. The Islanders were outplayed from the drop of the puck,
and afterward were ripped by their captain, Kenny Jonsson, who
wanted to see more heart and effort.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson did not get a better effort Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main problem is everyone is doing their own thing,'' he
said. ``It's more discipline than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's exceptionally young defense (the average age Saturday
night was about 22) has been plagued by injuries, and Jamie Heward
(concussion) and Rich Pilon (knee) are nowhere near returning.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes dominated the Islanders for nearly the entire
game..
</P>
<P>
   They took a 2-0 lead in the first 20 minutes on goals by Sean
Hill and Sami Kapenen, whose score was on a power play, while
outshooting the Islanders by 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' third goal came in the second period, a power
play score by the rookie David Tanabe at 1 minute 11 seconds. Jeff
O'Neill tallied Carolina's fourth goal on a power play late in the
third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
