A3868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-VATECH-PITT-NYT &LR;      10-30 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VATECH-PITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA TECH BEATS PITSSBURGH, 30-17  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ At one point during the fourth quarter of Saturday
night's game between Virginia Tech and Pittsburgh, game officials
lost track of the downs on the field and had to telephone officials
in the booth to find out whether it was second down or third down.
</P>
<P>
   The Pitt Panthers wished they could have confused Virginia Tech
the same way. But Virginia Tech, ranked No. 3 in both the New York
Times computer ranking and in the Associated Press news media poll,
proved just a little too strong on both sides of the ball, and
walked away with a 30-17 victory before a rather subdued crowd of
42,678 at Pitt Stadium. Much of the enthusiasm had been wrung from
the crowd in the first half when Virginia Tech (7-0, 3-0 Big East)
jumped to a 27-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (4-4, 2-3), on the strength of quarterback David
Priestley's arm, tried to come back with an air attack in the
second half. But Priestley could not connect in the end zone, and
the Hokies' defense was not in a giving mood.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, arguments can continue over whether Virginia
Tech, which has not played a demanding schedule, deserves its
ranking among college football's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh had a smart offensive game plan, balancing
quick-hitting passes with a rushing attack based on finesse. But
the Panthers soon found that it was best to put the ball in the air
if they were going to have any chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   So Priestley filled the air with footballs; his two main targets
were receivers Latef Grim and Antonio Bryant. It did not matter in
the first half, because as hard as the Panthers tried, they could
not keep up with Virginia Tech, which demonstrated why its offense
leads the Big East in rushing and scoring. The Hokies entered the
game rushing for an average of 242.7 yards and scoring an average
of 43.3 points. And they were fresh from a week off. Two weeks ago
the Hokies mauled Syracuse, 62-0, and it appeared the Panthers
would be in for a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh had a punt blocked on its first offensive series of
the game, when Virginia Tech's Andre Davis punched through the
middle of the line of scrimmage and got a hand on Greg DeBolt's
punt. Two plays later the Hokies scored their first touchdown when
Michael Vick started left and cut back right on an option keeper
and went 46 yards for the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies went ahead by 10-0 with 1:33 to play in the first
quarter on a 46-yard field goal by Shayne Graham. That score was
set up by a 34-yard run by Shyrone Stith, part of Virginia Tech's
one-two punch in its rushing attack. First the Hokies would hit
Pittsburgh straight on with Stith, a 5-foot-8-inch, 209-pound
battering ram. Then they would pop the Panthers with Andre
Kendrick, a 5-7, 180-pound speedster capable of getting around the
corner. In the first half, Kendrick had 106 yards on 6 carries,
including a 59-yarder to the 12-yard line in which it seemed every
Panther defender on the field had a chance at bringing him down.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh struck back near the beginning of the second quarter
when Priestley put together a seven-play, 72-yard drive capped by a
1-yard run by Nick Goings. Priestley was 4 of 4 passing for 69
yards on the drive, which cut Virginia Tech's lead to 10-7 with
14:09 to play in the half. Virginia Tech turned up the defensive
pressure on Priestley from that point, with defensive ends Corey
Moore and John Engelberger swooping in from opposite corners of the
line and making sure that Priestley was picking himself up off the
turf once he had let the ball go on almost every passing play.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vick was the perfect maestro for Virginia Tech. He
avoided most of the heavy pressure and kept the team moving. On a
37-yard touchdown pass to Davis that gave Tech a 17-7 lead in the
second quarter, he demonstrated why he is as dangerous a passer as
he is a runner. Pittsburgh cornerback Demetrious Rich had nearly
perfect coverage on Davis as he ran down the right side. It would
take a perfect pass to beat the coverage. Vick threw one, a
beautiful pass into the end zone that fell over Davis' shoulder and
just past Rich's fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 27-7 at halftime, the Panthers came out with plenty
of fight in the second half, scoring a touchdown on a 16-yard pass
from Priestley to Antonio Bryant to narrow Tech's lead to 27-14 at
12:02 of the third quarter. They had a golden opportunity to put
even more pressure on the Hokies at the beginning of the fourth
quarter, but could not punch the ball in for a touchdown on six
tries inside of the Virginia Tech 10-yard line. Instead they
settled for a 23-yard field goal by Lotz that made it 27-17 with
14:47 to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
