<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON FACES TOUGH DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Travis Knight's sore ankle is nearly ready for
action, which is good news for the Lakers but bad news for coach
Phil Jackson, who now faces a difficult decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' active roster must be pared from 15 to 12 by 3 p.m.
Monday. Kobe Bryant (broken right hand) is headed for the injured
list and Jackson had figured Knight would join him, leaving the
Lakers with just one more cut to make.
</P>
<P>
   But NBA rules require a player on injured reserve to miss five
games, and Jackson doesn't want to lose Knight for that long. The
7-foot forward-center is sorely needed and might be ready to play
by Saturday, the third game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called the five-game rule ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy could be injured, he could be ready after the first or
second game, but somehow they penalize you if you don't have him on
the roster,'' he said. ``He won't be ready for the Utah and
Vancouver games (Tuesday and Wednesday), but still ready for the
weekend against Portland and Dallas, which is highly likely. . . .
Our decision is how can we project a week and a half down the road
after five games, and what importance is it to our team to have a
player of his size on the team?''
</P>
<P>
   Knight severely sprained his right ankle Oct. 13 and only
recently began practicing again. He has not participated in
full-contact drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to sneak in there (to practice) for the last
week or so, just trying every day a little more, a little more,''
Knight said. As for playing opening night in Salt Lake City, ``if
it were up to me, I would say yeah,'' he said. ``Obviously, I would
rather not go on the injured list, but I don't want to do anything
that's going to make it nagging the whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Power outage: The season starts Tuesday, but it's still unclear
who the Lakers' starting power forward will be, Robert Horry or
A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made that decision yet,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's rotation is starting to take shape, though, with Fox
and guard Brian Shaw designated as the first two subs off the
bench. Rookie Devean George, despite an impressive exhibition
season, might not make the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy prospect: Former LSU standout John Williams worked out for
the Lakers on Saturday, but the beefy Crenshaw High product is not
likely to get a contract or solve the Lakers' need for a power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted 12th overall in 1986 by Washington, the promising
Williams played almost nine seasons for the Bullets, Clippers and
Pacers before weight problems ended his NBA career in 1995. He's
been playing overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to weigh him and see how he looked,'' Jackson said
of Williams, who played for Lakers assistant coach Tex Winter at
LSU. Jackson declined to say how much the 6-foot-9 Williams weighs
but by appearances, he's not in NBA shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bison watch: The Lakers continue to monitor the status of
retired Detroit forward Bison Dele. Dele, who played briefly for
Jackson in Chicago, could be acquired in trade if he decides to
play again. Jackson has not spoken to Dele but said he's returned
to the U.S. (he'd been in Lebanon) and is living in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got word through this ear and that ear that came back to me
that he's deliberating,'' Jackson said. ``He's considering whether
he wants to play basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
