<SLUG> BC-GOODY-TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODYKOONTZ: ON TV, QUALITY IS NO GUARAN TEE OF FAME AND FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the November sweeps hard upon us, with all the leprechauns
and prime-time game shows that implies, now is a good time to
assess the new fall television season's hits and misses.
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue that it's too early to judge TV's successes and
failures _ after all, the baseball playoffs have wreaked havoc with
two networks' schedules, and it takes some series a little time to
build an audience.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's ``never'' too early to judge television.
Just ask the people who made ``Manchester Prep'' _ Fox pulled the
``Cruel Intention''s-inspired drama before it aired a single
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Probably safe to chalk up ``Manchester Prep'' on the loser side
of the ledger, then.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, ``Judging Amy,'' the chick-friendly drama on
CBS, is a Top 10 hit. Sure, it's just a slightly better version of
the treacly NBC hit ``Providence'' (brilliant, ambitious babe of a
daughter returns to live at childhood home, encounters challenges,
finds self, others, etc.), but quality doesn't matter. Ratings do.
</P>
<P>
   This is TV, after all.
</P>
<P>
   In general terms, the season has been easy to judge so far:
Winners _ dramas; losers _ sitcoms. Of course, there is more to it
than that. Some bad shows deserve to fail. Some good shows don't.
And a gaping middle ground exists between those extremes. Herewith
a look at which shows fall where: &QL; 
JUST DESSERTS &QL; 
``The West Wing:'' It's sometimes sappy, it's occasionally corny
and they talk all the time. What's not to like? Nothing. Aaron
Sorkin's logical extension of ``Sports Night'' is a showcase for a
top-flight cast, especially Brad Whitford as a deputy chief of
staff and John Spencer as his boss. More entertaining than the real
White House, certainly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now and Again:'' Comedy? Drama? Science fiction? Who cares?
Great TV. Dennis Haysbert, as a government doctor (as in, Dr.
Frankenstein, only with humor), is a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel:'' OK, so it's a relative success _ it's not going to
land in the Nielsen Top 20, but the WB demographic loves it.
Deservedly so _ compared with the same character he played in
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' in this spinoff, David Boreanaz shows
a lot more soul. Curious, that _ he's playing a guy who doesn't
have one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roswell:'' Another specialized hit (see ``Angel,'' above). If
a show about alienated teenage aliens sounds stupid, well, you
haven't been watching. Either bad luck, a government conspiracy or
bone-headed networks landed this opposite ``The West Wing.''
Brutal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasteland:'' Proof that getting what you deserve isn't always
a good thing. Kevin Williamson couldn't follow up on the success of
his ``Dawson's Creek'' with this car wreck of a series. Actually,
that's not a fair comparison _ people watch car wrecks.  &QL; 
CRYING SHAMES &QL; 
(or, to quote Homer Simpson, ``Oh cruel fate, why do you mock
me?'') &QL; 
``Action:'' It's funny, it's biting, it's brilliant. Naturally,
it's unwatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks and Geeks:'' Thanks to the baseball playoffs, it's
aired only three times, but this series _ the best of the new lot,
bar none _ can't seem to scare up an audience. Heartbreaking, like
when Electric Light Orchestra broke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again:'' Yuck. Beautiful divorced yuppies emote;
viewers flock to see it. Why? Who knows why? Explain 'N Sync while
you're at it. In a much-publicized flap, ABC is delaying ``NYPD
Blu''e's season premiere until January (!) so it doesn't have to
bump this show early. Viewers are already deserting ``Once and
Again'' for ``Judging Amy'' _ how's ABC going to look when the
show's out of ideas completely? Like, say, next week?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Feet:'' True, it's not the best show on TV, but it
deserves better than the anemic ratings it's garnered so far. Not
exactly helped by having NBC dump a ``Dateline'' between it and
``Providence,'' which could appeal to a similar crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular:'' Isn't. Should be. At least a little. &QL; 
HOW'D THEY DO THAT? &QL; 
(or, shows that are succeeding despite themselves) &QL; 
``Snoops:'' Should have been David E. Kelley's first bomb. What's
drawing viewers? Gina Gershon's lips?
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Law:'' The only explanation for its success is that
every man-bashing woman in the country tunes in. Gives them
something to watch between Olympic figure-skating competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy:'' Watching Tyne Daly in this show is like
drinking Drano. Apparently some people enjoy that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stark Raving Mad:'' Move it out of the Magic Time Slot between
``Frasier'' and ``ER'' and it's dead meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkers:'' Mo'Nique is funny. This show isn't. Of course,
success on UPN is a relative thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown Ups:'' Life after Urkel for Jaleel White. See ``The
Parkers,'' above. &QL; 
FISH/BARREL &QL; 
(or, you had to see it coming) &QL; 
``WWF Smackdown!:'' The secret of its success? UPN and young,
intelligence-free, garrulous male viewers _ a match made just a few
feet below heaven, maybe, but no way it could fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack and Jill:'' One crown, broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies Man:'' Betty White, wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shasta McNasty:'' Not as bad as you think. But still bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real:'' Should take its own advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Money:'' Death, taxes, cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Odd Man Out:'' A tough fit for ABC's TGIF Fridays. Truly Great
It's Failing, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Grow Up:'' Or don't. No one will notice anyway. &QL; 
TOO EARLY TO TELL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Time of Your Lif''e; ``The Strip.'' &QL; 
BETTER LUCK NEXT TIME &QL; 
(or R.I.P. _ or, in some cases, DOA.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Manchester Prep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mike O'Malley Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Work With Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Harsh Realm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Came You'' (although it might be revived).
</P>
<P>
   That's where we stand now. Meanwhile, bring on the leprechauns. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991030.0296 </DOCNO>
