<SLUG> BC-RAC-CALCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGSHOT SHOWS HE CARES IN CAL CUP CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ John Toffan and Trudy McCaffery always believed
Bagshot was good enough to win. They just figured he didn't care to
win.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Saturday's California Cup Classic rolled around, the
5-year-old's losing streak had stretched to 18 races over three
seasons and his breeder-owners feared he'd never win again.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Smokester chose the right day to mend his ways.
Displaying a sense of occasion in front of 31,047 fans at the 10th
annual Cal Cup, he shot to the lead on the far turn under
aggressive riding by Chris Antley, opened up in the stretch and
beat favored Del Mar Gray by 2{ lengths in the $250,000 feature
race.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshot's only victories in 22 previous starts had come in a
July 6, 1996 maiden race at Hollywood Park and a Sept. 6, 1996
minor stakes at Del Mar. He actually finished second in the Del Mar
race and became the winner when Fearless Pirate was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd come up to the lead horses and just kind of watch them,''
Toffan said. ``But this time he got to the lead so early it was
kind of a new experience for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Classic, main event of the 10-race Cal Cup, the showcase for
California-bred horses, presented Bagshot with considerably lighter
competition than he'd faced in the 1997 Santa Anita Derby (eighth
to Free House) and the 1998 Strub (third to Silver Charm), Big 'Cap
(second to Malek) and Hollywood Gold Cup (sixth to Skip Away).
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If the Bag Boy's ever going to win, it'll be today,'
'' McCaffery said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned $10.40 as one of four upsetters in a pick-six that
paid $27,456. The Oak Tree association guaranteed a $1 million
pick-six pool and an insurance company kicked in the difference
when $873,605 was bet.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshot's win was the second of the afternoon for McCaffery,
Toffan and trainer Paco Gonzalez. Their 2-year-old colt Spacelink
scored his maiden victory in the Juvenile, leaving odds-on favorite
Stormy Jack six lengths back in third.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big day, too, for jockeys Garrett Gomez (three wins)
and Eddie Delahoussaye (two) and trainer Juan Garcia (two).
</P>
<P>
   Gomez and Garcia teamed up to win the Cal Cup Distaff hillside
sprint with 9-1 Chichim and the Cal Cup Mile on turf with Pomona
Invitational winner Native Desert. Gomez also won the Cal Cup
Sprint for trainer Leonard Duncan with overpowering stretch runner
Love That Red.
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye rode Feverish to her fourth straight victory in the
Cal Cup Matron and won a starter handicap race with J.R. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Also winning her fourth in a row to remain undefeated, Cover Gal
lived up to 1-2 odds in the Cal Cup Juvenile Fillies, giving jockey
Gary Stevens his 12th Cal Cup victory to break a tie with Corey
Nakatani at the top of the event's all-time leaders list.
</P>
<P>
   In the starter handicap that opened the program, front-running
Irrelevant gave Pat Valenzuela his first Cal Cup victory since his
four-win day in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Bob Hebert, a Los Angeles newspaper turf writer and
handicapper for four decades, died Friday at his home in Carlsbad.
Hebert celebrated his 90th birthday Sept. 25. . . . Fiji, the 1998
female turf champion who would have sought her first 1999 victory
in the Breeders' Cup Filly and Mare Turf next Saturday, has been
retired, trainer Neil Drysdale said at Gulfstream Park in Florida.
The 5-year-old was dull in races at Santa Anita and Keeneland since
fighting a respiratory infection. . . . Top New York 2-year-old
Greenwood Lake is out of the Breeders' Cup Juvenile. . . . Pomona
Derby winner Isaypete won the Calder Derby at 17-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
