<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3843 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     10-30 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS IS HOT TOPIC FOR GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- The Galaxy is aware of their friends from Dallas,
who must be walking on air after disposing of Chicago in last
week's playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn is on a roll and has renewed confidence entering
today's opening game of the best-of-three Western Conference final
series against the Galaxy at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Dallas won 10 of its past 11, but it is arguably
the league's most balanced team.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn finished second in MLS in goals allowed (35) and in
goals scored (54).
</P>
<P>
   The Burn finished second behind the Galaxy in the Western
Conference during the regular season, then gained some postseason
confidence by defeating Chicago, the defending MLS Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas trailed, 2-0, at halftime of its series-deciding match
with the Fire. But the Burn cut the lead to 2-1 midway through the
second half, then scored two goals in the final 10 minutes for a
3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that Dallas' MLS MVP candidate Jason Kreis, who led the
league in scoring with 51 points (18 goals, 15 assists) and other
scoring threats like Arial Graziani, Oscar Pareja and Jorge
Rodriguez, and it's easy to see why the Galaxy-Burn matchup is so
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the Galaxy has the league's best defense,
anchored by goalkeeper Kevin Hartman and defender Robin Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles hasn't given up a goal in the playoffs; Dallas has
yielded six in their past two games.
</P>
<P>
   But Dallas found a way to penetrate Chicago's stingy defense,
something L.A. couldn't do last year.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfielder Danny Pena and Co. are ready for the series to
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can jump on them early, I like our chances,'' Pena said.
``But the longer they stay in the game, the more difficult it's
going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they have a lot of luck on their side. But at the
same time, they deserve a spot in the conference finals for the
effort they gave against Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's top priority is to contain Kreis.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jason, you have to be aware of his shot from distance,''
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``He hits the ball very well. You
can't stop him on free kicks and stuff like that. But we have to be
aware because he gets behind the defense. He's great at showing the
ball and spinning away. We have to make sure we don't bite too
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri is concerned by the way Dallas
plays as a cohesive unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you see clearly in Dallas is they're a united
team,'' Caligiuri said. ``Everyone understands their roles and they
play well as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some talented forwards in Graziani and Kreis, and
they're dangerous from the first minute to the 90th minute. We will
have our hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy remembers all too well its 4-3 loss to Dallas in the
next-to-last game of the regular season. The Galaxy blew a 3-1
second-half lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me,'' Schmid said. ``It was something that, I know
when I flew back, somebody said, `Do you want to go out to dinner?'
and I said, `I'm not very good dinner company tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schmid said this series will come down to more than
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play with very good concentration,'' he said. ``If
we play our game and we concentrate on what we need to do, we'll be
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get caught up in what we saw last Wednesday (Dallas'
victory over Chicago) or what happened the last time we played
Dallas. If we have that in the back of our minds, it would make us
nervous and this isn't the time to be nervous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
