<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3851 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-FIX-TEX     10-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-FIX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES 12TH GRAF TO KERRY COLLINS, STED TODD COLLINS IN QB-SHORT
NFL, BUDDING STAR AND PROVEN STAR FACE OFF IN INDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a good look today at the quarterback play in Indy.
Something rare will be on display, which doesn't necessarily mean
Troy Aikman will force a few smiles for the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what we will have here is a young/heralded QB who is
showing NFL progress _ this was Aikman a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Aikman's long career is stuck in a
week-to-week gear of what have you done for us lately. But for
Peyton Manning, the career anticipation is immense. How far will he
eventually carry the up-and-coming Colts?
</P>
<P>
   In a critical stretch of schedule for the Cowboys, this is
another tell-tale contest of measuring recovery progress from those
twin disasters known as Eagles and Giants.
</P>
<P>
   For the Colts and Manning, this is a game that was earmarked on
the schedule last summer. Beat Dallas and you will get more credit
than you probably deserve. But a surprising 4-2 start for Indy now
makes this a springboard game into the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the short haul or the long run, of course, it will be about
the quarterback. Good, solid, consistent play at that position is
what each NFL club is seeking. Yet very few are finding it.
</P>
<P>
   But Manning, in his second year out of Tennessee, has been an
exception in this season of spotty-to-awful quarterback
performances. When Arena League product Kurt Warner of the St.
Louis Rams is the NFL's most valuable quarterback to date, what
does that say?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much talk about the shortage of potential franchise
type quarterbacks,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said, ``but I really
don't think it's any different than a decade ago. The search is
never ending for the quarterback who can hold up mentally and
physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are looking for someone with the skill to win a game and
the judgment not to lose it. That's a hard order to fill. Which is
also why a Manning jumps out at everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But consider this dwindling list:
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in the NFL, the elite quarterbacks were John Elway,
Brett Favre, Aikman, Steve Young and Dan Marino. Elway has retired,
Young should retire and while Marino is currently injured, Dolphins
coach Jimmy Johnson may also be preparing to move on without him.
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, the franchise builders at quarterback had
names like Kerry
</P>
<P>
   Collins, Mark Brunell, Trent Dilfer and Drew Bledsoe. Only
Bledsoe in New England remains highly regarded while Collins and
Dilfer no longer even register on the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   On the list of emerging QBs was once Jake Plummer, Elvis Grbac,
Kordell Stewart, Steve McNair, Scott Mitchell and Heath Shuler. All
of those are either disappointments or washouts, although Plummer
is a good bet for the bounce-back.
</P>
<P>
   The usual suspects among the retreads included Vinny Testaverde,
Doug Flutie, Chris Chandler, Jeff George, Randall Cunningham, Rich
Gannon and Brad Johnson. This would have been the most productive
group of QBs, except for injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks who have dropped in this season from either the
moon or Canada include Warner, Jon Kitna, Charlie Batch and Jeff
Garcia. Outside of Garcia, this is the best group in the league at
the moment. How scary is that?
</P>
<P>
   In the category of too-early-to-tell would be a promising catch
of rookies, along with Brian Griese in Denver and possibly the
headcase in San Diego, Mr. Ryan Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Put it all together, however, and it leaves the NFL in a
quarterbacking ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the position that impacts how a team plays and impacts
how a team drafts _ if you are wrong, you pay heavily,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   But all that scouting research can take place, and then a Warner
shows up in St. Louis and goes bombs away on the rest of the
league. Blind luck? Yes. But as long as the results are there, who
cares?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take every quarterback who has been available \Rin the
draft\S during the 90s, we had Manning rated the highest, with
Bledsoe real close,'' said Larry Lacewell, the Cowboys' director of
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I wondered if Bledsoe would be physically tough
enough, and I was wrong about that. He is. But for the total
package, Manning was it. And we are starting to see the total
package come together.''
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting that Manning somewhat goes against the trend
most teams now deem important _ the quarterback who moves around
freely, avoiding the rush. Manning is mobile, but his style is also
a lot like Aikman's _ the five-step drop and the quick release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what the trend is _ the only thing that
counts is if your quarterback can make plays,'' Lacewell added.
``Manning is still learning, but he can make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL of today, that has become a rare blessing.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
