<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-OKLAHOMA-ST.-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES REACH MILESTONES, SHED DOUBTS WITH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M, a team plagued by ragged
performances in recent weeks, sanded down some rough edges and
produced smooth, round numbers yesterday at Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   By dispatching Oklahoma State, 21-3, the 22nd-ranked Aggies
wrapped up the 100th career victory for coach R.C. Slocum and the
600th triumph in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which came in a daylong downpour in front of
74,008, may not have been artistic. But it proved to be emotional
and effective.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it erase some lingering doubts after last week's
51-6 loss to No. 24 Oklahoma, it allowed the Aggies (6-2, 3-2) to
remain within a game of No. 12 Texas (7-2, 4-1) in the Big 12 South
Division on the same day that fellow front-runners Oklahoma (4-3,
2-2) and Texas Tech (4-4, 3-2) suffered losses to North Division
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot more than win a football game out there. We came
together ... like we hadn't done all year,'' said quarterback Randy
McCown, who choked back tears during the postgame news conference
while reflecting on the mental transformation the Aggies have
undergone since the loss to Oklahoma. ``As seniors, a lot of people
questioned our leadership abilities and wondered if we could get
the job done. We wanted to show that we could.''
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of A&AMP;M heroes proved to be senior-laden.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing with a slight separation in his left
(nonthrowing) shoulder, McCown completed 20 of 29 passes for 242
yards and two touchdowns. Both of his scoring strikes went to wide
receiver Matt Bumgardner, a fifth-year senior who established
career highs for receptions (five), yards (79) and touchdowns (2).
Until yesterday, Bumgardner's only career touchdown catch came
against Oklahoma State in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bernard, another fifth-year senior, paced a resurgent A&AMP;M
ground game. Bernard picked up 80 of the Aggies' 152 yards against
a run defense that came in allowing 112.5 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Aggies turned to seniors Brandon Jennings and
Sedrick Curry as stabilizing influences on a unit that limited
Oklahoma State to 260 yards and only two snaps inside the A&AMP;M
20-yard line. Jennings, a free safety, led the team in tackles (9).
Curry, a cornerback, produced the game's lone turnover, an
interception that sparked an 89-yard touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   One week after being pillaged for 552 yards by Oklahoma, the
``Wrecking Crew'' collected six sacks and allowed OSU to convert
only three of 12 third downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a big step in the right direction,'' linebacker Brian
Gamble said. ``I think it will just keep snowballing from here. In
the locker room, we were all jumping around and feeling great.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Aggies stuffed a Cowboys' offense that played
without starting quarterback Tony Lindsay, who was a game-time
scratch because he was slow in recovering from a shoulder injury
suffered last week against Kansas State. But coach R.C. Slocum
pointed to several players ``who really stepped up'' to lift the
Aggies in their hour of need.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those played on an offense that cranked out 394 yards,
highlighted by time-consuming touchdown drives of 89, 79 and 69
yards. McCown ended the first march with an 11-yard touchdown
strike to Bumgardner, putting A&AMP;M up, 7-0, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies followed OSU kicker Tim Sydnes' second missed
field-goal attempt with a 14-play, 79-yard touchdown drive in the
third quarter, capped by D'Andre Hardeman's 1-yard blast. After
Sydnes connected from 36 yards, A&AMP;M stretched the lead to 21-3 when
McCown hit Bumgardner on a 14-yard fade route with 8:59 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our pride taken away last week,'' fullback Ja'Mar
Toombs said. ``We had to get our feet back on the ground, and we
did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Slocum collected career victory No. 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fitting that the 100th win came in a game where we really
needed to win,'' Slocum said. ``That's what means something to
me.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
