r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      10-30 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERING VIEWS ON MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
``Analysis'' 
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The question posed to Sen. John McCain was about
how to rebuild the armed forces, so it may have seemed odd that his
response referred to his own temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that perhaps John McCain gets angry,'' the Arizona
Republican said in replying to the query during Thursday's New
Hampshire town meeting with GOP presidential contenders. ``My
friends, I get angry when we spend $350 million on a carrier the
Navy doesn't want or need.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from a throwaway line, that was McCain's way of signaling,
in the coded language of politics, that he accepts the challenge of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's backers to make McCain's temperament a
presidential campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bring it on, McCain suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters did bring it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the Republican governors have talked about this
issue, the McCain temper, in casual conversation in the past,''
John Truscott, chief spokesman for Michigan Gov. John Engler, said
Friday in an interview with ``The'' ``Arizona Republic.'' Engler is
the Bush campaign's liaison to governors.
</P>
<P>
   Truscott said one reason why an overwhelming number of GOP
governors have endorsed Bush is because ``they know he has the
temperament to be president,'' implying that McCain does not.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain's critics call him a political bully, allies say
his occasionally white-hot personality, sometimes directed at rival
lawmakers, reporters or others, is just a piece of a man who is
less scripted and more direct than most politicians. They say he is
far more jocular than surly, especially with his core staff
members, who average more than eight years of service apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing the number of people who say, `He's just so
straightforward, he's so dead honest, he's so refreshing,' '' said
Torie Clarke, a former McCain press secretary who also worked on
the 1992 re-election campaign of Bush's father, the former
president. ``And, you know, his temper is a part of that. You know
where the guy stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarke added, ``It's no secret he does not suffer fools well. So
if you're a fool, if you're a hypocrite or you're obnoxious, look
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's press aides deny that the Texas governor is behind any
orchestrated effort to highlight McCain's inner demons or
personality.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign became suspicious of Bush when a ``New York
Times'' article last Monday quoted not only Arizona Gov. Jane Hull
but also Engler in a story about McCain's personality and his
difficulties securing the support of some top elected officials
back home. Hull and Engler have become two of Bush's
highest-profile gubernatorial allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally ridiculous to think Governor Bush can control
what the ``New'' ``York Times'' writes,'' Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan said. ``We're puzzled by the way the senator is
reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, last week, it seemed that the long
honeymoon that McCain has enjoyed with the national news media, a
string of favorable articles devoted to what ``New Republic''
Editor Charles Lane called ``the McCain swoon,'' was coming to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Following the ``Times'' story last week was a ``Wall Street
Journal'' column by John H. Fund portraying McCain as a moody
``Lone Ranger'' and questioning whether the Arizonan can ``build
and lead a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a ``Newsweek'' article chronicled McCain's raking in
special-interest campaign contributions while crusading against big
donors' influence on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you go up in the polls.'' said Dan
Schnur, McCain's national communications director. ``Every
candidate in the history of presidential politics who has made
significant upward movement in the polls, like John McCain has, is
going to get a lot more press scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know McCain say the negative publicity itself is less
important than how McCain chooses to react to it.
</P>
<P>
   He is not known locally to be laconic when things seem to go
against him in the press. His reaction to the shifting media
currents could turn out to be noteworthy in itself, particularly
since his disposition has been placed, at least for now, under the
media glare.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wouldn't return the calls of ``Republic'' reporters for
more than a year after the newspaper published a cartoon in 1994
depicting his wife, Cindy, shaking an emaciated Black child to get
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that year, Cindy McCain had said she was addicted to
painkillers and admitted stealing some pills from her charitable
organization.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Vietnam War POW, called the cartoon
``incredibly painful.'' He said in 1996 that ``it doesn't matter''
what some Phoenix columnists and radio talk show hosts think
because ``what I care about are the people whom I respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Other times, the blunt McCain has gotten into trouble for saying
too much to the press.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he told a ``Republic'' reporter that he simply didn't
have the votes to cut off a filibuster to keep alive his bill to
reform campaign finance laws. Some supporters, frantically trying
to salvage the bill, were upset at his candor when the article
appeared. McCain's office quickly issued a press release saying
hope was not lost. The bill died.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain slips up on occasion, his friends say it's forgivable
because he is trying to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's passionate, and he fights for the things he believes
in,'' said Arizona Rep. Matt Salmon, also a Republican. ``I for one
don't want some Joe Milquetoast who doesn't care about things. When
McCain plays, he plays to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Schnur, ``Show me a politician who never offends anyone,
and I'll show you a politician who never gets anything done. If
John McCain ever stopped fighting for what he believed in, he'd be
just another hack politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, his detractors say, McCain goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   GOP state Sen. Tom Smith of Phoenix, a Marine Corps veteran,
said in the ``Wall Street Journal'' story, ``He curries favor with
elitists, and his staff bullies people.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Barbara Barrett has said McCain ``aggressively
encouraged'' her not to run in the 1994 GOP gubernatorial primary
against former Gov. Fife Symington, a McCain ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The method and strong-handedness of this seemed excessive,''
she told ``The'' ``Republic'' in 1996. Barrett, who ran anyway and
lost, was out of town Friday and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said he spoke ``strongly'' with Barrett but did not
instruct her to stay out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Now that McCain's disposition has become part of the campaign
dialogue, the challenge will be for his campaign to attempt to turn
it into an asset by, for example, depicting him as forceful and his
rivals as indecisive.
</P>
<P>
   It was a calculated decision for McCain to invoke his own temper
in Thursday's town meeting. He had made a similar reference earlier
in a San Francisco appearance and opted to do it again during the
televised forum, when it mattered most. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
