<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FBC-FLAST-VIRGINIA-NY     10-30 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLAST-VIRGINIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE BEATS VIRGINIA, 35-10  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ After 68 years of fielding a football
team, the University of Virginia was host for the first time
Saturday night to an opponent ranked No. 1 nationally in the polls.
And the Cavaliers were stoked for Florida State's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Fans arrived early and cheered often, remembering how Virginia
had knocked the Seminoles from the unbeaten ranks here four years
ago. But that adrenaline could carry the Cavaliers only so far.
Florida State, which trailed at halftime, scored two touchdowns
late in the third quarter and two more in the fourth quarter to
win, 35-10, before 47,900 at Scott Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even three interceptions by quarterback Chris Weinke and a lost
fumble at the Virginia 2-yard line by his backup, Marcus Outzen,
could not stop Florida State from moving to 9-0 over all. The
Seminoles are No. 1 in the Associated Press poll and No. 2 in the
New York Times ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke wound up redeeming himself with his second-half play and
set a Florida State record for 200-yard passing games with his
18th, breaking the mark set by the Heisman Trophy winner Charlie
Ward. Weinke completed 24 of 35 passes for 297 yards and 3
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The bright light for Virginia was tailback Thomas Jones, who
came in averaging 158.4 rushing yards a game. He pierced the
Seminoles for 164 yards and a touchdown in 26 carries and broke the
school rushing record of 3,389 yards held by Tiki Barber, now of
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-quarter touchdowns by flanker Peter Warrick, on a
dazzling 50-yard pass play from Weinke, and Outzen, on a late
1-yard run, made this game seem much easier for Florida State than
it was.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Virginia led deep into the third quarter, 10-7, before
losing for the fourth time in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke got off to a nightmarish start that kept the Seminoles
stuck in neutral with four frustrating series. Pressured, he threw
away a third-down pass on Florida State's game-opening drive. Next,
he helped the Seminoles reach the Virginia 21-yard line, but then
flipped an interception to linebacker Byron Thweatt.
</P>
<P>
   That would start a pattern. Near the first quarter's end, with
Florida State at its 43-yard line, Weinke was forced to run to his
right looking for a receiver. What he found was Virginia safety
Jerton Evans with a soft, off-balance throw.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle was not yet complete. Early in the second quarter,
after Weinke appeared to be surprised by the center's snap on a
third-down play, cornerback Dwayne Stukes intercepted yet another
Weinke offering. This one particularly hurt as Virginia took over
at Florida State's 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers had not been able to capitalize on Weinke's first
two interceptions, but the third provided erratic Virginia with too
much generosity.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers scored a touchdown after two plays were smothered
by the Seminoles, setting up third down and 15 from the 16-yard
line. Jones took a handoff on a draw play, lunged forward several
steps, then bolted to his right and into the clear. He dived the
last 3 yards into the end zone, as the partisan crowd roared its
approval.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida State did not get flustered, and the Seminoles put
together their best drive of the game. It covered 91 yards and took
14 tension-building plays. Operating largely from a no-huddle
attack, Weinke completed 5 of 6 passes for 64 yards. One was for 38
yards to split end Robert Morgan, and the payoff came on a 4-yard
touchdown to flanker Marvin Minnis.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia did not need long to move ahead again. Jones ate up 71
yards with a stunning first-down run in which he set the Virginia
career rushing record. Jones took a step forward, then swung left,
faked cornerback Clevan Thomas off his feet and sprinted into the
clear. Roverback Derrick Gibson finally caught him at the Florida
State 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles stiffened from there, and Virginia settled for
Todd Braverman's 26-yard field goal, which was good for a 10-7
halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-30-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
